__d(function(e,t,a,i,r,o,n){r.exports=[{id:"water-001",category:"water",title:"Finding Water in the Wild",priority:"critical",tags:["water","sourcing","beginner","critical"],summary:"Locate reliable water sources using terrain, vegetation, and animal behavior cues.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Read the terrain",body:"Water flows downhill and collects in valleys, ravines, and low-lying areas. Follow natural drainages \u2014 dry creek beds, gullies, and canyon floors. After rain, these fill quickly. Even in drought, dig 1\u20133 feet in the outer bend of a dry streambed \u2014 moisture collects there."},{step:2,title:"Watch for vegetation signals",body:"Cattails, willows, cottonwoods, and bright green vegetation in an otherwise dry landscape almost always indicate a water table near the surface. Dig at the base of these plants. In desert terrain, look for lines of green cutting across hillsides \u2014 these follow underground water seeps."},{step:3,title:"Track animal movement",body:"Animal trails converge at water sources, especially at dawn and dusk. Follow worn trails leading downhill. Birds, especially doves and pigeons, fly to water at dawn and dusk in straight flight lines. Bees and wasps always nest within a mile of water. Follow flying insects toward water."},{step:4,title:"Locate rock seeps and springs",body:"Water seeps out of cliff faces, rock overhangs, and areas where geological layers change. Look for dark staining, moss, or algae growth on rock surfaces. Concave rock formations collect dew and rainwater. Dig at the base of cliff faces in rocky terrain."},{step:5,title:"Collect before purifying",body:"Collect all found water regardless of apparent clarity. Clear water can still carry pathogens. Turbid water may be safer after filtration and purification than clear water that appears clean. Collect as much as possible and purify what you intend to drink."}],warnings:["Never drink unpurified water regardless of how clear it appears \u2014 Giardia, Cryptosporidium, and bacterial contamination are invisible.","Water near animal carcasses, heavy vegetation die-off, or industrial areas may contain toxins that cannot be removed by field purification methods.","Saltwater and urine will accelerate dehydration \u2014 never drink either."],proTips:["At night, tie absorbent cloth (cotton shirt) around your shins and walk through heavy dew-covered vegetation. Wring out into a container \u2014 can yield significant water before sunrise.","Rock pools (tinaja) in canyon country hold water for days after rain. Memorize their locations from maps before entering desert terrain.","In cold climates, snow is water but eating it drops core temperature rapidly \u2014 always melt it first."],relatedGuides:["water-002","water-003","water-004"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are in a survival situation and need to locate water \u2014 dehydration becomes life-threatening within 24-72 hours without it",immediate:["Move downhill and follow drainages \u2014 water flows to low ground and collects in valleys","Watch for bright green vegetation, willows, or cattails in dry terrain \u2014 these signal water nearby","Track animal trails converging toward a single direction at dawn/dusk \u2014 they lead to water"],then:["Dig 1-3 feet into the outer bend of a dry streambed if no surface water found","Collect all water found regardless of clarity \u2014 purify before drinking"]}},{id:"water-002",category:"water",title:"Purification by Boiling",priority:"critical",tags:["water","purification","boiling","critical"],summary:"Boiling is the most reliable field method to eliminate biological water hazards.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Pre-filter sediment",body:"Pour water through cloth, a bandana, or improvised filter (sand over charcoal over grass in a tube) to remove sediment, debris, and particulate matter. This improves taste and reduces the amount of fuel needed to boil."},{step:2,title:"Bring to a rolling boil",body:"A rolling boil \u2014 not a simmer \u2014 is required. Place container over fire. A rolling boil is when the entire surface is bubbling vigorously, not just a few bubbles at the bottom. At altitudes below 6,500 feet, maintain a rolling boil for 1 minute. Above 6,500 feet, boil for 3 minutes (lower atmospheric pressure drops water's boiling point)."},{step:3,title:"Cool before drinking",body:"Remove from heat. Allow to cool to a safe drinking temperature before consuming. Drinking scalding water is a real hazard when dehydrated. Pour between containers to speed cooling. A piece of clean metal submerged in the water also speeds cooling."},{step:4,title:"Improve taste",body:"Boiled water tastes flat because dissolved oxygen is driven out. Transfer water back and forth between containers several times to re-oxygenate. Adding a small pinch of salt also improves palatability."}],warnings:["Boiling eliminates biological threats (bacteria, viruses, parasites) but does NOT remove chemical contamination, heavy metals, or radiological hazards.","Fuel is finite in a grid-down scenario \u2014 ration fire resources and consider combining boiling with solar disinfection (SODIS) for large quantities."],proTips:["A metal container is not required \u2014 a plastic bag, bark trough, or even a large leaf bowl can boil water using hot rocks. Heat rocks in fire (avoid river rocks \u2014 they can explode when heated), then drop them into the water-filled container.","In a pinch, a clear plastic bottle filled with clear water and left in direct sunlight for 6+ hours (SODIS method) will kill most biological pathogens through UV radiation."],relatedGuides:["water-001","water-003","water-005"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You have found water and need to make it safe to drink \u2014 biological contamination kills through diarrhea and dehydration",immediate:["Pre-filter water through cloth or bandana to remove sediment","Bring to a ROLLING boil \u2014 vigorous bubbles throughout, not just at bottom","Maintain rolling boil for 1 minute (3 minutes above 6,500 ft elevation)"],then:["Allow to cool before drinking \u2014 scalding water is a real hazard when dehydrated","Transfer between containers several times to re-oxygenate flat-tasting boiled water"]}},{id:"water-003",category:"water",title:"Improvised Water Filtration",priority:"advanced",tags:["water","filtration","improvised"],summary:"Build a multi-stage sediment and biological filter from available materials.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Gather materials",body:"You need a container with a hole at the bottom (plastic bottle, bamboo tube, hollowed log), layers of filtration media in order: coarse grass or leaves, fine sand, charcoal (from your fire \u2014 crush to small pieces), more fine sand, and a final grass layer. The flow is top to bottom."},{step:2,title:"Layer the filter",body:"Bottom layer (exits first): coarse grass plug to prevent media from washing out. Next: 2\u20133 inches of fine sand. Next: 2\u20133 inches of crushed charcoal (wood charcoal, not briquettes \u2014 briquettes contain additives). Next: 2\u20133 inches of fine sand. Top: coarse grass or cloth to pre-filter large debris."},{step:3,title:"Run and prime",body:"Pour water slowly through the top. The first several cups of output will be dark from the charcoal \u2014 discard this. Once output runs clear, the filter is primed. Never rush the filtration \u2014 pouring too fast bypasses the filter layers."},{step:4,title:"Collect and purify output",body:"Filtered water is significantly cleaner but still requires purification. Filtration removes sediment, improves taste, and reduces some biological load, but does not eliminate all pathogens. Always boil or chemically treat filtered water before drinking."}],warnings:["Field filtration is NOT a standalone solution \u2014 it must always be followed by boiling or chemical treatment.","Filters become breeding grounds for bacteria after 24\u201348 hours. Rebuild or sterilize the filter media regularly."],proTips:["Activated charcoal from your fire is far superior to unactivated \u2014 make it by burning hardwood in a low-oxygen environment (a closed metal can with a small hole works well).","In a pinch, a life straw-style filter can be improvised from a hollow reed or thin bamboo tube packed tightly with charcoal and moss."],relatedGuides:["water-002","water-004"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You have turbid or sediment-laden water that needs pre-treatment before chemical purification or boiling",immediate:["Gather container with hole at bottom, coarse grass, fine sand, and crushed charcoal from fire","Layer bottom to top: grass plug, sand, charcoal, sand, coarse grass/cloth on top","Pour water slowly \u2014 discard first several cups until output runs clear"],then:["Always boil or chemically treat filtered water \u2014 filtration alone does not eliminate all pathogens","Rebuild filter after 24-48 hours as it becomes a bacterial breeding ground"]}},{id:"water-004",category:"water",title:"Solar Still Construction",priority:"advanced",tags:["water","solar still","desert","advanced"],summary:"Extract water from soil and vegetation using solar evaporation \u2014 a last-resort desert technique.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Select a site",body:"Choose a low-lying area with moist soil or where you can bury vegetation. South-facing slopes and dry creek beds retain subsurface moisture. The hole must be where you can actually dig \u2014 avoid rock and caliche."},{step:2,title:"Dig the hole",body:"Dig a bowl-shaped hole approximately 3 feet wide and 2 feet deep. Place your collection container in the deepest center point. If you have a drinking tube, run it from the container up over the rim so you can drink without disturbing the still."},{step:3,title:"Add vegetation",body:"Pack the hole around the container with as much vegetation as possible \u2014 green leaves, cacti (chopped), fresh plant material. The more moisture-containing vegetation, the better the output. Do not cover the container opening."},{step:4,title:"Cover and seal",body:"Stretch clear plastic sheeting tightly over the hole. Weight the edges with soil or rocks to seal completely. Place a small rock in the center of the plastic directly over the container to create a depression \u2014 condensed water will drip off this low point into the container."},{step:5,title:"Wait for output",body:"In full sun, a well-built still produces 0.5\u20131 liter per day. Leave undisturbed during peak sun hours (10am\u20134pm). Check at the end of the day. Replace vegetation every 24\u201348 hours as it dries out."}],warnings:["A solar still requires more water to build (sweat from labor) than it often produces in arid conditions \u2014 it's a supplement, not a primary source. Prioritize finding natural water first.","Clear plastic only \u2014 black or colored plastic will not work. The greenhouse effect requires transparency to UV."],proTips:["Adding urine to the surrounding soil (not the container) significantly increases daily output \u2014 the still distills the water content and leaves contaminants behind.","A transpiration bag \u2014 a clear plastic bag tied over a leafy tree branch in sunlight \u2014 produces 200\u2013400mL per day with almost no labor. Build several at once."],relatedGuides:["water-001","water-002","water-005"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are in a desert or arid environment with no surface water \u2014 a solar still extracts moisture from the ground as a last resort",immediate:["Select a low-lying area with moist soil on a south-facing slope","Dig a 3-foot wide by 2-foot deep bowl-shaped hole with collection container at center","Pack the hole with as much green vegetation or cacti as available around the container"],then:["Cover with clear plastic sheet sealed at edges with soil \u2014 place a rock over the center above the container","Expect 0.5-1 liter per day in full sun \u2014 collect at end of peak sun hours (10am-4pm)"]}},{id:"water-005",category:"water",title:"Rainwater Collection",priority:"beginner",tags:["water","rain","collection","beginner"],summary:"Maximize water capture during rain events using available materials.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Set up catch surfaces",body:"Any clean, non-toxic surface can catch rain. Tarps, ponchos, large leaves (banana, taro, tropical varieties), plastic sheeting, or a rain fly create effective catch areas. Angle the surface to funnel water to a collection point. A 10x10 foot tarp in a 1-inch rain event catches over 60 gallons."},{step:2,title:"Create funnels and channels",body:"Tie corners of a tarp or poncho down, leaving the center hanging low as a collection basin. Or angle all four sides toward a center hole and run a tube or rope into a container. Bamboo or bark gutters can channel water from large catch surfaces over long distances."},{step:3,title:"Discard first flush",body:"The first few minutes of rainfall wash pollutants, debris, bird feces, and contaminants off collection surfaces. Let the rain run for 2\u20133 minutes before directing flow into your clean storage containers. This is especially important if collecting off metal roofs or vegetation."},{step:4,title:"Store properly",body:"Transfer collected water to closed containers immediately to prevent contamination, evaporation, and mosquito breeding. If containers are limited, prioritize filling the largest vessels. Even partially covered containers will breed mosquito larvae in 48\u201372 hours in warm weather."}],warnings:["In areas with industrial fallout, volcanic ash, or nuclear events, rainwater may be contaminated \u2014 filter and purify everything regardless of how clean it appears.","Moss and organic matter on collection surfaces can introduce biological contamination \u2014 clean surfaces before use when possible."],proTips:["Large tropical leaves (and even pine needles in quantity) can be layered into funnel shapes using natural Y-shaped branches as supports, creating effective collection structures with zero equipment.","Pre-position containers before forecasted rain \u2014 you may sleep through a valuable rain event."],relatedGuides:["water-002","water-003"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Rain is falling or forecasted \u2014 maximize water capture now to build a reserve before dry conditions return",immediate:["Deploy any clean catch surface \u2014 tarp, poncho, large leaves \u2014 angled to funnel to a collection point","Discard the first 2-3 minutes of rainfall \u2014 it washes contaminants off surfaces","Fill all available containers once the first flush has run off"],then:["Transfer collected water to closed containers immediately to prevent mosquito breeding","Purify all collected water before drinking \u2014 even rainwater can contain contaminants"]}}]},570,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,r,a,o,n){a.exports=[{id:"fire-001",category:"fire",title:"Bow Drill Fire Starting",priority:"advanced",tags:["fire","primitive","friction","bow drill"],summary:"Start fire using a friction-based bow drill \u2014 requires proper wood selection and technique.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Select wood species",body:"Both the spindle (drill) and fireboard must be dry, the same hardness, and low resin content. Good combinations: willow/willow, cedar/cedar, cottonwood/cottonwood, mullein spindle on basswood board. The moisture test: the wood should snap cleanly, not bend. If it bends, it's too wet."},{step:2,title:"Build the bow",body:"Select a stiff, slightly curved branch 24\u201330 inches long for the bow. Tie cordage (paracord, shoelace, or twisted plant fiber) tightly from tip to tip with about 20% sag \u2014 enough to wrap once around the spindle. Too tight and it won't spin; too loose and it slips."},{step:3,title:"Prepare the fireboard",body:"Cut a shallow depression into the fireboard about half an inch from the edge. Carve a V-shaped notch from the depression to the edge, with the point of the V reaching just past the center of the depression. Place a piece of bark or dry leaf under the notch to catch the coal."},{step:4,title:"Assemble and drill",body:"Trap the spindle in the bow string with one wrap. Place the spindle tip in the fireboard depression. Hold the spindle vertical with the handhold (a smooth rock or notched wood piece with a small lubricated depression). Apply firm downward pressure while drawing the bow horizontally \u2014 long, even strokes the full length of the bow."},{step:5,title:"Build speed and pressure",body:"Start at moderate pace to build heat. Increase speed and downward pressure as smoke begins. When thick smoke pours from the notch, give 10\u201315 fast powerful strokes then remove the bow. The coal is in the catch piece under the notch."},{step:6,title:"Transfer coal to tinder",body:"Carefully tap the notch to ensure the coal falls onto the catch. It will be black and glowing orange \u2014 fragile. Transfer the entire catch piece to your tinder bundle without disturbing the coal. Fold the tinder bundle loosely around the coal and blow gently with steady, deep breaths until the bundle bursts into flame. Drop it into your prepared fire lay immediately."}],warnings:["Wood selection is the most common failure point. Wet or mismatched wood species will not produce a coal regardless of technique.","Blisters on the handhold hand are inevitable until technique improves. Lubricate the handhold depression with forehead skin oil, ear wax, or lip balm \u2014 NOT the fireboard socket."],proTips:["The spindle should fit the bow string snugly \u2014 hold the bow horizontal, the spindle should not fall out. Wrap the string around the spindle once, not twice.","If you're getting smoke but no coal, carve the notch slightly larger \u2014 the V point may not reach the center of the friction depression.","Practice this skill extensively before you need it. A first-time bow drill user in a stress scenario will fail. Proficiency requires dozens of practice sessions."],relatedGuides:["fire-002","fire-003"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need fire and have no modern ignition source \u2014 friction-based fire starting with a bow drill is a viable primitive method that requires significant practice",immediate:["Select matched wood species \u2014 both spindle and fireboard must be dry, same hardness, low resin (willow, cedar, cottonwood)","Build bow 24-30 inches with cordage at 20% sag; prepare V-notch in fireboard with catch piece below","Drill with firm downward pressure and full-length even strokes until thick smoke pours from the notch"],then:["Give 10-15 fast powerful strokes then stop \u2014 carefully check for glowing coal in catch piece","Transfer coal to tinder bundle and blow steadily until bundle ignites, then add to fire lay"]}},{id:"fire-002",category:"fire",title:"Flint and Steel Fire",priority:"advanced",tags:["fire","flint","steel","striker"],summary:"Create fire by striking a high-carbon steel striker against flint or chert to produce sparks.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Identify suitable stone",body:"True flint, chert, quartzite, obsidian, and agate all work. The stone should have a glassy, conchoidal fracture and produce a sharp edge when struck. River cobbles of the right composition work well. Test by striking with the steel striker \u2014 if sparks fly, you have the right material."},{step:2,title:"Prepare char cloth",body:"Char cloth is the best catching material. Pack 100% cotton cloth into a metal tin with a small hole. Place in fire until smoke stops coming out of the hole, then plug the hole immediately. The result is blackened, carbonized cloth that catches a spark at any temperature. Store dry."},{step:3,title:"Striking technique",body:"Hold the stone with the sharp edge facing up and outward. Place char cloth on the top flat surface of the stone, pressed against the striking edge. Strike downward at a 45-degree angle with the steel striker, hitting the sharp stone edge a glancing blow. The goal is to peel hot metal particles onto the char cloth."},{step:4,title:"Catch and develop the spark",body:"A caught spark on char cloth appears as a small orange glow. Gently blow on it \u2014 the glow will spread. Once the char cloth is fully glowing, transfer to a tinder bundle. Fold the bundle loosely around the glowing char and blow with steady breath until it ignites."}],warnings:["Modern high-carbon steel strikers (ferro rods) produce abundant sparks and are far more reliable than traditional steel in wet conditions \u2014 carry one in your kit.","Always have tinder prepared BEFORE striking \u2014 the spark window is brief."],proTips:["Dried fungus (amadou from horse hoof fungus), cattail down, dried grass, and dried tree bark dust all catch sparks well as alternatives to char cloth.","A ferro rod (ferrocerium striker) requires no special stone \u2014 any rough surface works and it functions wet. This is your primary fire-starting tool; bow drill and flint/steel are backups."],relatedGuides:["fire-001","fire-003","fire-004"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need fire and have a ferrocerium rod or high-carbon steel striker available \u2014 this is your primary ignition method",immediate:["Prepare tinder bundle BEFORE striking \u2014 caught spark burns within seconds","Hold sharp stone with char cloth on top surface; strike steel downward at 45-degree angle against the edge","Once spark catches on char cloth, gently blow until entire cloth glows orange"],then:["Transfer glowing char cloth to tinder bundle \u2014 fold loosely around coal","Blow steadily with deep breaths until tinder bursts into flame, then add to prepared fire lay"]}},{id:"fire-003",category:"fire",title:"Starting Fire in Rain",priority:"advanced",tags:["fire","rain","wet conditions"],summary:"Techniques to start and sustain fire when everything is wet.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Source dry material first",body:"Wet is only on the surface. The inside of standing dead wood is usually dry. Split logs open with a knife, rock, or by batoning \u2014 the dry inner wood is your starting material. Look under overhangs, inside hollow trees, and beneath dense evergreen canopy where ground material stays relatively dry."},{step:2,title:"Build a base platform",body:"Wet ground will soak heat away from your fire and extinguish a struggling fire before it establishes. Build a platform of dry wood \u2014 use split logs or thick bark, stacked parallel. Your fire starts on this elevated surface, not on wet ground."},{step:3,title:"Shield from wind and rain",body:"Cup hands, use your body, an improvised windbreak of packed bark, rocks, or your pack. Even a small windscreen dramatically increases success rates. Wind both cools the early fire and blows rain directly into tinder."},{step:4,title:"Build small and dense",body:"In wet conditions, a large fire lay is the enemy. Build a very small, concentrated tinder bundle \u2014 finger-sized kindling tightly packed over your tinder. Small fires concentrate heat in wet conditions better than large spreads. Establish the small fire before scaling up."},{step:5,title:"Feed aggressively once lit",body:"The moment you have flame, feed it continuously with the best available fuel \u2014 do not let it breathe to the point of dying. Any pause at this stage risks losing it. Have abundant progressively-sized fuel ready before striking your first spark."}],warnings:["River rocks and wet rocks from creek beds can explode when rapidly heated \u2014 use dry rocks or metal for fire rings in wet conditions.","Never use accelerants on a struggling fire \u2014 control of the flare-up is impossible."],proTips:["Birch bark contains natural oils and will light even when soaking wet. It is one of the best wet-weather fire starters in any temperate climate.","Fatwood (resin-saturated dead pine heartwood) burns even when soaking wet. Learn to identify it by smell and the orange-amber color of the heartwood. It's found in old pine stumps and roots.","Commercial fire starters (WetFire, Tinder-Quik, Fatwood shavings) are critical kit items. They bridge the gap between a spark and a sustained fire in any condition."],relatedGuides:["fire-001","fire-004"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need fire in wet or rainy conditions \u2014 surface moisture is the challenge, but dry fuel exists inside standing dead wood",immediate:["Split standing dead wood open by batoning \u2014 dry inner wood is your starting material regardless of surface wetness","Build a base platform of dry split logs to elevate your fire off wet ground","Shield your tinder from wind and rain with your body or an improvised windscreen"],then:["Build small and concentrated \u2014 a compact fire lay establishes faster than a large one in wet conditions","Feed aggressively once flame appears \u2014 any pause at this stage risks losing the fire"]}},{id:"fire-004",category:"fire",title:"Fire Positioning and Safety",priority:"beginner",tags:["fire","safety","positioning","beginner"],summary:"How to site, build, and maintain a fire safely in any environment.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Site selection",body:"Clear a 10-foot radius of flammable material. Ground fires should be built in a depression or on mineral soil (sand, gravel, bare rock), never on forest duff, peat, or humus \u2014 these can smolder underground for days and start a wildfire after you leave. Avoid building under low-hanging branches or near standing dead trees."},{step:2,title:"Build the fire ring",body:"A ring of rocks contains the fire and reflects heat. Use dry, non-porous rocks \u2014 not river rocks, which can contain moisture that turns to steam and explodes. Arrange rocks in a circle 1\u20132 feet wider than your intended fire. Rocks must not be fully enclosed \u2014 leave gaps for airflow."},{step:3,title:"Construct the fire lay",body:"Start with a tinder bundle (dry grass, bark shreds, leaves). Add pencil-sized kindling in a loose teepee or log cabin pattern. Then add finger-sized fuel, then wrist-sized fuel ready to add once established. Never pack fuel tightly \u2014 fire needs oxygen to burn."},{step:4,title:"Control the fire size",body:"A fire the size of a dinner plate produces adequate cooking heat and significant warmth. Larger fires are fuel-inefficient, create more smoke, are visible at greater distance, and are harder to extinguish. Match fire size to your actual needs."},{step:5,title:"Extinguish completely",body:"Drown with water until all hissing stops. Stir the ash and add more water. The ground should be cold to the touch before you leave or sleep. Buried embers can reignite hours later. 'If it's too hot to touch, it's too hot to leave.'"}],warnings:["Fire is visible from aircraft and distances of several miles at night \u2014 in a security scenario, use Dakota Hole fires (two connected holes, fire in one, airflow through the other) to reduce visible flame and smoke.","Carbon monoxide kills silently. Never build fire in an enclosed space \u2014 always ensure significant ventilation."],proTips:["A Dakota Hole fire is the most fuel-efficient, low-visibility, weather-resistant fire design. Dig two 12-inch diameter holes about 12 inches deep, connected at the bottom by a diagonal tunnel. Light the fire in one hole \u2014 the tunnel creates a natural draft that feeds oxygen and keeps flame below surface level.","Reflected fire heat: build your fire between yourself and a natural or improvised reflector (large rock, log, bark panel). This directs 40\u201350% more heat toward you and reduces fuel consumption."],relatedGuides:["fire-001","fire-002","fire-003"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to establish a fire safely \u2014 improper site selection and extinguishing are the primary hazards",immediate:["Clear a 10-foot radius of flammable material around the site","Build on mineral soil, sand, or rock \u2014 never on forest duff or peat which can smolder underground","Build a fire ring of dry non-porous rocks (not river rocks) \u2014 leave gaps for airflow"],then:["Size the fire to actual need \u2014 a dinner-plate-sized fire produces adequate cooking heat","Extinguish completely: drown with water, stir ash, add more water until ground is cold to touch"]}}]},571,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,r,a,o,n){a.exports=[{id:"shelter-001",category:"shelter",title:"Debris Hut Construction",priority:"critical",tags:["shelter","debris hut","wilderness","insulation"],summary:"Build an insulating debris hut that retains body heat even in near-freezing temperatures without fire.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Select a site",body:"Choose a site on high, dry ground away from drainage paths. Avoid flood plains, ridge tops exposed to wind, and areas under dead standing trees (widowmakers). An ideal site has natural windbreak (a hillside, dense brush), is close to abundant dead leaf debris, and is not a natural wildlife trail."},{step:2,title:"Build the ridgepole",body:"Find a straight branch or sapling 9\u201310 feet long (1.5x your height). Support one end in a Y-shaped branch or rock at about hip height. The other end rests on the ground. This is the spine of your shelter. The opening faces downhill to drain any ground moisture away from you."},{step:3,title:"Add ribbing",body:"Lean branches along both sides of the ridgepole at 45-degree angles, creating a framework like a fish skeleton. Space ribs every 8\u201310 inches. Pack smaller sticks and brush across the ribs to create a lattice that holds your insulating debris. The interior width should be just wider than your shoulders \u2014 tighter is warmer."},{step:4,title:"Pile debris",body:"Add dead leaves, pine needles, dry grass, bark \u2014 any dry organic matter \u2014 to the outside of the framework. The debris layer must be 2\u20133 feet thick on all sides (arm-length). Thicker is warmer. Use a rough calculation: if you can't see the framework through the debris from outside, you have enough."},{step:5,title:"Fill the interior",body:"Pack the interior floor with 2\u20133 feet of dry debris. This is your insulation from ground cold, which steals heat faster than air. Crawl in feet-first, dragging more debris to plug the entrance behind you. Your body heat will warm the small interior rapidly."}],warnings:["A debris hut is wet-weather and cold-weather shelter, not fire shelter. Never build or maintain fire inside \u2014 it will ignite.","A debris hut that is too large will not retain body heat. Size it precisely to your body \u2014 extra space means extra volume your body must heat."],proTips:["A dry debris hut in near-freezing conditions can maintain 70\xb0F inside with no fire \u2014 based on body heat alone. The insulation principle is identical to a down sleeping bag.","Build it right before dark. Gathering debris takes 2\u20134 hours. In a survival scenario, shelter is your priority 1 in cold weather \u2014 hypothermia kills in hours.","Mark the entrance with a stick arrangement so you can locate it in the dark if you need to exit at night."],relatedGuides:["shelter-002","shelter-003"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / USAF SERE curriculum",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are facing cold weather survival with no tent or sleeping bag \u2014 hypothermia is the primary threat and you must build insulating shelter before dark",immediate:["Select dry high ground away from drainages, ridgetops, and dead standing trees","Cut or find a 9-10 foot ridgepole and prop one end on a Y-branch at hip height","Lean branches along both sides at 45 degrees and weave lattice across them"],then:["Pile dead leaves and debris 2-3 feet thick over the entire structure","Pack interior floor with 2-3 feet of dry debris \u2014 ground cold steals heat faster than air"]}},{id:"shelter-002",category:"shelter",title:"Lean-To Construction",priority:"beginner",tags:["shelter","lean-to","rain","beginner"],summary:"Build a quick lean-to for rain and wind protection using natural materials or a tarp.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Select two anchor trees or poles",body:"Find two trees, posts, or large rocks 7\u20139 feet apart. Tie your ridgeline (paracord, rope, or lashed sapling) between them at chest height. This is the horizontal support your shelter leans against."},{step:2,title:"Lay the roofing material",body:"Lean long straight branches or saplings from the ridgeline to the ground at a 45-degree angle \u2014 steeper angles shed rain better. Space them every 12 inches. Weave smaller branches horizontally across these ribs. The roof must be dense enough to shed water, not just block it."},{step:3,title:"Thatch the roof",body:"Starting from the bottom (ground end) and working upward, lay courses of bark, large leaves, pine boughs, or dense grass like roof shingles \u2014 each course overlapping the one below. Water must run from the top and shed off the bottom edge, not soak through."},{step:4,title:"Add side walls if needed",body:"For cold conditions, close the sides with additional brush and debris piled against staked branch frames. Leave one open side facing your fire (if you have one) \u2014 the lean-to and fire create a sandwich that reflects heat toward you efficiently."},{step:5,title:"Insulate the floor",body:"Pile 4\u20136 inches of dry leaves or pine boughs under your sleeping position. Cold ground will pull heat out of your body continuously \u2014 floor insulation is critical in any cold weather scenario."}],warnings:["A lean-to is not an insulating shelter \u2014 it blocks wind and rain but does not retain body heat the way a debris hut does. In near-freezing conditions without fire, a debris hut is required.","Do not build a lean-to on a ridgeline or exposed hillside \u2014 wind amplification can destroy it and drop your effective temperature."],proTips:["A tarp lean-to can be built in under 5 minutes with practiced technique. Learn to pitch your tarp in multiple configurations before you need it.","A 45-degree pitch sheds rain but increases wind catch. In heavy wind, pitch steeper (60+ degrees) and anchor the bottom edge."],relatedGuides:["shelter-001","shelter-003","fire-004"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / USAF SERE curriculum",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need quick rain and wind protection and have paracord or natural cordage available \u2014 a lean-to can be built in under 30 minutes",immediate:["Tie ridgeline between two trees at chest height","Lean long branches at 45 degrees from ridgeline to ground, spaced every 12 inches","Thatch from bottom up with bark, leaves, or pine boughs \u2014 each layer overlapping the one below"],then:["Insulate the floor with 4-6 inches of dry leaves or pine boughs","Position fire in front of the open side to reflect heat into the shelter"]}},{id:"shelter-003",category:"shelter",title:"Snow Shelter Construction",priority:"advanced",tags:["shelter","snow","winter","quinzhee"],summary:"Build a snow shelter (quinzhee) \u2014 interior stays near 32\xb0F regardless of outside temperature.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Understand the principle",body:"Snow is an excellent insulator. Interior of a snow shelter will stabilize at approximately 32\xb0F even when outside temperatures drop to -40\xb0F. Wind chill has no effect inside. A small candle or body heat alone is sufficient to raise interior temperature to 40\u201350\xb0F."},{step:2,title:"Pile and wait (Quinzhee method)",body:"Pile snow into a mound 8 feet wide and 5\u20136 feet tall. Pack it loosely \u2014 you want sintering (crystals bonding together) but not compression. Insert 12-inch long sticks throughout the mound as depth guides. Wait 2\u20134 hours for the snow to sinter and harden before hollowing."},{step:3,title:"Hollow the interior",body:"Dig a tunnel entrance from one side, angled upward into the center. Cold air pools at the lowest point \u2014 the raised interior sleeping platform stays warmer than the entrance. Hollow out the interior to just above your reference sticks. A 1-inch ceiling is plenty; thicker is not significantly stronger and reduces interior space."},{step:4,title:"Create a ventilation hole",body:"Poke a ventilation hole through the ceiling with a ski pole, stick, or your arm. This is not optional \u2014 it prevents CO2 buildup and condensation drip. Keep your pole or a stick inside to re-open the vent if snow blocks it."},{step:5,title:"Insulate the floor",body:"Place branches, a tarp, or a sleeping pad on the interior floor. Sitting or sleeping directly on snow wicks heat rapidly. Even 2 inches of insulation makes a significant difference. Block the entrance with a pack or snow block to retain heat."}],warnings:["Mark the entrance with skis, poles, or a bright flag \u2014 a buried quinzhee is impossible to locate after new snowfall.","Do not sleep in a quinzhee with a fire inside \u2014 CO and CO2 buildup will kill you before you wake. A single candle is the maximum safe heat source."],proTips:["A properly built quinzhee is structurally sound enough to support an adult standing on top \u2014 this is the test. If it collapses under body weight, add more time for sintering or increase wall thickness.","In an emergency with no tools, dig into a natural snow bank or create a snow trench \u2014 any configuration that gets you out of wind and off bare ground is survival-grade shelter."],relatedGuides:["shelter-001","shelter-002"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / USAF SERE curriculum",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are in a winter survival scenario with heavy snowfall \u2014 a snow shelter maintains near 32\xb0F interior regardless of outside temperature",immediate:["Pile snow into a mound 8 feet wide and 5-6 feet tall \u2014 insert 12-inch reference sticks throughout","Wait 2-4 hours for snow to sinter and harden before excavating","Hollow from one side angling upward \u2014 cold air pools at entrance, sleeping platform stays warmer"],then:["Poke a ventilation hole through the ceiling with a ski pole or stick \u2014 this is not optional","Block the entrance with your pack to retain heat and insulate the floor from snow contact"]}},{id:"shelter-004",category:"shelter",title:"Urban Grid-Down Shelter",priority:"critical",tags:["shelter","urban","grid-down","critical"],summary:"Assess, secure, and establish shelter in an urban environment during grid failure.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Structural assessment",body:"Before entering any building: look for foundation cracks, leaning walls, visible structural damage, collapsed sections. Check the ground floor for flooding signs or compromised floors. Smell for gas \u2014 if you detect gas, do not enter and do not use any flame or electrical switch nearby. Tag assessed buildings with chalk markers so others know the status."},{step:2,title:"Select for defensibility and concealment",body:"In a grid-down urban scenario, shelter selection must balance safety with security. Prefer buildings set back from main roads, with multiple exit routes, above ground floor (avoids flooding and easier breach), and without large visible windows on the ground level. Upper floors of multi-story buildings offer observation and concealment advantages."},{step:3,title:"Establish access control",body:"Secure entry points \u2014 not to stop a determined attacker, but to create noise and delay. Broken glass on sills, stacked cans that fall, fishing line at ankle height, bells on string. If you must leave, note what position you left items in to detect entry during absence."},{step:4,title:"Thermal management",body:"In winter grid-down, select the smallest room for habitation \u2014 easier to heat. South-facing rooms with windows capture passive solar heat. Seal drafts with cloth, tape, foam, or paper. Interior rooms with no exterior walls are the warmest in cold and coolest in heat. Mylar emergency blankets on windows reduce heat loss significantly."},{step:5,title:"Water and sanitation setup",body:"Identify all water storage in the structure (water heaters hold 40\u201380 gallons; toilet tanks hold 1\u20132 gallons of potable water if not chemically treated). Establish a toilet and waste disposal protocol immediately \u2014 improper waste in enclosed spaces creates rapid disease threat."}],warnings:["Post-earthquake structures that appear intact may have compromised load-bearing elements that fail hours later. Do not shelter in a building that has experienced ground shaking without assessment.","Open flames in enclosed urban structures for heat carry significant CO poisoning risk. Ensure constant airflow."],proTips:["A hotel or apartment building has advantages over a house in a grid-down scenario: multiple water sources (each unit has a tank), more defensive depth, and often better structural integrity than older housing stock.","The water heater is your first water source in an urban grid-down \u2014 turn off the inlet valve to prevent further contamination from outside the structure and use the drain valve to access the stored water."],relatedGuides:["water-001","security-001","disaster-005"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / USAF SERE curriculum",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"The power grid has failed and you need to assess, secure, and establish a defensible urban shelter position",immediate:["Check for gas smell before entering any building \u2014 do not enter if detected","Assess structural integrity: look for foundation cracks, leaning walls, collapsed sections","Select upper floor with multiple exit routes and minimal ground-floor window exposure"],then:["Identify water sources in the structure: water heater (40-80 gal), toilet tanks (1-2 gal)","Establish access control with noise-making trip lines and sealed entry points"]}}]},572,[]);
__d(function(e,i,a,t,o,r,s){o.exports=[{id:"food-001",category:"food",title:"Edible Plant Identification \u2014 North America",priority:"advanced",tags:["food","plants","foraging","identification"],summary:"Identify high-confidence edible plants using the universal edibility test and key North American species.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Understand the risk baseline",body:"Misidentification of edible plants kills people every year. The safest approach is to know 5\u201310 plants in your region with absolute certainty rather than attempting to identify hundreds from memory. Focus on high-confidence, widely-distributed, high-calorie species with no dangerous look-alikes."},{step:2,title:"High-confidence species",body:"Prioritize these for North American scenarios: Cattail (Typha) \u2014 roots, pollen, and young shoots are edible. Found near any standing water. Dandelion \u2014 entire plant edible, roots, leaves, flower. Acorns \u2014 all oaks produce edible acorns after leaching tannins in water for 24+ hours. Pine \u2014 inner bark (cambium layer) is edible, needles for tea. Wild garlic/onion \u2014 if it smells like onion, it is safe. Death camas looks similar but has no onion smell."},{step:3,title:"Universal edibility test",body:"When unsure: 1) Separate plant into parts (root, leaf, stem, seed). 2) Smell \u2014 avoid strong unpleasant chemical or almond odors. 3) Skin test \u2014 rub a small amount on inner wrist, wait 15 minutes for reaction. 4) Lip test \u2014 touch to lip for 3 minutes, wait 15 minutes. 5) Tongue test \u2014 place on tongue for 15 minutes. 6) Eat a teaspoon and wait 8 hours. Test only one part of one plant at a time. This takes time \u2014 start before you're critically hungry."},{step:4,title:"Processing and preparation",body:"Many edible plants are far safer cooked. Boiling eliminates many toxins and improves digestibility. Never eat raw elderberries (cook first). Leach bitter-tasting plants in multiple changes of boiling water to remove tannins and other irritants. Cooking also improves caloric availability."}],warnings:["Never eat wild mushrooms unless you have formal training and certainty of identification \u2014 Amanita phalloides (death cap) is fatal in small quantities with no antidote.","Avoid plants with milky white sap, umbrella-shaped flower clusters (Apiaceae family contains deadly hemlock), and shiny three-leafed plants.","The three-day starvation threshold: the energy cost of foraging over a wide area may exceed caloric return in some environments. Prioritize water, shelter, and rest over aggressive foraging."],proTips:["Cattail is called the 'supermarket of the swamp' for good reason. A single cattail rhizome (root) can be dried and ground into starch flour. The pollen in bloom is nutritious and tastes slightly sweet.","Acorn flour (after tannin leaching) is a reliable, storable, high-calorie food source. Cold-water leaching takes 2\u20133 days; hot-water leaching takes several hours with multiple water changes."],relatedGuides:["food-002","food-003","food-004"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are in a survival situation and need to supplement calories through foraging \u2014 focus on 5-10 high-confidence species, not a broad survey",immediate:["Identify high-confidence species first: cattail near water, dandelion in fields, acorns from any oak","Apply the edibility test for unknowns: smell, skin test, lip test, tongue test \u2014 one plant part at a time","Avoid anything with milky sap, umbrella flower clusters, or shiny three-leafed plants"],then:["Cook all foraged plants when possible \u2014 boiling eliminates many toxins","Leach bitter-tasting plants in multiple water changes to remove tannins"]}},{id:"food-002",category:"food",title:"Trapping and Snaring",priority:"advanced",tags:["food","trapping","snaring","protein"],summary:"Set effective small game traps and snares for continuous passive calorie collection.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Think in trap lines, not single traps",body:"Set 10\u201320 snares simultaneously rather than 1\u20132. Most snares fail. Trap lines give you statistical coverage. Check every trap every 4\u20136 hours \u2014 dead animals spoil quickly in warm weather, and live-caught animals damage snares."},{step:2,title:"Simple loop snare",body:"Use paracord, wire (preferred \u2014 holds shape), or cordage. Form a fixed loop 4\u20135 inches in diameter for rabbits, 2\u20133 inches for squirrels. Tie the other end to a fixed anchor (root, stake). Hang the loop at head height of the target animal \u2014 for rabbit, fist height off the ground. The loop must be on a game trail, near burrows, or on a natural pinch point (narrow gap between logs, brush, etc.)."},{step:3,title:"Twitch-up snare (live capture / quick kill)",body:"A spring snare attached to a bent sapling or counterweight triggers when an animal steps through the loop, jerking the animal upward off the ground. This kills or immobilizes quickly and keeps the catch off the ground and away from other scavengers. The trigger is a notched stick under tension \u2014 animal pulls the snare loop, trigger releases, sapling fires."},{step:4,title:"Site selection",body:"Look for: runs (paths animals use repeatedly \u2014 compressed grass, worn trail), droppings, fur on bark or wire, burrow entrances, and feeding signs (chewed vegetation, acorn shells). Animals are most active at dawn and dusk. Snares on active runs consistently outperform snares placed in likely-looking but inactive areas."},{step:5,title:"Scent control",body:"Human scent on traps and snares is a significant deterrent. Boil snares in pine bark or walnut hulls to neutralize scent. Handle traps with gloves or after rubbing hands with dirt and pine needles. Do not urinate near trap lines."}],warnings:["Check local regulations if applicable \u2014 in most true emergency scenarios, survival trapping supersedes normal regulatory constraints, but be aware of the distinction.","Snares do not discriminate \u2014 you may catch non-target animals. Know how to humanely dispatch any animal you catch."],proTips:["Fishing by trap (improvised fish weir, bottle trap, or hook and line) is far more calorie-efficient per hour of labor than land trapping in most environments with water access.","Insects are a high-protein, readily available food source that requires no trap skill. Beetles, grubs, grasshoppers, and caterpillars are all edible cooked. Avoid brightly colored insects, hairy caterpillars, and insects that sting."],relatedGuides:["food-001","food-003","food-004"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are in a survival situation that will extend beyond 3 days and need passive protein collection \u2014 set trap lines to collect food while you do other tasks",immediate:["Set 10-20 snares simultaneously on active game runs \u2014 statistical coverage is the key","For rabbits: loop 4-5 inches diameter, fist height off ground, on worn game trail or near burrow","Boil or rub snares with pine needles and dirt before placing to neutralize human scent"],then:["Check traps every 4-6 hours \u2014 dead animals spoil quickly in warm weather","Prioritize fishing over land trapping when water is available \u2014 it is more calorie-efficient per hour"]}},{id:"food-003",category:"food",title:"Fishing Without Gear",priority:"advanced",tags:["food","fishing","improvised"],summary:"Catch fish using improvised hooks, weirs, and hand-fishing techniques.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Improvised hook and line",body:"Hooks can be improvised from safety pins, thorns, bent nails, carved bone or hardwood, and metal can tab openings. Line can be paracord inner strands, thread, plant fiber cordage, or stripped electrical wire. Bait with worms (dig near river banks), insects, small fish pieces, or dough balls from found grain."},{step:2,title:"Gorge hook technique",body:"A gorge hook is a straight, pointed, double-ended piece of bone, hardwood, or metal (a toothpick-sized piece of wire bent at both ends). Tie line to the center. Bait it and let the fish swallow it whole. When the fish swallows and the line is pulled, the gorge turns sideways inside the throat and lodges \u2014 no bend required. Used globally as a primitive fishing method."},{step:3,title:"Fish weir",body:"A fish weir is a V-shaped wall of rocks built across a stream, with the point of the V facing downstream. Fish swimming upstream funnel into the point and cannot reverse out. Build the walls above the water line so fish do not simply swim over. This is a passive trap that works 24 hours with no attendance."},{step:4,title:"Hand fishing (noodling/tickling)",body:"In slow or still water, submerge your arm slowly under rock overhangs and logs where fish hide. Move extremely slowly. When you feel a fish, grab firmly behind the gills or around the body and remove quickly. Catfish, bass, and carp respond to this technique. Wear mental armor \u2014 you will also encounter crawdads, snakes, and snapping turtles."}],warnings:["Wash hands thoroughly after handling fish and raw protein \u2014 any cuts provide entry for infection.","Cook all freshwater fish thoroughly \u2014 raw freshwater fish can carry parasites including tapeworms. Saltwater fish are relatively safer raw but cooking is always preferable."],proTips:["Fish are most active at dawn and dusk in low-light conditions. Mid-day fishing is often unproductive in warm weather \u2014 fish move to deep, cool water.","Edible freshwater fish in North America include bass, trout, catfish, perch, crappie, carp, and bluegill. All are safe to eat cooked. Identify them by body shape rather than color \u2014 colors vary by region."],relatedGuides:["food-002","food-004"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You have access to a stream, lake, or river and need protein \u2014 improvised fishing is more calorie-efficient per hour than land trapping",immediate:["Improvise hook from safety pin, bent nail, or carved bone; use paracord inner strands as line","Build a fish weir: V-shaped rock wall across stream with point downstream \u2014 fish funnel in and cannot reverse","Use bait from riverbank: worms, insects, or small pieces of existing protein"],then:["Fish at dawn and dusk when fish are most active in shallow water","Cook all freshwater fish thoroughly \u2014 raw freshwater fish can carry tapeworms and parasites"]}},{id:"food-004",category:"food",title:"Food Preservation Without Refrigeration",priority:"advanced",tags:["food","preservation","drying","smoking"],summary:"Preserve meat, fish, and plant foods for days to weeks using primitive methods.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Smoking",body:"Cut meat into strips 1/4 inch thick, removing as much fat as possible (fat goes rancid rapidly). Hang strips on a wooden rack over a smoky fire \u2014 hardwood smoke (oak, hickory, apple, cherry) is best. Avoid softwoods (pine, fir) which contain resins. Smoke at low heat (150\u2013200\xb0F) for 6\u201312 hours until the meat is dark, hard, and dry with no moisture. Properly smoked meat can last 1\u20132 weeks without refrigeration."},{step:2,title:"Solar drying",body:"In low-humidity, sunny conditions, thin strips of meat or fish can be dried without smoking. Spread pieces on clean rocks or improvised racks in direct sunlight and wind. Cover loosely with cloth or screen to keep insects off. Turn every few hours. Full sun drying takes 2\u20133 days depending on temperature, humidity, and thickness. The product should be rigid and hard with no soft spots."},{step:3,title:"Salt curing",body:"Salt draws moisture out of meat through osmosis and inhibits bacterial growth. Pack meat pieces completely in salt \u2014 do not allow any surface to remain unsalted. Leave for 24\u201348 hours. Rinse, dry, and optionally smoke. Requires significant salt \u2014 roughly 1 pound of salt per 5 pounds of meat. Salt is a critical grid-down resource."},{step:4,title:"Root cellaring concept",body:"Many root vegetables (potatoes, turnips, carrots, beets) and squash remain edible for weeks to months in cool, dark, humid conditions. Dig a pit 2\u20133 feet below the frost line, line with straw, and store root vegetables. Temperature stabilizes at 35\u201345\xb0F below ground \u2014 natural refrigeration."}],warnings:["Improperly dried or smoked meat causes botulism and other food-borne illnesses. If meat smells off, is slimy, or shows mold, discard it. Food poisoning in a grid-down scenario with no medical care can be fatal.","Do not attempt to dry or smoke meat in high humidity \u2014 the surface dries before the interior, creating a case-hardened exterior that traps moisture and allows bacteria to grow inside."],proTips:["Pemmican \u2014 rendered fat mixed with dried meat powder and dried berries \u2014 was the original long-distance trail food used by indigenous peoples and fur traders. It lasts for months without refrigeration and is calorie-dense (400\u2013500 cal/100g).","Fish preserves much faster than mammal meat when smoked because fish is leaner and the tissue is less dense. A full-size salmon can be smoked to preservation in 8\u201310 hours."],relatedGuides:["food-001","food-002"],source:"US Army FM 21-76 / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You have more food than can be consumed today and need to preserve it \u2014 spoilage in a grid-down scenario wastes irreplaceable calories",immediate:["Cut meat into 1/4-inch strips removing all fat \u2014 hang over smoky hardwood fire","Smoke at low heat 150-200\xb0F for 6-12 hours until meat is dark, hard, and dry throughout","For solar drying: spread thin strips on rocks in direct sun, cover with cloth to keep insects off"],then:["Store smoked or dried meat in dry, sealed container \u2014 properly dried meat lasts 1-2 weeks","Salt curing requires 2.5% salt by weight of meat \u2014 pack completely with no exposed surface"]}}]},573,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,a,o,s,n){o.exports=[{id:"medical-001",category:"medical",title:"Tactical Combat Casualty Care (TCCC) Overview",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","TCCC","trauma","critical","military"],summary:"The three-phase framework for managing trauma casualties when evacuation is delayed or unavailable.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Phase 1 \u2014 Care Under Fire",body:"You are taking fire. The casualty is taking fire. The threat is immediate and active. Actions: Return fire. Take cover. Suppress the threat. Direct the casualty to return fire if able, or move to cover. Apply a tourniquet for life-threatening extremity bleeding \u2014 self-applied if able. Do NOT expose yourself to assess wounds. Do NOT move the casualty into the open. Threat elimination is the primary life-saving action at this phase."},{step:2,title:"Phase 2 \u2014 Tactical Field Care",body:"The immediate threat has been neutralized or you are in a covered position with adequate time. Now you assess and treat. Use the MARCH protocol: M \u2014 Massive hemorrhage (tourniquets, wound packing). A \u2014 Airway (position, open airway, nasopharyngeal airway if available). R \u2014 Respiration (check for tension pneumothorax, seal open chest wounds). C \u2014 Circulation (treat shock, establish IV/IO access if trained). H \u2014 Hypothermia prevention (get the casualty off the ground, cover). This phase is where most life-saving interventions occur."},{step:3,title:"Phase 3 \u2014 TACEVAC",body:"Tactical evacuation \u2014 the process of moving the casualty from the point of injury to a higher level of care. Actions: Reassess all interventions applied during Phases 1 and 2. Document what was done and when (time of tourniquet application is critical). Communicate casualty status to the evacuation team using the 9-Line MEDEVAC format or simplified status (immediate, delayed, minimal, expectant). Continue monitoring during transport \u2014 airway and bleeding status can change."},{step:4,title:"MARCH Rapid Reference \u2014 Field Card",body:"Commit this to memory or laminate a wallet card.\n\nM \u2014 Massive hemorrhage: tourniquet, wound packing, junctional pressure.\nA \u2014 Airway: chin lift, jaw thrust, NPA if available, recovery position.\nR \u2014 Respiration: chest seal (both sides) for penetrating chest trauma; needle decompression for tension pneumo.\nC \u2014 Circulation: establish IV/IO if trained; administer TXA within 3 hours of injury if available; treat hypothermia.\nH \u2014 Hypothermia/head trauma: get casualty off cold ground; use space blanket; monitor neurological status.\n\nCritical timelines: tourniquet within 60 seconds of arterial bleed; TXA within 180 minutes of injury; TACEVAC within the 'platinum hour' for penetrating trauma."}],warnings:["Uncontrolled hemorrhage is the leading cause of preventable combat death. Tourniquet application within seconds is more important than any other intervention.","TCCC is a framework \u2014 without training and repetition, execution under stress will be imperfect. Train with the tools you carry."],proTips:["MARCH replaces the old ABC (Airway, Breathing, Circulation) in tactical medicine because Massive hemorrhage kills faster than airway compromise in trauma. Address bleeding first.","The military switched to MARCH from ABC specifically because data from combat operations showed that preventable deaths were overwhelmingly hemorrhagic. M comes first for a reason."],relatedGuides:["medical-002","medical-003","medical-004"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"basic_edc",prerequisites:[],whenNotTo:["Do not attempt advanced interventions without prior TCCC training","Do not delay evacuation to perform procedures beyond your skill level"],quickGlance:{situation:"You or someone with you has sustained a traumatic injury and professional medical evacuation is not immediately available",immediate:["Eliminate or suppress active threat \u2014 move casualty to cover","Apply tourniquet to any life-threatening extremity bleeding immediately","Use MARCH protocol: Massive hemorrhage \u2192 Airway \u2192 Respiration \u2192 Circulation \u2192 Hypothermia"],then:["Document all interventions with time applied","Package casualty for TACEVAC \u2014 note tourniquet application time on forehead"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-002",category:"medical",title:"Tourniquet Application",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","tourniquet","hemorrhage","critical"],summary:"Apply a tourniquet correctly \u2014 including one-handed self-application \u2014 for life-threatening extremity bleeding.",steps:[{step:1,title:"When to apply",body:"Apply a tourniquet when: bleeding from an extremity cannot be controlled with direct pressure; bleeding is pulsatile (bright red, spurting \u2014 arterial); the wound is large or complex with multiple bleeding points; the casualty is losing consciousness from blood loss. If in doubt, apply the tourniquet. Tourniquet complications (nerve damage, tissue death) are extremely rare at treatment durations under 2 hours and are always preferable to hemorrhagic death."},{step:2,title:"Placement",body:"Apply 2\u20133 inches above the wound, NOT over a joint. For a wound below the knee or elbow, apply at mid-thigh or mid-upper arm ('high and tight' is the military standard for severe wounds \u2014 apply as high as possible on the limb). Place over clothing if necessary \u2014 do not waste time removing clothing in an emergency."},{step:3,title:"Application with a CAT or SOFTT-W",body:"Slide the limb through the loop. Pull the free end of the strap tight \u2014 as tight as you can manually before engaging the windlass. Twist the windlass rod until bleeding stops completely \u2014 not just reduces. Lock the rod in the retention strap or clip. The casualty will experience significant pain \u2014 this is expected and indicates proper application. Note the time on the tourniquet or the casualty's forehead."},{step:4,title:"One-handed self-application \u2014 arm",body:"Lay the tourniquet on a flat surface or your leg. Insert the injured arm through the loop. Use your other hand and your teeth to pull the strap tight. Use your good hand to operate the windlass. Bite and hold the windlass if needed while locking."},{step:5,title:"One-handed self-application \u2014 leg",body:"Loop tourniquet around the thigh. Pull the strap through the buckle with your good hand as tight as possible. Use your knee, a surface, or a tree to help lever the strap tight. Operate the windlass with your good hand. Twist until bleeding stops. Note the time."},{step:6,title:"Improvised tourniquet",body:"If no commercial tourniquet: use a cloth strip 2+ inches wide (narrower cuts into tissue and is less effective). Form a loop and tie around the limb. Insert a rigid rod (stick, pen, screwdriver) through the loop and twist until bleeding stops. Lock the rod against the limb with another wrap of cloth. Improvised tourniquets have higher failure rates than commercial devices \u2014 use as last resort only."}],warnings:["Never remove a tourniquet in the field once applied \u2014 re-application or conversion can be performed at a higher level of care with resuscitation capability.","A tourniquet that does not stop bleeding is either improperly applied (not tight enough) or requires a second tourniquet applied proximal to (above) the first.","Do not pad under a tourniquet \u2014 it reduces effectiveness."],proTips:["The rule of thumb: when you stop twisting the windlass, check if you can see pulsatile bleeding. If yes, keep twisting. If the bleeding has stopped, you're done. Do not 'just a little more' \u2014 that's the right tension.","Carry at minimum two tourniquets. Junctional hemorrhage (groin, armpit, neck) cannot be controlled with a limb tourniquet \u2014 have additional pressure dressings for these wounds."],relatedGuides:["medical-001","medical-003","medical-004"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"advanced_kit",prerequisites:["medical-001"],whenNotTo:["Do not apply tourniquet for venous (slow, dark) bleeding that can be controlled with direct pressure","Do not apply over a joint \u2014 position 2-3 inches above wound","Do not remove tourniquet in the field if applied for arterial bleed \u2014 removal must be done by trained medical personnel"],quickGlance:{situation:"You or someone with you has life-threatening arterial bleeding from an extremity \u2014 bright red blood pumping or spurting",immediate:["Position tourniquet 2-3 inches above the wound on the limb, not over clothing if avoidable","Tighten windlass until bleeding stops completely \u2014 not just slows","Note and mark the time of tourniquet application \u2014 write on patient's forehead if needed"],then:["Monitor for renewed bleeding around or below tourniquet","Do not remove \u2014 await trained medical personnel for conversion"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-003",category:"medical",title:"Wound Packing",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","wound packing","hemorrhage","critical"],summary:"Pack wounds with gauze or improvised materials to control hemorrhage that cannot be tourniqueted.",steps:[{step:1,title:"When to pack",body:"Pack wounds that: cannot receive a tourniquet (junctional wounds \u2014 neck, groin, axilla/armpit); are in the torso; are large complex wounds with multiple bleeding points. Wound packing is the primary intervention for junctional hemorrhage, which is the leading cause of preventable deaths that reach higher care."},{step:2,title:"Prepare the wound",body:"If bleeding is visible, use your fingers to identify the source \u2014 often deep in the wound cavity, not at the surface. Controlling surface bleeding while deep bleeding continues is a critical failure. Pack to the source, not the surface. Do not remove impaled objects \u2014 pack around them."},{step:3,title:"Pack with hemostatic gauze",body:"If you have combat gauze (QuikClot, Celox, HemCon): begin packing directly into the deepest point of the wound, against the bleeding source. Pack in a systematic figure-eight or accordion fold \u2014 do not bunch it randomly. Fill the wound cavity completely."},{step:4,title:"Pack with improvised material",body:"If no hemostatic gauze: use the cleanest cloth available \u2014 improvised dressing from a t-shirt, bandana, or any absorbent material. Tear into strips if needed. Pack into the wound the same way \u2014 to the deepest point, filling the cavity. The packing material is less important than the application technique."},{step:5,title:"Apply pressure",body:"Once the wound is packed full, apply firm, continuous direct pressure with both hands using bodyweight for 3 minutes with commercial hemostatic gauze, 10 minutes with improvised packing. This is not gentle pressure \u2014 it is maximum sustained pressure. Do not lift your hands to check during this time."},{step:6,title:"Secure the packing",body:"After direct pressure, apply a pressure bandage over the wound to maintain pressure. Improvise with cloth strips tied firmly. The goal is to maintain the pressure you just applied. Check every few minutes \u2014 bleeding through a saturated dressing means add more dressing on top and continue pressure. Do not remove the original packing."}],warnings:["Wound packing is painful. A conscious casualty will resist. Communicate what you are doing and why. If the casualty is unconscious, ensure airway is maintained as you work.","Never pack an open chest wound (penetrating chest wound that makes sucking noise) \u2014 see medical-005 for chest wound management. Packing a tension pneumothorax can be fatal."],proTips:["Junctional hemorrhage (neck, groin, armpit) is the leading cause of deaths that reach care but die before surgery. These wounds bleed out in minutes from major vessels. Pack aggressively and immediately.","QuikClot Z-fold combat gauze is the TCCC-recommended hemostatic agent. Carry it. The civilian equivalent (QuikClot Advanced Clotting Gauze) is available without prescription and should be in every kit."],relatedGuides:["medical-002","medical-004","medical-005"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"advanced_kit",prerequisites:["medical-002"],whenNotTo:["Do not pack wounds to the chest, neck, or abdomen \u2014 pack only for extremity and junctional wounds","Do not remove packing material once applied \u2014 re-packing without proper training can restart hemorrhage"],quickGlance:{situation:"You have a severe wound with uncontrolled hemorrhage that cannot be controlled with a tourniquet (junctional wound, neck, groin)",immediate:["Apply hemostatic gauze (QuikClot/Celox) \u2014 pack it deep into the wound cavity, not just on the surface","Apply firm direct pressure to the packed wound with full body weight for minimum 3 minutes","Secure with a pressure bandage to maintain compression"],then:["Monitor for bleeding through the dressing \u2014 if soaking through, add more pressure on top","Do not remove the packing in the field"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-004",category:"medical",title:"Junctional Hemorrhage Control",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","junctional","hemorrhage","neck","groin"],summary:"Control life-threatening bleeding at the neck, groin, and armpit where tourniquets cannot be applied.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Recognize junctional hemorrhage",body:"Junctional zones are where limbs attach to the body: the inguinal fold (groin), the axilla (armpit), and the neck. Major vascular structures in these zones \u2014 femoral artery (groin), axillary artery (armpit), carotid/jugular (neck) \u2014 can produce fatal hemorrhage in under 3 minutes. A tourniquet cannot be applied high enough to control these wounds."},{step:2,title:"Groin hemorrhage",body:"Apply firm bimanual pressure directly over the inguinal fold (where the leg meets the body). If trained and junctional tourniquet device (JETT, iTClamp, AAJT) is available, apply per training. Otherwise, pack the wound deeply with hemostatic gauze and apply maximum sustained direct pressure with bodyweight. Position: stand or kneel over the casualty, press both hands into the wound, lock your elbows and transfer your weight."},{step:3,title:"Axillary hemorrhage (armpit)",body:"Pack the axilla deeply with hemostatic gauze. Have an assistant or improvised pressure device maintain sustained pressure. Arm compression: fold the arm across the chest and apply a pressure wrap from axilla over shoulder and under the opposite axilla \u2014 this compresses the wound. Elevate the arm if possible."},{step:4,title:"Neck hemorrhage",body:"Penetrating neck wounds with arterial involvement are extremely time-critical. Pack the wound firmly with hemostatic gauze. Apply sustained manual pressure UNILATERALLY \u2014 do not apply circumferential pressure around the neck (occludes both carotids and the airway). Pressure on one side only. Maintain airway \u2014 blood in the airway can cause rapid death from asphyxiation independently of blood loss."}],warnings:["Neck wounds with arterial bleeding are surgical emergencies. Field management buys minutes, not hours. Aggressive evacuation is essential.","Do not remove your hands from a packing site to 'check progress' \u2014 you will lose the clot forming beneath."],proTips:["The iTClamp is a bridge device for neck hemorrhage \u2014 it clamps skin around the wound and creates an enclosed hematoma that tamponades the bleeding. It is a legitimate field device and EMTs and combat medics carry it. For civilian kits, it is available and worth considering.","Bilateral femoral artery wounds (both groin areas) are almost universally fatal without surgical capability. Understand the limits of field medicine."],relatedGuides:["medical-002","medical-003","medical-005"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"advanced_kit",prerequisites:["medical-001"],whenNotTo:["Do not attempt to control junctional hemorrhage without hemostatic gauze \u2014 improvised packing is a last resort only","Do not apply circumferential pressure around the neck \u2014 compress one side only to avoid airway occlusion"],quickGlance:{situation:"Life-threatening bleeding at the neck, groin, or armpit where a tourniquet cannot be applied",immediate:["Pack the wound deeply with hemostatic gauze \u2014 do not just apply to the surface","Apply maximum sustained direct pressure with both hands using bodyweight for minimum 3 minutes","For groin: stand or kneel over the casualty, lock elbows, and lean in"],then:["Maintain pressure continuously \u2014 do not lift hands to check until 3 minutes have elapsed","Secure packing and maintain pressure during evacuation"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-005",category:"medical",title:"Tension Pneumothorax Recognition and Treatment",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","chest","pneumothorax","needle decompression"],summary:"Recognize and treat a tension pneumothorax \u2014 a rapidly fatal chest condition with a simple field intervention.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Understand the mechanism",body:"A tension pneumothorax occurs when air accumulates in the pleural space (around the lung) without a means to escape. Each breath forces more air in, progressively collapsing the lung and eventually compressing the heart, causing obstructive shock and death. This can occur from penetrating chest trauma, blunt trauma, or occasionally from an improperly sealed chest wound."},{step:2,title:"Recognize the signs",body:"Signs of tension pneumothorax: penetrating or blunt chest trauma mechanism; increasing respiratory distress and tachycardia; absent or diminished breath sounds on the affected side (difficult to assess in field); trachea deviated away from the affected side (late sign); hypotension that does not respond to fluids; distended neck veins (JVD) \u2014 late sign. The casualty in tension PTX deteriorates rapidly \u2014 shock, unconsciousness, death follow in minutes without treatment."},{step:3,title:"Seal open chest wounds first",body:"Open (sucking) chest wounds \u2014 penetrating chest wounds that make a sucking or bubbling sound with breathing \u2014 must be sealed. Apply a vented chest seal (Halo, Russell) or improvise with a square of plastic secured on three sides (the fourth side acts as a flutter valve, allowing air out but not in). If the casualty deteriorates after sealing, consider that the seal has created a tension PTX \u2014 burp the seal by lifting one edge."},{step:4,title:"Needle decompression \u2014 indication",body:"Perform needle decompression when: the casualty has penetrating or severe blunt chest trauma AND is in respiratory distress and shock AND breath sounds are absent on one side. In a grid-down scenario without advanced assessment tools, treat the side of the wound (or the side of absent/diminished breath sounds). A tension PTX is fatal without decompression \u2014 the intervention is life-saving."},{step:5,title:"Needle decompression \u2014 procedure",body:"Site: Second intercostal space (ICS), midclavicular line (MCL) on the affected side. Find the clavicle \u2014 go 2 finger-widths below the clavicle, directly over the nipple line. Alternative site (used in TCCC): 4th or 5th ICS, anterior axillary line (on the side of the chest, above and forward of the armpit). Insert a 14-gauge needle/catheter (3.25 inches or longer \u2014 standard IV needles are often too short to penetrate the chest wall). Insert perpendicular to the chest wall, over the top of the rib (going under the rib risks the neurovascular bundle). A rush of air confirms decompression. Leave the catheter in place or remove the needle over the catheter."}],warnings:["Needle decompression is an invasive procedure. Performing it on a patient without tension PTX will cause a simple pneumothorax \u2014 an injury, but survivable. Not performing it on a patient with tension PTX is fatal. When the indication is met, err on the side of action.","Standard 14g 3.25-inch needles may not reach the pleural space in heavy-set individuals. Use the longest available needle."],proTips:["The anterior axillary line (4th/5th ICS) site is increasingly preferred in TCCC because it is more reliably effective for penetrating the chest wall and less likely to fail due to body habitus.","Carry a purpose-built chest decompression needle (Tactical Medical Solutions, North American Rescue) \u2014 they are pre-attached to a large-bore catheter at the appropriate length."],relatedGuides:["medical-001","medical-003","medical-006"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"advanced_kit",prerequisites:["medical-001"],whenNotTo:["Do not perform needle decompression without a confirmed or strongly suspected tension pneumothorax \u2014 the procedure creates a pneumothorax if one is not present","Do not seal an open chest wound completely (no flutter valve) \u2014 a fully sealed chest wound can cause or worsen tension pneumothorax"],quickGlance:{situation:"Patient has penetrating or severe blunt chest trauma with respiratory distress, shock, and absent breath sounds on one side",immediate:["Seal any open (sucking) chest wound with a vented chest seal or three-sided improvised seal","If patient deteriorates after sealing, burp the seal to release trapped air","If tension PTX confirmed: needle decompression at 2nd ICS midclavicular line or 4th/5th ICS anterior axillary line"],then:["Monitor respiratory status continuously after decompression","Reassess for recurrence \u2014 a second decompression may be required"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-006",category:"medical",title:"Shock \u2014 Recognition and Management",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","shock","hemorrhage","critical"],summary:"Recognize shock early and apply the field interventions that improve survival.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Types of shock",body:"Hemorrhagic shock (most common in trauma): caused by blood loss. Treat by controlling bleeding. Neurogenic shock: spinal cord injury causes vessel dilation. Septic shock: systemic infection. Obstructive shock: tension PTX, cardiac tamponade. Anaphylactic shock: severe allergic reaction \u2014 treat with epinephrine. In a trauma scenario, assume hemorrhagic shock until proven otherwise."},{step:2,title:"Early signs",body:"Heart rate >100 bpm; respiratory rate >20; skin pale, cool, clammy; anxiety, restlessness, confusion (brain is poorly perfused); pulse is rapid and weak at wrist (radial); capillary refill >2 seconds. These signs appear when approximately 15\u201330% of blood volume is lost. The body compensates well initially \u2014 do not be reassured by a casualty who appears 'okay' after significant blood loss."},{step:3,title:"Late signs \u2014 decompensated shock",body:"Blood pressure drops (systolic <90 mmHg); pulse is absent at wrist, present at carotid only; skin mottled and pale; decreased consciousness or unconsciousness; shallow, irregular breathing. Decompensated shock means compensatory mechanisms have failed. Death follows rapidly without intervention. Loss of radial pulse = approximately 50% blood volume lost."},{step:4,title:"Field treatment",body:"Stop the bleeding (tourniquets, wound packing, pressure). Position: lay flat, elevate the legs 12 inches if no suspected spinal injury \u2014 this shifts blood volume toward the core and brain. Keep warm \u2014 hypothermia worsens coagulopathy (the blood's ability to clot). If IV access is available and you are trained, administer IV fluids \u2014 permissive hypotension (systolic 80\u201390) is acceptable in hemorrhagic shock; aggressive fluid resuscitation worsens outcomes."}],warnings:["Oral fluids are contraindicated in a patient with altered mental status (aspiration risk) and may be contraindicated before surgical intervention depending on the wound type.","Hypothermia is a major complication of shock \u2014 the 'lethal triad' of trauma is hypothermia, acidosis, and coagulopathy. All three worsen each other. Keep the patient warm."],proTips:["The radial pulse check is your rapid field shock assessment tool: if you can feel a pulse at the wrist, systolic BP is approximately >80. If the radial pulse is absent but the carotid is present, systolic is approximately 60\u201380. No carotid: <60.","Jelly belly sign: in a supine patient, the abdomen becomes visibly distended and board-hard in internal hemorrhage. This indicates intra-abdominal bleeding requiring surgery \u2014 no field intervention stops this. Rapid evacuation is the only intervention."],relatedGuides:["medical-001","medical-002","medical-007"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",prerequisites:["medical-001"],whenNotTo:["Do not administer medications if the person has known allergies or you are uncertain","Do not move a trauma patient with suspected spinal injury unless immediate danger requires it"],quickGlance:{situation:"A person is showing signs of hemorrhagic shock: pale/grey skin, rapid weak pulse, confusion, excessive thirst, cold clammy extremities",immediate:["Control any identified bleeding source immediately \u2014 tourniquet or wound pack","Lay the casualty flat and elevate legs 6-12 inches if no spinal injury suspected","Prevent heat loss \u2014 cover with blankets or anything available"],then:["Monitor pulse and mental status every 5 minutes","Keep casualty warm \u2014 hypothermia accelerates shock progression"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-007",category:"medical",title:"Airway Management Without Equipment",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","airway","unconscious","critical"],summary:"Maintain a patent airway in an unconscious casualty using position and manual techniques.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Assessment",body:"Look: is the chest rising? Listen: air movement at the mouth and nose? Feel: airflow on your cheek? If no airflow, the airway is obstructed. Common causes: tongue (most common in unconscious patient), blood/vomit, foreign object, swelling, or jaw trauma."},{step:2,title:"Head-tilt chin-lift",body:"Place one hand on the forehead and push backward while lifting the chin with two fingers of the other hand. This extends the neck, lifting the tongue off the posterior pharynx and opening the airway. Do NOT use this technique if cervical spine injury is suspected \u2014 use jaw thrust instead."},{step:3,title:"Jaw thrust (spine precaution)",body:"Position behind the casualty's head. Place fingers behind the angles of the jaw on both sides. Push the jaw forward and upward without moving the neck. This opens the airway while maintaining cervical spine neutrality."},{step:4,title:"Recovery position",body:"In an unconscious breathing casualty with no suspected spinal injury, the recovery position (lateral recumbent) is the safest maintenance position. Roll the casualty onto their side, top knee bent forward, top arm supporting the head. This prevents aspiration of blood, vomit, and secretions and prevents the tongue from obstructing the airway without requiring ongoing manual support."},{step:5,title:"Finger sweep",body:"If you can visualize an obstruction in the mouth (blood, vomit, dislodged teeth, food), remove it with a gloved finger sweep. Do not perform blind finger sweeps \u2014 pushing an obstruction deeper is the risk. Only remove what you can see."},{step:6,title:"Nasopharyngeal airway (NPA)",body:"If an NPA is available: measure from the nostril to the earlobe for sizing. Lubricate with whatever is available (petroleum jelly, lip balm, saliva). Insert into the right nostril (the one with the bevel facing the septum), advancing gently along the floor of the nasal cavity. The NPA maintains airway without the need for the patient's cooperation and works in patients with clenched jaws or dental damage."}],warnings:["Airway compromise and hemorrhage must be managed simultaneously in trauma. Do not complete all airway steps before controlling an arterial bleed \u2014 MARCH applies.","If the airway is maintained with a maneuver and the patient vomits, roll them immediately to the recovery position to clear the airway."],proTips:["A comatose trauma patient should be maintained in the recovery position for transport whenever possible \u2014 this single position change prevents more aspiration deaths than any other airway intervention.","Carry a NPA in your medical kit. A size 28 French NPA fits the majority of adults. They cost a few dollars, weigh almost nothing, and have saved lives in scenarios where a surgical airway would otherwise be required."],relatedGuides:["medical-001","medical-006"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"advanced_kit",prerequisites:[],whenNotTo:["Do not attempt nasopharyngeal airway on a patient with facial fractures or suspected basilar skull fracture","Do not use a finger sweep on an unconscious patient without directly visualizing the obstruction"],quickGlance:{situation:"A person is unconscious or has compromised airway \u2014 gurgling, stridor, inability to speak, or apnea",immediate:["Tilt head back and lift chin to open the airway","Look, listen, and feel for breathing \u2014 assess for 10 seconds","If no breathing and trained: start rescue breaths; if not trained: position in recovery position"],then:["Insert nasopharyngeal airway if available and patient is unconscious without facial trauma","Monitor airway continuously \u2014 position changes can compromise it"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-008",category:"medical",title:"Oral Rehydration Therapy",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","dehydration","diarrhea","ORT","critical"],summary:"Treat severe dehydration and diarrheal illness with Oral Rehydration Salts \u2014 more effective than plain water.",steps:[{step:1,title:"When ORT is required",body:"Signs of severe dehydration: sunken eyes, extremely dry mouth and mucous membranes, decreased or absent urination, skin 'tenting' (pinch skin on back of hand \u2014 slow return to normal takes >2 seconds), confusion, weakness, inability to stand. In cholera and severe gastroenteritis, plain water replacement is insufficient \u2014 electrolytes are lost faster than water and plain water can paradoxically worsen cellular dehydration."},{step:2,title:"WHO ORS formula",body:"In 1 liter of clean (purified) water, dissolve: 6 level teaspoons of sugar (glucose or sucrose) AND 1/2 teaspoon of salt (sodium chloride). Stir completely until dissolved. This is the WHO standard ORS formulation. It should taste mildly salty and sweet \u2014 not strongly either. Too much salt is dangerous; measure carefully."},{step:3,title:"Administration",body:"Give small, frequent sips \u2014 not large volumes rapidly. In an adult: 200\u2013400mL per hour for the first 4 hours, then as much as tolerated. In a child under 2: 50\u2013100mL after each loose stool. The patient should show improvement (increased urination, improved skin turgor, improved alertness) within 4\u20136 hours of ORT."},{step:4,title:"Continue feeding",body:"Do not fast a patient with diarrhea. The gut can still absorb nutrients even during diarrheal illness. Bland, easily digestible foods (rice, plain crackers, bananas, boiled potato) are appropriate. Avoid dairy, fats, and high-fiber foods during acute illness. BRAT diet (bananas, rice, applesauce, toast) if available."}],warnings:["If vomiting prevents ORT administration, small sips every 5 minutes often succeed where larger volumes fail. Wait 10 minutes after a vomiting episode before resuming.","Bloody diarrhea (dysentery) with fever indicates a bacterial infection and requires antibiotics if available. ORT is still required but is not sufficient treatment alone.","ORT does not treat the cause of diarrhea \u2014 it prevents death from dehydration while the illness runs its course."],proTips:["Pre-packaged ORS packets (Pedialyte sachets, DripDrop, oral rehydration sachets) are compact, lightweight, shelf-stable, and far more reliable than field-mixed solutions. Stock them in your medical kit.","Coconut water contains natural electrolytes and serves as a reasonable ORS substitute in regions where coconuts are available."],relatedGuides:["medical-009","medical-010"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",prerequisites:[],whenNotTo:["Do not give ORT rapidly in large volumes \u2014 small sips only to avoid triggering vomiting","Do not substitute plain water alone for ORS in severe diarrheal illness \u2014 electrolyte replacement is essential"],quickGlance:{situation:"A person shows signs of severe dehydration: sunken eyes, dry mouth, decreased urination, confusion, or weakness",immediate:["Mix WHO ORS: 1 liter clean water + 6 teaspoons sugar + 1/2 teaspoon salt","Give small sips continuously \u2014 200-400mL per hour for adults","Monitor for improvement: increased urination, improved alertness within 4-6 hours"],then:["Continue ORT until dehydration signs resolve","Introduce bland foods as tolerated \u2014 do not fast the patient"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-009",category:"medical",title:"Field Sanitation and Latrine Construction",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","sanitation","latrine","disease prevention","critical"],summary:"Establish field sanitation systems that prevent the diseases that kill more people in disaster than trauma.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Why sanitation is survival-critical",body:"In a grid-down or disaster scenario, improper waste disposal is the primary driver of cholera, typhoid, hepatitis A, and dysentery outbreaks. These diseases killed more soldiers in every 20th century conflict than enemy fire until modern field sanitation was mandated. In a population without sanitation, waterborne disease outbreaks can kill 10\u201330% of an affected group within weeks."},{step:2,title:"Cat hole latrines (individual, short-term)",body:"For individuals or small groups over 1\u20133 days: dig holes 6\u20138 inches deep, at least 200 feet from water sources, camps, and trails. Defecate in the hole, cover with the excavated soil, and pack down. This puts waste in the biologically active layer of soil where decomposition occurs fastest. Mark used holes with a stick."},{step:3,title:"Pit latrine (group, extended operations)",body:"For groups or extended operations: dig a trench 2\u20134 feet deep, 1 foot wide, as long as necessary. Site it downhill and downwind from the camp, at least 200 feet from any water source. Build a straddle-trench design \u2014 users straddle the trench. Cover the opening with soil after each use. When the trench is 3/4 full, fill completely, mark the site, and relocate."},{step:4,title:"Hand hygiene enforcement",body:"Establish a hand-washing station at the latrine exit \u2014 water container with a hole or valve, soap or ash (ash is an effective soap substitute), and a drying towel. Make hand-washing mandatory, not optional, within the group. The single most effective disease-prevention measure in any field environment is hand hygiene after defecation and before food preparation."},{step:5,title:"Waste water and gray water",body:"Gray water (cooking, washing) must also be disposed of properly. Dig a sump pit \u2014 1-2 feet deep, filled with gravel or rocks \u2014 at least 200 feet from water sources. Pour gray water into the sump pit, which filters it through the soil. Do not dispose of gray water in running water sources."}],warnings:["Burning waste is preferable to open defecation but produces toxic fumes \u2014 never burn waste in enclosed spaces.","Do not site a latrine uphill from any water source. Groundwater flows downhill. Contamination of a water source from a poorly sited latrine can affect everyone downstream."],proTips:["Lime (calcium hydroxide) is the traditional field sanitation agent. Dusted over latrine contents, it deactivates pathogens, reduces odor, and accelerates decomposition. Pool shock (calcium hypochlorite) can substitute.","The F-diagram: Flies, Fingers, Fields, Fluids, Fomites, Food \u2014 the six fecal-oral transmission routes. Interrupting any route breaks the chain of disease transmission."],relatedGuides:["medical-010","medical-008"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",prerequisites:[],whenNotTo:["Do not site latrines within 200 feet of any water source \u2014 groundwater contamination can affect the entire group","Do not burn waste in enclosed spaces \u2014 toxic fumes pose serious respiratory risk"],quickGlance:{situation:"Your group needs to establish sanitation in a field or grid-down environment for more than 24 hours",immediate:["Designate a latrine site at least 200 feet downhill and downwind from camp and water sources","Dig cat holes (6-8 inches deep) for short-term or pit trench (2-4 feet deep) for group use","Set up a hand-washing station at the latrine exit with water and soap or ash"],then:["Enforce mandatory hand-washing after every use","Relocate latrine when trench is 3/4 full \u2014 mark used sites clearly"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-010",category:"medical",title:"Vector Control \u2014 Mosquitoes, Ticks, and Rodents",priority:"advanced",tags:["medical","vector control","insects","rodents","disease prevention"],summary:"Reduce vector-borne disease transmission through site selection, barriers, and environmental control.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Mosquito control",body:"Site camps away from standing water \u2014 mosquitoes breed in any standing water, including puddles, containers, and tire tracks. Drain, cover, or treat all water containers not intended for drinking. Sleep under a bed net (impregnated with permethrin is best). Apply DEET or permethrin to exposed skin and clothing. In high-malaria areas, chemoprophylaxis (doxycycline, mefloquine) is the only reliable prevention \u2014 field measures reduce but do not eliminate risk."},{step:2,title:"Tick prevention",body:"Wear long sleeves and pants tucked into boots in tick habitat (tall grass, brush, wooded areas). Treat clothing with permethrin. Conduct full body tick checks every evening \u2014 key areas: scalp, behind ears, back of neck, armpits, groin, behind knees. A tick must be attached for 24\u201336 hours to transmit Lyme disease \u2014 early removal is highly protective."},{step:3,title:"Tick removal",body:"Use fine-tipped tweezers or a tick removal tool. Grasp the tick as close to the skin surface as possible. Pull upward with steady, even pressure \u2014 do not twist or jerk. Do not use petroleum jelly, nail polish, heat, or other methods \u2014 these increase disease transmission by agitating the tick. Clean the bite site with alcohol or soap and water after removal."},{step:4,title:"Rodent control",body:"Rodents carry hantavirus, plague, typhus, leptospirosis, and numerous other serious pathogens. Do not leave food accessible to rodents \u2014 store in sealed containers off the ground. Do not sleep near rodent burrows or nesting sites. Do not handle dead rodents without gloves. If sleeping in structures with rodent evidence, clean with bleach solution and ventilate before occupying."}],warnings:["Hantavirus: Do not sweep or vacuum rodent droppings dry \u2014 the virus is airborne. Wet droppings with bleach solution (1:10 bleach to water) and allow to soak before wiping up with gloves.","In malaria-endemic areas, a single night without mosquito protection can result in infection. In grid-down tropical scenarios, malaria is a major threat."],proTips:["Permethrin-treated clothing remains effective through 6+ washes and provides significantly better protection than topical repellents alone. Treat your field clothing in advance of deployment.","Natural mosquito repellents (citronella, lemon eucalyptus oil \u2014 OLE specifically) have evidence-based efficacy but must be reapplied every 30\u201360 minutes versus 4\u20136 hours for DEET."],relatedGuides:["medical-009","medical-011"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",prerequisites:[],whenNotTo:["Do not handle dead rodents without gloves \u2014 hantavirus and plague are transmitted through contact and aerosolized droppings","Do not sweep or vacuum dry rodent droppings \u2014 wet with bleach solution first to prevent aerosolization"],quickGlance:{situation:"Operating in an environment with mosquitoes, ticks, or rodent presence that poses disease transmission risk",immediate:["Apply DEET to exposed skin and permethrin to clothing","Tuck pants into boots and wear long sleeves in tick habitat","Eliminate or avoid standing water near camp to reduce mosquito breeding"],then:["Conduct full-body tick check every evening \u2014 especially scalp, armpits, groin, and behind knees","Store all food in sealed containers off the ground to deter rodents"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-011",category:"medical",title:"Food Safety and Spoilage Identification",priority:"advanced",tags:["medical","food safety","spoilage","disease prevention"],summary:"Identify spoiled food, understand safe handling without refrigeration, and prevent food-borne illness.",steps:[{step:1,title:"The temperature danger zone",body:"Bacteria multiply rapidly between 40\xb0F and 140\xb0F (4\xb0C\u201360\xb0C). Without refrigeration, all perishable foods enter this zone. Cooked food left at ambient temperature in warm weather becomes dangerous within 2\u20134 hours. In a grid-down scenario with no refrigeration, cook only what you will eat immediately and preserve the rest (smoke, salt, dry)."},{step:2,title:"Identify spoilage \u2014 smell",body:"The most reliable field test. Any off, sour, or ammonia-like smell in meat or poultry indicates spoilage. Fish smells strongly of ammonia when spoiled (vs. mild sea smell when fresh). Dairy products smell sour and sometimes putrid. Trust your nose \u2014 the human nose evolved specifically to detect rotting protein."},{step:3,title:"Identify spoilage \u2014 visual",body:"Slime on meat or fish surfaces indicates bacterial growth. Mold on bread, cheese, and grains \u2014 visible green, blue, black, or white fuzzy growth. Discoloration in meat (gray, green, or brown patches in normally red meat). Bloated canned or sealed food \u2014 gas production from bacteria or botulism. Never eat from a bloated can."},{step:4,title:"Botulism risk",body:"Clostridium botulinum produces toxin in low-oxygen, low-acid, moderate-temperature environments \u2014 precisely the conditions in home-canned or improperly preserved food. Botulism toxin is one of the most lethal substances known. Signs: descending paralysis (starts with blurred vision, drooping eyelids, difficulty swallowing, then progresses to paralysis and respiratory failure). If suspected, there is no field treatment \u2014 only supportive care and antitoxin (hospital). Never take risks with canned or preserved food showing any suspect signs."}],warnings:["Do not apply the rule 'if it looks okay and smells okay, it's okay' universally \u2014 Salmonella, E. coli O157:H7, and Norovirus produce no detectable smell or appearance changes.","Food-borne illness in a grid-down scenario with dehydration risk can be fatal \u2014 it is not simply 'food poisoning' that will pass. It can trigger dehydration severe enough to require ORT or IV fluids."],proTips:["High-acid foods (vinegar-preserved, citrus-pickled) are significantly more resistant to spoilage. Vinegar pickling is a viable field preservation technique for vegetables.","The nose blind phenomenon: people who are used to being around spoiled food become desensitized. In a group, have different people smell-test food if possible \u2014 fresh noses detect spoilage that habituated noses miss."],relatedGuides:["medical-009","food-004"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",prerequisites:[],whenNotTo:["Do not eat from a bloated or swollen can \u2014 this is a sign of botulism toxin production and is potentially lethal","Do not rely solely on smell or appearance to determine food safety \u2014 many pathogens (Salmonella, E. coli, Norovirus) are odorless and invisible"],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to assess whether food is safe to eat without refrigeration or when uncertain about storage conditions",immediate:["Inspect for bloating, slime, unusual color, or mold \u2014 discard any food showing these signs","Smell test: off, sour, or ammonia odor in meat or fish indicates spoilage","Never eat from a bloated can \u2014 discard it without opening"],then:["Cook only what will be consumed immediately \u2014 do not store cooked food without refrigeration in warm weather","Prioritize high-acid or properly preserved foods (vinegar-pickled, dried, smoked) over fresh perishables"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-012",category:"medical",title:"Combat Stress Reaction \u2014 Recognition and Management",priority:"advanced",tags:["medical","mental health","combat stress","CSR"],summary:"Recognize combat stress reaction and apply BICEPS protocol to return personnel to function.",steps:[{step:1,title:"What is combat stress reaction",body:"Combat Stress Reaction (CSR) \u2014 also called battle fatigue or acute stress reaction \u2014 is a predictable, normal response to abnormal levels of physical and psychological stress. It is not a sign of weakness or psychiatric disorder. Under sufficient stress, any person can experience CSR. It is distinct from PTSD (which is a longer-term condition) and is typically reversible with proper immediate management."},{step:2,title:"Signs of CSR",body:"Trembling, shaking, startle response to minor stimuli. Confusion, poor decision-making, difficulty following instructions. Hypervigilance or, conversely, unresponsiveness/dissociation. Weeping or inappropriate emotional responses. Physical complaints without apparent physical cause (headache, GI symptoms, fatigue). Freezing under fire or in emergency action."},{step:3,title:"BICEPS protocol",body:"B \u2014 Brevity: intervention should last hours to days, not weeks. The goal is rapid return to function. I \u2014 Immediacy: address CSR immediately; delay worsens outcomes. C \u2014 Centrality: treat near the unit/group, not evacuated far away \u2014 this reinforces identity and belonging. E \u2014 Expectancy: explicitly tell the person they are normal, they will recover, and they will return to the group. P \u2014 Proximity: keep them close to their group, not isolated. S \u2014 Simplicity: basic needs \u2014 sleep, food, water, safety, and a trusted person to talk to."},{step:4,title:"Practical intervention",body:"Remove from the immediate stressor if possible. Ensure the person is physically safe, warm, and hydrated. Allow them to talk if they want to \u2014 do not force a debrief. Do not permit the person to isolate. Assign a simple, low-complexity task to restore sense of purpose and competence. Maintain normalcy of routine \u2014 meals, rest schedule."}],warnings:["Do not dismiss or shame CSR. Phrases like 'man up' or 'others have it worse' worsen outcomes and damage trust. Acknowledge the stress is real and the response is normal.","A person who has experienced CSR may have delayed reaction to trauma weeks later (PTSD). Be aware that initial recovery does not mean the person is fully processed."],proTips:["Sleep deprivation is the single largest contributing factor to CSR. A person who has not slept in 36+ hours has measurably impaired judgment equivalent to intoxication. Prioritize rotation schedules that allow minimum 4-hour sleep blocks.","Unit cohesion (strong interpersonal bonds within the group) is the most protective factor against CSR. Groups that trust each other, train together, and communicate openly have dramatically lower CSR rates under equivalent stress."],relatedGuides:["medical-013","medical-001"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",prerequisites:[],whenNotTo:["Do not dismiss or shame combat stress reaction \u2014 phrases like 'man up' worsen outcomes and damage unit trust","Do not isolate a person experiencing CSR \u2014 proximity to the group is a core part of treatment"],quickGlance:{situation:"A person in your group is showing signs of combat stress reaction: trembling, confusion, freezing, unresponsiveness, or inappropriate emotional response under stress",immediate:["Remove the person from the immediate stressor if tactically possible","Ensure they are physically safe, warm, fed, and hydrated","Tell them explicitly: their response is normal, they will recover, and they are not alone"],then:["Keep them near the group \u2014 do not evacuate or isolate unless medically necessary","Assign a simple, low-stakes task to restore sense of competence and purpose"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-013",category:"medical",title:"Long-Term Patient Care Without Resupply",priority:"advanced",tags:["medical","patient care","extended operations","nursing"],summary:"Manage a sick or injured person in an extended grid-down scenario without professional medical care or resupply.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Establish a sick bay",body:"Designate a specific area for patient care \u2014 separate from food preparation and the general camp if possible. The area should be: sheltered from weather, easy to access for a caregiver, equipped with the cleanest available bedding, positioned to allow monitoring without continuous attendance. A sick person in a cold, wet, or exposed position will deteriorate rapidly regardless of other interventions."},{step:2,title:"Monitoring and documentation",body:"Record vitals at least every 4 hours: heart rate (normal 60\u2013100), respiratory rate (normal 12\u201320), temperature (estimate with hand to forehead if no thermometer), mental status (alert, confused, unconscious), urine output (adequate hydration = urine produced every 4\u20136 hours, pale yellow). Write it down \u2014 memory of trends is unreliable under stress."},{step:3,title:"Fluid and nutrition management",body:"An ill person who cannot eat must still hydrate. Clear fluids (water, ORS, clear broth) every 30\u201360 minutes. As tolerance improves, progress to soft, easily digestible foods. A person with a fever loses significantly more fluid through sweating and respiration \u2014 increase fluid intake proportionally. Caloric deficit is survivable for weeks; dehydration is fatal in days."},{step:4,title:"Wound care and infection prevention",body:"Clean wounds daily with the cleanest water available (boiled and cooled is best). Inspect for signs of infection: increasing redness, warmth, swelling, pus, red streaks extending from the wound (lymphangitis \u2014 indicates spreading infection requiring antibiotics if available). Change dressings when saturated or soiled. Keep wounds covered to prevent further contamination."},{step:5,title:"Caregiver sustainability",body:"Extended patient care is exhausting. A single caregiver who does not sleep, eat, or maintain their own health will become a second patient. Establish rotation schedules. Define clear task handoff \u2014 what was given, when, what was observed. Caregiver fatigue causes medication errors, missed deterioration signs, and failure to maintain hygiene protocols."}],warnings:["Antibiotic use without diagnosis and appropriate selection drives antibiotic resistance and can cause significant adverse effects. Use antibiotics from your kit only when infection signs are clear and significant.","Pain management without opioids: ibuprofen (anti-inflammatory and analgesic) and acetaminophen taken together provide additive pain relief. Both should be in your medical kit in abundance."],proTips:["Honey is a legitimate wound care agent with documented antimicrobial properties. Medical-grade Manuka honey is preferred but any raw honey can be applied to clean wounds as a topical antimicrobial in the absence of commercial dressings.","Maggot debridement is effective and has been used in field medicine for centuries \u2014 sterile fly larvae (blowfly maggots, specifically Phaenicia sericata) clean necrotic tissue from wounds more effectively than many surgical debridement methods. This is a last-resort but evidence-based technique."],relatedGuides:["medical-009","medical-008","medical-012"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",prerequisites:[],whenNotTo:["Do not use antibiotics without clear signs of infection \u2014 inappropriate use drives resistance and can cause adverse effects","Do not allow a single caregiver to provide continuous care without rotation \u2014 caregiver fatigue causes errors and the caregiver becomes a second patient"],quickGlance:{situation:"You are managing a sick or injured person in a grid-down scenario without access to professional medical care or resupply",immediate:["Designate a sheltered, clean area for the patient \u2014 separate from food prep and the general camp","Establish a monitoring schedule: record heart rate, respiratory rate, temperature, and mental status every 4 hours","Ensure continuous hydration \u2014 clear fluids every 30-60 minutes even if the patient cannot eat"],then:["Clean wounds daily with boiled and cooled water \u2014 watch for redness, swelling, pus, or red streaks","Set up caregiver rotation to prevent fatigue \u2014 document all interventions at handoff"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0},{id:"medical-014",category:"medical",title:"Mass Casualty Triage \u2014 START Protocol",priority:"critical",tags:["medical","triage","mass casualty","START","critical"],summary:"Apply the START triage system to rapidly sort casualties and direct resources where they will save the most lives.",steps:[{step:1,title:"The triage principle",body:"In a mass casualty incident (MCI), there are more casualties than there are resources to treat them simultaneously. Triage is the process of sorting casualties by treatment priority to achieve the greatest good for the greatest number. It is explicit rationing of care. It requires the uncomfortable decision to delay care to some casualties so that others who are more savable can receive immediate intervention."},{step:2,title:"START categories",body:"START = Simple Triage and Rapid Treatment. Four categories: RED (Immediate) \u2014 life-threatening but survivable with immediate intervention. YELLOW (Delayed) \u2014 serious injury but can wait 30\u201360 minutes. GREEN (Minor) \u2014 walking wounded, can wait hours. BLACK (Expectant/Deceased) \u2014 unsurvivable given current resources, or dead. The system uses three assessments: respiration, perfusion, and mental status."},{step:3,title:"Step 1 \u2014 Walking wounded",body:"Announce loudly: 'If you can walk, move to [designated safe area].' Everyone who walks is GREEN. Tag them and direct them out of the scene. This immediately identifies a large portion of your casualties and removes them from the scene, clearing access to those who cannot ambulate."},{step:4,title:"Step 2 \u2014 Assess non-ambulatory casualties",body:"For each non-ambulatory casualty in sequence: Check respiration \u2014 if not breathing, reposition airway. If still not breathing after repositioning: BLACK. If breathing rate >30 per minute or very slow/gasping: RED. If respiratory rate is within normal: proceed to perfusion check."},{step:5,title:"Step 3 \u2014 Perfusion",body:"Check for capillary refill (compress the nail bed, release, count seconds to return pink) or radial pulse. Capillary refill >2 seconds or absent radial pulse: RED (hemorrhagic shock). Apply tourniquet or direct pressure immediately, then continue. Capillary refill <2 seconds: proceed to mental status check."},{step:6,title:"Step 4 \u2014 Mental status",body:"Give simple command: 'Squeeze my hand.' If the casualty cannot follow simple commands: RED. If the casualty can follow simple commands: YELLOW. Complete triage passes through the entire scene tagging each casualty. Then treatment begins, starting with all RED casualties. BLACK patients are triaged expectant \u2014 provide comfort if resources later allow, but do not delay care to RED casualties for BLACK casualties."}],warnings:["Triage is dynamic \u2014 a YELLOW patient can become RED and a GREEN can become YELLOW. Reassess all casualties every 15\u201330 minutes.","Emotionally, tagging a living person BLACK is one of the most difficult actions in emergency medicine. The decision is based on survivability given available resources \u2014 it is not abandonment, it is the system working correctly."],proTips:["Speed is the purpose of START \u2014 the entire system should complete triage of one casualty in under 30 seconds. Individual assessment should not exceed 60 seconds per patient. The goal is to identify all RED casualties as fast as possible.","Tag casualties with color or write on skin with a marker. In dark or smoke-filled environments, verbal relay between team members is required. Never hold a triage category in memory alone."],relatedGuides:["medical-001","medical-002","medical-006"],source:"TCCC Guidelines 2023 / CoTCCC / Stop the Bleed",lastReviewed:"2025-01",riskLevel:"high",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"basic_edc",prerequisites:["medical-001"],whenNotTo:["Do not spend more than 60 seconds assessing any single casualty during initial START triage \u2014 speed is the system's purpose","Do not tag a casualty BLACK and move on if the airway has not been repositioned \u2014 one repositioning attempt is required before BLACK assignment"],quickGlance:{situation:"You are responding to a mass casualty incident with more casualties than you can treat simultaneously",immediate:["Direct all walking wounded to a safe area \u2014 everyone who walks is GREEN","Move through remaining casualties: assess respiration, perfusion (capillary refill or radial pulse), and mental status","Tag each casualty RED, YELLOW, GREEN, or BLACK \u2014 apply tourniquets to RED casualties and continue"],then:["Begin treatment starting with all RED casualties","Reassess all casualties every 15-30 minutes \u2014 triage categories change as conditions evolve"]},requiresMedicalDisclaimer:!0}]},574,[]);
__d(function(e,t,a,i,o,n,r){o.exports=[{id:"nav-001",category:"navigation",title:"Terrain Reading and Topo Map Basics",priority:"critical",tags:["navigation","map","terrain","topo"],summary:"Read a topographic map to understand terrain before you move through it.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Understanding contour lines",body:"Contour lines connect points of equal elevation. Every contour line represents a specific elevation change (the contour interval \u2014 printed in the map legend). When lines are close together, terrain is steep. When lines are far apart, terrain is gentle. Concentric circles indicate a hill or peak. When contour lines form a V shape, the V points uphill for ridges and downhill (toward lower numbers) for valleys and drainages. Learning to see the 3D terrain from the 2D contour pattern is the foundational map skill."},{step:2,title:"Identify terrain features",body:"Ridge: an elongated high ground \u2014 contour lines form an elongated oval. Valley/Draw: low terrain between ridges \u2014 contour lines point uphill when tracing the valley. Saddle: a low point between two hills \u2014 look for an hourglass contour pattern. Cliff: contour lines touching or crossing (impassable terrain). Depression: a low area surrounded by higher ground \u2014 marked with hachure tick marks inside the contour. Spur: a short ridge extending from a main ridge."},{step:3,title:"Map orientation",body:"Orient the map by placing a compass on it and rotating the map (not the compass) until the magnetic north arrow on the compass aligns with north on the map. Account for declination (the difference between magnetic north and true north) \u2014 your map legend shows the local declination. Once oriented, the map is a 1:1 representation of the terrain around you: what is to your left on the ground is to the left on the map."},{step:4,title:"Locate yourself on the map",body:"Triangulation: sight two or three recognizable terrain features (hilltop, bend in river, road junction). For each feature, take a compass bearing. Draw a line back on your map from each feature on the bearing you measured. Your position is at the intersection of the lines. Resection with two features gives a line of position; three features give a point."}],warnings:["Magnetic declination varies significantly by location (up to 20\xb0+ in some areas). Not accounting for declination when navigating long distances causes significant positional error.","Topo maps have a publication date \u2014 major changes (new roads, structures, significant erosion, logged areas) may not appear on older maps."],proTips:["The 'map to ground, ground to map' habit: look at your map, visualize what you expect to see, look up and verify. Constantly correlate what you see with what the map shows.","US topo maps are available free from the USGS National Map (apps.nationalmap.gov). Download and print or cache them in a mapping app before you need them."],relatedGuides:["nav-002","nav-003","nav-004"],source:"US Army FM 3-25.26 (Map Reading) / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You have a topographic map and need to understand terrain before moving through it \u2014 map literacy is the foundation of all land navigation",immediate:["Orient map to terrain using compass: rotate map until magnetic north arrow aligns with compass needle","Identify your current location by triangulating visible terrain features to map features","Read contour lines: V-shapes pointing uphill = valleys; V-shapes pointing downhill = ridges"],then:["Verify your position with the 'map to ground' habit: look at map, predict what you will see, look up and confirm","Account for magnetic declination \u2014 failure to do so causes compounding error over distance"]}},{id:"nav-002",category:"navigation",title:"Celestial Navigation \u2014 Stars and Sun",priority:"advanced",tags:["navigation","stars","sun","celestial"],summary:"Use the sun during the day and Polaris at night to determine cardinal directions without a compass.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Polaris (North Star) \u2014 Northern Hemisphere",body:"Polaris sits within 1\xb0 of true north and does not appear to move as Earth rotates. Find it: locate the Big Dipper (Ursa Major). Follow a line through the two stars forming the front edge of the dipper's cup (Dubhe and Merak) \u2014 extend this line approximately 5 times the distance between those two stars. You will reach Polaris. Alternatively: find Cassiopeia (the W/M shaped constellation). Polaris is on the opposite side of Cassiopeia from the Big Dipper, roughly centered between the two when they are on opposite sides of the North Star."},{step:2,title:"Shadow stick method \u2014 daytime",body:"Find level ground. Plant a straight stick 3 feet tall vertically. Mark the tip of the shadow with a stone. Wait 15\u201320 minutes. Mark the new shadow tip with another stone. Draw a line between the two marks. This line runs approximately east-west (first mark is west, second is east in the Northern Hemisphere). Draw a perpendicular line from the east-west line \u2014 this is north-south."},{step:3,title:"Watch method \u2014 analog watch",body:"In the Northern Hemisphere with an analog watch: hold the watch horizontal. Point the hour hand at the sun. Bisect the angle between the hour hand and 12 o'clock \u2014 this bisection points approximately south. In the Southern Hemisphere: point 12 o'clock at the sun. Bisect the angle between the hour hand and 12 \u2014 this bisection points approximately north."},{step:4,title:"Southern Cross \u2014 Southern Hemisphere",body:"The Southern Cross (Crux) is a compact cross-shaped constellation near the Milky Way. Extend the long axis of the cross (from Gacrux to Acrux) 4\u20135 times beyond the foot of the cross. This imaginary point is approximately due south. Drop a line perpendicular to the horizon from this imaginary point \u2014 that is south."}],warnings:["The watch method has error of up to 15\u201320 degrees \u2014 it gives general direction, not precision navigation.","Light pollution, cloud cover, and horizon obstructions (trees, terrain) can make celestial navigation difficult or impossible. Have backup methods."],proTips:["Orion's Belt rises due east and sets due west almost exactly everywhere on Earth \u2014 a reliable east-west reference that works in both hemispheres.","At night, your eyes need 20\u201330 minutes to fully dark-adapt. Avoid white light sources during navigation \u2014 use red light, which does not interfere with night vision."],relatedGuides:["nav-001","nav-003"],source:"US Army FM 3-25.26 (Map Reading) / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:["nav-001"],quickGlance:{situation:"You have no compass and need to determine cardinal directions using the sun or stars",immediate:["At night: find the Big Dipper, follow the front cup edge stars 5x their distance \u2014 that is Polaris (true north)","During the day: plant a vertical stick, mark shadow tip, wait 15-20 minutes, mark again \u2014 line runs east-west","Analog watch method: point hour hand at sun, bisect angle to 12 o'clock \u2014 that line points south"],then:["Orion's Belt rises due east and sets due west \u2014 reliable east-west reference in both hemispheres","Allow 20-30 minutes for eyes to fully dark-adapt before celestial navigation at night"]}},{id:"nav-003",category:"navigation",title:"Dead Reckoning",priority:"advanced",tags:["navigation","dead reckoning","pace count"],summary:"Track your position by calculating distance traveled and direction moved when landmarks are unavailable.",steps:[{step:1,title:"The concept",body:"Dead reckoning: starting from a known position, track your direction of travel and distance covered to calculate your current position. Formula: new position = last known position + (direction \xd7 distance). The technique's accuracy degrades over time as small errors accumulate \u2014 it works best over short distances and in combination with occasional landmark verification."},{step:2,title:"Establish your pace count",body:"A pace count is your personal calibration for distance: count paces (every time your left foot hits the ground) over a known 100-meter distance. Most people require 65\u201375 paces per 100 meters on flat terrain. Uphill, steep terrain, and heavy loads increase pace count. Water and thick vegetation also affect pace count. Calibrate your own personal count on known terrain before relying on it."},{step:3,title:"Track direction",body:"Use a compass to take and hold a bearing. Identify a distant landmark in your direction of travel. Move to that landmark. Take another bearing. Identify another landmark. This technique (terrain association) is more accurate than staring at the compass while walking. Rotate between taking bearings and moving \u2014 do not walk and compass simultaneously."},{step:4,title:"Log your movement",body:"For serious navigation: maintain a navigation log. Starting position (grid coordinates or described position). Direction (compass bearing). Distance (pace count). Repeat for each leg. After multiple legs, plot your dead reckoning position on the map. Compare to any visible landmarks to correct accumulated error."}],warnings:["Dead reckoning errors compound \u2014 a 5\xb0 bearing error over 1 kilometer produces an 87-meter positional error. Over 5 kilometers, that becomes a 436-meter error. Verify against terrain features frequently.","In featureless terrain (dense forest, desert, open plains), dead reckoning with no landmarks is the only option \u2014 accept that positional confidence degrades with distance."],proTips:["A ranger bead (pace count bead) tool makes tracking paces simple \u2014 move one bead per 100 meters, one large bead per kilometer. Make one from paracord and 13 beads.","When moving in a team, designate one person as the navigator (focused on direction and pace count). Do not split attention between navigation and environment scanning."],relatedGuides:["nav-001","nav-004"],source:"US Army FM 3-25.26 (Map Reading) / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:["nav-001"],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to navigate to a destination in terrain with limited visible landmarks \u2014 dead reckoning tracks your position by direction and distance from a known start",immediate:["Establish your personal pace count: count left-foot strikes over 100 measured meters (typically 65-75 paces)","Take a compass bearing to your destination; identify a distant landmark on that bearing to walk toward","Log each leg: starting position + bearing + pace count distance before moving"],then:["Verify against visible terrain features every 500 meters \u2014 dead reckoning errors compound over distance","Aim for a line feature (road, river) rather than a point \u2014 eliminates overshoot/undershoot ambiguity"]}},{id:"nav-004",category:"navigation",title:"Land Navigation With Compass Only",priority:"critical",tags:["navigation","compass","bearing","land navigation"],summary:"Navigate confidently to a destination using only a compass when GPS and maps are unavailable.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Parts of a compass",body:"Needle: always points to magnetic north (red end). Bezel/Rotating dial: graduated 0\u2013360 degrees. Direction of travel arrow: points in the direction you are moving. Orienting lines (the box): align with the needle. Baseplate: straight edges for map work. To set a bearing: rotate the bezel to your desired degree. To follow a bearing: rotate your body until the north needle sits inside the orienting box ('put red in the shed'). Walk in the direction the travel arrow points."},{step:2,title:"Taking a bearing to a landmark",body:"Point the direction of travel arrow at your target. Without moving the compass, rotate the bezel until the orienting lines align with magnetic north (needle inside the orienting box). Read the bearing at the index line. This bearing describes the direction to your target. Write it down \u2014 if you lose sight of the target, you can navigate to it by following this bearing."},{step:3,title:"Back bearing",body:"A back bearing is the opposite direction from your bearing. Calculate: if your bearing is 180\xb0 or more, subtract 180. If your bearing is less than 180\xb0, add 180. Use: you have traveled a known bearing and need to return to your start. Set the back bearing and follow it. Also used for triangulation: take a bearing to two landmarks, calculate the back bearing, draw back-bearing lines on your map \u2014 your position is at the intersection."},{step:4,title:"Box around an obstacle",body:"When an obstacle blocks your path: turn 90\xb0 from your bearing (either direction). Count your paces. Turn back to your original bearing. Move past the obstacle. Turn 90\xb0 in the opposite direction of your first turn. Count the same number of paces. Resume your original bearing. You have now navigated around the obstacle without losing your line of travel."}],warnings:["Metal objects (firearms, vehicles, cell phones) affect compass accuracy. Hold the compass 12+ inches away from metal when taking a reading.","Power lines and underground utilities can create localized magnetic anomalies. Be aware of erratic compass behavior in these areas."],proTips:["The best navigators are rarely looking at their compass \u2014 they take bearings, pick distant aiming points in their direction of travel, and walk to those points. This is faster, more accurate, and leaves your eyes free to read terrain.","A military lensatic compass is far more durable and accurate than a typical baseplate compass. It also allows taking bearings while moving. Worth the investment for a serious kit."],relatedGuides:["nav-001","nav-003"],source:"US Army FM 3-25.26 (Map Reading) / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:["nav-001"],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to navigate to a specific destination using only a compass \u2014 GPS is unavailable",immediate:["Set bearing on compass: rotate bezel to desired degree","Rotate your body until the north needle sits inside the orienting box ('red in the shed')","Pick a distant landmark in the direction-of-travel arrow direction \u2014 walk to it, then re-shoot"],then:["To box around an obstacle: turn 90 degrees, count paces, turn back to original bearing, pass obstacle, turn 90 degrees opposite, count same paces","Hold compass 12+ inches from metal objects when taking a reading"]}}]},575,[]);
__d(function(e,r,i,a,t,s,n){t.exports=[{id:"comms-001",category:"comms",title:"Signal Mirror",priority:"critical",tags:["comms","signal","mirror","rescue"],summary:"Use a signal mirror to attract aircraft and search parties from up to 10+ miles away.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Why signal mirrors work",body:"A mirror flash is one of the most visible rescue signals available to a survivor. Under good conditions, a mirror flash can be seen by an observer 10\u201315 miles away and by aircraft at much greater distances. The reflected sunlight produces a flash of approximately 1 million candlepower \u2014 far brighter than a flare at equivalent distances and with no consumable fuel."},{step:2,title:"Aim the mirror \u2014 with a purpose-built signal mirror",body:"A military signal mirror has a reflective grid/hole in the center. Hold the mirror close to your eye with the reflective side facing the sun. Look through the aiming hole at your target (aircraft, ship, person). A bright spot of reflected light will appear on surfaces near your target. Tilt and adjust the mirror until the bright spot from the hole is aimed at your target. When aligned, you are signaling the target."},{step:3,title:"Aim the mirror \u2014 improvised",body:"Any reflective surface can work: phone screen, CD, metal pot lid, polished tin. Hold the reflective surface angled toward the sun. Extend your other hand at arm's length in front of you with two fingers forming a V (or create a small target area with your fingers). Position your hand so the target (aircraft, observer) appears between your fingers. Tilt the mirror until sunlight reflected from the mirror passes through your finger-V toward the target."},{step:4,title:"Signal pattern",body:"Three flashes: the international distress signal (three of anything \u2014 three shots, three whistle blasts, three flashes). Alternate between signaling in the target direction and resting. If you can see an aircraft but cannot get the signal on it, continue attempting \u2014 aircraft often alter course to investigate unexplained flashes. Signal toward aircraft regardless of whether they appear to be searching for you."}],warnings:["Do not use a signal mirror toward vehicles on the road at night \u2014 a mirror flash can temporarily blind a driver. On roads, signal upward toward the sky.","Signal mirrors are most effective with direct sunlight. Overcast skies significantly reduce range, though high overcast still allows limited signaling."],proTips:["A glass signal mirror is more reflective and effective than polished metal. The military issue glass signal mirror (MIL-S-18281) costs under $10 and should be in every survival kit.","Signal from the highest available terrain \u2014 elevation dramatically increases how far your signal can be seen and removes terrain obstructions."],relatedGuides:["comms-002","comms-003","comms-004"],source:"FCC Emergency Communications Guidelines / ARRL Emergency Manual",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to signal rescuers at long range \u2014 a mirror flash is visible 10-15 miles on a clear day and far brighter than a flare",immediate:["Get to the highest available terrain \u2014 elevation dramatically increases signal range","Aim mirror toward aircraft: hold reflective surface toward sun, use finger-V at arm's length to frame target, tilt mirror until flash passes through your fingers toward target","Flash three times (international distress signal), pause, repeat every few minutes"],then:["Signal toward any aircraft regardless of whether it appears to be searching for you","Any reflective surface works if no purpose-built mirror: phone screen, CD, polished tin, pot lid"]}},{id:"comms-002",category:"comms",title:"Emergency Radio \u2014 NOAA and HAM Basics",priority:"critical",tags:["comms","radio","NOAA","HAM","emergency"],summary:"Use emergency radios to receive weather alerts and broadcast distress in a grid-down scenario.",steps:[{step:1,title:"NOAA Weather Radio",body:"NOAA Weather Radio All Hazards (NWR) broadcasts 24/7 on seven frequencies between 162.400 MHz and 162.550 MHz. These broadcasts include weather forecasts, warnings, watches, and emergency alerts for all hazard types. A dedicated NOAA weather radio receiver is the most reliable way to receive official emergency information. Many solar/crank emergency radios include NOAA band. During a grid-down scenario, NOAA broadcasts continue as long as transmitter infrastructure is intact."},{step:2,title:"FRS/GMRS radios",body:"Family Radio Service (FRS) handhelds are the standard consumer walkie-talkie. Channels 1\u20137 (shared FRS/GMRS), maximum 2 watts, line-of-sight range typically 0.5\u20132 miles in real-world terrain. Channel 1 (462.5625 MHz) is the most commonly monitored emergency channel in the US among general public. For group communication within a retreat or neighborhood, FRS provides simple, license-free communication. Channel 22A is reserved for emergency use."},{step:3,title:"HAM radio \u2014 the long-range option",body:"Amateur (HAM) radio operators can communicate globally when all other infrastructure fails. In an emergency scenario, HAM operators often form nets (organized groups monitoring specific frequencies). Key frequencies: 146.520 MHz (national simplex calling frequency for 2m band \u2014 nationwide). 52.525 MHz (6m simplex calling). 7.200\u20137.300 MHz (40m voice, day/regional) and 14.225 MHz (20m voice, day/national). Receiving HAM broadcasts requires only a radio receiver \u2014 no license. Transmitting legally requires a license, though in a genuine life-threatening emergency, the FCC permits unlicensed transmission on any frequency."},{step:4,title:"Emergency broadcast protocol",body:"To broadcast distress on any radio: press and hold the push-to-talk button. State: MAYDAY MAYDAY MAYDAY (or PAN PAN for urgent non-life-threatening). Your name. Your position (GPS coordinates if available, described position if not). Nature of emergency. Number of people. Any special needs (medical, mobility). Release the button and listen. Repeat every few minutes. Channel 16 on marine VHF is the international distress channel, monitored by the Coast Guard."}],warnings:["Battery management is critical for emergency radios. At transmission, most radios draw 10\u201330\xd7 more power than in receive mode. Receive mode first, transmit mode only when necessary.","HAM radio requires a license to transmit under normal circumstances. Obtain a Technician class license (easiest \u2014 35-question multiple choice) before you need the capability."],proTips:["The Baofeng UV-5R is a sub-$30 dual-band HAM radio popular in preparedness communities. It can also receive NOAA, FRS/GMRS frequencies. Get one before you need one \u2014 and get your HAM license.","Keep a list of pre-programmed frequencies: local repeaters, NOAA, FEMA/RACES frequencies for your county. Most radios require manual programming or a cable/software connection to pre-program."],relatedGuides:["comms-001","comms-003"],source:"FCC Emergency Communications Guidelines / ARRL Emergency Manual",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"The power grid is down and you need to receive emergency information and maintain communication capability",immediate:["Tune to NOAA Weather Radio: 162.400-162.550 MHz for 24/7 official emergency broadcasts","Monitor FRS Channel 1 (462.5625 MHz) and Channel 22A for local emergency communications","Set HAM radio to 146.520 MHz \u2014 the national simplex calling frequency monitored by HAM operators nationwide"],then:["Conserve battery: receive mode draws far less power than transmit \u2014 listen first, transmit only when necessary","If transmitting distress: MAYDAY x3, your name, position, nature of emergency, number of people, any special needs"]}},{id:"comms-003",category:"comms",title:"Signal Fire Construction",priority:"critical",tags:["comms","signal","fire","rescue"],summary:"Build signal fires that produce maximum visible smoke for aerial rescue in daylight.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Site selection",body:"Choose the highest available ground \u2014 ridgelines, hill summits, cliff edges visible from the air. Clear the area of flammable material around your signal fire site. Clear land is visible from aircraft; smoke rising from forested areas often cannot be distinguished from ground level. If in forest, choose the largest clearing, lake shore, or open meadow available."},{step:2,title:"Build a three-fire triangle",body:"Three fires in a triangle pattern (equilateral, each fire 25\u201350 meters apart) is the international distress signal visible from aircraft. Prepare all three fires simultaneously so you can light all three quickly when an aircraft is heard. Each fire should be large enough to generate significant smoke independently."},{step:3,title:"Smoke color",body:"Daytime visibility: colored smoke \u2014 white, black, or colored \u2014 is more visible than clear fire. White smoke: add green leaves, grass, or moss to a well-established fire. Works well in dark terrain (forests, dark rock). Black smoke: rubber, petroleum products (tire, oil), plastics. Works well in snow, desert, or light terrain. Prioritize the color that contrasts with the background terrain."},{step:4,title:"Maintenance",body:"A signal fire is only effective when burning. Prepare fuel in advance so the fire can be maintained indefinitely. Assign a person to the signal fire if possible \u2014 an unmanaged fire dies within 30\u201360 minutes. Pre-position smoke-producing materials (green leaves, rubber) so they can be added quickly when an aircraft approaches."}],warnings:["A signal fire that spreads and becomes a wildfire will prevent rescue and endanger your group. Maintain a cleared firebreak of 10+ feet around the signal area.","Signal fires communicate distress \u2014 lighting one without genuine need consumes emergency resources and may be illegal. Reserve for actual emergencies."],proTips:["Automotive tires produce massive volumes of dense black smoke visible for dozens of miles. If you have access to a disabled vehicle in an emergency, a burning tire is one of the most effective aerial signals available.","Pre-build your signal fire and pre-stage smoke materials but do not light until an aircraft is present. A fire that burns for hours unobserved depletes fuel and alerts no one."],relatedGuides:["comms-001","comms-004"],source:"FCC Emergency Communications Guidelines / ARRL Emergency Manual",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need aerial rescue and have resources to build signal fires \u2014 a three-fire triangle is the international distress signal visible from aircraft",immediate:["Select highest available ground \u2014 ridgeline, summit, or large clearing visible from the air","Build three fires in an equilateral triangle pattern, 25-50 meters apart \u2014 prepare all three simultaneously","For maximum smoke visibility: add green leaves/grass for white smoke on dark terrain; rubber/petroleum for black smoke on light terrain"],then:["Pre-build fires and stage smoke materials but do not light until an aircraft is seen or heard","Assign a person to maintain signal fire \u2014 unmanaged fire dies within 30-60 minutes"]}},{id:"comms-004",category:"comms",title:"Whistle Codes and Ground-to-Air Signals",priority:"advanced",tags:["comms","whistle","signals","rescue"],summary:"Use auditory signals and ground markers to communicate with rescuers.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Whistle distress signal",body:"Three whistle blasts: the international distress signal. Blow three times, pause, listen. Repeat every 5 minutes. A quality emergency whistle (Fox 40, Acme Thunderer, military pealess) carries to 1 mile or more. It requires no fuel, works when wet, and can be heard when a person is too weak to shout. Every survival kit should include a pealess whistle \u2014 pea whistles fail when the pea freezes or gets wet."},{step:2,title:"Ground-to-air signal symbols",body:"Lay large symbols on the ground visible from aircraft. Use rocks, logs, clothing, or any high-contrast material. Minimum size: 3 meters long, letters/symbols spaced 3+ meters apart. Standard symbols: X = need medical assistance; V = need help; \u2192 = traveling in this direction; F = need food and water; LL = all is well; N = no; Y = yes. Make symbols as large as possible and use maximum contrast with the background."},{step:3,title:"Attract attention \u2014 any means",body:"Aircraft respond to anything unusual on the ground. Tramped-out patterns in snow or sand, bright colors spread on the ground, movement (waving clothing), or repeated flashes. If you see an aircraft, use all available signals simultaneously \u2014 whistle, mirror, wave. An aircraft that does not alter course has likely not seen you. Continue signaling."},{step:4,title:"Mirror signaling and pyrotechnics",body:"A signal mirror can be seen for 10+ miles on a clear day \u2014 far beyond any whistle. Aim reflected sunlight at an aircraft by looking through the sighting hole (military mirror) or holding the mirror at eye level and tilting toward the sun until you see the flash. Practice this skill before you need it.\n\nPyrotechnics: if you have flares, use them only when you see or hear a rescue asset \u2014 a flare burns for 15\u201360 seconds and should not be wasted. Day/night flares differ: smoke is more visible by day, flame by night. Orange smoke is the universal aircraft-to-ground distress color.\n\nCell phone screens flashed in a pattern can also attract night searches. Three short, three long, three short (SOS in light) is visible hundreds of yards away in darkness."}],warnings:["Do not fire weapons as a signal if there is any possibility that rescuers might misinterpret shots. In some scenarios, gunfire may cause rescuers to avoid an area.","A pea whistle is inadequate for emergency use. Test any whistle you rely on \u2014 blow it when wet and in cold temperatures. Pealess whistles function reliably in all conditions."],proTips:["The Fox 40 Classic pealess whistle produces 115 decibels and is used by lifeguards and military worldwide. At $5, there is no reason not to carry one.","In snow: stamping out a large X takes 5\u201310 minutes and can be seen by aircraft from thousands of feet. Fill the X with dark material (pine boughs, clothing) for maximum contrast with snow."],relatedGuides:["comms-001","comms-003"],source:"FCC Emergency Communications Guidelines / ARRL Emergency Manual",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to signal rescuers using sound or ground markers \u2014 you may be too weak to do more, or rescuers may be at short range",immediate:["Three whistle blasts = international distress. Pause. Repeat every 5 minutes","Lay ground-to-air symbols at least 3 meters long in high-contrast material: X = medical needed, V = need help, arrow = direction of travel","Use all available signals simultaneously when you see or hear aircraft: whistle + mirror + wave clothing"],then:["A pealess whistle carries 1 mile+ and works when wet \u2014 Fox 40 or equivalent","In snow: stomp out a large X and fill with dark material (pine boughs) for maximum aerial contrast"]}}]},576,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,a,o,n,r){o.exports=[{id:"sec-001",category:"security",title:"Situational Awareness Fundamentals",priority:"critical",tags:["security","situational awareness","safety"],summary:"Develop and maintain the environmental awareness that prevents threats before they materialize.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Cooper's Color Codes",body:"Condition White: unaware and unprepared \u2014 the condition of sleep, distraction, and complacency. Do not operate in White in any environment with risk. Condition Yellow: relaxed alertness \u2014 general awareness, no specific threat identified. This is the sustainable baseline for daily operation. Condition Orange: specific alert \u2014 something specific has triggered concern. Attention is focused, plan is forming. Condition Red: action \u2014 the threat is real and you are responding. Pre-determined responses execute without hesitation."},{step:2,title:"Baseline and anomaly detection",body:"Every environment has a baseline \u2014 the normal pattern of behavior, sound, activity, and people for that time and place. Threats appear as anomalies: something that does not fit the baseline. Practice: when you enter any space, establish the baseline in the first 30 seconds. Identify exits. Identify cover positions. Note any persons whose behavior does not fit. This is not paranoia \u2014 it is preparation."},{step:3,title:"Scanning technique",body:"The eye naturally focuses on movement and contrast. Train peripheral awareness \u2014 consciously expand your field of view rather than tunnel-focusing on a central point. Scan in arcs, near to far. In a crowd, look for behavioral indicators: nervous energy, incongruent clothing for the environment, hands (what are they holding), eyes (where is attention directed), posture (weight shifted ready to move). Clusters of people avoid areas for a reason \u2014 note where people are not."},{step:4,title:"Pre-event indicators",body:"Before violence, there are almost always pre-event indicators. Target glancing: a person repeatedly looks at the same person or location. Target interviewing: the threat approaches victims to assess vulnerability, asking innocuous questions to determine if you are alert, armed, or compliant. Pre-attack posturing: blading the body (turning sideways), target glance, hand movement toward concealment area, weight shift. Recognizing these indicators allows response before the attack initiates."}],warnings:["Situational awareness is not paranoia. Operating in Yellow is sustainable and not psychologically damaging. Healthy awareness and pathological hypervigilance are different \u2014 hypervigilance sees threats everywhere; awareness identifies actual anomalies.","Cell phone use drops most people to Condition White instantly. In any elevated-risk environment, phone use must be deliberate and brief."],proTips:["The 'What if' habit: in any environment, briefly ask 'What would I do if X happened right now?' Establish basic response plans before you need them. This is mental pre-loading, not paranoia.","Position: whenever possible, sit or stand with your back to a wall, facing the primary entrance. This position provides maximum visual coverage, eliminates the threat approaching from behind, and gives you maximum reaction time."],relatedGuides:["sec-002","sec-003"],source:"US Army FM 3-21.75 / Civilian preparedness best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are in an environment with elevated threat potential \u2014 situational awareness is the primary tool that allows you to avoid, detect, and respond to threats",immediate:["Enter Condition Yellow \u2014 relaxed alertness \u2014 as your baseline in any non-secure environment","Establish the baseline within 30 seconds of entering any space: exits, cover positions, behavioral anomalies","Identify pre-event indicators: target glancing, target interviewing, bladed body posture, hand movement to concealment"],then:["Position with your back to a wall facing the primary entrance whenever possible","Apply the 'What if' habit: pre-load responses to likely events before they happen"]}},{id:"sec-002",category:"security",title:"Perimeter Security Basics",priority:"advanced",tags:["security","perimeter","camp security"],summary:"Establish basic early-warning perimeter systems for a camp or retreat location.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Layered perimeter concept",body:"Effective perimeter security uses layers: Outer layer \u2014 detection at maximum range. Middle layer \u2014 channelization (force movement into areas you control) and delay. Inner layer \u2014 defense and immediate response. Threat is detected at the outer layer, slowed at the middle, and confronted at the inner. No single layer is sufficient \u2014 layers provide time for response and prevent a direct breach reaching your position."},{step:2,title:"Detection systems \u2014 trip wire and sound",body:"A simple perimeter alert: suspend fishing line or monofilament at ankle height between trees around your perimeter. Attach cans with rocks or pebbles inside to the line. Movement against the line rattles the cans. This is a noise-only early warning system \u2014 it tells you something crossed the line, not what or where. It requires a person awake and listening. Space alerts 10\u201315 meters apart at key approach routes."},{step:3,title:"Light discipline",body:"Light visible from outside your position reveals: that your position is occupied; approximately how many people are present; where sleeping/cooking areas are. In any security situation, maintain light discipline after dark. Use minimal light sources; use blue or red light if possible (less visible at distance); shield light sources from outside view with tarps, natural terrain features, or structure. A fire should be positioned to be visible inside the perimeter but not outside it."},{step:4,title:"Watch rotation",body:"Continuous manning of a perimeter is required at night and in elevated-threat conditions. Establish a watch rotation that allows minimum 4-hour sleep blocks. Two-person watches are preferable \u2014 one person watching, one resting at the post. Wake-up and handoff protocol: the incoming watch must be fully awake before the outgoing watch leaves the post. A single moment of no watch coverage is a vulnerability."}],warnings:["Any security system that relies on a single point of detection or a single alert method is insufficient. Redundancy in detection is fundamental.","Dogs are among the most effective early-warning systems available \u2014 they detect approach far earlier than human senses and reliably alert. In a grid-down scenario, a trained dog with guarding instinct is a significant security asset."],proTips:["Natural barriers (thorny vegetation, water obstacles, steep terrain) are the best perimeter elements \u2014 they require no maintenance, no watches, and no supplies. Site your position to take advantage of natural defensive terrain.","Establish rally points \u2014 pre-determined positions where members of your group assemble if separated from the camp. Every person in the group must know the primary and alternate rally points and the signal to move to them."],relatedGuides:["sec-001","sec-003"],source:"US Army FM 3-21.75 / Civilian preparedness best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You have established a camp or retreat location and need early warning of approach \u2014 perimeter security buys you reaction time",immediate:["Establish layered perimeter: outer detection, middle channelization, inner defense","Suspend fishing line at ankle height around key approach routes with cans containing pebbles","Implement light discipline \u2014 extinguish or shield all light visible from outside the perimeter"],then:["Establish watch rotation: minimum 4-hour sleep blocks, two-person watches preferred","Designate primary and alternate rally points known to every group member before dark"]}},{id:"sec-003",category:"security",title:"Bug-Out Planning",priority:"critical",tags:["security","bug out","evacuation","SHTF"],summary:"Develop a multi-scenario bug-out plan that enables rapid departure before conditions deteriorate.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Bug-in vs bug-out decision",body:"Bug-in (shelter in place) is almost always preferable to bugging out unless: your location will become dangerous to remain (wildfire, flood, civil unrest reaching your area); resources will run out faster than the crisis will resolve; forced evacuation is ordered. Bugging out is high risk \u2014 you become a refugee with limited resources, exposed to weather, road conditions, and other mobile populations. Bug-out only when staying will result in worse outcomes than leaving."},{step:2,title:"Destination first",body:"A bug-out plan requires a destination \u2014 a specific location where you intend to shelter and resupply. This should be: pre-scouted and known to you personally; accessible by multiple routes; capable of supporting your group's needs; stocked or stockable. A destination that is 'general direction of family' or 'somewhere safer' is not a plan. Establish primary and alternate destinations."},{step:3,title:"Multiple routes",body:"Map at least three routes to your destination \u2014 primary (fastest under normal conditions), alternate A (avoids highways, uses secondary roads), alternate B (foot-capable, usable if vehicles are impossible). For each route: know the chokepoints (bridges, passes, tunnels that could be blocked or dangerous). Know the water sources along the route. Know the distances and realistic travel times on foot."},{step:4,title:"72-hour bag minimum standard",body:"Your bug-out bag should sustain you for 72 hours minimum without resupply: water (1 liter plus filtration capability), food (3 days of calorie-dense foods \u2014 2,000+ cal/day), shelter (emergency bivy or light tent, sleeping bag appropriate for the season), fire (3 methods), navigation (map and compass for your region), medical (IFAK level, not just bandaids), communications (battery radio), power (charged battery bank, solar panel)."}],warnings:["A bug-out under panic, without a plan, with an over-loaded bag, by people who have not trained is one of the highest-risk scenarios a family can be in. The bag is meaningless without the plan. The plan is meaningless without the training.","Inform at least one trusted person outside your household of your bug-out destination and expected timeline. If you do not arrive, someone needs to know where to look."],proTips:["The biggest bug-out mistake is waiting too long. The window for safe evacuation often closes well before the emergency is obvious. Have a trigger list: specific, observable conditions that activate your bug-out plan. Do not negotiate with your trigger list in the moment.","A vehicle bug-out vs. foot bug-out have radically different gear requirements. Plan for both, and know at what point vehicle use becomes impossible (road gridlock, fuel unavailability, impassable terrain)."],relatedGuides:["sec-001","tools-002"],source:"US Army FM 3-21.75 / Civilian preparedness best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"advanced_kit",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Conditions at your current location are becoming untenable \u2014 you need to execute a planned evacuation before the window closes",immediate:["Activate your trigger list \u2014 do not negotiate with your predetermined departure criteria","Grab your 72-hour bag and confirm it has: water+filter, food 2000+ cal/day, shelter, 3 fire methods, navigation, medical, comms","Move via your primary route \u2014 have alternate A and alternate B routes pre-planned for different scenarios"],then:["Do not announce your destination to more people than necessary","Inform one trusted person outside your household of your destination and expected timeline"]}},{id:"security-004",category:"security",title:"Rally Points and Lost Person Protocol",priority:"critical",tags:["security","rally point","lost person","communication","group"],summary:"Pre-establish rally points and lost-person protocols before any operation so that separation does not become catastrophe.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Designate rally points before departure",body:"A rally point (RP) is a pre-designated location where group members regroup if separated. Establish at least two before any movement: an Immediate Rally Point (IRP) \u2014 a prominent landmark within sight of the route, usable if separation happens within the first mile; and a Distant Rally Point (DRP) \u2014 a well-known, unambiguous location (your campsite, a road intersection, a bridge) to be used if the IRP is compromised or you cannot reach it. Everyone in the group must know both locations, their grid coordinates or compass bearing, and the time window for waiting: typically 30 minutes at the IRP, 4\u20136 hours at the DRP."},{step:2,title:"Establish lost-person communication plan",body:"Before separating from a group, agree on: (1) Radio channel and check-in schedule \u2014 e.g., channel 3, check-in every hour on the hour. (2) A code word signaling genuine distress versus routine position updates. (3) What to do if radio contact is not re-established within two check-in periods \u2014 go to IRP, then DRP, then signal. (4) Who holds the map and compass for the group, and who has the backup. Write the plan on paper. Do not rely on memory under stress."},{step:3,title:"Immediate action on separation",body:"If you realize you are separated: STOP. Stop moving. Think. Observe. Plan. Panic drives people to walk in circles. Your instinct to keep moving is usually wrong \u2014 stay put and signal. Call out verbally. Use your whistle (3 blasts). If you have a radio, call on the agreed channel. Make yourself visible at a clearing or high ground. Do not attempt to retrace your route unless you can clearly identify your back-trail \u2014 a wrong guess compounds the problem. Wait at the IRP for the agreed time, then move to the DRP."},{step:4,title:"Searching for a separated group member",body:"If someone is missing: Do not immediately scatter to search \u2014 that creates more missing persons. Designate one person as search coordinator. Send at least two people together in each search direction; no one searches alone. Establish a 'hasty search' \u2014 cover the most likely routes quickly before conducting a systematic grid search. Use sound: shout, whistle, use vehicle horns. At night, use flashlights and wait for return signals before moving toward them. Contact SAR (search and rescue) early \u2014 the first six hours are the highest-probability window for a positive outcome."}],warnings:["A rally point is useless if not everyone knows it. Brief all group members \u2014 including children \u2014 before departure, not after separation occurs.","Searching for a lost person at night without a plan creates multiple casualties. Secure your own group before committing to a hasty search in darkness."],proTips:["Use a distinctive landmark for your IRP, not just \"the big tree\" \u2014 in a forest, there are thousands. Use a creek bend, a rock formation, or a junction visible on a map.","The STOP acronym (Stop, Think, Observe, Plan) was developed by the US Forest Service for lost-hiker protocols. It is the single most effective behavior change to prevent a bad situation from becoming fatal."],relatedGuides:["sec-001","sec-003"],source:"US Army FM 3-21.75 / Civilian preparedness best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Your group has separated during a movement \u2014 separation without a pre-established protocol can turn a temporary problem into a fatal one",immediate:["If separated: STOP \u2014 Stop, Think, Observe, Plan \u2014 do not keep walking","Signal with 3 whistle blasts and listen; call out verbally; radio on agreed channel","Move to the Immediate Rally Point (IRP) and wait for the agreed time window (30 minutes)"],then:["If not reunited at IRP after 30 minutes: move to the Distant Rally Point (DRP)","Searching parties: never send solo searchers \u2014 search in pairs minimum, designate a search coordinator"]}}]},577,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,a,r,o,s){r.exports=[{id:"tools-001",category:"tools",title:"The Essential EDC and Survival Kit",priority:"critical",tags:["tools","EDC","kit","gear"],summary:"What to carry every day and what to have in a 72-hour kit \u2014 ranked by survival impact.",steps:[{step:1,title:"EDC tier \u2014 on your person always",body:"The items you carry when you have nothing else: a folding knife (minimum 3-inch blade, locking mechanism \u2014 the Benchmade Griptilian, Spyderco Paramilitary 2, or Ka-Bar Dozier are proven platforms). A lighter (Bic wins on reliability-to-cost ratio; carry two). A small flashlight (Streamlight Microstream or Fenix E12 \u2014 runs on a single AA battery). A quality whistle (Fox 40 pealess). These four items fit in any pocket and address the most common everyday emergencies."},{step:2,title:"Trauma supplement \u2014 IFAK",body:"Individual First Aid Kit for carry: tourniquet (CAT or SOFTT-W), wound packing gauze (QuikClot or Celox), pressure bandage (Israeli bandage or OLAES), chest seal pair (vented \u2014 Halo or SAM), nasopharyngeal airway (28 French with lube). This combination addresses the 'Preventable Death' injuries identified by military trauma data. Commercial IFAKs from North American Rescue or Chinook Medical are pre-assembled. Learn to use everything in your kit \u2014 the kit without training is only potential value."},{step:3,title:"72-hour kit fundamentals",body:"WATER: 1L stored plus Sawyer Squeeze filter or SteriPen UV purifier and collapsible container. FIRE: Bic lighter, ferro rod (Bayite 4-inch), waterproof matches. SHELTER: emergency bivy sack (SOL Escape Bivy \u2014 0\xb0C rated, weighs 10 oz) or Mylar emergency blanket minimum. FOOD: 3 days of calorie-dense food: mountain house freeze-dried meals, protein bars, nuts, hard candy. NAVIGATION: waterproof paper topo map of your region, Suunto A-10 compass. COMMS: Baofeng UV-5R programmed with local repeaters, NOAA frequencies. MEDICAL: IFAK plus any personal medications (90-day supply if possible). POWER: USB battery bank (20,000+ mAh), solar panel."},{step:4,title:"What not to carry",body:"The failure mode of most survival kits is weight. Prioritize tools that serve multiple functions. What to evaluate skeptically: 'survival kits' with 100+ pieces of low-quality items; credit card multi-tools (too small to be useful); wire saw (effective but heavy \u2014 a folding saw does more work); survival straws (use a full Sawyer filter instead); paracord bracelets (too little cord to matter \u2014 carry a 50-foot hank instead). Every item in your kit must earn its weight with specific, high-priority capability."}],warnings:["A knife is a cutting tool, not a weapon. The defensive value of a knife is vastly overestimated; its utility value for survival tasks is vastly underestimated. Carry it, use it constantly for tasks, and develop the skills to use it effectively.","Lithium batteries perform significantly better than alkaline in extreme cold. For any device used in cold weather, use Energizer Ultimate Lithium or equivalent lithium cells."],proTips:["The Bic lighter is the survival community's most endorsed fire-making tool because it has been tested in extreme conditions worldwide and outperforms matches, ferro rods, and piezoelectric lighters in ease of use for most people. Carry two \u2014 one in pocket, one in kit.","Skill beats gear. A person who can start a fire with a bow drill and read a topo map will survive in conditions that defeat a person with a $5,000 kit and no skills. Invest in training commensurate with your investment in gear."],relatedGuides:["tools-002","tools-003","fire-001"],source:"Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to build or audit your everyday carry and 72-hour emergency kit \u2014 gear selection determines capability in a no-resupply scenario",immediate:["EDC minimum: locking folding knife, two Bic lighters, LED flashlight (AA battery), pealess whistle","IFAK minimum: CAT tourniquet, QuikClot gauze, Israeli pressure bandage, vented chest seal pair","72-hour bag: 1L water + Sawyer filter, 2000+ cal/day food, emergency bivy, 3 fire methods, compass + topo map"],then:["Weight is your enemy: evaluate every item for multi-function use; eliminate low-value single-purpose items","Skill beats gear \u2014 a person who can start a fire and read a topo map survives where a person with a $5,000 kit and no skills does not"]}},{id:"tools-002",category:"tools",title:"Fixed-Blade Knife \u2014 Skills and Maintenance",priority:"advanced",tags:["tools","knife","blade","maintenance"],summary:"Choose, use, and maintain a fixed-blade knife \u2014 the most important field tool.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Choosing a fixed blade",body:"A survival fixed blade: 4\u20136 inch blade (long enough for batoning wood, short enough for fine work), full tang construction (blade steel extends the full length of the handle \u2014 partial tang blades can fail under stress), high-carbon or quality stainless steel (1095 carbon steel, 440C, 154CM \u2014 all proven options). Handle material that maintains grip when wet (G-10, Micarta, textured rubber). Kydex sheath with positive retention. Proven platforms: ESEE-4, KA-BAR BECKER BK2, Morakniv Companion (value option at ~$15 \u2014 legitimate survival knife)."},{step:2,title:"Field sharpening",body:"A dull knife is dangerous \u2014 it requires more force, which increases slipping risk. Field sharpening: use a whetstone (medium grit to re-establish edge, fine grit to finish), ceramic rod, or diamond sharpener. Maintain a consistent angle \u2014 15\u201320 degrees per side for most knives (lay the blade flat on the stone, then raise the spine approximately the width of your thumbnail to set the angle). Use light, consistent pressure. Work from the base of the blade to the tip in sweeping strokes. Test sharpness: the knife should shave arm hair cleanly and catch on the edge of a thumbnail with minimal pressure."},{step:3,title:"Core tasks",body:"Batoning (splitting wood): place the knife blade across the wood, strike the blade spine with a heavy stick to split the wood. Use only a full-tang blade. Feathering tinder: hold the wood with one hand, draw the blade edge toward you at a steep angle to create fine wood shavings for fire starting. Carving: more control with a short grip near the blade, power strokes with a full grip. Cutting cordage: straight cuts with the belly of the blade; sawing motion for rope."},{step:4,title:"Maintenance",body:"After field use: clean the blade of sap, blood, and debris immediately. Carbon steel will rust rapidly if left wet or dirty \u2014 apply a thin coat of oil (mineral oil, olive oil in the field) after cleaning. Store in a dry environment. Do not store a carbon steel blade in a leather sheath for extended periods \u2014 leather retains moisture and accelerates rust. Kydex is the preferred sheath material for field storage."}],warnings:["Always cut away from your body and away from others. The most common knife injury is a cutting tool slipping toward the operator. Proper technique eliminates most knife injuries.","Never use your knife as a pry bar or lever \u2014 this will snap or damage the tip and potentially the blade. A pry bar is a different tool."],proTips:["The strop is the most underutilized sharpening tool. After sharpening on a stone, 10\u201315 light strokes per side on a leather strop (or even cardboard) removes the micro-burr from the edge and produces a razor finish without more stone work.","Learn to sharpen freehand without a jig. A sharpening jig is a crutch that requires equipment \u2014 freehand sharpening skill with any available abrasive is the real survival skill."],relatedGuides:["tools-001","tools-003"],source:"Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to select, use, and maintain a fixed-blade knife as your primary field tool",immediate:["Selection: 4-6 inch blade, full tang, high-carbon or quality stainless steel, Kydex sheath","Field sharpening: maintain 15-20 degrees per side \u2014 raise spine approximately one thumbnail width off the stone","Core tasks: batoning (split wood by striking blade spine with heavy stick \u2014 full tang only), feathering tinder, cutting cordage"],then:["After field use: clean blade of sap, blood, and debris; apply thin oil coat to carbon steel \u2014 it rusts rapidly if left wet","Do not store carbon steel blade in leather sheath long-term \u2014 leather retains moisture and causes rust"]}},{id:"tools-003",category:"tools",title:"Improvised Tools and Repairs",priority:"advanced",tags:["tools","improvised","repair","field craft"],summary:"Fabricate and repair essential tools from available materials when purpose-built tools are unavailable.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Paracord applications",body:"550 paracord (7-strand, 550 lb tensile minimum) is the most versatile field cordage. Applications: shelters (ridgeline, tarp tie-outs), snares and traps, tourniquet improvisation (3-strand flat braid minimum \u2014 still far inferior to commercial), gear lashing, equipment repair, fishing line (inner strands), fire-starting (inner strands for bow-drill cord). Carry a minimum 50-foot hank in your kit. Learn basic knots: bowline (non-slip loop), clove hitch (post attachment), taut-line hitch (adjustable tension), sheet bend (joining two ropes)."},{step:2,title:"Stone knapping \u2014 improvised blades",body:"Knapping produces sharp edges from flint, obsidian, chert, or any silicate rock with conchoidal fracture. It is a genuine skill that requires practice. Basic flake production: identify a suitable rock with sharp edges where previous flakes have broken off naturally. Strike with a hammerstone at the edge, angling down toward the face you want to remove. A proper flake strike produces a sharp-edged flake that can cut effectively. Do not attempt fine knapping without practice \u2014 begin with producing functional flakes for cutting, not finished tools."},{step:3,title:"Gear repair \u2014 field stitching",body:"A needle and heavy thread in your kit weighs nothing and repairs critical equipment. Field stitching for fabric gear (packs, tent poles, clothing): running stitch for basic seams, lock stitch for load-bearing seams. Waxed thread or dental floss is more durable than standard thread in field conditions. Duct tape is a rapid temporary patch for almost any surface \u2014 carry at least 10 feet wound around a water bottle or tool handle to reduce bulk."},{step:4,title:"Container improvisation",body:"Fluid containers can be improvised from: large-leaf plants formed into a cup (temporary), clay that can be fired (long-term), birch bark folded and pinned with thorns, sections of large bamboo (natural segments form waterproof chambers). Even a large plastic bag is a functional water container. For cooking: rocks heated in fire and transferred to a water-filled container (rock boiling) allow cooking without a fire-proof pot."}],warnings:["Stone knapping produces sharp microfragments that can embed in eyes and skin. Work with eye protection and brush off clothing after knapping. Never knap toward other people.","Field-improvised tools are inherently less reliable than purpose-built equipment. Increased inspection, care, and testing before reliance is required."],proTips:["The most useful skill is knowing which material properties to look for, not knowing which specific materials to use. A rope is a rope \u2014 grass, bark strips, roots, vines, and commercial paracord all serve when braided into a multi-strand cord. Recognize the principle, apply available materials.","Duct tape and paracord are the two most frequently useful field improvisation materials. Both are light, compact, and solve a disproportionate number of field problems. Never leave either out of your kit."],relatedGuides:["tools-001","tools-002","shelter-001"],source:"Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to fabricate or repair tools from available materials \u2014 paracord and duct tape solve a disproportionate number of field problems",immediate:["Paracord (550 lb, 7-strand) applications: shelter ridgelines, snares, tourniquet improvisation (inferior to commercial), gear lashing, fishing line from inner strands","Learn 4 essential knots: bowline (non-slip loop), clove hitch (post attachment), taut-line hitch (adjustable tension), sheet bend (join two ropes)","Gear repair: waxed thread or dental floss stitching for fabric; duct tape for rapid temporary patches on any surface"],then:["Stone knapping for improvised blades requires practice \u2014 start with producing functional flakes for cutting, not finished tools","Containers can be improvised: birch bark folded and pinned, large tropical leaves, bamboo sections, clay fired over time"]}}]},578,[]);
__d(function(e,t,o,a,i,r,s){i.exports=[{id:"dis-001",category:"disaster",title:"Hurricane \u2014 Preparation and Survival",priority:"critical",tags:["disaster","hurricane","storm","flood","evacuation"],summary:"Survive a major hurricane through pre-storm preparation, sheltering, and post-storm actions.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Before the storm \u2014 D-72 to D-48",body:"At 72 hours out: know your evacuation zone (NHC/local emergency management publishes zone maps). If in Zone A, B, or C and a Category 3+ is forecast, evacuate. If sheltering in place: fill vehicles with fuel now \u2014 gas stations will be sold out or closed within 24 hours. Fill bathtubs with water (WaterBob bladder is better than open tub \u2014 holds 100 gallons). Withdraw cash. Charge all devices. Secure outdoor items."},{step:2,title:"Before the storm \u2014 D-24",body:"Final shelter-in-place preparation: cover windows with pre-cut plywood (5/8-inch minimum) or hurricane shutters. Do not use tape on glass \u2014 it is ineffective and dangerous. Locate your interior safe room \u2014 the smallest interior room on the lowest floor that is not a garage or below flood level. Gather emergency supplies to this room. Confirm evacuation is no longer viable or order to stay has been given."},{step:3,title:"During the storm \u2014 surge and wind",body:"Storm surge is the primary killer in hurricanes, not wind. If storm surge flooding begins, move to the highest floor. Do not attempt to drive through flood water \u2014 6 inches of moving water can knock a person down; 12 inches can carry away a vehicle. In the home during the storm: stay in your safe room. Stay away from windows. If the roof begins to fail, move to an interior bathroom and get in the tub with a mattress over you."},{step:4,title:"The eye \u2014 do not go outside",body:"The eye of a hurricane can last 20\u201340 minutes and may appear to be clear and calm. It is not the end of the storm. The eyewall \u2014 the most violent part of the hurricane \u2014 will arrive from the opposite direction minutes after the eye passes. People who go outside during the eye are sometimes killed by the returning eyewall. Stay in your safe location until official all-clear."},{step:5,title:"After the storm \u2014 the hazard phase",body:"The storm's departure begins the hazard phase: downed power lines (assume any downed line is live), flooded roads, gas leaks, structural damage (do not enter damaged structures without inspection), wildlife driven into populated areas (snakes, fire ants). Do not run generators, camp stoves, or grills indoors or in enclosed spaces \u2014 CO poisoning kills more people after hurricanes than the storm itself."}],warnings:["Carbon monoxide poisoning from generators used indoors or too close to windows is the leading cause of hurricane-related deaths after the storm passes. Place generators 20+ feet from any window or opening.","Do not attempt to ride out a Category 4 or 5 storm in a mobile home. Mobile homes are not structurally rated for hurricane winds \u2014 evacuate regardless of evacuation zone if you live in a mobile or manufactured home."],proTips:["The WaterBob (100-gallon tub bladder, ~$30) stores significantly more water than an open tub with less contamination risk. It can provide 2 weeks of water for a family of four.","Post-hurricane: document all damage with photos before any cleanup or repairs \u2014 required for insurance claims. Do not sign contracts with repair companies that appear unsolicited \u2014 disaster fraud is extremely common after major storms."],relatedGuides:["dis-002","water-001"],source:"FEMA IS-100 / FEMA Ready.gov Guidelines",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"A hurricane is forecast to make landfall in your area within 72 hours \u2014 preparation decisions made now will determine outcomes",immediate:["Check evacuation zone \u2014 if Zone A/B/C with Cat 3+ forecast: evacuate NOW","Fill vehicle with fuel, fill bathtubs with water, withdraw cash, charge all devices","Secure all outdoor items; board windows with 5/8-inch plywood \u2014 tape on glass is useless"],then:["Identify interior safe room: smallest interior room on lowest non-flood floor","Do NOT go outside during the eye \u2014 the eyewall returns from the opposite direction within minutes"]}},{id:"dis-002",category:"disaster",title:"Tornado \u2014 Recognition and Response",priority:"critical",tags:["disaster","tornado","shelter","warning"],summary:"React correctly in the seconds available when a tornado threatens your location.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Warning vs Watch",body:"Tornado Watch: conditions are favorable for tornado development in the watch area. Be aware and prepared to act. Tornado Warning: a tornado has been confirmed by radar or spotters and is in or approaching the warned area. This is action time \u2014 move to shelter immediately. Do not wait to see the tornado \u2014 by the time a tornado is visible, you may have seconds. Move on the warning, not on visual confirmation."},{step:2,title:"Best shelter in a house",body:"Best: an underground storm shelter or FEMA-rated safe room. Second best: the lowest floor, most interior room, away from windows \u2014 a bathroom with interior walls provides some structural protection (plumbing pipes add rigidity) and the bathtub offers some protection from falling debris. Cover yourself with heavy blankets, a mattress, or a bicycle helmet. Get under something sturdy."},{step:3,title:"No safe shelter available \u2014 outdoors",body:"If in a vehicle: do not shelter under a highway overpass \u2014 the overpass funnels and accelerates wind, killing people who shelter there. If the tornado is at a distance and you have time: drive at 90 degrees to the tornado's path. If the tornado is imminent: abandon the vehicle and lie flat in a ditch or depression lower than the road with hands over your head. A vehicle will be rolled, flipped, and destroyed in an EF3+ tornado \u2014 there is no safe shelter in a vehicle from a major tornado."},{step:4,title:"After the tornado",body:"Structural assessment: do not enter buildings that have obvious damage to load-bearing walls or roof without inspection. Smell for gas leaks before entering. Check for downed power lines. In the tornado's path, roadways may be impassable \u2014 call for help before attempting to travel. Account for all household members. First responders will be overwhelmed \u2014 minor injuries should be self-treated if possible."}],warnings:["The 'go to southwest corner of basement' advice is outdated and incorrect. The safest basement location is under the stairs or a heavy workbench, or in an interior room with the most walls between you and the exterior \u2014 not a specific compass direction.","Mobile homes offer essentially no protection from tornadoes. If a tornado warning is issued and you are in a mobile home, you must evacuate to a substantial structure immediately."],proTips:["A NOAA weather radio with Specific Area Message Encoding (SAME) will wake you if a tornado warning is issued for your county while you sleep. This is life-saving technology that costs $25\u201340. Every residence in tornado-prone areas should have one.","Tornadoes in the Southeast US frequently occur at night, in winter, and in conjunction with tropical systems \u2014 all conditions that reduce visibility and public awareness. In the Southeast, NOAA radio is especially critical."],relatedGuides:["dis-001","dis-003"],source:"FEMA IS-100 / FEMA Ready.gov Guidelines",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"A tornado WARNING has been issued for your area \u2014 a warning means a tornado is confirmed, not just possible. Act immediately.",immediate:["Move to shelter IMMEDIATELY on warning \u2014 do not wait for visual confirmation","Best shelter: underground storm shelter or FEMA safe room. Second: lowest floor, most interior room, away from windows","Cover yourself with heavy blankets, mattress, or bicycle helmet to protect from debris"],then:["Do NOT shelter under a highway overpass \u2014 it funnels and accelerates wind velocity","After tornado: check for gas leaks before entering damaged structures \u2014 smell for gas before switching anything"]}},{id:"dis-003",category:"disaster",title:"Earthquake \u2014 During and After",priority:"critical",tags:["disaster","earthquake","drop cover hold"],summary:"Survive the shaking and navigate the aftermath of a significant earthquake.",steps:[{step:1,title:"During the shaking",body:"DROP-COVER-HOLD ON: Drop to hands and knees (this protects you from being knocked down and allows you to move if necessary). Cover your head and neck with one arm while getting under a sturdy table or desk if immediately available, or position yourself against an interior wall away from windows. Hold on until the shaking stops \u2014 it can last 20\u2013120 seconds and will feel much longer. Do not run outside during shaking \u2014 most earthquake injuries are from falling and falling objects, not structural collapse."},{step:2,title:"What not to do during shaking",body:"Do not run outside \u2014 the exterior of buildings is the most dangerous area during an earthquake (falling facade, glass, structural members). Do not stand in doorways \u2014 this is a persistent myth. A doorframe in a modern building offers no more protection than any other location and puts you in a high-traffic area. Do not use elevators. Do not use matches or lighters \u2014 gas line damage may be producing flammable gas."},{step:3,title:"Immediate post-shaking actions",body:"Expect aftershocks \u2014 often strong enough to cause additional damage. Check yourself and others for injuries. If gas smell is present: do not use any electrical switches or open flame. Evacuate the building and leave the door open. Call the utility company. Shut off gas at the meter only if you smell gas and know how to do it (wrench on the meter valve \u2014 90\xb0 from inline to perpendicular). Assess structural damage before fully occupying the space."},{step:4,title:"The first 72 hours",body:"After a major earthquake, expect: disrupted utilities (power, water, gas, telecommunications) for days to weeks. Roads and bridges may be impassable. Emergency services will be overwhelmed and response times will be measured in hours. Self-sufficiency for minimum 72 hours (preferred: 14 days) is essential in earthquake-prone areas. The most critical resources: water (municipal supply may fail), medications, communications."}],warnings:["Tsunami warning: if you are in a coastal area and feel a major earthquake, move to high ground immediately without waiting for an official warning. The shaking IS the warning. Tsunamis can arrive within minutes of the quake.","Search and rescue after collapse: if trapped under debris, cover your mouth with cloth to reduce dust inhalation. Make noise by tapping on pipes or walls \u2014 sound travels through structure better than shouting."],proTips:["In the US Pacific Northwest (Cascadia Subduction Zone), a M9.0 earthquake is not a question of if but when. The expected event will generate tsunamis reaching 100+ feet in some coastal locations. If you live or work in the inundation zone, know your vertical evacuation routes.","Store water before you need it: 5-gallon water containers ($8\u201315 each) filled from the tap and stored in a cool dark location last 6\u201312 months. Rotate annually."],relatedGuides:["dis-004","water-001"],source:"FEMA IS-100 / FEMA Ready.gov Guidelines",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Shaking has started \u2014 the next 20-120 seconds will determine your immediate safety outcome",immediate:["DROP to hands and knees \u2014 prevents being knocked down and allows movement","COVER head and neck with one arm \u2014 get under a sturdy table or desk if immediately reachable","HOLD ON until shaking stops \u2014 do NOT run outside during shaking"],then:["If in coastal area: move to high ground IMMEDIATELY after shaking stops \u2014 tsunami can arrive within minutes","Expect aftershocks \u2014 check yourself and others for injury, check for gas smell before using anything electrical"]}},{id:"dis-004",category:"disaster",title:"Flood \u2014 Flash Flood and Long-Duration Flood",priority:"critical",tags:["disaster","flood","flash flood","evacuation"],summary:"Survive flash floods through early recognition and correct response to both flash and river flooding.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Flash flood recognition",body:"Flash floods can move faster than a person can run and carry vehicles, trees, and boulders. Conditions producing flash floods: heavy rain upstream (the flood arrives without rain at your location), dam or levee failure, ice jam release. Warning signs: rapid rise in water level; roaring sound from upstream; change in stream color (brown, muddy water where it was clear); debris in water. Flash floods give minutes of warning \u2014 recognize the signs and move immediately."},{step:2,title:"Correct response to flash flood",body:"Move to high ground immediately \u2014 do not stop to gather belongings. Move perpendicular to the water flow, not downstream. Six inches of moving water can knock down an adult; two feet of moving water can carry away a vehicle. If caught in moving water: do not fight the current. Float on your back with feet downstream (feet absorb impact with obstacles, face is above water). Work toward shore at an angle."},{step:3,title:"Never drive into flood water",body:"TURN AROUND, DON'T DROWN. Most flood deaths in the US occur in vehicles driven into flood water. 12 inches of water can float most passenger vehicles; 24 inches can carry away most vehicles including pickups and SUVs. You cannot judge the depth of flood water from a vehicle \u2014 the road beneath may have washed away entirely. If your vehicle is swept away and begins to sink: do not try to open the door against water pressure. As water rises inside the vehicle, wait for the interior to fill (equalizing pressure), then open the door and swim out."},{step:4,title:"Post-flood safety",body:"Flood water is contaminated: with sewage, agricultural chemicals, fuel, industrial materials, and biological hazards. Do not walk through flood water if avoidable. If you must: waterproof boots minimum, clean wounds that contact flood water immediately. Do not consume food that has contacted flood water (canned goods with intact seals can be disinfected; all other food is suspect). Flood-damaged structures require mold assessment within 24\u201348 hours of water infiltration."}],warnings:["Flooded basements: do not enter a flooded basement if the water may be in contact with electrical systems. The electrocution risk is severe.","Gas and propane tanks may become buoyant in flood water and can rupture, creating fire and explosion hazard. Do not approach free-floating gas cylinders."],proTips:["FEMA flood maps (msc.fema.gov) show historical flood zones. If your property is in a Zone A or AE, you are statistically likely to flood within your 30-year mortgage period. Know your zone before you need to know it.","Flood insurance is separate from homeowners insurance and must be purchased before a flooding event \u2014 it has a 30-day waiting period. In flood zones, it is not optional."],relatedGuides:["dis-001","dis-003"],source:"FEMA IS-100 / FEMA Ready.gov Guidelines",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Water is rising rapidly or a flash flood warning has been issued \u2014 flash floods kill faster than almost any other natural disaster",immediate:["Move to high ground IMMEDIATELY \u2014 perpendicular to water flow, not downstream","Do NOT drive into flood water \u2014 12 inches can float your car; 24 inches carries away SUVs","If caught in moving water: float on back with feet downstream \u2014 absorbs impact, keeps face above water"],then:["TURN AROUND DON'T DROWN \u2014 most US flood deaths occur in vehicles that drove into water","Flood water is contaminated with sewage and chemicals \u2014 avoid contact; clean wounds immediately if contact occurs"]}},{id:"dis-005",category:"disaster",title:"EMP \u2014 Electromagnetic Pulse Response",priority:"advanced",tags:["disaster","EMP","grid down","electronics"],summary:"Understand the real-world effects of an EMP event and the practical immediate response.",steps:[{step:1,title:"What is an EMP",body:"An electromagnetic pulse (EMP) is a burst of electromagnetic energy that can damage or destroy electronics over a wide area. Sources: nuclear EMP (HEMP \u2014 High-altitude EMP), conducted from a nuclear detonation in near space; solar EMP (Coronal Mass Ejection \u2014 CME), a large solar storm that can produce geomagnetically induced currents; non-nuclear EMP devices (NNEMP), limited range. A large HEMP or CME event could damage power grid infrastructure, vehicles with electronic control units, communications infrastructure, and consumer electronics across a continent-sized area."},{step:2,title:"What fails and what survives",body:"Most vulnerable: connected infrastructure (power grid transformers are the primary vulnerability \u2014 they take years to manufacture and replace), vehicles with electronic ignition and ECU systems, modern aircraft avionics. More survivable: older mechanical systems, diesel engines without electronic injection, simple electronics not connected to long conductors during the event, electronics stored in Faraday cage protection. Some modern vehicles may survive depending on position, shielding, and pulse characteristics \u2014 research is ongoing and outcomes are not uniform."},{step:3,title:"Immediate response \u2014 the first 72 hours",body:"If electronics fail without obvious cause and the event is widespread: assume an EMP or CME event may have occurred. Check neighbors \u2014 is the failure localized or widespread? Check vehicles. Listen to any battery-operated radio that survived. Your immediate priorities shift to the same as any grid-down scenario: water, food, shelter, medical, security. The difference from a normal power outage: restoration timelines may be measured in months to years, not hours."},{step:4,title:"Faraday cage protection",body:"Electronics can be protected from EMP by storing them in a Faraday cage \u2014 a conductive enclosure that attenuates electromagnetic fields. A properly sealed metal trash can with a tight-fitting lid functions as a basic Faraday cage. Line the interior with cardboard or foam to prevent direct contact of electronics with the metal. Items worth protecting: backup NOAA/HAM radio, battery power banks, solar charge controller, medical devices. Multi-layered protection (electronics in static bags inside a metal can) provides more certainty."}],warnings:["EMP threat assessment: genuine EMP risk is real (solar CME events have occurred historically \u2014 the 1989 Quebec event knocked out grid power to 6 million people) but is frequently over-stated in preparedness discussions. Calibrate your preparation to realistic risk assessment.","Hardened electronics: there is significant misinformation about which specific consumer devices survive EMP. Testing under realistic conditions is limited. Do not assume any modern device will survive a major HEMP event."],proTips:["The Carrington Event (1859) was a massive CME that would destroy virtually all modern electrical infrastructure if it occurred today. A 2012 CME of comparable magnitude missed Earth by 9 days. The threat is real and is within the normal range of solar activity.","A basic Faraday cage for communications gear costs under $30 (metal trash can with lid, foam liner, static bags). There is no reason not to have one if your preparedness planning includes any grid-down scenarios."],relatedGuides:["dis-006","comms-002"],source:"FEMA IS-100 / FEMA Ready.gov Guidelines",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Electronics have failed without obvious cause and the failure appears widespread \u2014 an EMP or solar CME event may have occurred",immediate:["Check scope of failure: is it localized to your home, or are neighbors also without power?","Listen to any surviving battery-operated radio for information","Assume extended outage \u2014 shift immediately to water, food, shelter, medical, and security priorities"],then:["Retrieve any electronics stored in Faraday cage protection: backup radio, power banks, solar controller","Restoration timelines for a major EMP may be months to years \u2014 plan accordingly"]}},{id:"dis-006",category:"disaster",title:"Nuclear Incident \u2014 Blast, Fallout, and Shelter-in-Place",priority:"advanced",tags:["disaster","nuclear","fallout","shelter","radiation"],summary:"Understand the actionable steps that improve survival probability following a nuclear detonation.",steps:[{step:1,title:"The survivable zone \u2014 most people are not at ground zero",body:"The majority of nuclear scenarios that produce civilian casualties are detonations in or near population centers, not direct individual targeting. If you are alive after a detonation, you are in the survivable zone \u2014 the question is whether you take the correct actions. The two primary hazards for survivors at distance are initial blast (handled by cover and distance) and fallout (radioactive particles that descend from the fireball over hours). Correct response to fallout can reduce radiation dose by 90%+ compared to remaining outside."},{step:2,title:"Initial detonation \u2014 flash and blast",body:"If you see a flash: DROP immediately, face down. Cover your face and exposed skin. Stay down until the blast wave passes (approximately 30 seconds for a blast traveling from a distant detonation). The flash travels at the speed of light \u2014 the blast wave follows at the speed of sound. Distance = survival advantage. After the blast: do not approach or look at the mushroom cloud."},{step:3,title:"Fallout timing \u2014 the 15-minute window",body:"After a detonation, you have approximately 10\u201315 minutes before significant fallout begins to descend at ground level from a detonation within 10 miles (times vary with yield and atmospheric conditions). This window must be used to reach the best available shelter. The DHS and FEMA guidance is: GET INSIDE. GET INSIDE. STAY INSIDE."},{step:4,title:"Shelter \u2014 what protects and what does not",body:"Radiation shielding by mass: concrete and earth are the most effective. A large, multi-story concrete building provides significant shielding \u2014 particularly the center of middle floors (away from exterior walls and roof). Protection factors by location: outside in the open = 1 (baseline). In a vehicle = 2. In a wood frame house = 10. In a basement = 40+. In the center of a large concrete building on middle floors = 200\u2013300. You are trying to put as much mass as possible between yourself and the fallout particles outside."},{step:5,title:"Shelter-in-place \u2014 24 to 48 hours",body:"Fallout radiation levels decrease by approximately 90% every 7 hours (the 7:10 rule \u2014 for every 7-fold increase in time, radiation decreases by a factor of 10). At 24 hours, radiation levels are approximately 1/50 of peak levels. At 48 hours, 1/500. FEMA recommends sheltering in place in your best available shelter for minimum 24\u201348 hours, then following official guidance. During shelter: seal windows and doors with plastic sheeting and tape. Turn off HVAC and ventilation. Store water in sealed containers. Move to the most interior, lower-floor rooms."}],warnings:["Potassium iodide (KI): KI protects only the thyroid from radioactive iodine (I-131). It does not provide general radiation protection. It is recommended for fallout scenarios \u2014 follow official dosing guidance. Do not take iodine antiseptic as a substitute.","Leaving shelter prematurely is the major survivable error in nuclear incident response. The pressure to check on family or property causes people to exit protective shelter too early and absorb the highest-rate fallout radiation. Resist this pressure for a minimum of 24 hours."],proTips:["The Ready.gov and FEMA nuclear incident guidance is based on decades of research and is the legitimate authoritative source. The short version: Get Inside, Stay Inside, Stay Tuned. Following this guidance will save lives in virtually any nuclear scenario short of direct ground zero impact.","The greatest predictor of civilian survival in a nuclear scenario is distance from the detonation and speed of sheltering. If you do not live near a likely target (major military installations, port facilities, large cities), your odds of surviving the immediate effects and having time to implement fallout protection are substantially higher."],relatedGuides:["dis-005","shelter-004"],source:"FEMA IS-100 / FEMA Ready.gov Guidelines",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"A nuclear detonation has occurred within your region \u2014 if you are alive after the flash, you are in the survivable zone. Your next actions determine radiation dose.",immediate:["If you see a flash: DROP face-down immediately, cover exposed skin, stay down 30 seconds for blast wave","You have 10-15 minutes before significant fallout begins \u2014 GET INSIDE a substantial building NOW","Move to the center of middle floors of the largest concrete building available \u2014 mass between you and fallout"],then:["Seal windows and doors with plastic sheeting and tape; turn off HVAC; store water in sealed containers","Shelter in place minimum 24-48 hours \u2014 radiation decreases 90% every 7 hours (the 7:10 rule)"]}},{id:"disaster-007",category:"disaster",title:"Civil Unrest and Grid-Down Social Breakdown",priority:"advanced",tags:["civil unrest","social breakdown","security","grid-down","looting","riots"],summary:"Recognize the stages of social breakdown in a grid-down event and adapt your security posture, movement, and resource management accordingly.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Recognize the breakdown timeline",body:"Civil unrest follows a predictable arc after infrastructure collapse. Hours 0\u201324: most people comply, wait, assume government restoration. Stores sell out. Hours 24\u201372: frustration rises, opportunistic crime begins, shelves bare. Panic buying turns to conflict. Day 3\u20137: organized looting, breakdown of civil authority in dense urban areas, hospital and emergency services overwhelmed. Week 2+: resource scarcity drives territorial behavior; group dynamics become survival-critical. Understanding this timeline lets you act proactively \u2014 not reactively \u2014 at each stage. Decisions made in hour 6 are far less costly than decisions made in day 4."},{step:2,title:"Low profile and information security",body:"During social breakdown, visible wealth and resources become targets. Actions: Do not display food, weapons, generators, or fuel. Cover windows with opaque materials if lights must be used at night \u2014 visible light signals habitation and resources. Do not discuss your supplies with neighbors beyond your trusted group. Move at dawn or dusk to avoid peak-activity periods. Use plain, worn clothing; avoid tactical or military gear that marks you as a high-value target or draws law-enforcement attention. Reduce vehicle movement \u2014 fuel exhaustion during an unrest scenario can strand you in a dangerous location."},{step:3,title:"Group dynamics and threat identification",body:"A lone individual is a target. A cohesive group with clear roles is significantly safer. Establish a watch rotation \u2014 no single person can maintain alertness for more than 4\u20136 hours. Define group roles: communications, security, medical, logistics. Identify who makes decisions in an emergency. Establish a code word for 'threat imminent \u2014 execute plan' that can be spoken calmly without alerting outsiders. Threat identification: most people during breakdown are desperate, not predatory. Distinguish between someone begging for food (manageable, address with minimal resource exposure) and organized groups conducting systematic looting (avoid, do not engage)."},{step:4,title:"Shelter-in-place vs. evacuation decision matrix",body:"The decision to stay or go is the most consequential you will make. Default to shelter-in-place if: your home is defensible, you have 14+ days of supplies, the threat is generalized urban unrest at a distance. Move if: direct threat to your location is imminent, authorities have issued evacuation orders for your specific area, your supply chain is compromised and resupply is impossible. If you move: move before the mass of people do \u2014 roads become impassable and dangerous at peak exodus. Have three routes planned to your destination. Carry only what you can move quickly. Leave no indication of your destination."},{step:5,title:"Communication and intelligence gathering",body:"In a grid-down civil unrest scenario, information asymmetry is a force multiplier. Maintain radio monitoring (NOAA weather radio, local emergency services if scanners are available, shortwave for regional and national updates). Establish a neighborhood intelligence network \u2014 agree with two or three trusted neighbors to share information on a scheduled basis. Use a runner (person on foot) for short-distance communication when radio silence is preferred. Do not spread unverified information \u2014 panic is contagious and false threat reports drive poor decisions. Treat information as a resource: collect it deliberately, verify when possible, distribute selectively."}],warnings:["Engaging in armed conflict against looters carries serious legal risk even during a declared emergency. Know your jurisdiction's laws regarding use of force in property defense. In most states, lethal force is not legal to defend property \u2014 only to defend life.","Hoarding a visible resource surplus while neighbors starve creates enemies. Managing community perception of your preparedness level is a security strategy, not deception."],proTips:["The \"gray man\" concept from security professionals: dress, behave, and present yourself in a way that draws zero attention. Be forgettable. Average clothing, average pace, no tactical gear in public.","Historical case studies from Sarajevo 1992\u201395 and New Orleans 2005 post-Katrina show that neighborhood-level mutual aid networks dramatically outperformed isolated individual preppers in medium-to-long duration breakdown scenarios."],relatedGuides:["sec-001","sec-002","sec-003","dis-005"],source:"FEMA IS-100 / FEMA Ready.gov Guidelines",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Civil order is breaking down following a grid-down event \u2014 opportunistic crime is increasing and resource competition is escalating",immediate:["Reduce your profile immediately: cover windows, eliminate visible light, do not display food or supplies","Establish watch rotation \u2014 no single person can stay alert more than 4-6 hours","Move at dawn/dusk to avoid peak-activity periods; wear plain clothing that draws zero attention"],then:["Default to shelter-in-place if you have 14+ days of supplies and are not in immediate threat","Distinguish desperate individuals (begging for food) from organized threat groups \u2014 responses differ significantly"]}}]},579,[]);
__d(function(e,t,a,i,o,r,n){o.exports=[{id:"vehicle-001",category:"vehicle",title:"Emergency Tire Change Without a Jack",priority:"critical",tags:["vehicle","tire","emergency","field","mechanical"],summary:"How to change a flat tire when you have no jack, using military techniques and improvised methods.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Immediate Safety \u2014 Stop and Secure the Vehicle",body:"Pull completely off the road onto the firmest, flattest surface available \u2014 gravel shoulder, dirt pullout, or paved lot. Activate hazard lights immediately. Turn your wheels away from traffic. Set rocks, logs, or any solid debris behind and in front of the tires you are NOT changing \u2014 these are your wheel chocks. If on a slope, chock uphill and downhill. Do not skip chocking: without a jack, vehicle movement during the swap is your primary danger. If you have road flares or reflective triangles, place them 200 feet back. Notify someone of your location before starting work."},{step:2,title:"Break Lug Nut Torque Before Lifting",body:"This step is critical and must happen BEFORE you lift the vehicle by any method. With the flat tire still bearing full vehicle weight on the ground, place the lug wrench on each nut and break it loose with a firm counterclockwise push. The weight of the vehicle prevents the wheel from spinning. Lug nuts on modern vehicles are torqued to 80\u2013120 ft-lbs \u2014 if the tire were elevated first, spinning would defeat every improvised lifting method. Do not fully remove nuts yet, just crack them loose one full turn each. If the wrench slips, try a piece of rubber (like a floor mat) over the nut for grip. Mark cross-pattern order mentally: top, bottom, left, right."},{step:3,title:"Rock or Curb Method \u2014 Drive the Flat Onto an Elevated Surface",body:"Find a solid rock, concrete curb, raised tree root, or stacked logs 6\u20138 inches tall and roughly 8\u201312 inches wide. Drive the flat tire slowly onto the rock so the flat tire sits on top of the elevated object \u2014 this lifts the wheel off the ground by the height of the object, creating enough clearance to remove and swap the tire. The vehicle frame remains on the ground; only the flat wheel is elevated. This is the fastest and most stable improvised lift method. On a curb, pull the flat tire up onto the curb edge at an angle. Test stability: push the vehicle side-to-side before getting under the wheel area. Position your spare ready to hand."},{step:4,title:"Dig-Under Method \u2014 Excavate Clearance in Soft Ground",body:"If no elevated surface exists but the ground is soft (dirt, sand, gravel), use a shovel, large stick, rock, or your hands to dig a bowl-shaped depression under the flat tire \u2014 not a channel. The goal is to lower the flat tire into the hole, which effectively raises the hub and axle. Dig a circle roughly 18 inches in diameter and 4\u20136 inches deep centered under the tire contact patch. Clear loose material completely. The bowl shape prevents collapse better than a trench. Once the hole is dug, roll or push the vehicle so the flat tire sits in the bowl. Test stability. This method works best on dry dirt or compact gravel \u2014 loose sand may collapse and is unsafe."},{step:5,title:"Log Lever Method \u2014 Build a Fulcrum Lift",body:"Use a long, strong hardwood branch (minimum 2 inches diameter, 6\u20138 feet long) or a salvaged 2x4/4x4 as a lever. Find or stack rocks into a fulcrum 6\u201310 inches tall, positioned about 2 feet from the vehicle's frame jack point (check owner's manual or look for the reinforced metal notch behind the front wheels and ahead of the rear wheels on the frame rail). Slide the lever under the frame jack point with the fulcrum between you and the vehicle. Assign 2\u20133 people to push the long end down while one person works the wheel. This method requires coordination and is slower \u2014 use only if rock and dig methods are unavailable. Never place any body part under the vehicle while it is being levered."},{step:6,title:"Tire Swap \u2014 Remove, Mount, and Torque",body:"Once clearance is achieved, fully remove lug nuts in the same cross-pattern order you cracked them. Keep nuts in your pocket or cupped in a hand \u2014 losing one in a ditch is a serious problem. Remove the flat and immediately mount the spare, aligning the wheel holes to the studs. Thread lug nuts by hand first \u2014 cross-pattern \u2014 until all are snug. Apply final tightening with the wrench using your body weight plus foot leverage on the wrench arm. Without a torque wrench, snug and tight is the goal: firm, even pressure on each nut. After lowering and removing improvised lift, re-torque all nuts once the full vehicle weight is on the spare. Drive under 50 mph to the nearest shop to torque to spec (typically 90\u2013100 ft-lbs) and check spare pressure."}],warnings:["Never place any part of your body under a vehicle supported only by improvised methods \u2014 keep all limbs clear at all times","Identify the proper jacking points on the frame rail before applying any lift force \u2014 lifting on rocker panels, plastic body panels, or the differential will cause serious damage","In soft or loose ground, the dig-under method risks sudden collapse \u2014 test stability aggressively before working near the wheel","A spare tire that has been stored flat or underinflated will fail quickly \u2014 check spare pressure monthly","Lug nuts that are cross-threaded can cause wheel separation at speed \u2014 always thread by hand first and confirm smooth rotation before applying wrench force"],proTips:["Military vehicle crews practice the rock/curb method during field training \u2014 it is the fastest single-person improvised lift when a suitable surface exists","Carry a small hydraulic bottle jack (2-ton, fits under a seat) \u2014 it weighs 6 lbs and eliminates this entire problem","To prevent cross-threading, hold the lug nut between thumb and forefinger, align to the stud, and rotate counterclockwise slowly until you feel it drop into thread alignment, then reverse clockwise","Keep a can of Fix-a-Flat as a backup \u2014 it buys you 50\u2013100 miles at low speed on a puncture (not a blowout) and eliminates the need for a lift entirely"],relatedGuides:["vehicle-002","vehicle-003"],source:"USAF SERE curriculum / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You have a flat tire and no jack \u2014 you need to improvise vehicle lift to swap the tire and get moving",immediate:["BEFORE any lifting: break lug nut torque while tire is still on the ground bearing full weight \u2014 this prevents wheel spinning","Rock/curb method: drive flat tire onto a solid 6-8 inch rock or curb to create clearance \u2014 fastest and most stable improvised lift","Dig-under method: excavate a bowl 18 inches diameter and 4-6 inches deep under the flat tire to lower it and lift the hub"],then:["Thread all lug nuts by hand first in cross-pattern before applying wrench force","After tire swap: drive under 50 mph to nearest shop for proper torque spec (90-100 ft-lbs)"]}},{id:"vehicle-002",category:"vehicle",title:"Jump Starting and Battery Troubleshooting",priority:"critical",tags:["vehicle","battery","jump-start","electrical","emergency"],summary:"Correct jump-start cable procedure, battery vs. alternator diagnosis, push-starting manuals, and when jumping is dangerous.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Diagnose: Battery vs. Alternator vs. Starter",body:"Before grabbing cables, determine what actually failed. Turn on interior dome light and observe brightness, then attempt to start. If the dome light is bright but the engine cranks slowly and dies: weak or discharged battery \u2014 jumpable. If dome light is dim or off with no crank: very dead battery or major drain \u2014 jumpable but investigate the drain first. If lights are bright, the starter clicks once loudly, but engine does not crank: starter solenoid or bad connection \u2014 clean terminals before jumping. If the engine starts fine but dies shortly after or the battery warning light is on while running: the alternator is not charging \u2014 jumping will not fix this; driving will kill the new charge in 20\u201340 minutes. Voltage test with a multimeter: 12.6V+ is good, 12.0V is weak, below 11.8V is dead."},{step:2,title:"Inspect the Battery Before Connecting Cables",body:"Never jump a battery that shows a cracked or bulging case \u2014 electrolyte leaks are corrosive and hydrogen gas can ignite from a spark. Never jump a frozen battery \u2014 ice in the electrolyte causes explosive pressure. Feel the battery case: it should be room temperature or cool. Check for the rotten-egg smell of sulfur, which indicates a venting or failed battery. Check terminal posts: green or white corrosion buildup (lead sulfate or copper sulfate) dramatically increases resistance and may prevent a successful jump. Scrub posts with a wire brush, old toothbrush, or even pour a small amount of cola over them \u2014 the carbonic acid dissolves corrosion. Reconnect terminal clamps firmly. A clean connection is often the difference between a successful jump and a failed one."},{step:3,title:"Connect Jumper Cables in the Correct Order",body:"The order of connections matters \u2014 incorrect sequence can cause sparks near the battery or damage electronics. CORRECT ORDER: (1) Red clamp to dead battery POSITIVE terminal. (2) Red clamp other end to donor vehicle POSITIVE terminal. (3) Black clamp to donor vehicle NEGATIVE terminal. (4) Black clamp other end to an unpainted metal ground point on the dead vehicle \u2014 a bolt on the engine block, the alternator bracket, or the chassis rail. Do NOT connect the final black clamp to the dead battery negative terminal; connecting to a chassis ground keeps any hydrogen gas spark away from the battery. Start the donor vehicle and let it run at fast idle (1500\u20132000 RPM) for 2\u20133 minutes before attempting to start the dead vehicle. DISCONNECT in reverse order after the dead vehicle starts."},{step:4,title:"Push-Starting a Manual Transmission Vehicle",body:"If no donor vehicle is available and the transmission is manual, push-starting (also called bump-starting) bypasses the starter motor entirely. You need a downhill slope or at least 3\u20134 people to push on flat ground. Procedure: (1) Turn the ignition to ON (not start). (2) Depress the clutch pedal fully. (3) Shift into second gear (first gear causes a harsh lurch and often stalls immediately). (4) Have pushers build speed to at least 5\u20138 mph. (5) Release the clutch pedal quickly and firmly \u2014 the drivetrain compression will spin the engine. (6) If the engine fires, depress the clutch immediately to prevent stalling, then rev slightly to keep it running. This method only works if the engine itself is healthy and the battery failure is the sole problem. Do not attempt in automatic transmission vehicles \u2014 it will not work and can damage the transmission."},{step:5,title:"Identify a Sulfated or Failed Battery",body:"A battery that takes a jump charge but dies again within hours is likely sulfated \u2014 lead sulfate crystals have built up on the plates, permanently reducing capacity. Signs: battery is several years old (typical life is 3\u20135 years), takes a full charge on a charger but drops to 12.0V or below overnight, or voltage collapses under load (lights dim severely when you crank). A sulfated battery cannot be reliably recovered in the field. Slow-charging at 2 amps over 24\u201348 hours can sometimes break down light sulfation, but heavy sulfation is permanent. Test under load: connect a multimeter and crank the engine \u2014 if voltage drops below 9.6V during cranking, the battery has insufficient capacity and needs replacement regardless of resting voltage."},{step:6,title:"Common Mistakes and Reverse Polarity Consequences",body:"Reverse polarity \u2014 connecting cables backward (positive to negative) \u2014 is a serious electrical fault. In older vehicles it immediately destroys the alternator diodes and may blow fusible links. In modern vehicles with electronic control units, it can destroy the ECU, ABS module, and other modules in milliseconds. The consequences are expensive and not field-repairable. Prevention: red to red (positive), black to engine ground (not negative terminal). If you reverse the cables and see sparks or smoke, disconnect immediately and check all fuses before any further attempts. Other common mistakes: clips touching each other while connected to a live battery (causes arcing \u2014 keep clamps separated), running the donor vehicle in an enclosed space (carbon monoxide risk), and leaving cables connected too long after a successful start (heat buildup in cables)."}],warnings:["Never jump a cracked, bulging, leaking, or frozen battery \u2014 hydrogen gas and electrolyte can cause burns and explosion","Reverse polarity connection can permanently destroy the ECU and alternator in modern vehicles \u2014 always double-check red to positive, black to chassis ground","Carbon monoxide accumulates rapidly in enclosed garages \u2014 always ensure ventilation when running donor vehicles","A jump-start does not fix an alternator problem \u2014 if the battery light remains on after starting, the vehicle will die again; drive directly to a shop or you will be stranded again"],proTips:["A portable lithium jump starter (400\u20131000 peak amps, fits in a glove box) eliminates the need for a donor vehicle entirely and is one of the highest-value vehicle emergency tools available","The dome light brightness test is faster than a multimeter for a quick field assessment \u2014 a fully charged battery holds lights at near-full brightness even while cranking","If the battery terminals are corroded and no wire brush is available, a pen knife blade scraped firmly around the post works reasonably well to expose bare lead","Modern vehicles may require a 5\u201310 minute drive at highway speed after a jump to sufficiently recharge the battery \u2014 idling in a parking lot is much less effective"],relatedGuides:["vehicle-001","vehicle-003"],source:"USAF SERE curriculum / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Your vehicle will not start due to a battery issue \u2014 correct cable order prevents expensive electrical damage",immediate:["CORRECT ORDER: Red to dead positive \u2192 Red to donor positive \u2192 Black to donor negative \u2192 Black to chassis ground on dead vehicle (NOT battery negative)","Inspect battery before connecting: cracked case, bulging, frozen, or rotten-egg smell = do not jump","Run donor at fast idle (1500-2000 RPM) for 2-3 minutes before attempting to start the dead vehicle"],then:["If battery light stays on after starting: alternator is not charging \u2014 drive directly to a shop","Push-starting a manual: clutch in, second gear, 5-8 mph minimum, release clutch quickly \u2014 does not work on automatics"]}},{id:"vehicle-003",category:"vehicle",title:"Engine Overheating \u2014 Field Diagnosis and Response",priority:"critical",tags:["vehicle","engine","overheating","coolant","field-repair"],summary:"Immediate actions when the temperature gauge spikes, field diagnosis of the cause, and improvised remedies to get you moving again.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Immediate Actions \u2014 Pull Over Without Causing More Damage",body:"The moment the temperature gauge enters the red zone or the overheat warning light activates, take action within the next 30\u201360 seconds. Turn off the air conditioner immediately \u2014 it adds load to the engine. If on the highway and unable to pull over instantly, turn the cabin heater to full heat and full fan \u2014 this dumps engine heat into the cabin and can buy 1\u20132 minutes. Find a safe pullout and stop the engine. Do NOT open the radiator cap or overflow reservoir cap while hot \u2014 the cooling system is pressurized to 13\u201316 PSI when hot. Opening the cap releases pressure explosively, spraying 200\xb0F+ coolant. Leave the hood up to vent heat. Wait a minimum of 30 minutes or until the engine is cool enough to comfortably place your hand on the radiator hose."},{step:2,title:"Visual Diagnosis \u2014 Find the Cause Before Adding Fluid",body:"Once cool, open the hood and systematically check for the most common causes. Check the coolant overflow reservoir first \u2014 is it empty? Look for coolant puddles under the vehicle; trace the wetness upstream to find the leak source. Inspect all radiator hoses (upper and lower) by squeezing them \u2014 they should feel firm but flexible; cracked, soft, or collapsed hoses restrict flow. Check the radiator fins for clogging from debris, mud, or insect nests \u2014 blocked fins prevent airflow. Check the drive belt (serpentine belt) routing \u2014 if it is cracked or broken, the water pump is not spinning. Look for a failed radiator hose clamp or split seam where the hose meets the radiator neck. Most overheats in the field are caused by coolant loss, a blown hose, or a snapped drive belt \u2014 all visible without tools."},{step:3,title:"Improvised Coolant \u2014 What You Can and Cannot Use",body:"In an emergency, clean water is an acceptable substitute for coolant/antifreeze to get you to safety. Water alone lacks the freeze protection, boiling-point elevation, and corrosion inhibitors of proper coolant, but it will not damage the engine in a one-time emergency use. Use only clean water \u2014 avoid water with sediment, salt water, or heavily mineralized well water, which can leave deposits on cooling passages over time. Do not use motor oil, brake fluid, or any petroleum product in the cooling system \u2014 these will damage seals and hoses. If the overflow reservoir is accessible and cool, fill it to the MAX line. If coolant is critically low and the engine is completely cool, carefully remove the radiator cap (cloth over cap, turn to first stop, let pressure release, then fully remove) and add water directly to the radiator until full. Expect the temperature gauge to read higher than normal with water only \u2014 monitor closely."},{step:4,title:"Radiator and Hose Field Pressure Test",body:"Once the engine is cool and the system is refilled, perform a quick field pressure test before driving. Squeeze the upper and lower radiator hoses firmly \u2014 a healthy hose resists compression and springs back. A hose that collapses under light pressure or feels mushy has internal delamination and will fail. Look for wetness or coolant residue (dried coolant appears as whitish-green crystalline deposits) around hose clamps, the water pump shaft, the thermostat housing, and radiator seams. Start the engine cold and watch the temperature gauge as it warms. A healthy thermostat opens at 185\u2013195\xb0F and the temp gauge stabilizes in the normal range within 5 minutes. If the temperature climbs steadily without stabilizing, the thermostat is stuck closed \u2014 this is the second most common overheat cause after coolant loss. A stuck-closed thermostat must be removed or bypassed to limp to safety."},{step:5,title:"Head Gasket Check \u2014 Identify a Catastrophic Failure",body:"A blown head gasket is the most serious overheat-related failure. It allows combustion gases into the cooling system and coolant into the combustion chamber. Identify it by these signs: white sweet-smelling smoke from the exhaust (steam from coolant burning), a mayonnaise-like brown froth under the oil filler cap or on the dipstick (coolant mixed with oil), rapid and repeated coolant loss with no visible external leak, and bubbling in the radiator or overflow tank with the engine running. A combustion leak tester (block tester, blue chemical) is the definitive field test \u2014 the chemical turns yellow in the presence of combustion gases. Without a tester, repeated coolant disappearance with white exhaust and mayo on the dipstick is near-conclusive."},{step:6,title:"Driving with a Compromised Engine \u2014 How Far and How",body:"With a confirmed or suspected blown head gasket, continuing to drive risks permanent engine destruction \u2014 warped cylinder head, spun rod bearings from oil dilution, or hydrolocked cylinders. However, in a survival scenario where getting to safety is the priority: monitor the temperature gauge constantly, pull over and let cool every 5\u201310 minutes of driving, keep speed low (under 45 mph reduces heat load), check and refill coolant before every restart, and stop immediately if the gauge hits red. Change the oil as soon as possible \u2014 coolant in the oil destroys bearing surfaces rapidly. A vehicle with a minor head gasket seep can sometimes travel 50\u2013200 miles this way. A major failure \u2014 rapid coolant loss, severe white smoke, oil that looks milky \u2014 may give you only 1\u20135 miles before seizure. The decision to drive on is a calculated risk; stopping and calling for help is almost always the better option if available."}],warnings:["Never open a hot radiator cap \u2014 the cooling system is pressurized; sudden cap removal releases boiling coolant explosively and causes severe burns","Coolant (ethylene glycol) is toxic to animals and has a sweet taste that attracts pets \u2014 contain all spills and do not leave puddles on the ground","Driving with coolant in the oil (blown head gasket) can destroy engine bearings in minutes \u2014 do not continue driving without assessing the risk carefully","A thermostat bypass (removing the thermostat to allow free coolant flow) is a valid emergency measure but will cause heater failure and potential overcooling in cold weather"],proTips:["Carry two quarts of pre-mixed 50/50 coolant and a roll of duct tape in your vehicle at all times \u2014 most field coolant leaks can be temporarily slowed with duct tape over a split hose","Radiator hose repair tape (self-fusing silicone tape) is far superior to duct tape for cooling system repairs and can hold 50+ PSI when properly applied","Bars Leaks or similar radiator stop-leak tablets can seal minor leaks in the field and are worth carrying \u2014 they will not fix major failures but can get you home from a small pinhole seep","If you must bypass a stuck thermostat in the field, locate the thermostat housing (where the upper radiator hose meets the engine), remove it, extract the thermostat, and reinstall the housing without it \u2014 coolant will now flow unrestricted"],relatedGuides:["vehicle-001","vehicle-002","vehicle-004"],source:"USAF SERE curriculum / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Your temperature gauge is in the red zone \u2014 you have 30-60 seconds to respond before potential engine damage",immediate:["Turn off AC immediately; if on highway: turn heater to full heat to dump engine heat \u2014 buys 1-2 minutes","Find safe pullout and stop the engine \u2014 do NOT open radiator cap while hot (200\xb0F+ pressurized coolant)","Wait minimum 30 minutes or until you can comfortably touch the radiator hose before inspecting"],then:["Check for coolant puddles, cracked or collapsed hoses, broken serpentine belt, clogged radiator fins","Emergency coolant: clean water is acceptable one-time substitute to get you to safety \u2014 never use petroleum products in cooling system"]}},{id:"vehicle-004",category:"vehicle",title:"Fuel System Basics and Siphoning",priority:"advanced",tags:["vehicle","fuel","siphoning","storage","field"],summary:"Safe fuel siphoning techniques, identifying contaminated fuel, proper storage, and calculating remaining range.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Safe Siphoning \u2014 Gravity Method With a Clear Hose",body:"The safest method to siphon fuel uses gravity and a clear hose \u2014 no mouth contact with fuel at any point. You need a clear flexible hose 6\u20138 feet long (clear vinyl tubing, 3/8\" to 1/2\" ID works well) and a container lower than the fuel tank. Insert one end of the hose into the donor tank as deep as possible. Prime the siphon by submerging the entire hose in the tank, capping your thumb over the exit end to hold the fuel, then quickly lowering the exit end into your container below the tank level. Release your thumb \u2014 fuel flows by gravity as long as the exit end remains lower than the liquid surface in the donor tank. Most modern vehicles have anti-siphon screens in the fuel filler neck that block a hose \u2014 you may need to access the fuel line directly at the fuel pump or fuel rail instead. Never use oral suction to start a siphon \u2014 inhaling fuel vapor causes chemical pneumonitis, and swallowing fuel causes severe poisoning."},{step:2,title:"Identifying Contaminated Fuel by Sight and Smell",body:"Fresh unleaded gasoline is light yellow and has a sharp, hydrocarbon solvent smell. Fresh diesel is slightly amber and has an oily, heavier smell. Fuel that has gone bad or is contaminated shows these warning signs: gasoline stored over 3\u20136 months begins to oxidize \u2014 it darkens to orange or brown and smells sour or varnish-like; phase-separated ethanol-blend fuel (common E10) shows a distinct cloudy layer at the bottom of a clear container \u2014 the water-ethanol mixture separates from gasoline and will not combust. Water contamination causes cloudiness or a visible water layer at the bottom. Diesel contaminated with microbial growth (diesel bug) appears dark with visible black or brown particulate and smells musty or rotten. Never use phase-separated or heavily degraded fuel in a fuel-injected engine \u2014 the varnish deposits clog injectors and the water causes misfires and internal corrosion."},{step:3,title:"Fuel Storage Safety \u2014 Containers and Location",body:"Use only UL-listed red plastic jerry cans or metal fuel cans with a proper venting spout for gasoline storage. Never store gasoline in clear plastic water bottles, milk jugs, or non-approved containers \u2014 the plastic degrades, the containers lack proper venting (pressure buildup causes bloating and can split seams), and there is no label differentiation from water containers, which is a serious safety hazard. Store fuel in a detached structure, never inside a living space or an attached garage with ignition sources. Keep containers out of direct sunlight \u2014 UV and heat accelerate oxidation and increase vapor pressure. Ground metal cans before pouring to discharge static \u2014 touch the can to a metal part of the vehicle before opening the spout. Maximum recommended home storage: 25 gallons in most jurisdictions (check local fire codes). Never store near water heaters, furnaces, or any pilot light."},{step:4,title:"Draining a Carburetor Float Bowl",body:"Carbureted engines (older vehicles, most small engines, generators) have a float bowl at the bottom of the carburetor that holds a small reservoir of fuel. When stored with fuel in the bowl, this fuel evaporates and leaves behind varnish deposits that clog the main jet and idle circuit \u2014 the primary cause of small engine no-start after storage. To drain: locate the carburetor (follow the air filter housing), find the brass drain screw or drain plug on the bottom of the float bowl, and turn it out 1\u20132 turns over a rag or small container. Let the bowl drain completely. On carburetors without a drain screw, close the fuel petcock valve on the fuel tank (if equipped), then start and run the engine until it starves and dies \u2014 this empties the bowl naturally. Always drain carburetors before storing any small engine for more than 30 days."},{step:5,title:"Fuel Line Bleeding and Priming After Running Dry",body:"Running a fuel-injected engine completely dry can introduce air into the fuel lines and high-pressure fuel rail, causing hard or no-start conditions even after refueling. The fuel pump must reprime the system. Procedure: add at least 2 gallons of fuel. Turn the ignition key to the ON position (not crank) for 3\u20135 seconds \u2014 you will hear the fuel pump run; it primes the system. Turn back to OFF. Repeat this ON-OFF cycle 3\u20135 times before cranking. Each cycle builds fuel pressure in the rail. Then crank normally \u2014 the engine may take longer than usual to fire on the first start. Diesel engines that have run dry require bleeding air from the fuel filter housing and injection lines \u2014 a more involved procedure; consult the vehicle service manual for the specific bleed screw location and sequence."},{step:6,title:"Fuel Range Calculation and Long-Term Storage",body:"Estimate your remaining range with this formula: (gallons in tank) x (realistic MPG for current conditions) = range in miles. For conservative field planning, use 80% of your rated highway MPG to account for load, terrain, and lower-quality fuel. Example: 8 gallons x 24 MPG x 0.8 = 153 miles. Track actual consumption: reset your trip odometer at each fill, note the gallons added, and divide miles driven by gallons \u2014 this gives your real-world MPG over time. For long-term fuel storage (90 days+), add a petroleum-based fuel stabilizer (PRI-G, Sta-Bil, or equivalent) at the manufacturer-specified ratio, typically 1 oz per 2.5 gallons. Stabilizer prevents oxidation and varnish formation. It does not rejuvenate already-degraded fuel \u2014 add it to fresh fuel immediately. Rotate stored fuel every 6\u201312 months by using it in your vehicle and refilling with fresh fuel and new stabilizer."}],warnings:["Never use oral suction to start a siphon \u2014 fuel vapor inhalation causes chemical pneumonia and fuel ingestion causes poisoning; always use the gravity or hand-pump method","Gasoline vapors are heavier than air and accumulate at floor level \u2014 a single spark from a light switch 30 feet away in the same room can ignite them; store only in well-ventilated detached structures","Never use non-approved containers for fuel storage \u2014 standard plastic water bottles and milk jugs are not rated for fuel and will fail, creating spill and ignition hazards","Phase-separated ethanol fuel (cloudy, layered appearance) will damage fuel injectors and rubber fuel system components \u2014 do not use it in any modern engine"],proTips:["A dedicated hand-operated siphon pump (available for under $10) is more reliable than gravity siphoning and requires no improvisation \u2014 it belongs in every emergency vehicle kit","PRI-G fuel stabilizer is rated to keep gasoline stable for up to 2 years and can rejuvenate mildly degraded fuel \u2014 it is significantly more effective than Sta-Bil for long-term storage","Mark all fuel storage containers with the date filled and the fuel type using a paint pen \u2014 unlabeled containers are a serious safety and engine-compatibility hazard","To quickly test if stored gasoline is still usable: pour a small amount on white concrete \u2014 good fuel evaporates leaving almost no residue; bad fuel leaves an oily or dark stain"],relatedGuides:["vehicle-003","vehicle-005"],source:"USAF SERE curriculum / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to siphon fuel from another vehicle, assess stored fuel quality, or safely store fuel for extended periods",immediate:["Gravity siphon: submerge full hose in donor tank, cap exit with thumb, lower exit end into container below tank level \u2014 release thumb","NEVER use mouth suction \u2014 fuel vapor causes chemical pneumonitis; swallowing fuel causes serious poisoning","Assess fuel quality: good gasoline is pale yellow with sharp smell; degraded fuel is orange-brown with sour/varnish smell"],then:["Store fuel only in UL-listed red jerry cans \u2014 never in water bottles or non-approved containers","Add fuel stabilizer to fresh fuel immediately for storage beyond 30 days \u2014 it does not rescue already-degraded fuel"]}},{id:"vehicle-005",category:"vehicle",title:"Basic Generator Maintenance and Troubleshooting",priority:"beginner",tags:["vehicle","generator","maintenance","power","fuel"],summary:"Essential maintenance schedule for portable generators, troubleshooting common no-start and running problems, and calculating your power load.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Oil \u2014 The Most Critical Maintenance Item",body:"Most portable generators use a small air-cooled engine similar to a lawn mower. These engines hold only 0.6\u20131.0 quarts of oil and have no oil filter \u2014 oil degrades quickly and metallic particles accumulate with no filtration. Check the oil level before EVERY use using the dipstick or sight glass; never run a generator without confirming oil level. Change the oil after the first 5\u20138 hours on a new engine (break-in period), then every 50\u2013100 hours of operation or once per season (annually), whichever comes first. Use SAE 10W-30 for most conditions; switch to SAE 30 in summer heat above 85\xb0F. Drain when warm for complete drainage \u2014 remove the drain plug under the engine, let drain fully, reinstall plug firmly, then refill to the full mark on the dipstick. Low oil is the single most common cause of generator seizure and permanent engine failure."},{step:2,title:"Air Filter \u2014 Clean or Replace Annually",body:"The air filter prevents dust, debris, and insects from entering the carburetor and cylinder. A clogged air filter causes rich running (too much fuel, not enough air), black sooty exhaust, loss of power, hard starting, and excessive fuel consumption. Locate the air filter cover on the side of the engine (usually a plastic cover held by one screw or clip). Remove the foam or paper element. Foam filters: wash in warm soapy water, rinse completely, let dry fully, then lightly coat with clean engine oil and squeeze out excess before reinstalling. Paper filters: tap gently against a hard surface to dislodge dust \u2014 never wash a paper filter. Inspect for holes or tears; replace if damaged. A visibly gray or black clogged filter should be replaced, not cleaned. Air filter elements cost $3\u20138 and should be replaced at least once per year in regular use."},{step:3,title:"Spark Plug \u2014 Inspection, Gap, and Replacement",body:"The spark plug is both a diagnostic tool and a wear item. Remove the plug with a spark plug socket (usually 5/8\" or 13/16\") and examine the electrode. A healthy plug has a light tan or gray deposit on the tip \u2014 this indicates correct combustion. A black, sooty plug indicates rich running (too much fuel) \u2014 clean or replace the plug and check the air filter. A white or blistered electrode indicates lean running or overheating \u2014 check coolant (air-cooled: check air passages for blockage) and load. An oily plug indicates oil entering the combustion chamber \u2014 worn rings or valve seals. Check the electrode gap with a feeler gauge: most small engines spec 0.028\"\u20130.031\" (0.7\u20130.8mm). Adjust by carefully bending the side electrode. Replace the plug every 100 hours or annually. Plugs cost $2\u20135 and are the cheapest insurance against starting problems."},{step:4,title:"Carburetor Cleaning \u2014 The Stale Fuel Problem",body:"The single most common cause of generator no-start after storage is a varnish-clogged carburetor from stale fuel. Ethanol-blend gasoline begins degrading in as little as 30 days. The varnish deposits coat the main jet (a precisely drilled 0.025\"\u20130.045\" orifice), the idle jet, and the needle valve seat, preventing fuel delivery. Remove the air filter and carburetor bowl (one or two screws on the bottom). Inspect the bowl for brown varnish coating and sediment at the bottom. Remove the main jet (brass hex piece inside) and look through it at light \u2014 you should see a perfect circle of light. If obstructed, soak in carburetor cleaner for 15\u201330 minutes and clear with compressed air or a piece of wire. Soak the bowl and all brass parts in carb cleaner. Do not use wire in the main jet bore \u2014 it enlarges the orifice and ruins it. After reassembly, the engine should start with fresh fuel."},{step:5,title:"Starting a Flooded Engine",body:"A flooded engine has too much fuel in the cylinder, preventing ignition. It happens from repeated failed starting attempts or leaving the choke closed too long. Signs: strong gasoline smell from the exhaust, engine spins freely but will not fire, spark plug is wet with fuel. Procedure: (1) Move the generator outdoors or to a well-ventilated area. (2) Remove the spark plug with a spark plug socket. (3) Set the choke to OPEN (run position, not choke). (4) Set the throttle to full open. (5) Crank the engine 5\u201310 times with the plug removed to blow fuel vapor out of the cylinder. (6) Dry the plug electrode with a cloth or wait 5 minutes. (7) Reinstall the plug. (8) Attempt to start normally with choke open. If the plug is thoroughly soaked, use a replacement plug \u2014 a wet plug often fails to produce a hot enough spark. After the engine starts, run it at half load for 5 minutes to clear remaining fuel vapor."},{step:6,title:"Load Calculation and Runtime Efficiency",body:"Never exceed your generator's rated wattage \u2014 this causes overheating, trips the circuit breaker, and shortens engine life. Calculate your load by summing the wattage of everything you intend to run simultaneously. For motor-driven appliances (refrigerators, well pumps, AC units), use the starting wattage (typically 2\u20133x running wattage) for sizing \u2014 a refrigerator that runs at 150W may require 600\u2013800W to start the compressor. Label all critical appliances with their running and starting watts. A 3500W generator can typically handle: a refrigerator (800W starting), two LED light strings (50W total), a phone/radio charger (20W), and a window fan (75W) \u2014 totaling about 945W running with 800W surge capacity reserved. Fuel consumption varies dramatically with load: a 3500W generator uses roughly 0.5 gallons/hour at 25% load, and nearly 1.0 gallon/hour at full load. Run at 50\u201375% capacity for the best efficiency and longest runtime."}],warnings:["Never run a generator indoors, in a garage, or near open windows \u2014 gasoline engines produce lethal carbon monoxide that is odorless and accumulates rapidly in enclosed spaces","Never refuel a running or hot generator \u2014 fuel on a hot exhaust or engine block ignites instantly; shut down and allow to cool for 2 minutes minimum before adding fuel","Low oil will cause engine seizure within minutes \u2014 always check oil level before starting; most modern generators have a low-oil shutoff but do not rely on it as your only protection","Do not backfeed a generator into house wiring without a proper transfer switch \u2014 backfeed electrocutes utility workers and is illegal; use extension cords or a licensed transfer switch installation"],proTips:["Run your generator under load for 30 minutes every 90 days \u2014 this keeps the carburetor clear, exercises the engine, and confirms it will work when needed; note the date on a piece of tape on the generator","Use ethanol-free gasoline (available at marinas and some gas stations, labeled E0) in generators and other small engines \u2014 it dramatically extends fuel stability and prevents carburetor varnishing","A Champion, Honda EU2200i, or Yamaha EF2200iS inverter generator produces clean sine-wave power safe for sensitive electronics \u2014 standard open-frame generators produce dirty power that can damage laptop power supplies and medical equipment","Keep a spare spark plug, air filter, and oil on the shelf next to the generator \u2014 these three items cost under $20 total and cover 90% of all maintenance needs for a full season"],relatedGuides:["vehicle-004"],source:"USAF SERE curriculum / Wilderness survival best practices",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"Your generator will not start or is running poorly \u2014 most generator failures are caused by oil level or stale fuel in the carburetor",immediate:["Check oil level first \u2014 low oil is the most common cause of permanent generator seizure","Check for flooded engine: strong gas smell from exhaust, engine spins but won't fire \u2014 remove plug, crank 5-10 times plug-out, reinstall and retry","Clean carburetor main jet if engine starts but dies or runs rough after storage \u2014 varnish from stale ethanol fuel is the most common cause"],then:["Never run generator indoors or near open windows \u2014 CO kills silently and accumulates rapidly","Run your generator under load for 30 minutes every 90 days to keep carburetor clear and confirm readiness"]}}]},580,[]);
__d(function(e,t,a,o,i,r,s){i.exports=[{id:"homestead-001",category:"homesteading",title:"Raising Chickens for Grid-Down Food Security",priority:"beginner",tags:["homesteading","chickens","food","livestock","eggs"],summary:"Setting up a minimum-viable chicken operation for year-round eggs and meat during grid-down scenarios.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Breed Selection \u2014 Dual-Purpose Birds for Eggs and Meat",body:"Choose dual-purpose heritage breeds that provide both reliable egg production and adequate meat when cockerels (young males) are culled. Top choices for grid-down resilience: Rhode Island Red \u2014 250\u2013300 brown eggs/year, excellent foragers, cold-hardy, calm temperament. Barred Plymouth Rock \u2014 250\u2013280 eggs/year, heavy body for meat, very cold-hardy, docile. Sussex (Speckled or Light) \u2014 250 eggs/year, outstanding foragers that reduce feed dependency, good meat bird. Black Australorp \u2014 holds the world record for egg production (364 eggs in 365 days), very calm, heat-tolerant. Avoid hybrid commercial layers (Leghorns, ISA Browns) \u2014 they burn out in 18 months, are poor foragers, rarely go broody, and cannot be bred true. Heritage breeds can hatch and raise their own replacements \u2014 critical in a long-term grid-down scenario. Start with 6\u201310 hens and 1 rooster minimum for a self-sustaining flock."},{step:2,title:"Minimum Coop Requirements \u2014 Space, Ventilation, Nesting",body:"Overcrowding is the primary cause of disease, pecking, and egg-eating in small flocks. Provide a minimum of 4 square feet per bird inside the coop (roosting area) and 10 square feet per bird in the outdoor run. A flock of 10 birds needs a 40 sq ft interior (roughly 5x8 feet) and a 100 sq ft run. Roosting bars should be 2\u20134 inches wide (flat or rounded, not round dowels) \u2014 chickens sleep with flat feet, not gripping. Place roosting bars 18\u201324 inches above the floor and space them 12\u201318 inches apart. Provide one nesting box per 4\u20135 hens; boxes should be 12\"x12\"x12\" filled with straw or pine shavings and positioned lower than roosting bars to discourage sleeping in boxes (fouling eggs). Ventilation is non-negotiable: chicken manure produces ammonia that causes respiratory disease. Install vents at the ridge or upper walls \u2014 1 square foot of ventilation per 10 square feet of floor space minimum."},{step:3,title:"Predator-Proofing \u2014 Hardware Cloth Is Non-Negotiable",body:"Chicken wire (hexagonal wire mesh) is inadequate for predator exclusion \u2014 raccoons, foxes, and dogs pull through it, and weasels and minks squeeze through the openings. Use 1/2\" or 1/4\" galvanized hardware cloth for all openings, windows, and run covering. Bury or lay a 12-inch apron skirt of hardware cloth horizontally outward from the base of the run fence \u2014 predators dig straight down at the fence line; the apron redirects them outward where they cannot dig effectively. Anchor the apron with landscape staples or rocks. Cover the top of the run \u2014 aerial predators (hawks, owls) are highly effective in open runs. Use a predator-proof latch on coop doors \u2014 simple hook-and-eye latches are opened by raccoons. Use a double-latch or spring-loaded carabiner. Close the coop door every night before dark \u2014 a single night of a coop door left open will result in total flock loss to a predator."},{step:4,title:"Feeding Without Commercial Feed \u2014 Whole Grains, Foraging, and Calcium",body:"Commercial chicken feed is convenient but creates a dependency on supply chains. Build a resilient feeding system: whole grains \u2014 wheat, corn, barley, oats, and black oil sunflower seeds can replace commercial pellets when mixed appropriately. A basic ration is 50% cracked corn, 30% wheat berries, 10% barley, 10% BOSS (black oil sunflower seeds). This is lower in protein than commercial feed (16\u201318%) so supplement heavily with protein sources. Kitchen scraps \u2014 meat scraps, cooked eggs, vegetable trimmings, bread \u2014 are important free protein. Fermented grains (soak grain in water 48\u201372 hours until bubbling) increase nutrient bioavailability and stretch feed 20\u201330%. Foraging \u2014 a free-range or large run flock derives 20\u201330% of nutrition from grass, insects, and worms. Calcium for eggshell formation is critical \u2014 without it, hens lay soft-shell eggs and pull calcium from their own bones. Provide crushed oyster shell in a separate free-choice feeder, or dry, crush, and re-feed eggshells back to the flock."},{step:5,title:"Water Management and Winter Watering",body:"Chickens require 0.5\u20131.0 cup of water per bird per day under normal conditions, and up to double that in heat. Without sufficient water, egg production drops within 24 hours and ceases entirely within 48\u201372 hours. Use a waterer that prevents contamination \u2014 nipple-style waterers stay clean the longest but require pressure; gravity-fed bell waterers work without electricity. In freezing temperatures, water freezes solid and birds can go without water for dangerous lengths of time. Solutions without electricity: use a deep, wide-diameter water container (a 5-gallon bucket) \u2014 larger water mass freezes more slowly. Check and break ice at least twice daily \u2014 morning and again in early afternoon. Place the waterer in a sunny south-facing location. A black rubber livestock pan absorbs solar heat and freezes slower than metal or white containers. Consider heating with a fire-safe black rubber pan set on a heated base (solar or low-wattage), or float a ball in the water \u2014 the thermal movement slows freezing."},{step:6,title:"Egg Storage Without Refrigeration and Cockerel Butchering",body:"Fresh, unwashed eggs have an intact natural coating called the bloom (cuticle) that seals the shell against bacteria. Unwashed eggs at room temperature remain safe to eat for 2\u20133 weeks. The refrigerator habit is an American artifact of commercial egg washing (which removes the bloom), which requires refrigeration afterward. Do not wash eggs you plan to store at room temperature \u2014 wipe dry if needed. For longer storage, use the water glass method: dissolve pickling lime (calcium hydroxide, sold as Mrs. Wages Pickling Lime) in clean water at a ratio of 1 oz lime per 1 quart water. Submerge clean, unwashed, fresh eggs fully and store in a cool location. Eggs stored this way remain edible for 12\u201318 months. Test-float eggs before eating: a fresh egg sinks flat; an older but still good egg stands on end; a bad egg floats \u2014 discard it. Cockerels (young males) not needed for breeding should be butchered at 16\u201320 weeks \u2014 they are lean but edible; beyond 20 weeks they fight other birds and consume feed without productive return."}],warnings:["Chicken wire (hexagonal mesh) does not stop raccoons, foxes, minks, or determined dogs \u2014 use only 1/2\" galvanized hardware cloth for all predator-exposed surfaces","Medicated chick starter contains amprolium (a coccidiostat) and should not be fed to laying hens or ducks \u2014 it affects waterfowl seriously and accumulates in eggs","Botulism can develop in wet, rotting feed or carcasses in the run \u2014 remove any dead birds immediately and do not leave wet feed to ferment in the feeder","Lime (calcium hydroxide) used in water glassing is caustic \u2014 wear gloves when handling and keep out of eyes; it is safe once dissolved in the storage solution but handle dry powder carefully"],proTips:["A broody hen is worth 10 incubators in a grid-down scenario \u2014 breeds like Silkies, Cochins, Sussex, and Australorps go broody reliably; let them hatch and raise your replacement flock instead of using an electric incubator","Plant comfrey (Symphytum officinale) near the chicken run \u2014 it is a prolific, perennial, high-protein green that chickens eat readily and it grows back aggressively after cutting; it supplements feed costs significantly","The deep litter method (add fresh bedding on top of soiled litter monthly; clean only once or twice a year) produces lower ammonia levels than frequent cleaning due to beneficial bacterial decomposition, and the composted result is excellent garden fertilizer","Ducks are a worthwhile addition to a chicken setup \u2014 they are hardy, lay larger eggs consistently through winter when chickens slow down, and are more resistant to many common poultry diseases"],relatedGuides:["homestead-002","homestead-003","homestead-005"],source:"Wilderness survival best practices / Traditional homesteading knowledge",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to establish a sustainable protein source that does not depend on supply chains \u2014 a self-sustaining chicken flock provides year-round eggs and meat",immediate:["Select heritage dual-purpose breeds: Rhode Island Red, Barred Rock, or Black Australorp \u2014 they forage, go broody, and breed true","Provide 4 sq ft per bird inside, 10 sq ft per bird in run; one nesting box per 4-5 hens","Use 1/2-inch hardware cloth for ALL predator-exposed surfaces \u2014 chicken wire fails against raccoons and weasels"],then:["Establish a feed system independent of commercial pellets: whole grains (corn/wheat/barley/BOSS) plus kitchen scraps plus foraging","Close the coop door every night before dark \u2014 a single night open will result in total flock loss to a predator"]}},{id:"homestead-002",category:"homesteading",title:"Emergency Gardening \u2014 High-Yield Crops for Survival",priority:"beginner",tags:["homesteading","gardening","food","crops","seeds"],summary:"Calorie-dense and fast-producing crops, no-till planting methods, and seed saving for a sustainable grid-down food supply.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Caloric Density Rankings \u2014 Grow What Feeds You",body:"In a food security scenario, calories per square foot are more important than variety. Rank your planting choices by caloric yield: Potatoes are the undisputed king of caloric gardening \u2014 a 10x10 plot yields 50\u2013100 lbs (roughly 35,000\u201370,000 calories) in 70\u2013120 days. They grow in almost any soil, require minimal inputs, and store for months. Field corn (dent corn, not sweet corn) stores dry and provides 1,500+ calories per pound. Winter squash (Hubbard, Butternut, Acorn) yields 20\u201340 lbs per plant, stores 3\u20136 months without refrigeration at 50\u201355\xb0F, and provides meaningful calories and vitamin A. Dry beans (Pinto, Black, Navy, Kidney) fix their own nitrogen and provide protein and complex carbohydrates \u2014 500 calories per cup dry. The Three Sisters method (corn, beans, squash planted together) uses space and nutrients maximally: the corn provides a trellis for beans; the beans fix nitrogen that feeds the corn; the squash shades the ground preventing weeds and moisture loss."},{step:2,title:"Fastest Crops to Harvest \u2014 Food While Waiting for Calories",body:"While your caloric crops mature over months, fast-maturing crops provide fresh nutrition within weeks. Radishes: 22\u201330 days from seed to harvest; plant densely between slower crops. Leaf lettuce: 30\u201335 days to first harvest, cut-and-come-again for weeks. Spinach: 25\u201340 days, highly nutritious (iron, vitamin C, folate), bolts in heat so plant in spring and fall. Arugula: 21\u201330 days, extremely fast, self-seeds prolifically. Turnips: 45\u201360 days \u2014 both greens (edible at 25 days) and the root are edible; very cold-hardy. Bush beans: 50\u201360 days, high yield for space. Kale and collards: 55\u201370 days but leaves can be harvested continuously for months; extremely nutritious and frost-tolerant. Plant fast crops intensively in any available space \u2014 even containers \u2014 for immediate food production while your main crops develop. Succession plant radishes and lettuce every 2 weeks for continuous harvest."},{step:3,title:"No-Till Sheet Mulch Method \u2014 Garden Without Digging",body:"Tilling is labor-intensive and degrades soil structure over time by destroying fungal networks and worm habitat. The sheet mulch method (also called lasagna gardening) creates productive growing beds with no digging. Procedure: (1) Mow or knock down existing vegetation as short as possible. (2) Lay overlapping cardboard directly over the grass or weeds, at least 4 sheets thick, overlapping edges by 6 inches \u2014 this smothers existing plants and breaks down into carbon over 6\u20138 weeks. (3) Soak the cardboard thoroughly with water. (4) Apply 4 inches of compost, aged manure, or a mix of both directly on top of the wet cardboard. (5) Apply 2\u20133 inches of straw or wood chip mulch over the compost layer. (6) Plant immediately by pushing transplants through the mulch into the compost layer. Seeds can be sown directly into the compost layer. The cardboard decomposes, worms colonize the bed from below, and by the following season the soil structure under the bed is noticeably improved."},{step:4,title:"Seed Saving \u2014 Open-Pollinated vs. Hybrid and Storage Method",body:"Commercial hybrid seeds (marked F1 on the packet) do not breed true \u2014 second-generation plants revert to unpredictable parent traits and are often sterile or reduced-yield. For a self-sustaining food supply you must grow open-pollinated (OP) or heirloom varieties exclusively. Reliable OP seed sources: Baker Creek Heirloom Seeds, Seed Savers Exchange, Southern Exposure Seed Exchange. To save seeds: allow the best specimens to fully mature and begin to dry on the plant before harvesting. Tomatoes \u2014 ferment seeds in water for 2\u20133 days to remove germination-inhibiting gel, rinse, and dry thoroughly. Beans and corn \u2014 allow pods/ears to dry completely on the plant, then shell. Squash \u2014 scoop seeds, rinse, and dry for 2\u20134 weeks on screens. All seeds must be fully dry before storage \u2014 any residual moisture causes mold and germination failure. Store in sealed glass jars with a silica gel desiccant packet added, labeled with species and year. Store in a cool, dark location. Most vegetable seeds remain viable 3\u20135 years; onions and parsnips decline rapidly (1\u20132 years)."},{step:5,title:"Spacing and Intensive Planting for Maximum Yield",body:"Traditional row gardening wastes significant space to paths that serve machinery. For hand-tended gardens, use the biointensive method: create raised or mounded beds 3\u20134 feet wide (reachable from either side without stepping on the growing area, which compacts soil), and space plants in a hexagonal offset pattern at the closest recommended distance. Hexagonal spacing fits 15\u201320% more plants per square foot than grid spacing. Recommended intensive spacings: lettuce 6 inches, spinach 4 inches, radish 2 inches, kale 12 inches, beans 4 inches, carrots 2 inches, potatoes 10\u201312 inches, tomatoes 18 inches (with support). Eliminate all paths within beds \u2014 walk only on permanent pathways between beds. A well-managed 20x20 foot biointensive bed can produce as much food as a conventional 40x40 plot using the same seed investment."},{step:6,title:"Companion Planting for Natural Pest Management",body:"Companion planting reduces pest pressure through aromatic confusion, predator attraction, and physical barriers \u2014 replacing chemical pesticides with plant relationships. Proven combinations: Tomatoes + Basil \u2014 basil repels aphids, thrips, and whitefly; the volatile oils confuse pest navigation. Tomatoes + Marigold (French, Tagetes patula) \u2014 marigold roots produce alpha-terthienyl, a compound toxic to root-knot nematodes; plant densely as border. Brassicas (cabbage, broccoli, kale) + Dill or Fennel \u2014 attracts parasitic wasps that prey on cabbage worms and aphids. Squash + Nasturtium \u2014 nasturtium acts as a trap crop for aphids, drawing them away from squash. Carrots + Onions \u2014 alternating rows confuse carrot fly and onion fly, both of which navigate by scent. Plant pest-repelling alliums (garlic, onions, chives) as borders around any high-value bed. Diversity itself is protective \u2014 monoculture amplifies pest populations; mixed planting disrupts them."}],warnings:["Hybrid (F1) seeds will not produce reliable offspring \u2014 always source and store open-pollinated or heirloom varieties for any long-term food security plan","Seed viability drops rapidly with heat and moisture \u2014 never store seeds in a shed, attic, or any space with temperature swings; a cool basement or refrigerator with desiccant is ideal","Potatoes exposed to sunlight turn green and produce solanine, a toxic alkaloid \u2014 always hill soil up over developing tubers and store in complete darkness","Raw dry beans (especially red kidney beans) contain phytohaemagglutinin (PHA), which causes severe nausea and vomiting if undercooked \u2014 always boil dried beans for at least 10 minutes before any slow-cooking method"],proTips:["One 5-gallon bucket of Yukon Gold potato seed pieces (eyes) planted in early spring will produce 40\u201360 lbs of potatoes in 90 days \u2014 no other vegetable matches this return on investment for caloric production","Inoculate bean and pea seeds with rhizobium nitrogen-fixing bacteria (available as dry powder at garden stores) before planting \u2014 this dramatically increases nitrogen fixation and is especially important in new or depleted soil","Save cardboard from any source throughout the year \u2014 it is one of the most useful homesteading materials for weed suppression, sheet mulch, and composting; flatten and stack in a dry location","A cold frame (bottomless wooden box with an old window or clear plastic as a lid) extends the growing season 4\u20136 weeks on both ends \u2014 allowing spring and fall crops in climates where frosts end the season early"],relatedGuides:["homestead-001","homestead-003","homestead-004"],source:"Wilderness survival best practices / Traditional homesteading knowledge",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"beginner",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"low",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to establish a food-producing garden prioritized for calories per square foot, not variety",immediate:["Plant potatoes first: a 10x10 plot yields 50-100 lbs (35,000-70,000 calories) in 70-120 days","Plant fast crops for immediate nutrition while caloric crops mature: radishes 22 days, leaf lettuce 30 days, spinach 25 days","Use only open-pollinated (OP) or heirloom seeds \u2014 hybrid F1 seeds do not breed true for second generation"],then:["Use sheet mulch method to create beds without digging: cardboard + compost + straw mulch","Save seeds from best specimens allowed to fully dry on the plant \u2014 store in sealed glass jars with silica gel"]}},{id:"homestead-003",category:"homesteading",title:"Preserving Food Without Electricity",priority:"advanced",tags:["homesteading","food-preservation","canning","fermentation","salt-curing"],summary:"Proven off-grid food preservation methods including salt curing, smoking, lacto-fermentation, root cellaring, and drying \u2014 with safety-critical details on botulism prevention.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Salt Curing Meat \u2014 Ratios, Pink Salt, and Timing",body:"Salt curing preserves meat by reducing water activity (aw) to levels that prevent microbial growth. A cure ratio of a minimum 2.5% salt by weight of fresh meat is required for preservation \u2014 below this level, pathogen suppression is unreliable. To calculate: 1,000g of meat requires at least 25g of salt. Dry curing method: weigh meat, calculate salt needed, add pink curing salt (sodium nitrite, sold as Prague Powder #1 or Instacure #1) at the manufacturer-specified rate \u2014 typically 1 tsp per 5 lbs of meat. Pink salt prevents Clostridium botulinum growth in anaerobic (low-oxygen) environments like the interior of thick cuts. Mix curing salt with kosher salt, rub thoroughly over entire meat surface, place in a non-reactive container (glass, ceramic, food-grade plastic), and refrigerate or store in a cool space (35\u201340\xb0F). Allow 7 days per inch of thickness at the thickest point. Turn the meat every 2 days and drain brine that forms. Pink salt is not optional for thick cuts cured without heat \u2014 it is the primary botulism barrier."},{step:2,title:"Smoking \u2014 Cold Smoke for Preservation vs. Hot Smoke for Cooking",body:"Smoking alone does not fully preserve meat \u2014 it must be combined with curing or drying to achieve shelf-stable preservation. Cold smoking (smoke temperature below 90\xb0F, ideally 60\u201380\xb0F) adds antimicrobial phenolic compounds from wood smoke to the surface of cured meat without cooking it \u2014 it is a preservation enhancement, not a cooking method. Cold smoked products (bacon, salmon, salami) must be pre-cured before cold smoking. Hot smoking (smoke temperature 165\u2013225\xb0F) cooks meat to a food-safe internal temperature and adds smoke flavor \u2014 but without salt curing or drying, hot-smoked meat has the same shelf life as cooked meat (3\u20134 days unrefrigerated). For true shelf-stable smoked products: cure with salt and pink salt first, cold smoke 8\u201324 hours, then dry at 130\xb0F until the meat reaches 35\u201340% weight loss. Hardwoods only for smoking: hickory, oak, apple, cherry, maple, alder. Never use pine, cedar, or any resinous softwood \u2014 the resin produces toxic compounds."},{step:3,title:"Lacto-Fermentation \u2014 Salt Brine, Temperature, and Timing",body:"Lacto-fermentation uses salt to selectively suppress pathogens while allowing beneficial Lactobacillus bacteria (naturally present on vegetables) to produce lactic acid, which preserves the food and creates the characteristic sour flavor of sauerkraut, kimchi, and pickles. This is one of the safest preservation methods \u2014 the lactic acid environment is hostile to nearly all food pathogens including Clostridium botulinum (which requires neutral pH). Salt brine: 2% salt by weight of the total brine solution \u2014 dissolve 20g of non-iodized salt per 1,000g (1 liter) of clean water. Iodized salt inhibits fermentation bacteria; use kosher, sea, or pickling salt. Pack vegetables tightly into clean glass jars, pour brine over to fully submerge. Vegetables must remain submerged \u2014 exposure to air causes mold, not safe fermentation. Use a zip-lock bag filled with brine as a weight, or a small jar filled with water. Ferment at room temperature 60\u201375\xb0F for 3\u20137 days. Taste daily \u2014 the product is ready when pleasantly sour. Move to cold storage (40\xb0F) to slow further fermentation; lacto-fermented vegetables keep for 6\u201312 months when kept cold."},{step:4,title:"Root Cellaring \u2014 Temperature, Humidity, and Crop Compatibility",body:"A root cellar exploits the natural thermal mass of the earth to maintain 40\u201355\xb0F and 85\u201395% humidity \u2014 ideal conditions for long-term vegetable storage without energy. If you lack a purpose-built root cellar, a buried trash can, a corner of an uninsulated basement, or even a well-insulated outdoor pit can approximate these conditions. Suitable crops for root cellar storage: carrots (sand-packed in boxes, 32\u201340\xb0F, 90\u201395% humidity \u2014 last 4\u20136 months), potatoes (40\u201350\xb0F, 85\u201390% humidity, complete darkness \u2014 last 4\u20136 months), beets (sand-packed, 32\u201340\xb0F \u2014 3\u20135 months), cabbages and kohlrabi (32\u201340\xb0F, 90\u201395% humidity \u2014 3\u20136 months), winter squash (50\u201355\xb0F, 50\u201370% humidity, cured 10 days at 80\xb0F before storage \u2014 3\u20136 months). Critical incompatibility: never store apples with any other produce. Apples emit ethylene gas that accelerates ripening and spoilage in every adjacent vegetable \u2014 they require an isolated section or separate storage."},{step:5,title:"Drying and Dehydration \u2014 Meat Jerky and Vegetables",body:"Drying removes moisture to below 20% water activity, at which point mold, yeast, and bacteria cannot grow. For meat jerky: use lean cuts only \u2014 fat does not dry and turns rancid quickly, shortening shelf life. Slice meat 1/4\" thick against the grain for tenderness, with the grain for chewier texture. Pre-treat with salt cure or soy sauce brine (high sodium) for both flavor and microbial safety. Dry at 130\u2013160\xb0F for 6\u20138 hours in a dehydrator or low oven with the door cracked for airflow. The USDA recommends heating jerky to 160\xb0F internal temperature \u2014 either heat the dried jerky in an oven at 275\xb0F for 10 minutes after drying, or pre-heat wet meat strips in marinade on the stovetop to 165\xb0F before drying. Sun drying works in hot, dry climates: lay slices on mesh screens elevated above a dark surface (absorbs heat), cover with cheesecloth to exclude insects, and bring inside at night. Full sun drying takes 2\u20134 days. Finished jerky should bend and crack, not snap brittlely or feel moist."},{step:6,title:"Botulism \u2014 Understanding and Preventing the Deadliest Preservation Risk",body:"Clostridium botulinum is an anaerobic bacterium that produces the most toxic substance known \u2014 botulinum toxin. It thrives in low-oxygen, low-acid, moist environments at temperatures from 40\u2013120\xb0F: exactly the conditions inside improperly canned, cured, or sealed foods. Signs of botulism contamination in preserved foods: bulging lids, off odors, unusual appearance, or visible gas when opened \u2014 discard any such food without tasting it. Botulism toxin is destroyed by boiling (212\xb0F) for 10 minutes \u2014 heating suspect canned foods before eating is a safety measure, but do not rely on it. Prevention by method: for canning, use a pressure canner (240\xb0F) for all low-acid foods (meats, vegetables, beans) \u2014 water bath canning at 212\xb0F is insufficient for low-acid foods. For curing, use pink salt (sodium nitrite) \u2014 it directly inhibits C. botulinum. For fermentation, maintain sufficient salt concentration (2%+) and ensure vegetables stay submerged \u2014 the lactic acid pH drop kills botulinum spores. Never taste-test any low-acid preserved food before heating it if you are uncertain of the method used."}],warnings:["Pink curing salt (Prague Powder, Instacure) contains sodium nitrite, which is toxic in large amounts \u2014 do not substitute regular salt and do not exceed recommended ratios; measure by weight, not volume","Water bath canning is NOT safe for low-acid foods (meats, vegetables, beans, soups) \u2014 these require pressure canning at 240\xb0F to destroy botulinum spores; improperly canned low-acid foods have caused multiple fatal botulism outbreaks","Cold-smoked foods that are not pre-cured are NOT shelf stable \u2014 cold smoke alone does not prevent spoilage in the interior of thick cuts","Lacto-fermentation produces CO2 gas \u2014 do not seal jars airtight during active fermentation or jars will build pressure and may crack; use an airlock lid or loosen the jar ring to allow gas to escape"],proTips:["A vacuum sealer combined with oxygen absorbers dramatically extends the storage life of dried foods \u2014 dried beans sealed with oxygen absorbers in Mylar bags inside 5-gallon buckets remain viable for 25+ years","The Weston Price Foundation and the Ball Blue Book of Canning are the two most reliable references for home preservation safety \u2014 consult USDA-tested recipes for canning; do not use old family recipes that predate modern safety testing","Fermented hot sauce is one of the easiest and most rewarding lacto-ferments \u2014 blend peppers with 2% salt, ferment in a jar with an airlock for 5\u20137 days, blend smooth; the result is a probiotic condiment that lasts months under refrigeration","Render animal fat (lard from pork, tallow from beef) and confit meat in the rendered fat \u2014 meat submerged and sealed under a layer of solid fat is a traditional preservation method that keeps unrefrigerated for weeks to months in a cool space; this is how cassoulet and duck confit were preserved for centuries"],relatedGuides:["homestead-001","homestead-004","homestead-005"],source:"Wilderness survival best practices / Traditional homesteading knowledge",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You have more food than you can consume and need to preserve it \u2014 off-grid preservation prevents waste of irreplaceable calories",immediate:["Salt curing: minimum 2.5% salt by weight of meat \u2014 pack completely with no exposed surface; add pink curing salt (Prague Powder) for thick cuts to prevent botulism","Lacto-fermentation: 2% salt brine (20g per liter water), pack vegetables tightly, keep fully submerged \u2014 never let them contact air","Smoking: only hot smoke fully cured meat; cold smoke requires pre-curing first or product is not shelf-stable"],then:["Root cellaring: potatoes, carrots, beets, and winter squash at 40-55\xb0F with 85-95% humidity last 3-6 months","Never taste-test low-acid preserved food before heating if uncertain of method \u2014 botulism has no odor or taste"]}},{id:"homestead-004",category:"homesteading",title:"Water Collection and Storage for a Homestead",priority:"critical",tags:["homesteading","water","rainwater","storage","filtration"],summary:"Rainwater harvesting setup, cistern sizing, gravity-fed distribution, treatment and storage, and calculating household water needs.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Rain Barrel Setup \u2014 Diverters, First-Flush, and Screening",body:"A basic rain barrel connects to a downspout to capture roof runoff. The collection rate is significant: 1 inch of rain on 1,000 square feet of roof yields approximately 600 gallons of runoff. Install a downspout diverter at the appropriate height \u2014 a Y-fitting that sends water into your barrel while allowing overflow to bypass to the original downspout when the barrel is full. More important than the diverter is a first-flush diverter: the first 1/10 inch of rain per 100 square feet of roof washes accumulated bird droppings, dust, decomposed organic material, and roofing chemicals off the surface \u2014 this water is significantly more contaminated than subsequent flow. A first-flush diverter is a standpipe (typically 4\" diameter PVC) that fills with the first dirty flush, then diverts subsequent cleaner water to storage. Screen all inlets with fine mesh (window screen minimum, 20-mesh ideally) to exclude insects \u2014 open water containers breed mosquitoes in 4\u20135 days. Cover all storage containers completely."},{step:2,title:"Cistern Sizing \u2014 55-Gallon Barrels to 1,000-Gallon IBC Totes",body:"Calculate your storage needs based on your household daily usage and average dry-spell duration in your region. At the survival minimum of 1 gallon per person per day, a family of 4 needs 120 gallons for a 30-day dry spell. For basic living (drinking, cooking, minimal hygiene) at 3 gallons/person/day: 360 gallons for 30 days. For comfortable homestead operation with garden irrigation, livestock watering, and hygiene: 5\u201315 gallons/person/day is realistic, requiring 600\u20131,800+ gallons of storage. Storage options by scale: 55-gallon food-grade drums (widely available, stackable, manageable) \u2014 multiple drums daisy-chained with overflow fittings scale well. 275\u2013330 gallon IBC totes (Intermediate Bulk Containers) \u2014 food-grade versions are excellent cisterns; avoid totes that held chemicals. 500\u20131,000 gallon poly tanks \u2014 purpose-built water storage, UV-stabilized, with fittings. Underground cisterns (1,000\u201310,000 gallons) \u2014 the gold standard, maintains cool temperature that inhibits algae and bacterial growth."},{step:3,title:"Gravity-Fed Distribution \u2014 Head Pressure Calculations",body:"Municipal water pressure is 40\u201380 PSI, provided by pumps or elevated water towers. A gravity-fed system generates pressure purely from elevation: every 1 foot of vertical height between the water surface in the storage tank and the outlet generates 0.433 PSI (commonly rounded to 0.43 PSI). To calculate: (tank height in feet) x 0.43 = PSI available at the outlet. A standard shower requires 8\u201312 PSI minimum for acceptable flow. To generate 10 PSI, your tank water surface must be at least 23 feet above the showerhead (10 / 0.43 = 23.2 feet). For garden irrigation via drip lines, 5\u201310 PSI is usually sufficient \u2014 achievable with a tank 12\u201325 feet high. For toilet flushing, 5 PSI is adequate (10\u201312 feet of head). Build your cistern on the highest available point \u2014 hilltop, elevated platform, or upper floor of a structure. Every additional foot of elevation is significant. A 500-gallon IBC tote on a 15-foot elevated platform provides 6.5 PSI \u2014 sufficient for drip irrigation and toilet flushing, marginal for showers."},{step:4,title:"Water Treatment Before Storage \u2014 Chemical Disinfection",body:"Collected rainwater is not potable without treatment, even from a clean roof \u2014 it can contain bird feces (Salmonella, Campylobacter, Cryptosporidium), atmospheric contaminants, and roof material leachate. Treat with unscented sodium hypochlorite bleach (plain household bleach, 6\u20138.25% concentration): add 8 drops (0.4 mL) per gallon of clear water, or 16 drops per gallon of turbid water. Double these amounts if bleach is 3\u20136% concentration (check the label). Stir and let stand 30 minutes before use. After 30 minutes, treated water should have a faint chlorine smell \u2014 if it does not, repeat the dose and wait another 15 minutes. If it still has no chlorine smell after two doses, discard the water and start fresh. Bleach loses potency over time \u2014 use bleach manufactured within the last 6 months for reliable disinfection. For stored water, add bleach at the time of filling; rechlorinate every 6 months. Alternative: calcium hypochlorite (pool shock, 68\u201378% concentration) is more stable than liquid bleach and stores for years; use 1/8 tsp per 5 gallons."},{step:5,title:"Contamination Prevention and Annual Container Maintenance",body:"Long-term stored water develops contamination from algae (if light reaches the water), biofilm on container walls, and recontamination from improperly sealed lids. Prevention: use only food-grade containers \u2014 HDPE #2 plastic, polypropylene, or food-grade fiberglass. Never use galvanized metal containers (zinc leaches into water), non-food-grade plastics, or any container that held petroleum products. All containers must be opaque or kept in complete darkness \u2014 algae requires light for photosynthesis. A green IBC tote placed in sunlight develops algae within weeks; wrap in dark tarp or paint with outdoor spray paint. Annual maintenance: drain the container completely, scrub interior walls with a soft brush and dilute bleach solution (1 tablespoon bleach per gallon of water), rinse thoroughly twice with clean water, refill with fresh treated water. Inspect all gaskets, fittings, and screens for cracks or gaps. Record the cleaning date on the container."},{step:6,title:"Legal Considerations and Household Water Needs Calculation",body:"Many U.S. states historically restricted or prohibited rainwater collection, though most have since reformed these laws. As of 2025: rainwater collection is fully legal and sometimes incentivized in most states. States with remaining restrictions or permit requirements include Colorado (limited to two 110-gallon barrels per property for outdoor use only under most conditions), and several western states where water rights doctrine applies to precipitation. Always verify your local and state regulations before installing significant collection capacity. Household water needs: drinking water minimum is 0.5 gallons/person/day; FEMA recommends 1 gallon/person/day for emergencies including minimal sanitation. Realistic homestead needs: drinking and cooking 1\u20132 gallons, hygiene (sponge bath) 1\u20132 gallons, dish washing 1\u20132 gallons, toilet flushing (if available) 1.5 gallons/flush. Total realistic minimum: 5\u20138 gallons/person/day. For livestock: chickens need 0.5 cup/bird/day minimum, goats 2\u20134 gallons/day, dairy cows 30\u201350 gallons/day. Factor all uses when sizing your collection and storage system."}],warnings:["Rainwater collected from roofs with asbestos shingles, lead flashing, or treated wood contains toxic leachate \u2014 never collect from these surfaces for any use without thorough testing","A full 55-gallon drum weighs 459 lbs \u2014 ensure any elevated platform is engineered to bear the load; a 1,000-gallon IBC tote weighs over 4 tons when full","Sodium hypochlorite bleach (household bleach) loses 50% of its potency within 6 months of manufacture and is largely ineffective after 1 year \u2014 do not use old bleach for water treatment and check manufacture dates","Collected rainwater is NOT a substitute for tested well or municipal water for drinking without multiple treatment steps \u2014 at minimum, filter then disinfect; ideally filter, disinfect, and UV-treat"],proTips:["A Sawyer Squeeze or Berkey gravity filter provides a final safety layer before drinking collected rainwater \u2014 chemical disinfection kills pathogens but does not remove heavy metals or chemical contaminants that filtration addresses","Calcium hypochlorite (pool shock, 68% concentration, unscented) is the most cost-effective long-term water treatment supply \u2014 a 1-lb bag treats approximately 10,000 gallons and stores reliably for 3\u20135 years if kept cool and dry","Install a sight glass (clear section of tubing or a float gauge) on your cistern so you can monitor water level without opening the container, which introduces contamination risk","Place a sand-and-gravel pre-filter box (filled with washed gravel, then sand, then a layer of activated charcoal) between your roof collection and your cistern \u2014 this settles particulates, improves taste, and reduces the disinfection load before chemical treatment"],relatedGuides:["homestead-001","homestead-002","homestead-003"],source:"Wilderness survival best practices / Traditional homesteading knowledge",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to establish a rainwater collection and storage system for your homestead \u2014 1 inch of rain on 1,000 sq ft of roof yields 600 gallons",immediate:["Install first-flush diverter \u2014 first 1/10 inch of rain per 100 sq ft washes off concentrated contaminants","Screen all inlets with fine mesh to exclude insects \u2014 open water breeds mosquitoes in 4-5 days","Calculate storage need: 5-8 gallons per person per day for basic homestead operation"],then:["Treat with unscented bleach at 8 drops per gallon clear water; stir and let stand 30 minutes before use","Use only food-grade opaque containers \u2014 keep in complete darkness to prevent algae growth"]}},{id:"homestead-005",category:"homesteading",title:"Livestock Slaughter and Butchering Basics",priority:"advanced",tags:["homesteading","butchering","livestock","meat","food"],summary:"Humane dispatch methods by species, proper bleed-out and evisceration procedure, cooling requirements, aging, and food safety.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Humane Dispatch Methods by Animal",body:"Humane dispatch means causing rapid unconsciousness and death with minimal distress. Method by species: Chickens and turkeys \u2014 cervical dislocation is appropriate for small birds and experienced hands: hold the bird by the legs with one hand, place your other thumb and forefinger at the base of the skull, and pull sharply while simultaneously pushing the head back \u2014 this dislocates C1/C2 vertebrae and severs the spinal cord. Alternatively, a sharp hatchet or purpose-built killing cone with a sharp knife across both carotid arteries and the jugular is effective and reliable. Rabbits \u2014 sharp blunt trauma to the back of the skull just behind the ears using a heavy dowel or the back of a hatchet. A .22 blank pistol at point-blank is an alternative. Pigs and goats \u2014 a firearm is the most reliable dispatch method: a .22 LR hollow point or a .38 caliber shot to the forehead aimed toward the opposite ear, at a downward angle. Draw an X between the eyes and ears to identify the target point. Cattle \u2014 must be stunned before bleeding due to size and danger. A penetrating captive bolt stunner (or .22 magnum to the same X-point) renders the animal unconscious; then bleed immediately. Failure to stun cattle before sticking is illegal in commercial operations and dangerous for the handler."},{step:2,title:"Bleed-Out \u2014 Immediately After Dispatch",body:"Bleeding out (exsanguination) must occur immediately \u2014 within 60 seconds \u2014 after dispatch to ensure the heart is still beating, which assists blood evacuation. Retained blood causes meat discoloration (dark spotting), shortened shelf life, and off-flavor. For poultry: after cervical dislocation or stunning, cut both carotid arteries at the neck with a sharp knife \u2014 one cut from side to side just below the jaw works. Allow the bird to hang inverted in a killing cone or by the feet for 2\u20133 minutes until bleeding slows. For pigs, goats, cattle: after stunning, the animal will collapse. Roll it so access to the chest is available. For the chest stick method: insert a sharp, long-bladed knife (6\u20138 inches) at the base of the throat aimed into the chest cavity at a 45-degree angle toward the heart \u2014 sever the aorta and jugular. Blood will flow rapidly. Elevate the hindquarters to assist drainage. For smaller ruminants, a simple throat cut through both carotid arteries and the jugular vein while the animal hangs by its hind legs works well and drains fully in 3\u20135 minutes."},{step:3,title:"Scalding and Hair or Feather Removal",body:"Scalding opens the follicles, allowing feathers or hair to pull free cleanly. Incorrect temperature is the most common scalding error. Poultry scalding: heat water to exactly 145\u2013152\xb0F (63\u201367\xb0C). Higher temperatures begin to cook the skin and tear it during plucking; lower temperatures do not open follicles sufficiently. Submerge the bird by its legs and agitate for 30\u201360 seconds \u2014 test pluck a tail feather; if it pulls free easily, scalding is complete. Over-scalding is immediately apparent when skin tears with light pull. Mechanical drum pickers dramatically speed feather removal; hand plucking takes 5\u201310 minutes per bird. Pigs: heat water to 140\u2013145\xb0F (60\u201363\xb0C). Submerge or pour water over sections and scrape with a bell scraper or the back of a knife \u2014 hair releases in sheets. Repeat on all areas. Target the scrotal area, ears, and head \u2014 these are most difficult. Goats and sheep: most homesteaders skin rather than scald \u2014 pull the hide free starting from the hind legs; no scalding needed."},{step:4,title:"Evisceration \u2014 Sequence and Do-Not-Nick Rules",body:"Evisceration removes the visceral organs (intestines, stomach, bladder) without contaminating the meat with gut contents. Contamination with intestinal bacteria is the primary cause of field-dressed meat spoilage and foodborne illness. For all species: (1) Cut around the vent (anal opening) to free it from the body wall \u2014 this is called the bung cut. Circle the vent completely without cutting into the intestine; pull it out slightly and tie it off with a zip tie or string to prevent fecal contamination. (2) Make a midline belly incision from pubic bone to sternum, cutting only through skin and abdominal wall \u2014 use two fingers as a guide under the blade to lift the body wall away from organs. Go slowly. (3) Reach in and work organs free from the body cavity. The bladder (in pigs and cattle) should come out intact \u2014 a punctured bladder releases urine onto the meat. (4) Remove all viscera completely. (5) Inspect organs for disease signs \u2014 pale or spotted liver, fluid-filled lungs, pus-filled lymph nodes. (6) Rinse the body cavity with cold clean water, then pat dry \u2014 do not leave water pooled in the cavity."},{step:5,title:"Cooling the Carcass \u2014 The 40-Degree Requirement",body:"Rapid and complete cooling is not optional \u2014 it is the single most important food safety step in butchering. The USDA requires carcasses to reach 40\xb0F (4\xb0C) at the deepest point within 24 hours. Above 40\xb0F, bacterial populations double every 20 minutes. A carcass that stays in the 40\u2013140\xb0F danger zone for more than 2 hours begins developing unsafe bacterial loads. Methods for field cooling: hang the carcass in a cool, shaded, fly-free location \u2014 temperatures below 40\xb0F ambient allow natural cooling, which works in late fall and winter butchering. In warm weather (above 50\xb0F), the carcass must be refrigerated or packed with ice bags. Split large carcasses (pigs, cattle) along the spine into two halves immediately after evisceration \u2014 halves cool faster than intact carcasses. For poultry: immerse in an ice-water bath (32\u201334\xb0F) for 30\u201345 minutes immediately after evisceration. The carcass absorbs water and cools rapidly. Dry the bird before refrigerating or freezing. Do not stack warm carcasses \u2014 stacking prevents airflow and creates heat pockets."},{step:6,title:"Aging, Hanging Time, and Carcass Condemnation",body:"Aging improves tenderness and flavor in beef and lamb through enzymatic breakdown of muscle fibers (proteolysis). Poultry and pork benefit minimally from aging and should be used or frozen within days. Beef: hang at 34\u201338\xb0F, 70\u201380% humidity for 7\u201314 days minimum (21\u201328 days for premium dry-aged flavor). The outer surface develops a dry crust (pellicle) that is trimmed away before cutting. Pork: hang at 34\u201338\xb0F for 3\u20135 days maximum \u2014 longer aging in pork produces rancidity in fat. Lamb and goat: 3\u20137 days at 34\u201338\xb0F. Poultry: none \u2014 use or freeze within 24\u201348 hours. Carcass condemnation \u2014 when to discard the whole animal: widespread abscesses (yellow pus pockets scattered through muscle); pneumonia with lung consolidation and pleuritis (fibrous tissue attaching lungs to ribs); septicemia signs \u2014 darkly discolored carcass, blood-tinged fluid in cavities, enlarged discolored lymph nodes throughout the carcass; icterus (jaundice) \u2014 yellow tinting of fat and connective tissue; severe emaciation or cachexia; any tumor involvement of multiple lymph nodes. When in doubt, do not eat it. A single localized abscess can be excised with a 2-inch margin and the rest of the carcass used, but systemic signs condemn the whole animal."}],warnings:["Dispatch a large animal (pig, goat, cattle) only with a firearm \u2014 attempting to dispatch pigs or goats by knife without prior stunning is inhumane, dangerous to the handler, and results in poor meat quality from adrenaline release","Intestinal contamination of meat surfaces causes rapid spoilage and serious foodborne illness (E. coli O157:H7, Salmonella) \u2014 if you nick the intestine during evisceration, flush the contaminated area thoroughly with water and trim away any contacted meat","Do not age poultry or pork at room temperature \u2014 aging applies only to beef and lamb in refrigerated conditions; poultry aged above 40\xb0F will cause foodborne illness","Wear cut-resistant gloves on the non-knife hand during all butchering operations \u2014 knife slips during evisceration and skinning account for the majority of butchering injuries"],proTips:["Keep butchering knives razor-sharp \u2014 a sharp knife requires less force and is significantly less likely to slip than a dull knife; sharpen before each butchering session with a whetstone and steel","A gambrel (a spreader bar that hooks into the Achilles tendons of the hind legs) hung from a sturdy beam or tree branch with a block-and-tackle makes all butchering steps easier, cleaner, and safer than working on the ground","Learn to identify the kidneys and adrenal glands during evisceration \u2014 beef kidney fat (suet) is valuable for rendering into tallow (excellent cooking fat and waterproofing agent); do not discard it","Organ meats (liver, heart, kidneys, tongue) are the most nutritionally dense parts of the animal \u2014 liver from a healthy animal provides more vitamin A, B12, iron, and folate per ounce than any other food; learn to cook and preserve them as a priority"],relatedGuides:["homestead-001","homestead-003"],source:"Wilderness survival best practices / Traditional homesteading knowledge",lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to dispatch and process an animal for food \u2014 humane dispatch and rapid cooling are the two critical safety factors",immediate:["Dispatch humanely by species: poultry via cervical dislocation or sharp knife across both carotids; pigs/goats via firearm to the X-point between eyes and ears","Bleed out within 60 seconds of dispatch while heart still beats \u2014 hang inverted or elevate hindquarters","Eviscerate without puncturing intestines or bladder \u2014 circle the vent, make belly incision using fingers as guide"],then:["Cool carcass to 40\xb0F within 24 hours \u2014 bacteria double every 20 minutes above 40\xb0F","Beef and lamb benefit from aging 7-14 days at 34-38\xb0F; poultry should be used or frozen within 24-48 hours"]}}]},581,[]);
__d(function(e,a,t,r,i,o,n){i.exports=[{id:"power-001",category:"power",title:"Solar Power Basics for Grid-Down",priority:"advanced",tags:["power","solar","energy","grid-down"],summary:"Size, wire, and operate a basic solar power system to survive extended grid outages.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Understanding Solar Basics",body:"Solar panels generate DC (direct current) electricity from sunlight. That raw DC power must pass through a charge controller before reaching your battery bank, and then through an inverter to produce usable AC power for standard appliances. Rule of thumb: a 100W solar panel generates approximately 30\u201340 amp-hours (Ah) per day in full sun. This figure drops sharply on cloudy days or when panels are shaded or poorly angled. Understanding the flow \u2014 panel \u2192 charge controller \u2192 battery \u2192 inverter \u2192 load \u2014 is the foundation of every solar system."},{step:2,title:"Sizing Your System",body:"Calculate your daily watt-hour (Wh) consumption by listing each device, its wattage, and hours of daily use. Examples: LED lights (5W \xd7 6 hrs = 30Wh), phone charger (15W \xd7 2 hrs = 30Wh), laptop (45W \xd7 4 hrs = 180Wh). Add all Wh values, then multiply the total by 1.25 as a safety factor for inefficiency and weather variation. This gives your minimum daily solar production target. Divide by average peak sun hours in your region (typically 4\u20136 hours in the continental US) to determine the total panel wattage required."},{step:3,title:"Charge Controllers \u2014 PWM vs MPPT",body:"The charge controller sits between your solar panels and battery bank, preventing overcharge and managing current flow. Two main types: PWM (Pulse Width Modulation) \u2014 simple, cheap, but only 70\u201375% efficient; best for small 12V systems where panel voltage closely matches battery voltage. MPPT (Maximum Power Point Tracking) \u2014 more complex, 93\u201397% efficient, extracts 25\u201330% more energy from the same panels, required for larger systems and whenever panel voltage significantly exceeds battery voltage. For any system above 200W or using 24V architecture, MPPT is the correct choice. Size your controller by total panel amperage: a 400W 12V panel array produces ~33A, requiring a 40A controller minimum."},{step:4,title:"Battery Banks \u2014 Types and Sizing",body:"Battery capacity is measured in amp-hours (Ah). Total stored energy in watt-hours = Ah \xd7 voltage. Common chemistries: Flooded lead-acid (cheapest, requires venting and monthly maintenance, ~300\u2013500 cycles to 50% depth of discharge). AGM (sealed, maintenance-free, handles vibration well, moderate cost, similar cycle life to flooded). Lithium LiFePO4 (most expensive upfront, lightest, 2000\u20133000+ cycles, can discharge to 80% without damage, no maintenance). To size your bank: take your daily Wh consumption, divide by battery voltage, and multiply by 2 (for lead-acid, to stay above 50% depth of discharge) or by 1.25 (for lithium). A 200Wh daily need on a 12V system requires at minimum a 100Ah lead-acid bank or 50Ah lithium bank."},{step:5,title:"Inverters and Load Distribution",body:"An inverter converts DC battery power to 120V AC. Two types: Modified sine wave \u2014 cheaper, produces a stepped waveform approximation of AC. Damages or degrades variable-speed motors, medical equipment (CPAP), sensitive audio gear, and some LED dimmers. Pure sine wave \u2014 output is identical to utility power; safe for all devices. Always choose pure sine for medical equipment and electronics. Size your inverter to the largest single load or combined load you'll run, plus 20% margin. Distribute loads deliberately: prioritize refrigerator, lighting, and communication. Use a power strip with surge protector between inverter and sensitive electronics."},{step:6,title:"Wiring and Safety",body:"Proper wiring is the difference between a functional system and a fire. Key rules: install an appropriately-rated fuse within 12 inches of the battery on every positive cable run. Use the correct AWG wire gauge \u2014 undersized wire causes voltage drop and heat. Quick reference: 12V system, 20A load = 10 AWG minimum for runs under 10 feet; 30A load = 8 AWG; 50A load = 6 AWG. Use ring terminal crimps (not tape-wrapped bare wire) on all battery connections. Keep your battery bank in a ventilated area \u2014 lead-acid batteries off-gas hydrogen during charging. Label all conductors with polarity and circuit. All connections should be snug, corrosion-free, and periodically inspected."}],warnings:["Never connect solar panels directly to a battery without a charge controller \u2014 unregulated charging destroys batteries and can cause fire.","Lead-acid batteries emit hydrogen gas during charging \u2014 never operate near open flame, sparks, or in sealed spaces.","MC4 connectors on solar panels carry live voltage any time panels are exposed to light \u2014 never make or break bare wire connections in daylight."],proTips:["A single 100W panel + 100Ah AGM battery + 400W pure sine inverter is a viable baseline survival power system buildable for $300\u2013$400.","A 45W foldable panel can charge a battery bank through a vehicle cigarette lighter/USB charging port while you drive or shelter.","South-facing panels tilted at an angle equal to your geographic latitude capture maximum annual solar energy year-round."],relatedGuides:["power-002","power-005","power-006"]},{id:"power-002",category:"power",title:"Deep-Cycle Battery Banks \u2014 Setup and Maintenance",priority:"advanced",tags:["power","batteries","energy-storage"],summary:"Select, configure, and maintain deep-cycle battery banks for multi-day off-grid power.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Battery Chemistry Comparison",body:"Three main chemistries dominate off-grid storage. Flooded lead-acid: lowest upfront cost ($80\u2013$150 per 100Ah), requires monthly electrolyte checks, venting to prevent hydrogen buildup, 300\u2013500 cycles at 50% depth of discharge (DoD). AGM (absorbed glass mat): sealed, no maintenance, handles vibration well, moderate cost ($150\u2013$250 per 100Ah), similar cycle life to flooded but no venting required. Lithium LiFePO4: most expensive ($400\u2013$800 per 100Ah), lightest weight (1/3 the weight of lead-acid equivalent), 2000\u20133000+ cycles, can safely discharge to 80% DoD versus 50% for lead-acid, no maintenance, built-in BMS. For serious grid-down use, lithium pays for itself over time; for budget-constrained situations, flooded lead-acid and AGM remain practical."},{step:2,title:"12V vs 24V System Architecture",body:"12V systems are simpler to integrate with vehicles, standard RV equipment, and consumer devices. They work well for systems up to about 1,000W. 24V systems are more efficient for larger loads because power (watts) equals voltage \xd7 current \u2014 at 24V, you carry the same power at half the current, which means smaller wire gauge requirements, less resistive loss, and smaller breakers. For systems above 1,000W or with long wire runs, 24V is the preferred architecture. A 24V system requires batteries connected in series (two 12V batteries in series = 24V). Most MPPT charge controllers and inverters are available in both 12V and 24V configurations \u2014 choose your system voltage before purchasing any component."},{step:3,title:"Series vs Parallel Wiring",body:"Series wiring connects positive terminal of one battery to negative terminal of the next, which adds voltage while keeping capacity the same. Two 12V 100Ah batteries in series = 24V 100Ah (2,400Wh total). Parallel wiring connects all positive terminals together and all negative terminals together, which doubles capacity while keeping voltage the same. Two 12V 100Ah batteries in parallel = 12V 200Ah (2,400Wh total \u2014 same energy, different configuration). Series-parallel combines both: four 12V 100Ah batteries wired as two parallel pairs connected in series = 24V 200Ah (4,800Wh). Critical rule: all batteries in a bank must be identical chemistry, identical brand and model, and ideally from the same production batch. Mixing old and new batteries forces new batteries to compensate for old ones, degrading the whole bank."},{step:4,title:"State of Charge Monitoring",body:"Knowing your battery's state of charge (SoC) is essential for preventing over-discharge damage. For lead-acid, voltage is a reasonable proxy after a 30-minute rest period (no charging or discharging): 12.7V = ~100% SoC; 12.5V = ~90%; 12.4V = ~75%; 12.2V = ~50% (stop here for flooded/AGM); 12.0V = ~25% (critically low, potential damage); 11.8V or below = severely discharged. A basic digital multimeter can measure this. For lithium, a battery management system (BMS) with a voltage/SoC display or a Bluetooth-enabled battery monitor (Victron BMV-712 or SmartShunt) gives accurate real-time tracking including amp-hours consumed and remaining capacity \u2014 far superior to voltage-only estimation."},{step:5,title:"Lead-Acid Maintenance",body:"Flooded lead-acid batteries require routine maintenance that AGM and lithium do not. Monthly: inspect electrolyte level in each cell (cells are visible under removable caps). Level should be just above the plates \u2014 top off with distilled water only (never tap water \u2014 mineral content damages cells). Every 3 months: perform an equalization charge \u2014 a controlled overcharge at slightly elevated voltage (15.5V for 12V bank) that stirs the electrolyte and dissolves sulfation. Terminals: clean any white/blue corrosion with a paste of baking soda and water (neutralizes acid), rinse, dry, and apply terminal grease. Inspect cables for cracking or corrosion. Record each maintenance event with date."},{step:6,title:"Maximizing Battery Lifespan",body:"Depth of discharge (DoD) is the primary determinant of battery cycle life. A 100Ah flooded lead-acid battery cycled to 80% DoD (down to 20% SoC) may yield only 200 cycles. The same battery cycled to 50% DoD yields 500+ cycles. At 30% DoD, it may yield 1,200+ cycles. Every 10% reduction in average DoD roughly doubles cycle life. In practice: monitor SoC constantly, recharge before reaching your DoD limit, and size your bank large enough that typical daily use doesn't require deep cycling. Temperature also matters: batteries lose capacity in cold and degrade faster in heat. Ideal operating temperature for all chemistries is 50\u201377\xb0F."}],warnings:["Never mix old and new batteries in the same bank \u2014 weak cells force strong cells to overwork, degrading the entire bank rapidly.","Never mix different battery chemistries (e.g., AGM and flooded lead-acid) in the same bank.","Lithium LiFePO4 batteries without a BMS can experience thermal runaway if overcharged or over-discharged \u2014 a BMS is non-optional.","Sulfated batteries (white crystalline crust on terminals or inside cells) may partially recover with slow equalization charging but are often permanently damaged."],proTips:["Four 6V golf cart batteries (L16 or T-105 type) wired in series-parallel provide 12V at 220Ah for roughly $300\u2013$400 \u2014 one of the best cost-per-Wh values in lead-acid storage.","Batteries stored in cold (below 32\xb0F) self-discharge more slowly \u2014 ideal storage temperature is 50\u201360\xb0F.","A dedicated battery monitor (Victron BMV-712 or similar) that tracks amp-hours consumed is worth every dollar \u2014 it prevents over-discharge damage that destroys batteries in weeks."],relatedGuides:["power-001","power-005"]},{id:"power-003",category:"power",title:"Generator Selection and Safe Operation",priority:"critical",tags:["power","generator","safety","fuel"],summary:"Select the right generator size, operate it safely, and avoid the most common deadly mistake.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Sizing Your Generator",body:"Calculate the running watts required for all devices you need simultaneously, then add surge capacity for motor-driven appliances \u2014 motors require 2\u20133\xd7 their running wattage to start. Common loads: standard refrigerator (700W running, 2,100W surge), well pump (1,000W running, 3,000W surge), window AC unit (1,200W running, 3,600W surge), sump pump (800W running, 1,500W surge), 60W equivalent LED (10W running, minimal surge). For a household running essentials \u2014 fridge, lights, phone charging, and a window AC \u2014 a 3,500\u20135,000W generator covers typical needs. Match the generator's surge/peak wattage to your highest single-device surge, not just running total."},{step:2,title:"Generator Types",body:"Conventional portable generators: least expensive ($400\u2013$800 for 3,500\u20135,500W), loud (70\u201385 dB), fuel-hungry even at partial load, produce less-clean power. Inverter generators: more expensive ($800\u2013$2,000 for 2,000\u20134,500W), significantly quieter (50\u201365 dB), use 20\u201340% less fuel through automatic throttling, produce cleaner power (lower THD) that is safe for sensitive electronics and medical equipment. Dual-fuel generators run on gasoline or propane \u2014 valuable for fuel flexibility. Standby generators (whole-home): permanently installed, run on natural gas or propane, start automatically via transfer switch, most expensive ($3,000\u2013$15,000 installed), but zero setup time when the grid fails. For grid-down preparedness, an inverter generator is the best all-around choice for most households."},{step:3,title:"Carbon Monoxide Safety \u2014 The Deadly Mistake",body:"Carbon monoxide (CO) is the most lethal generator hazard. CO is colorless, odorless, and tasteless \u2014 you will not detect it before it incapacitates you. At 400 ppm, CO causes headaches and dizziness within 2\u20133 hours. At 1,600 ppm, incapacitation within 2 hours and death within 3 hours. Generators produce CO at levels exceeding 10,000 ppm in engine exhaust. Absolute rules: generators must be run OUTDOORS ONLY, at least 20 feet from any door, window, or vent opening, with exhaust directed away from the structure. NEVER run in a garage \u2014 even with the door fully open, CO accumulates to lethal concentrations within minutes. Install CO detectors on every level of your home before you need a generator."},{step:4,title:"Fuel Management",body:"Fuel consumption depends on generator size and load level. A 3,500W generator at 50% load consumes approximately 0.5\u20130.7 gallons per hour. At 75% load, 0.7\u20131.0 gallons per hour. A 5-gallon tank at 75% load = 4\u20136 hours of runtime. Calculate your fuel reserve by multiplying daily runtime hours by fuel consumption rate, then multiplying by your target outage duration. For a 7-day outage running 8 hours/day at 0.75 GPH = 42 gallons minimum reserve. Gasoline must be stored with fuel stabilizer (STA-BIL or equivalent). Only refuel when the engine is completely COOL \u2014 gasoline contacting a hot engine or exhaust can ignite instantly. Always turn off the generator and wait 10\u201315 minutes before refueling."},{step:5,title:"Load Shedding and Power Distribution",body:"Running a generator continuously at full rated capacity causes accelerated wear and elevated fuel consumption. Best practice: shed non-critical loads and run the generator at 50\u201375% capacity. Rotate high-draw appliances: run the AC for 2 hours to cool the house, then switch to refrigerator, well pump, etc. Use a surge-protected power strip between the generator's outlets and sensitive electronics. Avoid extension cord daisy-chaining \u2014 each cord adds resistance and voltage drop. Prefer 12 AWG extension cords (rated 20A) over the ubiquitous 16 AWG household cords (rated 13A) for any load above 1,000W."},{step:6,title:"Maintenance Schedule",body:"A generator that won't start is useless in an emergency. Monthly: run the engine under load for 30 minutes (connects fresh fuel through the carburetor, charges starter battery, identifies problems before you need it). First 8 hours of use: change engine oil (break-in period). Every 50 hours of operation: change oil, check air filter, inspect spark plug. Annually: replace spark plug, clean/replace air filter, inspect fuel lines for cracking, test battery if electric start. Before any extended storage (over 30 days): run engine until fuel-starved (drains carburetor to prevent gum/varnish buildup) OR add fuel stabilizer to full tank and run for 10 minutes to distribute through system. Log all maintenance with dates and hours."}],warnings:["CO KILLS. Running a generator indoors \u2014 including in garages with open doors \u2014 causes hundreds of deaths annually in the US. This rule has no exceptions.","Backfeeding a generator to the utility grid through an improper hookup is illegal, potentially fatal to utility linemen, and can destroy your generator. Use a proper transfer switch.","Never refuel a running or recently-run hot generator \u2014 gasoline contacts hot exhaust components and can ignite immediately.","Generators at night or at idle attract attention during civil disturbances \u2014 consider acoustic shielding or operation timing to reduce your profile."],proTips:["A transfer switch ($200\u2013$500 installed by an electrician) is the only safe way to connect a generator to your home electrical panel \u2014 it physically disconnects from the grid before connecting to generator power.","Propane-fueled generators store fuel indefinitely versus gasoline (1\u20132 year shelf life with stabilizer) \u2014 a significant advantage for long-term preparedness.","The Honda EU2200i and Yamaha EF2000iS are the benchmark inverter generators for quiet, fuel-efficient, reliable emergency power \u2014 used extensively by emergency management professionals."],relatedGuides:["power-004","power-005"]},{id:"power-004",category:"power",title:"Fuel Storage \u2014 Safety and Shelf Life",priority:"advanced",tags:["power","fuel","storage","safety"],summary:"Store fuel types safely and legally for extended grid-down scenarios.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Gasoline Shelf Life",body:"Untreated automotive gasoline begins degrading within 3\u20136 months. The primary culprits are oxidation and ethanol content. Modern pump gasoline in the US is typically E10 (10% ethanol blend), which is hygroscopic \u2014 it absorbs atmospheric moisture, accelerating phase separation and corrosion of fuel system components. Ethanol-free gasoline (available at many marinas, small airports, and some dedicated fueling stations) stores significantly longer \u2014 12\u201318 months untreated. Fuel stabilizer (STA-BIL 360, PRI-G) added at the correct ratio extends E10 gasoline to 12\u201324 months. Store fuel in opaque containers away from temperature swings, which accelerate degradation. Label every container with the fill date."},{step:2,title:"Safe Gasoline Storage",body:"Use only approved containers: red plastic gasoline cans (polyethylene, CARB/EPA compliant) or metal jerry cans (NATO-style steel fuel cans). Never use water jugs, milk jugs, or any container not designed for fuel \u2014 they off-gas through the container walls, are structurally weak, and lack proper venting. Maximum capacity per container: 5 gallons plastic, 20L (5.3 gallons) for NATO metal cans. Store in a detached shed, garage, or dedicated outdoor fuel locker \u2014 not in your home or basement. Keep away from water heaters, furnaces, electrical panels, and any ignition source. Typical residential legal storage limit is 25 gallons \u2014 check local fire codes. Store on a cool, ventilated surface. Never stack fuel cans."},{step:3,title:"Diesel Fuel Storage",body:"Diesel is substantially more stable than gasoline. Untreated diesel stores 6\u201312 months without significant degradation. With a quality diesel stabilizer (PRI-D, Sta-Bil Diesel), shelf life extends to 24+ months. Diesel has a flash point of 125\u2013180\xb0F versus gasoline's \u221245\xb0F, making it significantly safer to store and handle. No explosion risk from vapor at room temperature. Primary long-term storage threat for diesel is microbial growth \u2014 bacteria and fungi thrive at the water/diesel interface in storage tanks. A diesel biocide (Biobor JF) added at fill prevents this. Diesel is the preferred fuel for serious long-term storage and for anyone running diesel generators, tractors, or vehicles."},{step:4,title:"Propane Storage",body:"Propane is the safest fuel to store for longevity \u2014 it has an indefinite shelf life with no degradation. It is stored as a pressurized liquid in steel cylinders. Store all propane cylinders upright, outdoors or in a detached ventilated structure. Critical point: propane vapor is 1.5\xd7 heavier than air and settles at floor level \u2014 a leaking propane cylinder in a garage or basement creates an explosive layer at ground level that can be ignited by a furnace pilot light, water heater, or even a light switch. Always store propane outdoors. 20 lb cylinders (standard BBQ size) hold approximately 4.6 gallons of propane. Inspect cylinders annually for rust, valve damage, and OPD (overfill protection device) functionality."},{step:5,title:"Rotation Schedule",body:"All fuel storage requires a FIFO (first in, first out) rotation schedule to prevent degradation buildup. Establish a rotation calendar: for gasoline, rotate every 6\u201312 months (transfer stored fuel to your vehicle, refill containers with fresh stabilized gas). For diesel, rotate every 12\u201324 months. Keep a written fuel log attached to or stored with your containers listing: fuel type, fill date, stabilizer added (type and amount), and rotation/disposal date. The simplest system: date labels on every container in large permanent marker. Rotate one container at a time rather than all at once to ensure continuity of supply. Dispose of degraded fuel at a local hazardous waste collection site \u2014 never pour it down drains or on the ground."},{step:6,title:"Fire Safety and Code Compliance",body:"Keep a minimum 5 lb ABC dry chemical or CO2 fire extinguisher mounted within reach of your fuel storage area. Never store fuel near the home's main electrical panel, water heater, furnace, dryer, or any appliance with a pilot light. Ground fuel containers when transferring fuel to prevent static discharge ignition \u2014 metal-to-metal contact between container and receiving vessel before opening either container. Check with your local fire marshal or fire code for legal storage limits \u2014 most jurisdictions allow 25 gallons of flammable liquid (gasoline) and 60 gallons of combustible liquid (diesel) in residential settings with some allowing more in approved storage cabinets."}],warnings:["Gasoline vapors are heavier than air and pool at floor level \u2014 explosive concentrations form invisibly in enclosed spaces with even small leaks.","Never store fuel in non-approved containers such as water jugs or milk jugs \u2014 they are not designed for fuel, off-gas through walls, and are a fire hazard.","If you smell propane, evacuate immediately and call emergency services \u2014 do not use any switches, lighters, or electronics inside the structure."],proTips:["NATO-spec German-design jerry cans (Wavian brand) seal significantly better and resist vapor permeation better than standard US plastic fuel cans \u2014 the premium cost is justified for serious storage.","100LL aviation gasoline (avgas), available at small airports, is ethanol-free and stores longer than automotive gasoline, though it costs more and is not labeled for automotive use.","A 50-gallon diesel drum with a hand-pump bung is the most cost-effective high-volume fuel storage solution for serious preparedness \u2014 stores more, requires fewer containers to manage."],relatedGuides:["power-003","power-001"]},{id:"power-005",category:"power",title:"Inverters and Off-Grid Power Distribution",priority:"advanced",tags:["power","inverter","distribution"],summary:"Select the right inverter type, size it properly, and distribute off-grid power safely.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Pure Sine vs Modified Sine Wave",body:"Pure sine wave inverters produce output that is electrically identical to utility grid power \u2014 a smooth sinusoidal waveform. Modified sine wave (MSW) inverters produce a stepped square wave approximation that carries the right average voltage but has significantly more harmonic distortion. Devices that are damaged or degraded by modified sine wave output: variable-speed motor drives (HVAC, some appliances), medical equipment including CPAP and oxygen concentrators, uninterruptible power supplies (UPS devices), sensitive audio equipment, and some modern LED driver circuits. Devices generally safe on modified sine: incandescent and basic LED bulbs, simple resistive heating elements, basic phone chargers, and laptop power bricks (though some run hotter). When in doubt and budget allows, use pure sine \u2014 it is compatible with all loads and eliminates the risk of silent equipment damage."},{step:2,title:"Sizing Your Inverter",body:"Inverter continuous wattage rating must exceed your peak combined AC load with margin. Add all appliances you may run simultaneously, then add 20% safety margin. Account for inverter efficiency: inverters are 85\u201395% efficient, meaning a 1,000W output load actually draws 1,050\u20131,175W from the battery bank. Inverters also have a surge/peak rating (typically 2\xd7 continuous rating) for motor startup loads \u2014 ensure this exceeds your highest single-device surge requirement. Common sizing: for a home office setup (laptop, lights, router, phone charging) a 600\u20131,000W inverter suffices. For a refrigerator + lights + fan, a 1,500\u20132,000W inverter. For whole-room AC or power tools, 3,000W+. Undersized inverters overload, overheat, and trip their thermal protection \u2014 select one size up from your calculated need."},{step:3,title:"Battery-to-Inverter Wiring",body:"High-current DC wiring between the battery bank and inverter is where most installation errors occur. The wire must be appropriately gauged for the current load. On a 12V system: 1,000W load draws ~83A; 1,500W load draws ~125A; 2,000W load draws ~167A. At 125A, a minimum of 2/0 AWG wire is required for runs under 4 feet \u2014 3/0 AWG for runs up to 8 feet. Keep battery-to-inverter cables as short as possible (under 6 feet ideally) to minimize resistive losses. Install an ANL or MIDI fuse within 18 inches of the battery positive terminal \u2014 this is the critical safety fuse that prevents cable fires in a short circuit event. All connections must be crimped ring terminals, properly torqued, and coated with anti-oxidant compound."},{step:4,title:"Load Prioritization",body:"In a grid-down scenario, treat your inverter output as a limited resource. Categorize all loads before connecting anything: Critical loads (medical equipment, communication devices, emergency lighting) \u2014 always powered. Important loads (refrigerator/freezer for food preservation, phone charging, fans in heat emergencies) \u2014 powered during available capacity. Non-essential loads (television, entertainment, non-emergency appliances) \u2014 powered only when battery bank is full and solar/generator is actively charging. Create a physical load list taped near your inverter showing what's connected to each outlet, wattage, and priority. During low-battery periods, disconnect non-essential loads first, important loads second, and never sacrifice critical loads."},{step:5,title:"Extension Cord Safety",body:"Extension cords are a frequent source of voltage drop and fire risk in improvised power setups. Two fundamental rules: never daisy-chain extension cords (cord-to-cord connections increase resistance and reduce the fire rating), and match cord gauge to load. A 16 AWG extension cord (common household type) is rated for 13A / approximately 1,500W at 120V. Running a 1,200W load through 50 feet of 16 AWG wire causes significant voltage drop and heat. For loads above 1,000W or cord runs over 25 feet, use 12 AWG (20A rated) cords. Label your cords: yellow = 12 AWG heavy duty, white/brown = 16 AWG light duty. Inspect all cords before use \u2014 cracked insulation on an inverter-powered cord in a survival scenario is a fire waiting to happen."},{step:6,title:"Distribution Panel",body:"A small sub-panel with circuit breakers allows organized, safe distribution of inverter power to multiple loads. For a permanent or semi-permanent setup, a 6-space AC sub-panel ($30\u2013$60) with individual breakers for each circuit provides overload protection at the load level, not just at the inverter. Pre-wiring critical circuits to a transfer switch allows instant switchover without running extension cords during an emergency. For a portable setup, a power distribution unit (PDU) with individual breakers per outlet serves the same function. The goal is that each circuit can be individually tripped and reset, rather than having a single inverter overload trip that kills all power simultaneously."}],warnings:["On a 12V system, a 1,500W inverter draws 125+ amps \u2014 any undersized wire, loose connection, or missing fuse in that circuit is a serious fire hazard.","Modified sine wave inverters can silently damage sensitive equipment over weeks or months rather than causing immediate failure \u2014 the damage accumulates undetected.","Never mount an inverter in a sealed or enclosed space \u2014 inverters produce significant heat under load and require airflow for cooling."],proTips:["A quality UPS (uninterruptible power supply) that accepts external battery pack connections provides instant automatic switchover with zero setup time during a power outage.","24V or 48V battery systems are dramatically more efficient for large inverters \u2014 at 48V, a 2,400W load draws only 50A versus 200A at 12V, allowing much smaller and cheaper wiring.","A Victron SmartShunt or similar Bluetooth battery monitor lets you track real-time energy flow and remaining capacity from your phone \u2014 essential for managing a solar + battery system intelligently."],relatedGuides:["power-001","power-002","power-003"]},{id:"power-006",category:"power",title:"Hand-Crank and Portable Emergency Power",priority:"beginner",tags:["power","emergency","portable","low-tech"],summary:"Practical guide to hand-crank radios, solar chargers, and power banks for emergency use.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Hand-Crank NOAA Weather Radios",body:"The hand-crank NOAA weather radio is the minimum viable emergency power and communication device \u2014 every household should own one. Key features to look for: NOAA weather alert reception (automatically triggers alarm for severe weather alerts in your area), AM/FM radio bands, USB phone charging output port, built-in LED flashlight, and a solar panel for supplemental charging. Reputable options include the Midland ER310, Kaito KA500, and RunningSnail Emergency Radio. Realistic expectations: the typical hand-crank generator produces 0.5\u20131W of power. One minute of vigorous cranking yields approximately 20\u201340 minutes of radio playback. This is not a primary power source \u2014 it is a backup to the backup, sufficient to receive emergency broadcasts and make a few phone calls when all other power is exhausted."},{step:2,title:"Power Banks \u2014 Selection and Capacity",body:"Power banks are rated in milliamp-hours (mAh). To translate to phone charges: a modern smartphone has a 3,000\u20135,000 mAh battery. A 10,000 mAh power bank provides approximately 2\u20133 full phone charges accounting for conversion losses (~80% efficiency). A 20,000 mAh bank provides 4\u20136 charges. For 72-hour emergency use for two people, a 20,000 mAh bank minimum. Features to prioritize: USB-C Power Delivery (PD) port for fast charging compatibility with modern devices; USB-A Quick Charge 3.0 for older devices; pass-through charging capability (charge the bank while simultaneously charging a device); solar input port for field recharging. Reputable brands: Anker, UGREEN, Nitecore, Goal Zero. Avoid unbranded units \u2014 actual capacity is often 20\u201330% of the labeled value."},{step:3,title:"Portable Solar Chargers",body:"Foldable portable solar panels in the 15\u201325W range connect to power banks or directly to devices via USB. They are a supplemental charging source, not a primary one. Performance in ideal conditions: a 15W panel in direct, unobstructed summer sun charges a 10,000 mAh power bank in 8\u201312 hours. Cloud cover reduces output by 50\u201380% \u2014 a fully overcast day may produce so little power that self-discharge of the power bank exceeds input. Practical approach: maximize panel exposure by angling toward the sun throughout the day, keep panels clean (dust and water spots reduce output significantly), and use them to top off banks during daylight rather than expecting rapid charging. Quality matters: look for panels specifying actual cell efficiency (20%+ is good) not just wattage claims."},{step:4,title:"Setting Correct Expectations",body:"Hand-crank, small solar, and power banks are communication and lighting tools \u2014 not survival power systems. They will maintain: phone communication (calls, texts, basic apps), radio reception for emergency broadcasts, LED lighting for orientation and safety, and the ability to charge a secondary device (radio, headlamp). They will not power: refrigerators, microwaves, power tools, fans, CPAP machines, or any significant AC appliance. Understanding this hierarchy prevents the most common emergency power mistake: draining your power bank running a device that kills your ability to communicate. Protect communication devices first, lighting second, everything else is secondary."},{step:5,title:"Cold Weather Performance",body:"Lithium-ion batteries \u2014 used in virtually all power banks \u2014 lose significant capacity in cold temperatures. Performance degradation: below 32\xb0F (0\xb0C), expect 20\u201330% capacity loss. Below 14\xb0F (\u221210\xb0C), expect 40\u201350% loss. Below \u22124\xb0F (\u221220\xb0C), batteries may fail to discharge entirely. Additionally, charging lithium batteries below 32\xb0F causes permanent internal damage (lithium plating). In cold weather operations: keep power banks in an inner jacket pocket against your body heat, do not charge power banks in freezing temperatures, and warm them to above 40\xb0F before use. Cold-temperature-rated lithium batteries (LiFePO4 chemistry) handle cold significantly better than standard lithium-ion."},{step:6,title:"Maintenance and Testing",body:"Portable emergency power devices have a short shelf life if neglected. Power banks: discharge and fully recharge every 3\u20136 months to prevent cell imbalance and capacity degradation. Most batteries lose capacity faster when stored at 100% charge \u2014 for long-term storage, keep at 50\u201360% charge. Solar panels: clean the panel surface with a damp cloth periodically and inspect connecting cables for UV cracking. NOAA radios: test the crank mechanism and all charging modes quarterly. Verify NOAA alert reception by initiating a test (most radios have a test alert button). Replace internal batteries in any device that uses rechargeable NiMH cells every 2\u20133 years regardless of use. Document your test dates and results. Equipment that hasn't been tested in 12 months should be considered unreliable."}],warnings:["Cheap solar panels sold at discount stores and online marketplaces rarely deliver their rated wattage \u2014 test before you trust them in an emergency.","Counterfeit power banks from unknown brands commonly contain cells with 20\u201330% of the advertised capacity \u2014 buy from recognized brands with verified reviews.","Never charge lithium power banks in freezing temperatures \u2014 it causes irreversible internal damage that permanently reduces capacity."],proTips:["A Goal Zero Yeti 200X or Jackery Explorer 240 bridges the gap between a power bank and a generator \u2014 187\u2013240Wh capacity, AC output for small appliances, solar input, and a display. The sweet spot for portable emergency power.","Keep a dedicated communications kit (hand-crank radio, 20,000 mAh power bank, foldable 15W solar panel, and all required charging cables) pre-packed in your 72-hour bag and tested quarterly.","USB-C Power Delivery (PD) is the universal standard to target \u2014 charges modern laptops, tablets, and phones significantly faster than USB-A and uses a single cable type for all your devices."],relatedGuides:["power-001","power-003"]}]},582,[]);
__d(function(e,t,a,i,o,r,n){o.exports=[{id:"urban-001",category:"urban",title:"Apartment and High-Rise Emergency Preparedness",priority:"critical",tags:["urban","apartment","high-rise","shelter"],summary:"Specific preparedness strategies for urban vertical living when elevators, utilities, and exits fail.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Know Your Building",body:"Spend 30 minutes on a deliberate building survey before any emergency. Locate and count every stairwell in your building and the number of flights to ground level from your floor. Walk to every exit door \u2014 know which ones are alarmed versus freely accessible. Note fire hose cabinet locations, fire extinguisher locations, and the designated exterior fire assembly point. Locate the building's emergency contact board (typically in the lobby or management office) with the superintendent and emergency contact numbers. Ask management about backup generator coverage \u2014 what does it power? (Typically emergency lighting, elevators, possibly fire suppression systems.) Write a one-page building reference sheet with floor plan sketch, exit locations, and emergency contacts. Keep it in your go-bag."},{step:2,title:"Stairwell Navigation",body:"Elevators will be unavailable during power outages, fires, and many other emergency scenarios. If you live above the ground floor, stairwells are your primary egress route \u2014 know them in darkness. Practice: walk your stairwell descent carrying your go-bag with a phone flashlight as your only illumination \u2014 once. Count the number of doors from your floor to the ground. In smoke conditions, visibility may be near-zero; physical door counting is reliable, visual identification is not. Practical aids: place a strip of reflective tape or a ChemLight/glow stick at stairwell entry door at your floor level (accessible from inside the stairwell) as a floor marker. In the stairwell door, memorize a distinctive tactile marker \u2014 a specific bolt position, a texture difference \u2014 that identifies your floor by feel."},{step:3,title:"Shelter-in-Place vs Evacuate",body:"The default response to most urban emergencies is shelter-in-place \u2014 staying in your apartment is usually safer than moving into the street. Reasons: your apartment is a known, secured space; you have your supplies; street-level during civil disturbance, active air quality events, or chaos is more dangerous than a secured apartment. Evaluate against these criteria: Is the threat inside your building? (Fire, gas leak \u2192 evacuate immediately.) Is the threat immediate to your floor? (Structural damage, flood encroachment \u2192 move.) Is the threat street-level? (Civil disturbance, traffic emergency \u2192 shelter in place above it.) Is there a mandatory evacuation order from authorities? (Follow it.) Default to shelter-in-place unless one of these conditions is met. Revisit the decision every 30\u201360 minutes as information develops."},{step:4,title:"Vertical Evacuation Scenarios",body:"Different emergencies require moving in different directions. Flood: always move up \u2014 water fills from the bottom. Move to the highest accessible floor or roof. Roof access doors should be tested in advance \u2014 some require a key held by building management. Fire: move down via stairwell. If your floor or a lower floor is on fire, move upward, close fire doors behind you, and proceed to roof for helicopter rescue visibility. Do not use elevators in any fire scenario. Medical emergency (personal): your phone works in most stairwells \u2014 call 911 and move toward building entrance to meet responders. Roof as rescue platform: in a genuine emergency where the building is compromised, the roof is a viable helicopter rescue platform. Signal with a mirror, brightly colored clothing, waving both arms, or a ChemLight."},{step:5,title:"Water Pressure and High-Floor Residences",body:"Municipal water systems maintain street-level pressure through a combination of water towers, pumps, and gravity. High-rise buildings above approximately 6\u20138 stories typically rely on electric booster pumps to maintain water pressure on upper floors. When building power fails (either utility or building generator not covering pumps), water pressure fails at your floor within 30\u201360 minutes as the building's reserve pressure equalizes. Solution: fill all available water containers immediately when a power outage occurs or is forecast \u2014 before pressure drops. Fill bathtubs, pots, Tupperware, large Ziplock bags. A WaterBOB bathtub liner ($30) adds 100 gallons of clean storage in one bathtub in under 20 minutes. Know that your hot water heater (if gas-powered) holds 30\u201380 gallons of potable reserve water accessible via its drain valve at the bottom."},{step:6,title:"Light Discipline and Security",body:"In a widespread grid-down scenario, a lit apartment on an otherwise dark building communicates that you have power and resources \u2014 drawing unwanted attention. Light discipline means managing what's visible from outside. Primary rule: no light visible through windows after dark. Hang blankets, heavy curtains, or pre-cut blackout fabric (cardboard + black construction paper) over windows before using any light inside. This applies to candles, lanterns, and phone screens in direct line of sight of windows. Sound discipline applies equally: voices carry through thin apartment walls and empty corridors; cooking sounds, movement, and activity are audible from outside your door. Keep voices low, minimize appliance use that creates distinctive sounds. Know your immediate floor neighbors \u2014 a pre-established mutual aid relationship with even one neighbor dramatically changes your options in a prolonged emergency."}],warnings:["Never use an elevator during a fire or when any fire alarm is active \u2014 elevator shafts become chimneys that concentrate heat and smoke.","Never prop stairwell fire doors open \u2014 they are self-closing for a reason, and open fire doors allow fire and smoke to spread through the stairwell shaft.","The roof is a last resort, not a primary exit \u2014 use it only when all stairwell paths are blocked."],proTips:["A rated emergency rope escape ladder (X-It or Kidde brand, rated for your floor height) is inexpensive insurance for high-rise residents if stairwells become inaccessible and rescue is delayed.","A door security bar (Master Lock 265DCCSEN or similar) costs $30\u2013$50 and adds significant forced-entry resistance to your apartment door during civil disturbance scenarios.","Get to know your immediate floor neighbors now \u2014 one pre-arranged mutual aid agreement with a trusted neighbor multiplies your options and safety margin in any emergency."],relatedGuides:["urban-002","urban-003"]},{id:"urban-002",category:"urban",title:"City Water Outage \u2014 Finding and Storing Urban Water",priority:"critical",tags:["urban","water","city","outage"],summary:"Urban-specific water sourcing and storage when municipal supply fails.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Water Heater Reserve",body:"If your apartment or home has a tank-style water heater (typically 30\u201380 gallon capacity), it contains potable water that is already treated and safe to drink \u2014 it is part of the municipal supply that was treated before entering your building. To access: locate the drain valve at the bottom of the tank (looks like a hose bib). Attach a garden hose or use a bucket. Open the valve. Let the first quart of water run to clear sediment before collecting for drinking. This water supply is gravity-fed and does not require pump pressure to access. A 50-gallon water heater provides one person 25 days of minimum drinking water (2L/day) or a family of four approximately 6 days. This is your highest-priority hidden water supply \u2014 identify it in your home before any emergency."},{step:2,title:"Toilet Tank Reserve",body:"The toilet tank \u2014 the ceramic reservoir behind the seat, not the bowl \u2014 contains clean, potable water that is part of the municipal supply. Each toilet tank holds approximately 1.5\u20133 gallons. Do not flush toilets once a water outage begins \u2014 each flush drains this reserve and it will not refill as pressure drops. Two toilets provides 3\u20136 gallons of clean water for drinking or cooking. The bowl water is NOT potable \u2014 it is contaminated with cleaning chemicals and biofilm. Access the tank water by removing the lid and scooping or pouring directly. You can also drain it through the fill valve by manually triggering the float. Treat the tank as a sealed clean water supply; replace the lid after accessing to prevent contamination."},{step:3,title:"Building Pipes and Reserve Pressure",body:"When water supply fails, significant water remains in your building's pipe network under residual pressure. Open faucets at the lowest point in your unit (typically a floor-level utility faucet or the bathtub) to drain water pooled in pipes above you. Higher floors drain into lower floors through gravity as pressure equalizes \u2014 ground-floor and basement units collect the most pipe reserve. In large commercial or residential buildings, rooftop storage tanks (common in NYC-style buildings over 6 stories) may hold thousands of gallons of reserve water that continues to supply by gravity long after municipal pressure fails. Your building superintendent can tell you if such tanks exist. In hospitals, hotels, and large commercial buildings, dedicated on-site cisterns may provide days or weeks of reserve supply."},{step:4,title:"Urban Water Sources",body:"When building reserves are exhausted, urban environments offer additional sources \u2014 all requiring treatment. Fire hydrant water is municipal supply and technically potable, but accessing it requires specialized wrenches and authorization; in a declared emergency, local authorities may designate distribution points. Ponds, decorative fountains, retention basins, and park lakes are NOT safe to drink without aggressive treatment \u2014 they contain high bacterial loads, algaecides from fountain treatment, heavy metals from urban runoff, and potential pharmaceutical contamination. They are viable for drinking ONLY after filtration (0.1 micron minimum) followed by chemical or UV treatment. Rainwater collected from clean surfaces (not asphalt or lead-painted roofing) is a relatively clean source after allowing first-flush runoff to clear debris."},{step:5,title:"Large-Scale Storage Before Outage",body:"When a water outage is announced or forecast (storm approach, known infrastructure issue), execute immediately: Fill every bathtub with a WaterBOB liner first ($30, holds 100 gallons per bathtub, protects water from contamination). Fill all large pots, Tupperware containers, pitchers, and Ziplock bags. Run your washing machine to the fill point and stop it \u2014 the drum holds 15\u201320 gallons. Fill every available vessel before pressure drops. Calculate: 1 gallon per person per day for drinking and minimal sanitation; 3 gallons per person per day for comfortable living. For 72-hour planning with 2 people, store minimum 6 gallons, target 18 gallons. A 72-hour forecast gives enough time to fill a 55-gallon drum from a garden hose on a balcony or patio."},{step:6,title:"Purification in Urban Context",body:"Municipal water infrastructure failure scenarios range in contamination risk. Pressure loss only (pump failure, broken main): stored water in your pipes and water heater is likely safe \u2014 no new contaminants have entered the system. Boil advisory (potential biological contamination): boil water for 1 minute (3 minutes above 6,500 ft elevation). Filter then treat if drawing from open sources. Chemical contamination (industrial spill, deliberate contamination): standard field filtration and chemical treatment DO NOT remove dissolved chemicals, pharmaceuticals, or heavy metals. Only distillation or reverse osmosis removes chemical contaminants. If confirmed chemical contamination of the municipal supply is announced, do not use any municipal water from taps, pipes, or water heaters \u2014 it is contaminated throughout the system. Evacuate to access bottled or known-clean water."}],warnings:["City fountains and decorative reflecting pools contain algaecides, potentially high bacteria, and chemical additives \u2014 treat aggressively before drinking even after filtration.","Never store water in containers previously used for chemicals, cleaning products, or fuel \u2014 residual contamination cannot be reliably removed.","Chemical contamination of municipal water cannot be made safe with standard survival filtration \u2014 if this is confirmed, evacuate rather than attempting to treat it in the field."],proTips:["A 55-gallon HDPE water storage barrel ($50\u2013$80) on a balcony or patio filled from rain collection provides a substantial building reserve that is completely independent of municipal supply.","A WaterBOB bathtub liner ($30) stored flat in a closet takes 30 seconds to deploy and 20 minutes to fill \u2014 it should be in every urban dweller's emergency kit.","In multi-day urban outages, YMCA facilities, community centers, Red Cross shelters, and major hotels often maintain independent water systems \u2014 know the locations of 3 near your home in advance."],relatedGuides:["urban-001","urban-003"]},{id:"urban-003",category:"urban",title:"Civil Disturbance \u2014 Shelter in Place Protocol",priority:"critical",tags:["urban","security","shelter","civil-unrest"],summary:"Protocols for sheltering safely during civil disturbances without drawing attention or providing access.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Decision Point \u2014 Shelter vs Leave",body:"The first and most important decision in any civil disturbance is whether to stay or move. Civil disturbances are almost always geographically localized \u2014 a specific street, area, or district. Before deciding anything, determine where the disturbance is relative to your location. Sources: local news (TV/radio/streaming), official city Twitter or emergency management feeds, NextDoor or neighborhood apps for real-time neighborhood-specific reports. If the disturbance is not in your immediate block or neighborhood, staying home keeps you out of the zone entirely. Leaving during an active disturbance means moving through or toward the problem. Default: shelter in place and monitor. Reassess every 30\u201360 minutes as information updates."},{step:2,title:"Light Discipline",body:"A lit interior visible through windows signals occupation, resources, and potential target value. At night, your lit apartment in a darkened neighborhood is highly visible from the street. Light discipline during civil disturbance at night: close all blinds, curtains, and shades immediately. If you need interior lighting, use the minimum intensity needed and position the light source away from windows rather than directly beside them. An LED headlamp on dim red-light setting preserves your night vision for situational awareness through windows and produces minimal light bleed. Avoid moving past windows holding a light source \u2014 silhouettes are clearly visible from the street. Black paper, construction-grade garbage bags, or blankets hung over windows provide fast, effective blackout coverage."},{step:3,title:"Sound Discipline",body:"Sound travels through apartment walls and windows with surprising clarity \u2014 especially in urban environments that have become quiet during a disturbance. Normal household sounds become conspicuous: television, conversation at normal volume, running appliances, cabinet doors, and movement are audible from hallways and adjacent units. Sound discipline: keep all conversation to a low murmur, turn off the television in favor of a phone with earbuds for news monitoring, silence all phone ringers and notification sounds, and avoid cooking appliances that generate significant noise (blenders, food processors). Move deliberately rather than quickly \u2014 running or heavy movement is audible. Sound discipline is particularly important for building hallways \u2014 sounds through your front door communicate your presence and activity level."},{step:4,title:"Entry Hardening",body:"Standard apartment door locks are weak \u2014 most can be bypassed with forced entry in seconds. Supplemental hardening requires no modification to the door itself. Primary door: a door security bar (Master Lock 265DCCSEN, Buddybar) costs $30\u2013$50 and provides significant resistance by bracing against the floor \u2014 it resists kick-in force rather than relying on the lock mechanism. Rubber door stop wedges (3\u20134 of them stacked) provide basic resistance at minimal cost. Sliding glass doors (patio/balcony): cut a wooden dowel or 1\xd72 board to fit the track \u2014 this prevents the door from being lifted or slid open. Pin secondary security in the upper track with a cut-down steel bar. Windows: standard latches are weak; a secondary window lock bar or pin prevents opening beyond a ventilation gap. Security films on glass windows prevent glass shattering from projectile impact."},{step:5,title:"When to Leave",body:"Certain conditions override the shelter-in-place default and require immediate evacuation. Leave immediately if: fire threatens your position (smoke entering unit, fire on your floor or above \u2014 don't wait for confirmation). You receive a mandatory evacuation order from law enforcement or emergency management \u2014 these are not suggestions. A utility failure creates immediate life-safety risk: gas leak (smell gas \u2192 leave immediately, do not use any switches), structural compromise of your building (obvious damage, building authority declaration). The disturbance physically enters your building \u2014 lobby breach, active confrontation in your corridor. If leaving: your pre-packed go-bag should be ready. Use stairwells \u2014 not elevators. Know your alternate exit from your floor. Pre-identify your destination: a friend's home outside the area, a hotel, or a designated shelter."},{step:6,title:"Communication During a Disturbance",body:"Stay informed through multiple channels simultaneously \u2014 single-source information is vulnerable to delay and gaps. Priority stack: battery/crank NOAA radio for official emergency broadcasts (works when cellular networks are overloaded). Local AM radio stations carry continuous coverage of civil emergencies. Your phone for official emergency management social media feeds and neighborhood apps. Text messaging works when voice calls fail on overloaded networks \u2014 SMS traffic uses different bandwidth. Pre-establish a communication protocol with an out-of-area contact: a person outside the affected region who family members check in with, who then relays status between parties. This prevents overloading local networks with unnecessary calls. Conserve phone battery \u2014 avoid streaming video for news monitoring; prefer radio or text-based updates."}],warnings:["Property defense has serious legal implications \u2014 know your state's specific laws regarding defense of property and use of force before any confrontation.","Do not confront or engage individuals outside your unit \u2014 situations that would have passed by often escalate irreversibly through direct confrontation."],proTips:["Make keeping curtains and blinds closed a daily habit \u2014 during an incident, you'll have nothing to change and no time wasted.","A simple 3-step civil disturbance decision rule: Hear it \u2192 stay home and tune to radio. See it \u2192 move away from windows. Feel it (inside your building) \u2192 execute your exit plan immediately.","Keep $40\u2013$80 in small bills ($5s and $10s) in your go-bag \u2014 card readers and ATMs will likely be offline during extended disturbances."],relatedGuides:["urban-001","urban-004"]},{id:"urban-004",category:"urban",title:"Urban Navigation Without Power",priority:"advanced",tags:["urban","navigation","power-out","movement"],summary:"Navigate a dark, traffic-light-free city using street grids, landmarks, and low-tech techniques.",steps:[{step:1,title:"The Grid Principle",body:"Most US cities were built on grid systems \u2014 streets laid out in parallel and perpendicular patterns with systematic numbering. Understanding your city's grid logic allows dead-reckoning navigation without street signs or maps. Common patterns: in Manhattan, street numbers increase going north (downtown to uptown) and addresses on cross streets increase going west to east. In Chicago, address numbers increase outward from the city center on a consistent grid. In Phoenix, the grid uses numbered avenues (west) and streets (east) from Central Avenue as the zero point. Before an emergency: walk your neighborhood and map these patterns mentally. A city grid allows you to say 'I need to go 8 blocks north and 3 blocks east' and execute it in total darkness without a map."},{step:2,title:"Physical Map Preparedness",body:"Digital maps require power. Physical maps require nothing. Every urban preparedness kit needs a paper street map of your city at a scale detailed enough to show individual streets (1:20,000 or larger). AAA road maps work for regional navigation; local transit authority maps (available free at transit stations) show street grids at usable detail. Laminate your most important map to protect it from rain and folding damage. Download offline maps to your phone using apps that do not require data connection (Google Maps offline areas, Maps.me, OsmAnd) \u2014 these work with GPS only, no cell signal needed. GPS functionality is separate from cell service \u2014 your phone's GPS chip works independently as long as you have battery power."},{step:3,title:"Dead Reckoning in the City",body:"Dead reckoning is the practice of tracking your position by starting from a known point, tracking direction and distance traveled, and calculating your current position without external reference. Urban dead reckoning: establish your starting point (your building address). Note your initial compass direction. Count blocks as you travel \u2014 one city block in most US cities is approximately 250\u2013400 feet (50\u201380 meters). Track turns with their direction and block count. At each turn, update your mental position. City buildings are the most reliable landmarks \u2014 each intersection has a specific building or corner store that is consistent reference. If your mental track diverges from landmarks you recognize, stop and reconcile before continuing."},{step:4,title:"Subway and Underground Networks",body:"Most major US transit systems maintain emergency lighting in subway stations and tunnels \u2014 dim battery-backed lighting at platforms, exit signs, and evacuation routes. Station exits are marked with illuminated or reflective signs in most systems and physically marked with painted text on tile. Know multiple stations near your home and workplace, and know which surface exits they use (many stations have 4+ street exits). NYC: study the subway system's local vs express track differences \u2014 wrong platform can add 30+ blocks. Chicago: know which CTA lines run above vs below grade for different terrain navigation. Critical warning: never use underground tunnels or culverts in any scenario involving flooding or heavy rain \u2014 underground spaces fill rapidly and without warning."},{step:5,title:"Crowd and Bottleneck Avoidance",body:"During a mass evacuation or emergency movement event, crowds naturally flow toward the widest, most recognizable routes: main boulevards, bridges, and transit terminals. These routes bottleneck rapidly and become impassable. Parallel routing: for every major route, identify the parallel side street one block over \u2014 it carries a fraction of the traffic and moves faster. Know your city's secondary bridge and river crossings \u2014 most major bridges have pedestrian paths, and many cities have ferry terminals that are used rarely in normal operations. For cross-borough or cross-river movement: identify at least 3 crossing points, not just the most prominent one. Move earlier than the crowd whenever possible \u2014 the first hour of an evacuation is significantly faster than hour 3."},{step:6,title:"Night Movement",body:"Moving in a city without power at night presents specific challenges: vehicle traffic continues without traffic signals, creating chaotic intersections; other pedestrians are largely invisible; street features that are obvious by day disappear in darkness. Human night vision: the eye dark-adapts fully in 30\u201340 minutes, providing meaningful low-light vision in moonlit or starlit conditions. White flashlight use destroys dark adaptation in seconds and marks your position visibly for blocks. Technique: allow your eyes to fully adapt before moving if possible. Navigate with white light only at moments of immediate necessity. Move along building walls rather than open sidewalks \u2014 walls provide tactile guidance and reduce your exposure profile. Red light (red LED) preserves night adaptation better than white and is less visible at distance."}],warnings:["In a city power outage, all traffic signals fail \u2014 every intersection becomes an uncontrolled 4-way, and vehicle traffic continues. Cross intersections with extreme caution.","Pedestrians on dark streets at night wearing dark clothing are essentially invisible to drivers \u2014 white or reflective material on your clothing or bag is a safety essential."],proTips:["Know 3 identifiable landmarks in each cardinal direction from your home address \u2014 buildings, bridges, or distinctive towers that are visible at distance and serve as navigation anchors without any map.","Pre-identify all bridges, tunnels, and river crossings on a physical map and mark them before you need them \u2014 these are the critical chokepoints in any urban evacuation.","A laminated wallet card with your home address coordinates in decimal degrees (from Google Maps \u2192 right click \u2192 'What's here') and 2\u20133 pre-selected rally points takes 5 minutes to make and works when your phone is dead."],relatedGuides:["urban-005","urban-003"]},{id:"urban-005",category:"urban",title:"Public Transportation Failure \u2014 Getting Home on Foot",priority:"advanced",tags:["urban","navigation","walking","bugout"],summary:"When all transportation fails, execute a planned on-foot return home from anywhere in your city.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Distance Assessment",body:"Know the walking distance from your key daily locations to your home before any emergency. Using Google Maps, measure the walking distance and time from: your workplace, your children's schools, your most frequent secondary locations (gym, regular errands, family member's home). Most urban workers are within 5\u201315 miles of home. Walking performance on flat urban terrain: a fit adult walks 3\u20134 mph; a mixed-fitness adult maintains 2.5\u20133 mph; encumbered with a bag, add 30 minutes per 5 miles. Planning estimate: budget 4\u20136 hours for 12\u201315 miles including rest stops. If you have children, budget 1\u20132 mph slower and plan for more rest stops. This time estimate needs to exist in your head before the event \u2014 calculating it under stress is harder than it sounds."},{step:2,title:"Get-Home Bag",body:"A get-home bag (GHB) is distinct from a bug-out bag \u2014 it is lighter, workplace-appropriate, and optimized for one task: returning to your home from your daily environment. Contents for a GHB kept at your workplace: a pair of broken-in, flat-soled walking shoes (not dress shoes or heels), 1 liter of water plus a filter straw (Sawyer Squeeze or LifeStraw), 2\u20133 protein bars or dense calorie items, a phone charging battery pack (10,000 mAh minimum), $40\u2013$80 cash in small bills, a laminated physical map showing your home-to-work route, a compact rain layer (packable jacket), basic first aid (moleskin, ibuprofen, bandages), and a small LED flashlight. Total weight: under 10 lbs. Keep this in a desk drawer, locker, or inconspicuous bag that travels with you regularly."},{step:3,title:"Route Planning",body:"Pre-plan two complete routes home from your workplace: a primary route and an alternate that diverges significantly. For each route, identify and mark on your physical map: every bridge, tunnel, and elevated crossing (bridges are chokepoints \u2014 know alternatives if primary is blocked or crowded). Rest locations at approximately 3-mile intervals: hospital lobbies (water, warmth, often operational on backup power), fire stations (ask for water during emergencies \u2014 they will typically assist), public libraries, large grocery stores with generators, churches. Mark police precinct locations. Mark areas you assess as potentially problematic (areas you prefer to route around in a high-tension scenario). Study both routes in normal conditions by walking at least part of each one so the territory is familiar."},{step:4,title:"The First 30 Minutes",body:"Resist the impulse to immediately join the flow of people moving. The first 30 minutes after a transit failure are chaotic \u2014 people are making immediate, poorly-informed decisions. Spend this time: gather information from multiple sources (news, official social media, conversations with people from different locations). Assess the nature of the event: is this local (stay) or citywide (go home)? Is it temporary (20-minute delay) or extended (days)? Communicate your status and intentions to your household contact and out-of-area contact. Identify your group: are you moving with coworkers? Establish roles and pace agreements before departing. A 30-minute information-gathering delay frequently saves hours of wrong-direction movement \u2014 people who leave immediately often make poor initial decisions and have to backtrack."},{step:5,title:"Group Movement",body:"Moving with a group of 3\u20135 people is statistically safer than solo travel in a city emergency, provides load distribution, and creates mutual accountability. Establishing group protocols before departing: set the pace to the slowest sustainable pace (not the fastest person's pace \u2014 exhausting the slowest member strands everyone). Assign roles: navigator (holds the map, makes route decisions), rear (maintains situational awareness behind the group), medic (carries and is trained in first aid). Distribute loads \u2014 the person in best physical condition can carry more to equalize the group's speed. Agree on decision-making: who has final say when the group disagrees on route? This disagreement will happen, and settling it now prevents a street argument at a critical moment. Establish regular status checks: every 30 minutes, group stops, checks headcount, status, and route position."},{step:6,title:"Foot Care",body:"Blisters and foot injuries are mission-ending at mile 8\u201310 \u2014 they slow pace, distract attention, and can become infected. The most common cause: wrong footwear. This is why broken-in walking shoes in your GHB are non-negotiable. Dress shoes, heels, and new shoes that aren't broken in create pressure points that form blisters within 3\u20135 miles on pavement. Prevention: wear moisture-wicking socks (not cotton, which holds sweat and causes friction). At the first sign of a hot spot \u2014 a warm, tender area that precedes blister formation \u2014 stop immediately and address it. Apply moleskin, athletic tape, or in a pinch, duct tape over the affected area. Carry an extra pair of dry socks; wet socks from rain or puddles accelerate blistering dramatically. Take a 10-minute foot-airing rest every 2 hours of walking \u2014 remove shoes and socks, inspect, retape if needed."}],warnings:["Do not take shortcuts through unknown alleys, underpasses, or terrain you have not assessed \u2014 in a widespread emergency, isolated routes carry elevated risk from opportunistic threats.","Never wade through flood water at street level in a city \u2014 storm drains and manhole covers are invisible under water and the current in flooded streets can knock adults off their feet."],proTips:["A folding bicycle kept at your workplace transforms a 5-hour walking evacuation into a 1-hour ride on bike lanes and paths that are typically less crowded than pedestrian routes.","On days with elevated risk (major public events, severe weather forecast, high-tension situations), wear your walking shoes to work and have your GHB with you \u2014 preparation cost is zero if nothing happens.","If you know a potential transit failure is coming (storm, major event), drive halfway to work and park at a known garage or street location, shortcutting your potential walking distance in half."],relatedGuides:["urban-004","urban-001"]}]},583,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,o,s,n,a){s.exports=[{id:"psych-001",category:"leadership",title:"Managing Panic \u2014 Yours and Others'",priority:"critical",tags:["leadership","psychology","panic","stress-management"],summary:"Understand the physiological panic response and apply proven techniques to regain control for yourself and calm others.",steps:[{step:1,title:"The Physiology of Panic",body:"Panic is not a character flaw \u2014 it is a predictable physiological response to perceived life threat. The amygdala (the brain's threat-detection center) triggers an adrenaline surge that causes: heart rate spike to 100\u2013180 BPM, peripheral vision narrowing (tunnel vision), fine motor skill degradation (hands shake, fine coordination fails), and downregulation of the prefrontal cortex \u2014 the rational, planning portion of your brain. This is your survival system activating. It is optimized for immediate physical threat response \u2014 run or fight \u2014 not for complex problem-solving. The core challenge in a crisis is that the very brain systems you need for good decision-making are the first to be degraded by the threat response. Recognition of this process as it happens is the first intervention: 'This is the adrenaline response. My brain is narrowing. I need to intervene.'"},{step:2,title:"Tactical Breathing (Box Breathing)",body:"Box breathing is the fastest evidence-based intervention for physiologically downregulating the panic response. Mechanism: controlled breathing activates the vagus nerve, triggering the parasympathetic nervous system (rest-and-digest), which directly counteracts the sympathetic (fight-or-flight) activation. Protocol: Inhale slowly through the nose for 4 counts. Hold breath for 4 counts. Exhale slowly through the mouth for 4 counts. Hold (empty) for 4 counts. Repeat for 4 cycles. Effect: measurable reduction in heart rate within 60\u201390 seconds, partial restoration of prefrontal cortex function within 2\u20133 cycles. Adopted by Navy SEALs (where it is called tactical breathing), emergency room surgeons, and combat veterans because it works under genuine life-threat conditions \u2014 not just exercise-induced stress. Learn it now, before you need it \u2014 technique learned under calm conditions transfers to high-stress conditions."},{step:3,title:"Grounding Technique (5-4-3-2-1)",body:"The 5-4-3-2-1 grounding technique is used for acute panic or dissociation \u2014 states where the individual is losing contact with present reality and spiraling into catastrophic thinking. Protocol: force sensory engagement with the current physical environment by sequentially naming: 5 things you can currently see (describe them specifically \u2014 'the red exit sign, the cracked ceiling tile, the water on the floor'). 4 things you can physically touch right now (press your hands against them). 3 things you can currently hear. 2 things you can smell. 1 thing you can taste. The mechanism: the exercise forces sensory processing through multiple channels simultaneously, which cannot co-occur with abstract fearful rumination. It anchors the person in the present moment, interrupts the catastrophic thought spiral, and restores enough executive function to take the next small action."},{step:4,title:"Calming Others",body:"Panic is contagious \u2014 but calm is equally contagious. Before attempting to calm another person, verify that you have first stabilized your own state with tactical breathing. Attempting to calm someone else from a place of personal panic produces the opposite effect. With the other person: lower your own voice before speaking \u2014 a calm, measured tone at moderate volume is more effective than raised volume. Make appropriate physical contact if the person is receptive: a firm hand on the shoulder or arm creates a physical connection that grounds the panicking person. Use short, direct sentences rather than complex explanations: 'Look at me. Good. Breathe with me.' Never say 'calm down' \u2014 it is not actionable and can increase frustration. Instead, give a task: 'Hold this flashlight here and keep it pointed at that door.' Tasks engage the cognitive system and interrupt the emotional loop."},{step:5,title:"Managing Group Panic",body:"A single panicking individual in a group can cascade \u2014 panic activates threat-detection in observers who then panic themselves, amplifying the original response. Group panic management: first priority is to prevent cascade, not to resolve the individual. Move the panicking person away from the group if possible \u2014 create physical separation before the emotional state spreads. In a fixed space where separation is not possible, the leader's most effective tool is rapid, authoritative action: say something specific, direct, and calm. 'Everyone stop. Listen to me. Here is what we are doing right now.' The specificity ('here is what we're doing') gives people cognitive traction \u2014 something to think about other than the threat. Then give each person a task immediately. People with assigned tasks stop feeding the panic loop and start executing. Track for secondary panic responses in the group for the next 10\u201315 minutes \u2014 initial calming is not permanent resolution."},{step:6,title:"After-Action \u2014 Processing the Response",body:"Panic suppression without acknowledgment creates a delayed response problem \u2014 the unprocessed event resurfaces as intrusive thoughts, irritability, or excessive fear response to subsequent stressors. After the immediate threat has passed: acknowledge that the panic response occurred without shame (it happened, it is a normal physiological event, it does not indicate unfitness). Privately or in a small trusted group, work through: what was the trigger? What early physical signs appeared before full panic (elevated heart rate, tunnel vision, urge to run)? What worked \u2014 breathing, grounding, task assignment? What would I do differently? Build this into your mental model. Each analyzed event improves your recognition speed and intervention effectiveness in subsequent events. This is how emergency professionals develop stress inoculation \u2014 not by being fearless, but by having detailed experience of their own response patterns."}],warnings:["Suppressing panic without acknowledging it creates a delayed cascade \u2014 the unprocessed state emerges later at a worse moment.","Telling someone 'everything is fine' when it is clearly not destroys trust and creates a larger panic response when reality contradicts the false reassurance.","Do not attempt to physically restrain a panicking individual unless they are actively harming themselves or others \u2014 physical restraint often intensifies the panic response."],proTips:["Practice box breathing daily for 5 minutes until it is a completely automatic sequence \u2014 it only transfers to genuine high-stress conditions through repetition, not just knowledge.","As a group leader, your emotional affect is transmitted to your group at approximately 3\xd7 your own perceived intensity \u2014 control your face and voice before you open your mouth in any crisis situation.","The most useful pre-crisis activity is having an honest conversation about panic with your group before an emergency: 'If someone panics, here's what we'll do.' Named protocols reduce the stigma and response time."],relatedGuides:["psych-002","psych-003"]},{id:"psych-002",category:"leadership",title:"Decision Making Under Stress",priority:"advanced",tags:["leadership","psychology","decision-making","OODA"],summary:"Apply proven frameworks for making better decisions when stress degrades cognitive function.",steps:[{step:1,title:"How Stress Degrades Decisions",body:"Under high stress, your brain defaults to System 1 thinking \u2014 fast, automatic, intuitive, pattern-matching cognition that evolved for rapid response to familiar threats. System 1 is effective when the current situation closely matches situations you have encountered before. It is dangerous when the situation is novel, complex, or requires nuanced trade-offs \u2014 exactly what most emergencies present. System 2 thinking \u2014 slow, deliberate, analytical, capable of considering novel problems \u2014 is the first casualty of stress-induced cortisol and adrenaline release. The prefrontal cortex that handles System 2 thinking is literally downregulated by the stress hormones designed to activate System 1. Solution: do not try to think better under stress. Instead, install deliberate decision frameworks into memory through practice, so that when stress forces you into automatic mode, those frameworks are the automatic patterns that activate."},{step:2,title:"The OODA Loop",body:"The OODA Loop was developed by US Air Force Colonel John Boyd through analysis of fighter pilot combat performance in the Korean War. OODA stands for: Observe \u2014 gather raw sensory data from the environment without filtering or interpretation. What is actually, literally happening right now? Orient \u2014 apply context to raw data. What does this mean? What have I seen like this before? What is likely true? What is certainly true? Decide \u2014 select a course of action from the available options. Act \u2014 execute the decision. Then immediately return to Observe with new data. Boyd's insight was that in any competitive or rapidly evolving scenario, the winner is almost always the person or system that cycles through OODA fastest \u2014 not necessarily the one with the best individual decisions. Applied to emergency response: move through the loop quickly, be willing to make small decisions rapidly and update them, and avoid getting stuck in Orient or Decide phases waiting for certainty."},{step:3,title:"Prioritization Framework",body:"When a crisis presents multiple simultaneous problems, the instinct to address the most visible or most emotionally salient problem first is often wrong. A structured prioritization framework prevents this: Step 1 \u2014 Life safety. Immediate threats to human life are addressed first, regardless of resource cost or complexity. Nothing else happens until life threats are addressed. Step 2 \u2014 Prevent escalation. What is currently stable but will become worse if not addressed? A containable fire, a person approaching a dangerous state of mind, a resource that will be lost if not secured. Address these second. Step 3 \u2014 Stabilize. Establish baseline capability \u2014 food, water, shelter, communication. Step 4 \u2014 Optimize. Now improve your position. The sequence exists because people regularly skip Step 1 and 2 to jump to Step 4 \u2014 because optimizing feels productive. Optimization while a fire spreads is a mistake."},{step:4,title:"The Good Enough Decision",body:"Perfectionism kills decision-making under time pressure. The cognitive bias toward seeking a complete solution before acting is adaptive in stable environments and catastrophic in dynamic emergencies. The military standard for decision-making under time pressure is the '70% solution' principle: a decision made on 70% of the information you'd ideally want, executed now, produces better outcomes than the optimal decision executed 30 minutes from now. Why: emergencies are dynamic. By the time you've gathered the remaining 30% of information and decided, the situation has changed and your decision may no longer apply to reality. The objective is to move from no-action to action, accepting that your decision will be imperfect and you will adjust as you observe results. 'Don't let perfect be the enemy of good enough' is not a resignation to mediocrity \u2014 it is an operationally sound approach to time-critical decision-making."},{step:5,title:"Decision Fatigue",body:"Each decision you make depletes a measurable, finite cognitive resource. Research consistently shows that decision quality degrades as the number of decisions made increases, regardless of the individual decision's complexity. This is decision fatigue. In a crisis that requires many decisions over hours or days, fatigue-induced poor decisions accumulate and compound. Mitigations: pre-plan decisions before the crisis. SOPs (standard operating procedures) for predictable events transform a decision into an execution \u2014 no cognitive cost. 'If the building loses power, I do X, Y, Z' requires no decision under stress. Delegate routine decisions to capable group members immediately \u2014 free your cognitive bandwidth for strategic choices. Reduce optionality: fewer choices per decision means less depletion per decision. Preserve significant decisions for your highest-functioning periods (after rest, after eating, early in the day before fatigue accumulates)."},{step:6,title:"When to Delegate",body:"A leader who tries to make every decision in a crisis fails through cognitive overload and creates a dependent group that stops thinking. The test for any decision: Does this require my unique knowledge, authority, or perspective? If the answer is no, it should be delegated to the most capable available person. Effective delegation: assign the task to a named individual (not 'someone'), state the desired outcome rather than prescribing exactly how to achieve it (allows the delegate to apply their own competence), establish a reporting expectation ('Tell me what you find in 15 minutes'), and trust the result unless there is evidence of a problem. Delegation benefits compound: the delegating leader reclaims bandwidth, the delegated-to individual develops competence and confidence, and the group develops capacity for distributed decision-making \u2014 which is more resilient than single-point leadership."}],warnings:["Confirmation bias \u2014 the tendency to seek information that confirms your existing belief \u2014 is dramatically amplified under stress. Actively seek disconfirming evidence and assign someone to argue against your chosen course of action before committing.","Analysis paralysis \u2014 cycling through options without deciding \u2014 is as dangerous as a poor decision in time-critical situations. Set a decision deadline and honor it."],proTips:["Run a pre-mortem before committing to a major decision: ask 'If this plan fails, what are the most likely reasons?' Pre-identified failure modes are far easier to prevent than post-identified ones.","Red-teaming \u2014 assigning someone to actively argue against your decision \u2014 is the most reliable way to catch the blind spots that stress-induced tunnel vision creates.","Write decisions down when possible, even one sentence on paper. The act of writing forces precision and creates a reference that prevents the stress-induced memory distortion that makes people later misremember what they actually decided."],relatedGuides:["psych-001","psych-003"]},{id:"psych-003",category:"leadership",title:"Group Leadership in a Crisis",priority:"advanced",tags:["leadership","group","crisis","authority"],summary:"Establish effective leadership in an improvised group during emergencies, manage conflict, and keep people moving forward.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Establishing Authority",body:"In a crisis, authority is not conferred by title, age, or seniority \u2014 it is earned in real time through demonstrated competence and composure. The person who acts first with visible confidence and specific, correct action draws others. The corollary: the person who hesitates, asks questions without answers, or visibly panics loses the room, regardless of their formal title. In the first minutes of a crisis, people are looking for someone who knows what is happening. Establish authority through action sequence: assess the situation quickly (even 30 seconds of visible, methodical looking around communicates competence). State what you know and what you don't (honesty about uncertainty builds trust; false certainty destroys it when reality diverges). Take one specific visible action that addresses the highest-priority problem. This sequence \u2014 assess, state, act \u2014 done within the first 2 minutes, establishes you as the decision point for the group."},{step:2,title:"The Initial Address",body:"When you have established yourself as the acting leader, your first formal address to the group should occur within the first 2 minutes and follow a specific structure. Acknowledge the situation honestly: 'Here is what has happened: [brief factual statement]. This is serious and we are dealing with it.' State what you know and explicitly state what you don't: 'What I know: [facts]. What I don't know yet: [gaps]. I am finding out.' Give one specific, immediate task to every available person: 'Sarah \u2014 check on everyone in rooms 1 through 5 and report back to me in 10 minutes. Marcus \u2014 find every water source in this building and bring me an inventory. Jenna \u2014 you're with me.' Project control through specificity \u2014 named tasks, specific deliverables, specific timeframes. This communication structure provides cognitive traction for everyone in the group and transforms passive frightened observers into active contributors within 60 seconds."},{step:3,title:"Task Delegation",body:"Effective delegation in an improvised crisis group requires assessing competence in real time with limited information. Prioritize: ask directly for relevant experience ('Does anyone here have medical training? Does anyone have a vehicle? Who has been in this building before?'). Self-reported expertise is the fastest initial signal \u2014 and it comes with accountability when the person volunteers it. Match task to claimed competence. Critical: close the delegation loop with accountability. A delegated task without accountability is often incomplete. 'Marcus, you have 10 minutes to inventory the water sources \u2014 come back to me with what you found whether it's complete or not.' At the checkpoint, acknowledge results (positive or negative) and re-assign as needed. Track all delegated tasks either mentally or on paper \u2014 multiple simultaneous delegations without tracking leads to tasks falling between the gaps."},{step:4,title:"Managing Conflict",body:"Conflict within a crisis group is not a leadership failure \u2014 it is predictable, and handling it is part of the job. Conflict arises from: resource scarcity (who gets what, how much), direction disagreement (where should we go, what should we do), and authority contests (why should you decide, not me). Address conflict directly and immediately \u2014 unresolved conflict consumes group energy, disrupts coordination, and erodes trust. Protocol for conflict in a crisis: acknowledge the disagreement publicly and briefly ('There's a real disagreement here'). Give both positions a single brief hearing (no extended debate \u2014 one exchange each). Make a decision: 'Here's what we're doing and why.' Execute and move. Post-decision, the expectation is compliance even from those who disagreed \u2014 disagreement is allowed, defiance is not. Revisit the decision only if new information significantly changes the situation \u2014 not because the dissenting party continues to lobby."},{step:5,title:"Consensus vs Command",body:"Two leadership styles exist on a spectrum: command (one person decides, others execute) and consensus (all parties deliberate, group decides). Neither is universally correct \u2014 the context determines which is appropriate. Command is appropriate when: decisions are time-critical, life safety is at stake, the leader has clearly superior information or expertise, or the group is in a state of cognitive overload and needs a decision injected. Consensus is appropriate when: time is available, the decision significantly impacts all group members over the long term, the decision is reversible, or buy-in is more important than speed. Critical errors: using command for low-stakes decisions creates resentment and removes group initiative. Using consensus for time-critical decisions causes dangerous delay. Apply the test: 'What is the cost of the wrong decision here, and how much time do I have?' High cost + low time = command. Lower cost + more time = consensus."},{step:6,title:"After-Action and Leadership Transition",body:"Once the immediate crisis phase passes, the leadership structure needs to evolve. Single-leader command is appropriate for emergency response but unsustainable and counterproductive in an extended scenario \u2014 it causes leader burnout, creates dangerous single-point dependency, and generates resentment. Transition to a council or distributed model when the immediate crisis stabilizes: establish a formal group decision-making process with rotating chair, formalize resource distribution rules, and explicitly distribute authority over different domains (one person owns food inventory, one owns medical, one owns security). Conduct a brief after-action review of the crisis response: what worked, what failed, what was our decision quality, what do we do differently next time. Keep it under 30 minutes \u2014 long enough to generate insight, short enough to not exhaust the group. Document decisions and insights where possible."}],warnings:["Authoritarian command leadership produces compliance but eliminates initiative \u2014 people stop observing, thinking, and reporting problems on their own, which is catastrophic in a dynamic emergency where the leader cannot perceive everything.","Losing your composure in front of the group \u2014 raised voice, visible panic, emotional outburst \u2014 can permanently damage your authority in the group, which then reduces your effectiveness when it matters most."],proTips:["Name people explicitly when assigning tasks \u2014 'John, I need you to\u2026' not 'Someone should\u2026'. Named individuals accept accountability; unnamed groups diffuse it and the task frequently goes undone.","The first 10 minutes of crisis leadership sets the psychological tone for the entire event that follows \u2014 invest disproportionately in composure, clarity, and decisive action in that window.","Having a pre-established agreement within your household or team about who leads in different scenarios (fire, medical, security) prevents authority contests from consuming time during the emergency itself."],relatedGuides:["psych-001","psych-002","psych-004"]},{id:"psych-004",category:"leadership",title:"Morale and Psychological Endurance",priority:"advanced",tags:["leadership","psychology","morale","endurance"],summary:"Sustain psychological strength and group morale through extended crisis scenarios.",steps:[{step:1,title:"The 72-Hour Psychological Wall",body:"Most people can sustain high-performance, high-alertness functioning for 24\u201372 hours on the physiological cocktail of adrenaline, cortisol, and urgency that an acute crisis produces. This window also compresses time perception \u2014 48 hours of crisis often feels like 12. After 72 hours, the hormonal response fades, the reality of the situation's duration becomes tangible, exhaustion accumulates, and the grief or loss that was suppressed during the acute phase surfaces. This is the 72-hour psychological wall \u2014 the period where the greatest risk of morale collapse, conflict escalation, and dangerous despair occurs. Leaders who understand this wall plan for it: deliberately schedule a group conversation at the 48-72 hour mark to acknowledge the transition from acute crisis to sustained response, reset expectations, and surface and address the emotional weight the group is carrying."},{step:2,title:"Managing Hope",body:"Hope in a survival context is not optimistic wishful thinking \u2014 it is a specific cognitive state comprising two components: a belief that the situation can improve, and an understanding of what actions are available to improve it. Hope without a path forward is fragile and collapses when external rescue fails to arrive. Path-connected hope is resilient. As a leader, you manufacture hope not through reassurance but through action: 'Here is the problem. Here is what we are doing about it. Here is what improvement looks like.' False hope \u2014 stating rescue timelines you cannot verify, minimizing genuine dangers \u2014 destroys trust when reality contradicts it, and the collapse of false hope is far more demoralizing than the original difficulty. Preferred language: 'I don't know when this ends. Here's what I do know: we have [X days of water], we have [functioning communication], and here's what we're doing today to improve our position.'"},{step:3,title:"Realistic Optimism",body:"The psychological disposition most predictive of sustained performance under adversity is neither optimism nor pessimism but realistic optimism: an accurate, honest assessment of the difficulty of the current situation combined with a genuine belief in the group's capability to manage it. Distinguish it from: toxic positivity ('Everything will be fine!' \u2014 minimizes legitimate concern and erodes credibility); pessimism ('We probably won't make it' \u2014 self-fulfilling, destroys initiative); and denial ('This isn't that bad' \u2014 prevents accurate assessment and preparation). Realistic optimism sounds like: 'This is genuinely hard. We are missing [X]. We're going to lose [Y] if we can't solve [Z]. Here is what we have going for us: [list genuine assets]. And here is the next thing we're going to do.' The combination of honest difficulty + enumerated capability + specific forward action is the most effective morale formula known in leadership psychology."},{step:4,title:"Small Wins",body:"Large problems \u2014 weeks without power, uncertain rescue timeline, depleted supplies \u2014 are psychologically paralyzing because the gap between the current state and the desired state is enormous and the path is unclear. Break large problems into visible daily wins that can be achieved, completed, and celebrated. Examples: 'Today's goal: secure a 3-day water supply.' 'Today's goal: establish contact with the neighbors in units 4 and 5.' 'Today's goal: complete a full inventory of food.' When a small win is achieved, name it explicitly to the group: 'We found 3 gallons of water today. That extends our water supply by 1.5 days. Good work.' The psychology: small wins create evidence that progress is possible, which maintains the belief that larger progress is possible. Track and display wins visibly when you can \u2014 a physical tally, a list on paper, a verbal inventory recited at morning and evening check-in."},{step:5,title:"Routine and Predictability",body:"Anxiety is amplified by unpredictability \u2014 the psychological stress of not knowing what happens next compounds the stress of the actual situation. Creating routine and predictable daily structure reduces ambient anxiety by giving the brain a framework of expected events to navigate rather than a constant stream of uncertainty. Structure elements: fixed wake and sleep times, even if the hours are unusual. A morning briefing (5\u201310 minutes: status update, today's priorities, task assignments). Defined mealtimes, even if meals are small or simple. Regular group check-ins at consistent intervals. Rest periods that are genuinely observed, not just scheduled. Task rotations that give everyone a defined role each day. Children are especially sensitive to routine disruption \u2014 giving children age-appropriate tasks within the group structure (not pretend tasks but genuinely useful ones) maintains their sense of capability and reduces their anxiety transmission to adults."},{step:6,title:"Grief and Loss",body:"In extended crisis scenarios, group members may have experienced or be experiencing loss \u2014 of property, of normalcy, of contact with loved ones, potentially of people. Unacknowledged grief does not disappear; it manifests as behavioral problems: aggression, withdrawal, risk-taking, paralysis, conflict with other group members. Acknowledge grief explicitly and create structured space for it. This does not require professional counseling \u2014 it requires: naming the loss ('We know Marcus lost contact with his family two days ago and we don't know yet if they're okay. That's real and it's hard'), providing a brief period for expression (end of day, 5\u201310 minutes where people can speak or not as they choose), and then returning to forward motion ('We're going to keep going because that's what we can do'). The structure \u2014 acknowledgment + expression + forward movement \u2014 honors the emotion without allowing it to consume the group's capacity to act."}],warnings:["Morale collapse in a survival group is as operationally dangerous as any physical threat \u2014 it leads to inaction, poor decisions, conflict, and group separation. Treat it as a priority threat, not a soft concern.","Never mock or minimize another person's emotional response during a sustained crisis \u2014 what looks like overreaction is often the accumulation of multiple unprocessed stressors expressing themselves at once."],proTips:["Stories of human survival under worse conditions \u2014 polar expeditions, shipwrecks, prolonged captivity \u2014 expand the psychological boundary of what people believe is survivable. Keep a few such stories in your knowledge base and deploy them when the group needs expanded perspective.","Appropriate humor is one of the most effective morale tools available \u2014 it signals that the situation, while serious, has not destroyed the group's ability to find humanity in it. Earn it with real work, then use it.","A predictable small pleasure at a regular interval \u2014 a cup of coffee, a piece of hard candy, a song played on a radio, a few minutes of non-crisis conversation \u2014 has a morale impact disproportionate to its cost. Build it into the daily structure deliberately."],relatedGuides:["psych-003","psych-005"]},{id:"psych-005",category:"leadership",title:"Sleep Deprivation Management",priority:"advanced",tags:["leadership","psychology","sleep","performance"],summary:"Manage sleep deprivation in yourself and your group without compromising safety or decision quality.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Performance Degradation Timeline",body:"Sleep deprivation degrades cognitive performance along a well-documented timeline. 18 hours without sleep: cognitive impairment equivalent to 0.05% blood alcohol content (BAC) \u2014 legally impaired for driving in most US states. 24 hours: equivalent to 0.10% BAC, above the legal limit in all US states. Performance on complex tasks degrades by 25\u201340%. 36 hours: emotional dysregulation begins \u2014 irritability, disproportionate emotional responses, impaired empathy. Early perceptual distortions (misidentifying sounds or shadows) begin. 48 hours: significant memory consolidation failure, severe executive function impairment. Visual hallucinations can begin. 72+ hours: psychosis-like symptoms, profound judgment failure, life-threatening decision errors become likely. The critical and counterintuitive finding: severely sleep-deprived individuals dramatically underestimate their own impairment. A person at 36 hours often believes they are functioning normally. Do not rely on self-assessment for sleep-deprived individuals."},{step:2,title:"Sleep Rotation in Groups",body:"The cardinal rule in any extended crisis scenario: never allow all group members to sleep simultaneously. Establish a watch rotation as a mandatory structure, not a suggestion. Minimum rotation for a group of 4: 2-hour watches (each person sleeps 6 hours in a 8-hour cycle if all 4 participate). For groups of 3: consider 90-minute watches for a 6-hour cycle. Watch rotation rules: the on-watch person has one job \u2014 active alertness. Routine tasks, phone scrolling, or repetitive tasks that allow mental drift are not watch activities. Active watch means: periodic perimeter or building checks at irregular intervals, listening monitoring, note-taking of anything unusual, maintaining the ability to immediately wake the sleeping group. The person coming off watch should verbally brief the incoming watch person on anything observed before sleeping. This hand-off prevents critical information from being lost between rotations."},{step:3,title:"Strategic Sleep Prioritization",body:"When sleep is limited and must be allocated, it should not be distributed randomly. Prioritize sleep for: the primary decision-maker first \u2014 impaired judgment at the leadership level cascades to the entire group. Medical personnel second \u2014 fatigue errors in medical care are particularly consequential. Then rotate based on physical task requirements for the next cycle. If total sleep available is 4 hours, splitting into two 2-hour blocks (with a brief activity period between) is more restorative than a single 4-hour block for some people \u2014 it reduces sleep inertia (the grogginess from deep-sleep stage interruption) if the 4-hour block coincides with deep sleep. In practice: sleep in the longest uninterrupted blocks possible within watch rotation constraints. Even 90 minutes of sleep \u2014 which contains one full sleep cycle \u2014 provides meaningful cognitive recovery compared to zero."},{step:4,title:"Micro-Sleep Recognition",body:"Micro-sleep events \u2014 involuntary sleep episodes lasting 2\u201330 seconds \u2014 begin occurring when an individual is severely sleep-deprived. They happen without warning and without the individual's awareness. Micro-sleeps during critical tasks cause life-threatening lapses: a person driving, on watch, or managing a fire for cooking can micro-sleep mid-task without any subjective awareness of the gap. Precursor signs to watch for in yourself and others: eyes blinking more slowly than normal, eyes losing focus and going glassy, head nodding or dropping and correcting, blank staring rather than active looking, slow verbal response or trailing off mid-sentence, forgetting what was just said. If you are experiencing these precursors, you must stop critical activities immediately. If you observe these in another person, relieve them immediately \u2014 do not leave them in a safety-sensitive position."},{step:5,title:"Caffeine Management",body:"Caffeine is a cognitive performance aid, not a substitute for sleep. It delays the subjective feeling of sleepiness by blocking adenosine receptors, but does not restore the cognitive functions that sleep deprivation degrades. Critically: caffeine masks the subjective experience of impairment while the impairment continues. A caffeine-sustained person can feel alert while performing at 70% capacity. Used correctly, caffeine extends functional performance. Used incorrectly, it creates overconfident impaired people. Strategic caffeine use: 200mg (approximately 1\u20132 cups of coffee or 1 strong energy drink) taken at the natural low points of the circadian rhythm (0200\u20130600 and 1300\u20131500) provides maximum impact. Reserve caffeine for critical decision and action windows rather than continuous use. Caffeine tolerance builds rapidly with sustained use \u2014 if possible, cycle off for 3\u20135 days before a predicted high-demand period to restore sensitivity."},{step:6,title:"Recovery",body:"After extended sleep deprivation, recovery is not instantaneous even with unlimited sleep opportunity. A single 8-hour recovery sleep restores much (not all) of physical performance and basic cognitive function. Two full-night recovery periods restore near-complete cognitive function for most people. Emotional regulation and social judgment are the slowest to recover \u2014 expect irritability, poor social calibration, and overreaction to minor stressors to persist for 24\u201348 hours after physical performance has largely recovered. In a group context: lower the threshold for conflict during post-deprivation recovery. Provide extra space for irritability, slow processing, and emotional responses that seem disproportionate. Avoid irreversible major decisions in the first 24 hours of recovery \u2014 cognitive biases are significantly elevated. Schedule significant decisions for 48+ hours post-deprivation whenever the situation allows."}],warnings:["The most dangerous sleep-deprived person is the one who insists they are fine and is confident in their own judgment \u2014 impaired self-assessment is a core symptom of sleep deprivation.","Do not allow severely sleep-deprived individuals (36+ hours awake) to perform safety-sensitive tasks alone: driving, fire management, medical care, armed watch, or primary decision-making.","Micro-sleeps cannot be prevented through willpower \u2014 if precursor signs are present, the only reliable intervention is actual sleep or immediate removal from safety-critical activities."],proTips:["A strategic 20-minute nap (set an alarm before entering deep sleep \u2014 typically around 20\u201325 minutes after lying down) provides significant cognitive restoration without causing sleep inertia from a deep-sleep stage interruption.","A consistent pre-sleep ritual sequence \u2014 same 3\u20135 actions every time before sleeping \u2014 trains the brain to initiate sleep onset faster, which is valuable when sleep windows are short and every minute of sleep counts.","Brief exposure to bright light (daylight or a bright LED) at the start of a watch period suppresses melatonin and extends alertness for 2\u20133 hours \u2014 a natural, zero-cost performance aid for night watch assignments."],relatedGuides:["psych-004","psych-002"]}]},584,[]);
__d(function(e,t,a,i,r,o,n){r.exports=[{id:"children-001",category:"children",title:"Teaching Kids to Call 911",priority:"critical",tags:["children","emergency","911"],audience:"children",parentGuide:!0,summary:"How to teach children to call 911 confidently and communicate effectively in an emergency.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Address First",body:"Teach children to memorize their full home address including street number, street name, and city. Practice by having them recite it daily for 2 weeks. Make it a game. Address is the single most critical piece of information dispatchers need."},{step:2,title:"What to Say",body:"Script: 'I need help. My address is [ADDRESS]. [NAME OF PROBLEM]. My name is [NAME].' Practice this script until it's automatic. Role-play scenarios: 'Daddy is on the floor and won't wake up.' 'There's a fire in the kitchen.'"},{step:3,title:"When to Call",body:"Call 911 for: someone unconscious or not breathing, a fire, someone breaking in, a serious accident. NOT for: lost toys, power outages (unless someone is hurt), non-emergency questions. The rule: 'Is someone in danger RIGHT NOW?'"},{step:4,title:"Don't Hang Up",body:"Teach children to stay on the line. The dispatcher will talk them through it. 'Stay on the phone with the nice person who answered. They will help you until help arrives.'"},{step:5,title:"Practice Drills",body:"Conduct quarterly 'what would you do' scenarios. Do NOT dial 911 during practice. Use a disconnected phone or simply talk through scenarios verbally. 'If mommy fell and couldn't get up, what would you do? Show me.'"},{step:6,title:"Where Are Phones",body:"Identify all phones in the home and their locations. Know that cell phones can call 911 even without service. Know the neighbor's door number who can help."}],warnings:["Teach children that calling 911 for non-emergencies ties up lines needed for real emergencies. Tell them they will never get in trouble for calling 911 if they genuinely thought it was an emergency."],proTips:["Write your home address on a card and tape it near every phone and to the back of each child's phone/device. Children as young as 3-4 can memorize addresses with consistent practice."],relatedGuides:[]},{id:"children-002",category:"children",title:"What to Do If You're Lost \u2014 Child Version",priority:"critical",tags:["children","lost","wilderness","STOP"],audience:"children",parentGuide:!0,summary:"Teach children the STOP method and survival basics for when they become separated from adults.",steps:[{step:1,title:"STOP",body:"Stop the moment you realize you're lost. Do not keep walking \u2014 every step may take you further from your last known position. Panicking and running is the most dangerous response. Standing still gives searchers a smaller area to search."},{step:2,title:"Think",body:"Take 3 deep breaths. Think about where you last saw your parents or group. Think about what you did to get here. Did you go uphill? Turn right? Cross a stream?"},{step:3,title:"Observe",body:"Look around for familiar landmarks. Can you hear voices, water, or traffic? Can you see buildings, trails, or open sky? Note what is around you."},{step:4,title:"Plan",body:"Make a simple plan: Stay in one place and signal for help. Children should NOT try to find their way out alone in wilderness. Adults will come looking for YOU. Your job is to be VISIBLE and LOUD."},{step:5,title:"Hug a Tree",body:"Literally hug a tree or sit against a large visible object in a clearing. This is your waiting spot. Do not leave it. Searchers will find you faster if you stay put. If you must move, leave a trail of sticks/rocks pointing your direction."},{step:6,title:"Signal",body:"Use your whistle (always carry one): 3 blasts = SOS. Repeat every few minutes. Blow as loud as you can. Shout your name clearly every few minutes. Use a mirror, shiny wrapper, or phone screen to reflect sunlight."}],warnings:["The biggest danger for lost children is walking \u2014 it leads to falls, exhaustion, and makes the search area larger. Trust the rule: STOP and STAY."],proTips:["Every child should wear a bright-colored whistle around their neck in any outdoor setting. The rule 'hug a tree' was created by BC Search and Rescue and has saved hundreds of children's lives. Practice this drill in your backyard so it's automatic."],relatedGuides:[]},{id:"children-003",category:"children",title:"Stranger Safety in Emergencies",priority:"high",tags:["children","strangers","safety","emergency"],audience:"children",parentGuide:!0,summary:"Teach children updated, realistic stranger safety rules that adapt to emergency situations.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Trusted Adults",body:"Children should have a pre-established list of 5 trusted adults (besides parents): specific named family members, teachers, neighbors. Practice naming them. In an emergency, a child should seek these specific people, not 'any adult.'"},{step:2,title:"Safe Words",body:"Establish a family safe word. If someone says 'your mom sent me to pick you up' and doesn't know the safe word, the child does NOT go. Period. Practice: 'What's the safe word?' Safe words should be memorable but not guessable."},{step:3,title:"When the Rules Change",body:"In some emergencies (parent injured, lost), a child may need to approach a stranger for help. Teach the difference: seek a uniformed person first (police, firefighter, paramedic), then a mother with children, then a store employee (behind a counter). Approach in public, visible locations \u2014 never go somewhere private."},{step:4,title:"Information Rules",body:"Children should know their parents' first and last names, one parent's phone number, and their home address. They should NOT tell strangers: their home address (unless calling for help), that they're home alone, or their full daily schedule."},{step:5,title:"In Public Emergencies",body:"If separated during an emergency (earthquake, crowd event): Stay in place at first. Look for uniformed emergency personnel. If none: go to the nearest open store with employees. Do not follow crowds."},{step:6,title:"Practice Scenarios",body:"Role-play monthly: 'A person says your dad is sick at the hospital and they need to take you there. What do you do?' Answer: Ask for the safe word. If they don't know it, go into the nearest building and ask for help calling your parents."}],warnings:["Old 'stranger danger' rules are outdated \u2014 most child abductions are by known adults. Focus on trusted-adult lists and safe words over general stranger avoidance."],proTips:["Write your child's trusted adult list and family safe word on an index card and review quarterly. Children under 8 have difficulty implementing abstract rules \u2014 practice specific scripts rather than general principles."],relatedGuides:[]},{id:"children-004",category:"children",title:"Kids Emergency Contact Card",priority:"high",tags:["children","emergency","contact","card"],audience:"children",parentGuide:!0,summary:"Create and practice using a personal emergency contact card that every child should memorize and carry.",steps:[{step:1,title:"What to Memorize",body:"Every child age 5+ should memorize: full home address, at least one parent's 10-digit phone number, one out-of-area family member's phone number, family safe word, and school address (for older children)."},{step:2,title:"Create the Card",body:"Make a wallet-sized card (3x5 index card, laminated) with: Child's name, Parents' names and phone numbers, Out-of-area contact, Home address, Allergies, Doctor's name and phone, Family safe word (optional \u2014 some families prefer not to write it)."},{step:3,title:"Where to Keep It",body:"Keep one card in: child's school backpack (inside, not visible), child's wallet or coin purse if old enough, sewn into a jacket lining for outdoor activities, and kept by the school nurse."},{step:4,title:"Practice the Info",body:"Weekly or bi-weekly quiz: 'Tell me our home phone number.' Make it a game with small rewards. Practice until it's instant recall, not slow recitation. 10-second recall under stress vs 30-second recall under stress is an important difference."},{step:5,title:"Update Regularly",body:"Review and update the card: whenever you move, when phone numbers change, at start of each school year. Keep a parent copy with the date last updated."},{step:6,title:"Older Children",body:"Children 10+ should also know: family meeting point after school emergency, how to use a payphone or borrow a phone from a stranger (the sequence for calling mom/dad), what to do if phone calls aren't connecting (text, leave voicemail, try alternate contact)."}],warnings:["Do not put child's full name visibly on the outside of backpacks \u2014 it allows strangers to call them by name and appear familiar."],proTips:["Many school emergencies result in phones being jammed with traffic. Pre-establish a family text tree: everyone texts one central family member rather than all texting each other simultaneously."],relatedGuides:[]},{id:"children-005",category:"children",title:"Age-Appropriate Wilderness Basics for Kids",priority:"medium",tags:["children","wilderness","survival","outdoor"],audience:"children",parentGuide:!0,summary:"Teach children fundamental outdoor survival awareness appropriate for their age and stage of development.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Whistle Signals",body:"Every child should carry and know how to use a Fox 40 or similar pea-less whistle: 3 blasts = I need help. 1 blast = I'm OK (responding to someone). Keep whistle accessible (around neck, not in pocket). Blow until someone hears you \u2014 don't stop because you're tired."},{step:2,title:"Stay Visible",body:"In wilderness, visibility is survival. Wear bright colors. If you hear searchers or aircraft, move to the biggest open space you can find (clearing, lakeshore, ridge top). Wave your arms, lay bright items flat on the ground in an X pattern."},{step:3,title:"Basic Fire Safety (ages 8+)",body:"Fire triangle: heat + fuel + oxygen = fire. Three rules for children: Never start a fire without adult supervision. If you find a fire and adults aren't there, move away from it, don't investigate it. In fire, stay low (smoke rises)."},{step:4,title:"Water Safety",body:"Never drink stream, pond, or lake water without adult treatment. Signs of dehydration to tell adults: headache, dark yellow pee, feeling dizzy or very tired. Even if you're very thirsty, finding water is a job for adults."},{step:5,title:"Animal Encounters",body:"Make noise when hiking (talk, sing) to avoid surprise encounters. If you see a wild animal: stop moving, back away slowly, do NOT run. Tell an adult immediately. Do not touch or feed any wild animal \u2014 ever."},{step:6,title:"The Rule of Three",body:"Simplified version for children: You can survive 3 MINUTES without air. 3 HOURS without warmth (in cold and wet). 3 DAYS without water. 3 WEEKS without food. 'If it's cold and wet, staying warm is more important than finding food.'"}],warnings:["Children should not be given adult responsibilities (fire-starting, navigation) until they consistently demonstrate the preceding skills. Overconfidence creates dangerous situations."],proTips:["Buy a bright orange emergency whistle for every child before any camping or hiking trip \u2014 they cost $3-8 and are literally life-saving tools. Teach children that knowing when to ask for help is a skill, not a weakness."],relatedGuides:[]}]},585,[]);
__d(function(e,i,t,n,r,a,s){r.exports=[{id:"fm-001",category:"security",title:"FM 21-76 Urban Survival \u2014 Key Principles",priority:"critical",source:"US Army Field Manual (Public Domain)",tags:["field-manual","survival","urban","military","FM21-76"],summary:"Core principles from the Army Survival Manual adapted for urban grid-down scenarios: signaling, water, shelter, and maintaining will to survive.",steps:[{step:1,title:"The Will to Survive",body:"Psychological toughness is the #1 survival factor per FM 21-76. Use the SURVIVAL acronym as a mental checklist: S \u2014 Size up the situation (surroundings, physical condition, equipment); U \u2014 Undue haste makes waste (slow down and think before acting); R \u2014 Remember where you are (stay oriented to terrain and objective); V \u2014 Vanquish fear and panic (acknowledge fear, then control it through action); I \u2014 Improvise (adapt military tools and techniques to what you have); V \u2014 Value living (your life and your group's lives are worth fighting for); A \u2014 Act like the natives (blend into your environment, avoid standing out); L \u2014 Live by your wits (use knowledge and training, not just gear). Survivors in extreme scenarios consistently report that the decision to live \u2014 made consciously \u2014 was the turning point."},{step:2,title:"Urban Water Sources",body:"Urban structures contain significant water reserves often overlooked: (1) Fire suppression standpipes \u2014 buildings with sprinkler systems have pressurized lines containing treated water; access via hose bib connections. (2) Water heater tanks \u2014 residential units hold 40\u201380 gallons of treated water; drain via the bottom spigot. (3) Toilet tanks (NOT bowls) \u2014 the tank behind the toilet holds 1\u20133 gallons of potable water untouched by bowl contents. (4) Closed-loop HVAC systems in commercial buildings may contain large water volumes. Important: all recovered urban water should still be treated before consumption \u2014 contamination from pipe damage, chemical spill, or system breach is possible. Avoid floodwater entirely; it combines sewage, chemical, and biological hazards."},{step:3,title:"Urban Shelter Priorities",body:"In urban grid-down environments, security takes precedence over comfort \u2014 unlike wilderness survival where warmth and dryness come first. Key principles: (1) Upper floors provide observation advantage and make forced entry more difficult; (2) Ground floor access points must be reinforced or blocked \u2014 door frame reinforcement, window barricades, early warning systems (cans on wire, broken glass on sills); (3) Avoid open fires indoors if possible \u2014 heat signature and smoke column identify your position to opportunistic threats; use rocket stoves vented through existing chimneys or cook only during hours when ambient smoke is common (morning, evening); (4) Thermal signature management: body heat through windows is visible to thermal optics \u2014 use interior rooms; (5) Single entry/exit is a trap \u2014 always identify secondary egress before settling a location."},{step:4,title:"Signaling for Rescue in Urban Areas",body:"When rescue or evacuation is the goal, active and passive signaling increases your chances significantly. Methods: (1) VS-17 signal panel \u2014 international orange/pink panel visible from aircraft at altitude; display on rooftops or open areas. (2) Mirror flash \u2014 improvised signal mirror (CD, chrome surface, makeup mirror) aimed at aircraft; effective range exceeds 10 miles. (3) Whistle pattern \u2014 three blasts repeated = universal distress; pause and repeat; carry a Fox 40 or similar pealess whistle. (4) Ground-to-air signals (stomp or arrange in open area, minimum 10 feet across): X = need medical assistance; arrow pointing = direction of travel; triangle (\u0394) = safe to land here; N = negative/no. (5) Fire and smoke: black rubber smoke (burn tires cautiously) is visible in daytime sky; white smoke from green vegetation is used at night when fire itself is the signal."},{step:5,title:"Urban Navigation Without GPS",body:"GPS-denied urban navigation relies on map literacy and environmental awareness: (1) Grid reference to street intersection \u2014 convert military grid to street address using pre-downloaded offline maps (Maps.me, CalTopo saved tiles); (2) Dead reckoning by block count \u2014 average city block is 260\u2013900 feet depending on city; calibrate to your specific city beforehand; (3) Sun/shadow navigation \u2014 sun rises E, sets W; at noon, shadows point north in northern hemisphere; (4) Building numbering systems \u2014 in US cities, numbers typically increase away from a central baseline; even/odd sides are consistent within a city grid; (5) Utility infrastructure orientation \u2014 water mains follow streets and flow toward treatment plants (typically downhill or toward rivers); power transmission lines lead to substations on the grid periphery; these can orient you when street signs are missing or misleading."}],warnings:["FM 21-76 is a military document \u2014 civilian application requires judgment about context. Tactics appropriate for combat zones may be illegal or counterproductive in a domestic disaster environment.","Urban survival priorities differ significantly from wilderness \u2014 security and concealment matter more in populated grid-down environments where resource competition is higher."],proTips:["Carry a VS-17 signal panel \u2014 it folds to fit in a cargo pocket and is visible from search aircraft at high altitude. Costs under $20 and weighs almost nothing.","Survival is 90% mental \u2014 the will to survive has kept people alive in conditions where it should have been statistically impossible. Maintain purpose, routine, and group cohesion."],relatedGuides:["fm-002","fm-004","water-purification-101","urban-shelter"],lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are in an urban environment during a grid-down scenario and need to apply military survival principles to civilian conditions",immediate:["Apply SURVIVAL acronym: Size up, Undue haste avoidance, Remember location, Vanquish fear, Improvise, Value life, Act like natives, Live by wits","Identify water in urban structures: water heater tanks (40-80 gal), toilet tanks (1-3 gal, not bowls), fire suppression standpipes","Select shelter prioritizing security over comfort: upper floors, multiple exits, blocked ground-level entry points"],then:["Signal for rescue from rooftop: mirror flash, ground-to-air symbols minimum 10 feet across, three-fire triangle","Navigate without GPS using block counts, building numbering systems, sun/shadow direction finding"]}}]},586,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,o,a,n,r){a.exports=[{id:"fm-002",category:"navigation",title:"Navigation by Map and Compass \u2014 Military Method",priority:"critical",source:"US Army Field Manual (Public Domain)",tags:["field-manual","navigation","compass","map","military"],summary:"Military land navigation techniques adapted for civilian grid-down use \u2014 map orientation, contour reading, compass bearings, pace count, resection, and dead reckoning.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Map Orientation",body:"Orienting your map to the terrain is the foundation of land navigation. Method: place compass on map with direction-of-travel arrow pointing toward the top (true north) of the map; rotate the map and compass together until the compass needle aligns with the map's north. Critical step: apply declination correction for your region. US magnetic declination varies from approximately -20\xb0 (Pacific Northwest) to +20\xb0 (Northeast) \u2014 check your specific location at ngdc.noaa.gov/geomag. Failure to apply declination creates compounding positional error over distance. Practical habits: fold map accordion-style so only your current area of operations is exposed (reduces size, protects the rest); laminate or use map case in wet conditions; identify at least two visible ground control points (terrain features visible on both map and ground) before moving."},{step:2,title:"Reading Contour Lines",body:"Contour lines connect points of equal elevation and are the key to reading terrain in 3D. Rules: (1) Each line represents a fixed elevation interval \u2014 check the map legend for the contour interval (commonly 20 or 40 feet on USGS topos); (2) V-shapes pointing uphill (toward higher numbers) = valleys or stream drainages; water flows in the direction the V points; (3) V-shapes pointing downhill = ridges or spurs projecting from high ground; (4) Depression contours have small tick marks pointing inward toward the low point; (5) Closely spaced contour lines = steep terrain (cliff if touching); widely spaced = gentle slope or flat; (6) A closed circle of contours = a hilltop or knob. Practice by identifying a known summit on your topo and tracing contours outward \u2014 this builds the mental translation between flat map and 3D terrain."},{step:3,title:"Taking a Compass Bearing",body:"Procedure for shooting a bearing to a destination: (1) Point the direction-of-travel arrow on your compass baseplate toward your destination; (2) Rotate the bezel (rotating housing) until the orienting arrow aligns with the magnetic needle \u2014 needle must be inside the orienting arrow, not 180\xb0 off; (3) Read the bearing at the index line on the bezel \u2014 this is your magnetic bearing. Declination adjustment: apply your region's declination to convert to a true bearing if your map uses true north. Use the memory rule 'East is Least, West is Best': in eastern US (easterly declination), subtract declination from your magnetic bearing to get true; in western US (westerly declination), add declination. Back-bearing (used to confirm you came from the right direction) = bearing \xb1 180\xb0. Travel technique: shoot bearing, pick a distant landmark on that bearing, navigate to it, re-shoot. Never stare at compass while walking."},{step:4,title:"Pace Count",body:"Pace count measures distance traveled on foot with no electronic aids. Calibration: walk a measured 100-meter course and count every time your LEFT foot strikes the ground; this is your pace count for 100 meters. Average adult is 62\u201366 paces per 100m on flat terrain. Record your personal count on compass housing with a paint pen or tape. Adjustments for terrain: add 15\u201320% for steep uphill; add 10% for dense brush or snow; add 5\u201310% for carrying heavy load; downhill pace count is generally slightly lower. Tracking method: ranger beads (9 beads on upper strand = hundreds of meters, 4 beads on lower strand = thousands of meters); slide one bead per 100m traveled. Limitations: pace count is cumulative-error-prone over long distances \u2014 verify against terrain features every 500m when possible and reset from a confirmed position."},{step:5,title:"Resection \u2014 Finding Your Position",body:"Resection is the technique for determining your unknown position using known landmarks. Procedure: (1) Identify at least 3 landmarks visible both on your map and on the ground (hilltops, road intersections, tower structures); (2) Shoot a compass bearing TO each landmark; (3) Add or subtract 180\xb0 to each bearing to get the back-bearing FROM each landmark; (4) Draw a line on your map from each landmark along its back-bearing (use a straight edge through the landmark in the back-bearing direction); (5) The intersection of the 3 lines is your location. A 'triangle of error' (small triangle rather than perfect intersection) is normal \u2014 you are somewhere inside it; a small triangle indicates high accuracy. Refine by identifying which triangle corner best matches your view of surrounding terrain. Note: resection requires you to positively identify each landmark on both map and ground \u2014 misidentification produces wildly incorrect results."},{step:6,title:"Dead Reckoning",body:"Dead reckoning projects your position forward from a known starting point using bearing and distance. Method: (1) Start from a confirmed known position on the map; (2) Travel on a precise compass bearing for a measured distance (pace count); (3) Plot each leg on the map \u2014 distance in pace count converted to map scale, direction per bearing; (4) Your estimated position is the end of the plotted leg. Multi-leg dead reckoning: record each leg as a vector (bearing + distance) in a navigation log; cumulative error grows with each successive leg, so confirm against terrain features whenever possible and reset the dead reckoning from the confirmed point. Error management: aim-off deliberately toward a known line feature (road, river, fence line) rather than a point target \u2014 when you hit the line feature you know which direction to turn. This eliminates the 'did I overshoot or undershoot?' problem at the destination."}],warnings:["Declination must be applied or positional error will grow to hundreds of meters over a few kilometers \u2014 always verify your local declination before the mission.","A compass held near metal objects, electric wires, or vehicles will give false readings \u2014 move at least 10 meters away from vehicles and 1 meter from personal metal gear before taking a bearing."],proTips:["Write your personal pace count and local declination directly on your compass housing with a fine-tip paint pen \u2014 it is always with you when you need it.","Practice resection in familiar terrain before you need it in an emergency. The skill requires repetition to execute quickly under stress."],relatedGuides:["fm-001","urban-navigation","edc-kit"],lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"medium",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You need to navigate using a topographic map and compass \u2014 GPS is unavailable and you must move to a specific destination",immediate:["Orient map: place compass on map, rotate both together until magnetic needle aligns with map north \u2014 apply local declination correction","Shoot bearing to destination: point travel arrow at target, rotate bezel until orienting arrow aligns with needle, read bearing at index line","Establish pace count on a known 100-meter stretch: count left-foot strikes \u2014 most adults average 62-66 paces per 100m"],then:["Resection to find your position: shoot bearings to 3 known landmarks, take back-bearings, draw lines on map \u2014 intersection is your location","Use aim-off technique: target a line feature (road, river) to the left or right of your destination so you know which way to turn when you hit it"]}}]},587,[]);
__d(function(e,a,i,t,o,n,r){o.exports=[{id:"fm-003",category:"medical",title:"Field Sanitation \u2014 Military Standards",priority:"advanced",source:"US Army Field Manual (Public Domain)",tags:["field-manual","sanitation","hygiene","disease-prevention","military"],summary:"Military field sanitation standards adapted for civilian grid-down camps \u2014 latrine siting, waste disposal, hand hygiene, vector control, water discipline, and field kitchen sanitation to prevent disease outbreak.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Latrine Site Selection",body:"Proper latrine siting prevents the most common cause of group collapse in grid-down scenarios: fecal-oral disease transmission. Minimum standards: (1) Site latrines at least 100 meters (330 feet) from any water source, living area, or food preparation site; (2) Position downhill and downwind from the camp when terrain allows \u2014 prevents contaminated runoff and odor drift toward living areas; (3) Individual cat hole: dig 6\u20138 inches deep (this is the active aerobic decomposition zone where soil bacteria break down waste most effectively); place at least 200 feet from any water source; refill and mound when 2/3 full; (4) Group straddle trench: 1 foot wide x 2.5 feet deep x 4 feet long accommodates approximately 25 people per day; extend length as needed; (5) Mark latrines clearly, especially night-use paths \u2014 trips in the dark without clear marking lead to misuse and contamination of random areas."},{step:2,title:"Waste Disposal and Fly Control",body:"Flies are the primary mechanical vector for fecal-oral disease \u2014 a single fly can carry millions of pathogens from latrine to food surface. Protocols: (1) Cover all human waste immediately after use \u2014 no exceptions; dirt, ash, or a purpose-built latrine cover; (2) Cat hole: refill and mound slightly above grade when 2/3 full (prevents rainwater infiltration and surface exposure); (3) Burn toilet paper separately from waste \u2014 paper buried in cat holes resurfaces; (4) Latrine fly screen: construct a simple screened structure over the straddle trench to prevent fly access while allowing ventilation; (5) Lime or wood ash application: sprinkle a thin layer over waste after each use \u2014 reduces odor, raises pH, and disrupts fly breeding cycle; lime is more effective but ash is widely available; (6) Sandbag or wood seat construction over straddle trench improves compliance \u2014 people avoid latrines that require awkward posturing, leading to misuse."},{step:3,title:"Hand Washing Protocol",body:"Hand washing is the single highest-impact disease prevention measure available in any field environment. Minimum effective procedure when water is scarce: (1) Dampen hands with a small amount of water; (2) Apply soap \u2014 hard soap is preferred for durability; improvised substitutes include wood ash (alkaline, mild antimicrobial effect) or plant-based saponins; (3) Scrub for minimum 20 seconds, covering all surfaces: palms, backs, between fingers, under nails, wrists; (4) Rinse with the minimum water needed to remove soap; (5) Air dry or use a dedicated personal cloth \u2014 shared cloths become fomites. Waterless hand sanitizer requires minimum 60% alcohol concentration to be effective \u2014 lower concentrations do not reliably kill norovirus and many bacteria. Critical moments requiring hand washing without exception: before any food preparation, after latrine use, after treating any wound, after handling animals or animal waste."},{step:4,title:"Vector Control \u2014 Mosquitoes and Rodents",body:"Arthropod and rodent vectors are responsible for malaria, dengue, hantavirus, leptospirosis, plague, and numerous other diseases that become significant threats when medical care is unavailable. Mosquito control: (1) Eliminate all standing water \u2014 even bottle caps and upturned lids hold enough water for Aedes mosquito breeding; patrol camp perimeter for containers, tarps, and hollows; (2) Mosquito activity peaks at dawn and dusk \u2014 schedule outdoor activity accordingly and maximize skin coverage during peak hours; (3) Permethrin treatment of clothing and gear is highly effective and lasts approximately 40 washes \u2014 treat before deployment, not after; (4) Bed nets over sleeping areas drastically reduce nighttime exposure. Rodent control: (1) Eliminate harborage \u2014 dense debris piles, wood stacks against structures, and abandoned equipment all shelter rodents; (2) Store all food in hard-sided sealed containers elevated minimum 18 inches off the ground; (3) Remove dead animals promptly using gloves \u2014 hantavirus is transmitted via aerosolized rodent excreta in disturbed nests."},{step:5,title:"Water Discipline in the Field",body:"Waterborne disease \u2014 primarily diarrheal illness \u2014 is historically the most common cause of incapacitation in field operations. All water must be treated before consumption regardless of apparent source quality. Treatment methods in order of reliability: (1) Boil \u2014 rolling boil for 1 minute (3 minutes above 6,500 ft elevation) kills all pathogens; effective but fuel-intensive; (2) Bleach (sodium hypochlorite 6\u20138.25%) \u2014 8 drops per gallon of clear water, 16 drops if cloudy, wait 30 minutes before drinking; (3) Iodine tablets \u2014 2 tablets per liter, wait 30 minutes (double time if water is cold or turbid); less effective against Cryptosporidium; (4) Mechanical filter (0.2 micron or smaller) removes protozoa and bacteria but not viruses \u2014 must be combined with chemical treatment for complete protection. Canteen discipline: the lip of your canteen contacts your mouth \u2014 your canteen is personal, never shared without full treatment of the container. Shared water sources (pots, jugs) become disease vectors when people drink directly from them."},{step:6,title:"Field Kitchen Sanitation",body:"Foodborne illness can incapacitate an entire group within hours \u2014 field kitchen sanitation is a group survival issue, not a personal preference. Standards: (1) Three-pot wash system: pot 1 = hot soapy wash water; pot 2 = clean hot rinse water; pot 3 = sanitizer solution (1 teaspoon bleach per gallon of water); all dishes, utensils, and cooking pots cycle through all three after every use; (2) Dish temperature: water at or above 160\xb0F for final rinse kills most pathogens on contact; (3) Food temperature danger zone: bacteria multiply rapidly between 40\xb0F and 140\xb0F \u2014 cook food to internal temperature above 165\xb0F; do not leave cooked food in the danger zone for more than 2 hours; (4) Sick cook protocol: any person with fever, diarrhea, vomiting, or skin infection on hands must not handle food for others \u2014 this is non-negotiable in a grid-down environment where a single outbreak can be catastrophic; (5) Insect exclusion: cover all prepared food immediately; work under screening when possible; (6) Waste disposal: food waste must go to a dedicated disposal site away from the kitchen and living areas to avoid attracting both insects and rodents."}],warnings:["A single sanitation failure in a group living situation can produce a disease outbreak that incapacitates everyone within 48 hours. Field sanitation is a group survival issue, not optional personal hygiene.","Cryptosporidium is resistant to iodine and chlorine at normal doses \u2014 boiling or a certified 0.2-micron filter is required for full protection against this common waterborne parasite."],proTips:["A handwashing station at the latrine entrance \u2014 even a simple jug with a drilled hole \u2014 dramatically increases compliance by making hand washing the path of least resistance.","Pre-treat all camp clothing and gear with permethrin before a grid-down scenario; it is far easier to treat before you leave than to manage mosquito exposure in the field with limited supplies."],relatedGuides:["fm-005","water-purification-101","camp-setup","disease-prevention"],lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"basic_edc",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are establishing or managing a multi-person camp and need to implement sanitation practices that prevent disease outbreak \u2014 a single sanitation failure can incapacitate everyone within 48 hours",immediate:["Site latrines minimum 100 meters from any water source, living area, or food preparation \u2014 downhill and downwind from camp","Establish hand washing station at the latrine entrance: dampen, soap, scrub 20 seconds covering all surfaces, rinse, air dry","Eliminate all standing water around camp \u2014 even bottle caps breed mosquitoes in 4-5 days"],then:["Use three-pot wash system for all cooking equipment: hot soapy wash, hot rinse, bleach sanitizer solution","Any person with fever, diarrhea, vomiting, or hand skin infection must not handle food for others \u2014 non-negotiable"]}}]},588,[]);
__d(function(e,o,t,i,a,n,r){a.exports=[{id:"fm-004",category:"security",title:"Immediate Action Drills \u2014 Contact and Escape",priority:"advanced",source:"US Army Field Manual (Public Domain)",tags:["field-manual","security","immediate-action","escape","awareness"],summary:"Simplified civilian adaptation of military immediate action drills \u2014 focused on situational awareness, threat recognition, and rapid escape. NOT combat doctrine. The goal is always to avoid, evade, and escape \u2014 not to engage.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Color Code Awareness System",body:"The Cooper Color Code provides a mental framework for calibrating alertness to environment. White \u2014 unaware, relaxed; this is unsafe in any grid-down public environment where baseline social controls have broken down; only appropriate when sleeping in a secured location with trusted watch posted. Yellow \u2014 relaxed alertness: you are aware of your surroundings, scanning for anomalies, not fixated on any one thing; this is the sustainable baseline for all grid-down movement and public interaction. Orange \u2014 specific alert: you have identified a specific person, vehicle, or situation that may present a threat; you are developing a plan ('if X happens, I will do Y'); you are ready to act but have not yet acted. Red \u2014 action mode: threat has materialized, you are executing your pre-planned response. The key insight: pre-building your 'if-then' plan in Orange means you do not have to think in Red \u2014 you simply execute. Transitions between conditions should be deliberate, not reactive."},{step:2,title:"Contact Recognition",body:"Recognizing a developing threat before it materializes gives you the most critical resource: time to choose your response. Environmental indicators: (1) Mass exodus of bystanders from an area without apparent cause \u2014 people near the threat often know before you do; (2) Vehicles positioned to block egress routes \u2014 especially multiple vehicles at choke points; (3) Individuals converging from multiple directions on a single point (you); (4) Staged strangers who appear to be communicating with each other while appearing unrelated; (5) Animals (dogs, birds) reacting suddenly to a direction before humans are aware of the cause. Sound indicators: gunfire \u2014 immediately get below the level of cover, identify the rough direction of fire, move at 90 degrees away from the direction of fire (not directly away \u2014 direct retreat keeps you in the line of fire longer). Do not run toward the sound to investigate. Your first task is to put distance and cover between yourself and the threat."},{step:3,title:"Immediate Action \u2014 Break Contact",body:"The civilian immediate action drill is built around one goal: break line of sight, gain distance, reach a rally point. Movement: never run in a straight line directly away from a threat; move at 90 degrees to the threat axis \u2014 this takes you out of the most likely engagement direction fastest. Cover vs. concealment: cover stops projectiles (concrete walls, engine blocks, dense earthen berms, large trees); concealment only hides you (car doors, drywall, plywood, most bushes); always prioritize cover over concealment. Move from cover to cover, not across open ground if possible. Breaking line of sight is the priority \u2014 once you are not visible, the threat's ability to track you degrades dramatically. Distance: after breaking line of sight, gain as much distance as terrain allows before slowing to reassess. Do not stop in the first concealed spot \u2014 it is the first place that will be checked."},{step:4,title:"Rally Point Protocol",body:"A rally point is a pre-designated location where group members reassemble after separation. This must be established BEFORE movement \u2014 it cannot be improvised under stress. Two rally points required for any movement: (1) Near rally point (NRP) \u2014 a location within sight or short distance of the current position; used for immediate reassembly if contact occurs; must be a defensible or concealed position; group waits here for 30 minutes before moving to far rally point if not all members have arrived; (2) Far rally point (FRP) \u2014 a pre-planned location away from the area of operations, known to all group members; used after escape when immediate reassembly is not possible or the near rally point is compromised; provides a rendezvous option hours later. Rally point requirements: unambiguous (everyone pictures the same location), defensible or concealed, known to all members, has a time limit (how long to wait before assuming lost members are not coming). Conduct a verbal briefing on both rally points before any movement outside a secure area."},{step:5,title:"Bounding Overwatch for Civilian Movement",body:"Bounding overwatch is a movement technique that ensures at least one person is always in a position to observe and respond while the other moves. Applicable to any high-uncertainty movement: clearing a building, crossing open ground, moving through unknown urban terrain. Basic procedure for pairs: (1) Person A (overwatcher) takes a covered or concealed position with clear view of the route ahead; (2) Person B (mover) moves to the next covered position on the planned route \u2014 approximately 25\u201350 meters in open terrain, shorter in urban environments; (3) Person B signals 'set' (hand signal or verbal in low-noise environments) when in position; (4) Person A moves to the next position, passing Person B or leapfrogging forward; (5) Repeat until objective is reached. Key rule: never have both people moving simultaneously \u2014 this is when a threat can engage without anyone in an observation position. In groups larger than two, the principle scales: half the group moves while half observes and is prepared to respond."}],warnings:["This guide covers situational awareness and escape doctrine for civilians \u2014 it is NOT combat training. Attempting to execute military contact drills without extensive training is dangerous.","The goal is always ESCAPE and AVOID. Physical confrontation is a last resort when all avoidance and escape options have been exhausted.","Use these skills only in genuine self-defense scenarios. Domestic law governs use of force \u2014 know your jurisdiction's laws before any scenario unfolds."],proTips:["Establish near and far rally points with your group before every movement outside your secure area \u2014 even short trips. It takes 60 seconds and eliminates chaos if you get separated.","Practice the color code system daily in normal life. Spending time in Yellow in grocery stores, parking lots, and public spaces builds the habit before you need it under stress."],relatedGuides:["fm-001","fm-002","home-security","group-movement"],lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"intermediate",gearRequired:"none",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],quickGlance:{situation:"You are moving through an uncertain or hostile environment and need a framework for threat recognition and escape \u2014 the goal is always to avoid, evade, and escape",immediate:["Operate in Condition Yellow baseline \u2014 relaxed alertness scanning for anomalies in the behavioral baseline","On contact recognition: move at 90 degrees to threat axis \u2014 not directly away, which keeps you in the line of fire longer","Break line of sight immediately \u2014 prioritize cover (stops projectiles) over concealment (only hides you)"],then:["Move to pre-established Near Rally Point (NRP) \u2014 wait 30 minutes, then Far Rally Point (FRP) if not reunited","Use bounding overwatch for pairs: one person covers from a fixed position while the other moves to the next covered position"]}}]},589,[]);
__d(function(e,i,a,t,n,o,r){n.exports=[{id:"fm-005",category:"medical",title:"Combat Lifesaver Extended Care",priority:"advanced",source:"US Army Field Manual (Public Domain)",tags:["field-manual","medical","trauma","extended-care","CLS"],summary:"Extended field care protocols for when evacuation is delayed 6 or more hours \u2014 reassessment cycles, pain management, wound care, hydration and nutrition, vital sign monitoring without equipment, and casualty packaging for eventual evacuation.",steps:[{step:1,title:"Reassessment Cycle",body:"Extended care begins where initial trauma care ends. Every 15 minutes, reassess in this order: (1) Airway \u2014 verify position is maintained (unconscious casualty may need repositioning if recovery position was used); suction or clear secretions if available; (2) Breathing \u2014 count respiratory rate (normal: 12\u201320 breaths per minute); note quality (shallow, labored, gurgling indicate deterioration); (3) Circulation \u2014 check tourniquet: if more than 2 hours have passed since application, attempt conversion to wound packing with direct pressure if bleeding has stopped and evacuation is not imminent; document tourniquet application time prominently (on forehead with marker, or on tourniquet tag); (4) Consciousness level using AVPU scale: Alert (awake, oriented), Voice (responds to voice), Pain (responds only to painful stimulus), Unresponsive; any downward change is significant; (5) Temperature \u2014 check for hypothermia continuously, not once; wet or shaded casualty loses core temperature rapidly; add insulation, remove wet clothing, use vapor barrier. Log each assessment with time."},{step:2,title:"Pain Management in the Field",body:"Untreated severe pain causes physiological stress response that worsens outcomes \u2014 pain management is a medical intervention, not a comfort measure. Available analgesics ranked by preference: (1) Meloxicam 15mg orally \u2014 NSAID with anti-inflammatory properties; preferred for musculoskeletal injuries, sprains, fractures without hemorrhage; safe for most casualties; give with food if available; (2) Acetaminophen 1,000mg orally \u2014 safe for all injury types including penetrating trauma; does not affect bleeding or hide internal hemorrhage signs; maximum 4g/24 hours total; (3) Ibuprofen 800mg orally \u2014 NSAID, effective but more GI side effects than meloxicam; adequate alternative if meloxicam unavailable. Critical contraindications: do NOT administer aspirin to any trauma casualty (antiplatelet effect increases bleeding); do NOT administer opioids or NSAIDs to penetrating torso trauma (opioids mask deterioration signs indicating internal bleeding; NSAIDs impair clotting). Opioid administration requires specific training, authorization, and ongoing monitoring capability."},{step:3,title:"Wound Care \u2014 Extended Protocols",body:"Initial hemostasis (stopping bleeding) must transition to infection prevention in extended care. Dressing changes: change wound dressings every 24 hours minimum, or immediately when saturated; note wound appearance at each change. Wound irrigation: clean wounds with irrigation before dressing change; improvised irrigation device: fill 20cc syringe, attach 18-gauge angiocath or improvised nozzle, irrigate at 8 PSI (arm's length from wound); clean water is acceptable when sterile saline is unavailable; irrigate until visibly clear. Wound closure decisions: primary closure (suturing or closure strips) is appropriate ONLY for clean wounds that are less than 6 hours old with no contamination and no signs of infection; contaminated wounds, bite wounds, or combat wounds should be left open; delayed primary closure (3\u20135 days post-injury) is preferred for contaminated wounds that are clean and uninfected at reassessment. Infection signs requiring urgent intervention: increasing redness with advancing border, localized warmth and swelling, purulent discharge, fever above 101\xb0F, or red streaking extending from wound (lymphangitis = systemic infection, urgent)."},{step:4,title:"Hydration and Nutrition in Extended Care",body:"Fluid and nutritional support become critical when evacuation extends beyond 6\u201312 hours. Conscious casualty oral hydration: offer small, frequent sips rather than large amounts at once; minimum 2 liters per day for a wounded adult, more in heat or with significant wound drainage; oral hydration takes priority over IV in a conscious, non-vomiting casualty with intact gut. Monitoring hydration status: urine color is the most accessible indicator \u2014 dark yellow to amber = dehydrated, pale yellow = adequate, colorless = over-hydrated (rare in field); absence of urination for 6+ hours = significant dehydration or shock. Nutrition: conscious casualties with intact gut and non-abdominal injuries can begin small amounts of food after 24 hours \u2014 high protein is preferred for wound healing; do not attempt to feed unconscious casualties. IV/IO fluid management (if trained and equipped): Lactated Ringer's is preferred over normal saline for large-volume resuscitation (lower risk of hyperchloremic acidosis); if hemorrhage is not fully controlled, limit IV fluids to 500mL\u20131L and target a palpable radial pulse (permissive hypotension) rather than normal blood pressure \u2014 aggressive IV fluid resuscitation before hemorrhage control 'pops the clot.'"},{step:5,title:"Monitoring Vital Signs Without Equipment",body:"Manual vital sign assessment provides essential information about casualty trajectory. Heart rate: locate radial pulse (wrist, thumb side); if not palpable, check carotid pulse in neck; count beats for 30 seconds and multiply by 2; normal: 60\u2013100 bpm; trauma patients often run 100\u2013120; very fast (>120) plus weak, thready pulse plus pale, cool, clammy skin = shock, reassess hemorrhage control immediately. Respiratory rate: count chest rises for 30 seconds and multiply by 2; normal: 12\u201320; above 30 or below 8 = critical \u2014 reassess airway and breathing interventions. Temperature (without thermometer): assess forehead warmth (back of hand most sensitive); shivering and goosebumps = hypothermia developing; flushed, dry skin plus hot forehead = fever or heat illness. Mental status (AVPU + orientation): ask three questions \u2014 'What is your name? Where are you right now? What year is it?' Confusion or inability to answer indicates hypoxia, hemorrhagic shock, head injury, hypoglycemia, or sepsis; note baseline at first assessment and track any changes; deterioration in mental status is the most sensitive early indicator of worsening condition."},{step:6,title:"Casualty Packaging for Evacuation",body:"When evacuation becomes possible, proper documentation and physical preparation determine continuity of care. Documentation \u2014 the MIST report: Mechanism of injury (fall, gunshot, blunt trauma, burn); Injuries found (anatomic description \u2014 'gunshot wound right thigh, tourniquet applied, wound packed'); Signs and symptoms at time of handoff (last vital signs, mental status); Treatment given (all interventions with times: tourniquet applied 14:35, morphine 5mg IV 15:10, 500mL LR infusing). Record medications given with dose, route, and time \u2014 the receiving provider must know. Allergy documentation must accompany the casualty. Physical packaging: wrap casualty in insulating layer (blankets, sleeping bag, poncho liner) to prevent further heat loss during transport; secure casualty to litter or improvised stretcher; spinal precautions (manual stabilization and padding, not necessarily a rigid collar) for: falls greater than 3 times the patient's height, vehicle accidents with intrusion, diving injuries, or any unconscious trauma patient with unknown mechanism. Continuously reassess airway during transport \u2014 position changes can compromise an airway that was patent at rest."}],warnings:["Extended trauma care requires hands-on training \u2014 reading alone is insufficient preparation. Take a Wilderness First Responder (WFR) or Combat Lifesaver (CLS) course before a grid-down scenario.","Tourniquet conversion (removing a tourniquet after extended application) carries risk of rebleeding and reperfusion injury \u2014 only attempt when you are confident in your wound packing skills and can manage potential rebleeding."],proTips:["Write the tourniquet application time on the patient's forehead with a marker \u2014 'TK 14:35' \u2014 so it is visible to anyone who encounters the casualty, even if your written notes are lost.","The MIST report takes 60 seconds to recite and dramatically improves continuity of care at handoff. Practice saying it aloud during training so it becomes automatic under stress."],relatedGuides:["fm-003","stop-the-bleed","trauma-assessment","hypothermia-treatment"],lastReviewed:"2025-01",skillLevel:"advanced",gearRequired:"advanced_kit",riskLevel:"high",prerequisites:[],whenNotTo:["Do not attempt tourniquet conversion (removing an applied tourniquet) without confidence in wound packing skills and ability to manage rebleeding \u2014 rebleeding from premature conversion can be fatal","Do not administer opioids or NSAIDs to casualties with penetrating torso trauma \u2014 opioids mask deterioration signs; NSAIDs impair clotting","Do not attempt primary wound closure (suturing or closure strips) on contaminated wounds, bite wounds, or combat wounds \u2014 leave open for delayed primary closure at 3-5 days"],quickGlance:{situation:"A casualty has received initial trauma care but evacuation is delayed 6 or more hours \u2014 extended care protocols apply",immediate:["Reassess every 15 minutes in order: Airway \u2192 Breathing (count RR) \u2192 Circulation (tourniquet check, pulse quality) \u2192 Consciousness (AVPU) \u2192 Temperature","Pain management: Meloxicam 15mg or Acetaminophen 1000mg orally \u2014 do NOT give aspirin or NSAIDs to penetrating torso trauma","Document tourniquet application time prominently on forehead with marker: 'TK 14:35'"],then:["Oral hydration for conscious casualty: minimum 2 liters per day \u2014 monitor urine color (pale yellow = adequate)","Prepare MIST report for handoff: Mechanism, Injuries, Signs/symptoms, Treatment given with times"]}}]},590,[]);
__d(function(g,r,_i,a,m,e,d){Object.defineProperty(e,"__esModule",{value:!0}),e.getDrillInfo=n,e.selectDailyDrillQuiz=function(){return n().quizId};var t=r(d[0]);function i(t){let i=0;for(let n=0;n<t.length;n++)i=31*i+t.charCodeAt(n)&2147483647;return i}function n(){const n=(new Date).toISOString().split('T')[0],l=(0,t.getAllQuizzes)();if(0===l.length)return{quizId:'',category:'',difficulty:'',format:'',title:''};const o=l[i(n)%l.length],c='decision_tree'===o.type?o.title:o.scenario?o.scenario.slice(0,70)+'...':o.id;return{quizId:o.id,category:o.category,difficulty:o.difficulty,format:o.type,title:c}}},591,[592]);
__d(function(g,r,i,a,m,e,d){var t=r(d[0]);Object.defineProperty(e,"__esModule",{value:!0}),e.getAllQuizzes=function(){return B},e.getQuizById=function(t){return B.find(u=>u.id===t)},e.getQuizzesByCategory=function(t){return B.filter(u=>u.category===t)};var u=t(r(d[1])),f=t(r(d[2])),l=t(r(d[3])),n=t(r(d[4])),o=t(r(d[5])),c=t(r(d[6])),y=t(r(d[7])),z=t(r(d[8])),s=t(r(d[9])),_=t(r(d[10])),v=t(r(d[11])),Q=t(r(d[12]));const B=[...u.default,...f.default,...l.default,...n.default,...o.default,...c.default,...y.default,...z.default,...s.default,..._.default,...v.default,...Q.default]},592,[1,593,594,595,596,597,598,599,600,601,602,603,604]);
__d(function(e,t,a,i,r,o,n){r.exports=[{id:"quiz-water-001",category:"water",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You approach a clear, still pond in a forest clearing. The water is transparent, no obvious smell. You have no filter or purification tablets. What is the most accurate statement about drinking this water?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Clear water is safe \u2014 clarity indicates no biological contamination"},{id:"b",text:"The water may contain Giardia, Cryptosporidium, or chemical runoff \u2014 appearance cannot confirm safety"},{id:"c",text:"Still water is always more dangerous than moving water"},{id:"d",text:"Water is safe if animals have drunk from it recently"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Clarity has nothing to do with microbiological safety. Giardia cysts and Cryptosporidium oocysts are invisible to the naked eye and survive in crystal-clear mountain streams. Chemical runoff from agriculture or mining is also colorless. The 'animals drink it, so it's safe' logic fails because animals carry and pass many of these pathogens. ALWAYS purify before drinking regardless of appearance.",relatedGuide:"water-001",tags:["water","beginner"]},{id:"quiz-water-002",category:"water",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"After 2 days post-disaster with limited water access, your partner is showing symptoms. Which combination of signs indicates SEVERE dehydration requiring immediate oral rehydration treatment?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Feeling thirsty and slightly tired"},{id:"b",text:"Sunken eyes, dry mouth, rapid weak pulse, and confusion or irritability"},{id:"c",text:"Mild headache and infrequent urination"},{id:"d",text:"Dark yellow urine and occasional dizziness when standing"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Thirst indicates mild dehydration (~1-2% body weight loss). Dark urine/dizziness = moderate (3-5%). Sunken eyes + rapid weak pulse + confusion = severe (6-8%+). At this stage, the person cannot regulate blood pressure adequately. Start ORS immediately: WHO formula is 6 level teaspoons of sugar + 0.5 teaspoon of salt dissolved in 1 liter of clean water. Give 200-400mL every 30 minutes. If unconscious or vomiting, cannot use oral route \u2014 position on side to prevent aspiration.",relatedGuide:"water-001",tags:["water","beginner","dehydration"]},{id:"quiz-water-003",category:"water",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You've found a murky, sediment-heavy pond. You have: a cloth bandana, a water bottle, and iodine tablets. No fire. Place these 5 steps in the correct order to produce the safest drinking water.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Add iodine tablet and replace cap loosely \u2014 wait 30 min (or 60 min if cold/turbid)"},{id:"2",text:"Collect water from 6 inches below surface, away from the bank"},{id:"3",text:"Strain water through doubled-over cloth into bottle to remove sediment"},{id:"4",text:"Shake bottle and loosen cap briefly to disinfect threads and cap"},{id:"5",text:"After wait time, drink \u2014 do not mix with food for 4 hours (iodine affects nutrient absorption)"}],correct_order:["2","3","1","4","5"],explanation:"Collect away from bank (less stir-up, less surface contamination). Strain first \u2014 sediment physically blocks chemical penetration of microbes and is the top cause of tablet failure. Add tablet AFTER straining \u2014 clear water allows iodine to contact pathogens directly. Loosen cap to treat the threads \u2014 a common contamination point. Wait the full time. Cold or turbid water requires double the contact time. Iodine is effective against bacteria, viruses, and Giardia, but NOT Cryptosporidium \u2014 use filter or boiling if crypto risk is high.",relatedGuide:"water-001",tags:["water","intermediate","purification"]},{id:"quiz-water-004",category:"water",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Desert Water \u2014 No Canteen",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"You are in high desert terrain. 8 hours since your last water. Mild headache, urine is dark amber. 200m north you see green vegetation growing on a hillside. 400m east you see the dry bed of a seasonal wash (arroyo). You have a folding shovel. Which do you investigate first?",options:[{text:"Investigate the arroyo for sub-surface water",next:"arroyo_choice"},{text:"Head to the vegetation on the hillside",next:"veg_choice"}]},arroyo_choice:{id:"arroyo_choice",scenario:"Good instinct. Dry washes often have water a foot or two below the surface \u2014 especially at the outside of bends where water pools during flash floods. In the arroyo, where do you dig?",options:[{text:"Dig at the outside curve of the arroyo bend, where the flow was strongest",next:"dig_outside"},{text:"Dig in the flat center of the dry channel where it's widest",next:"dig_center"}]},dig_outside:{id:"dig_outside",outcome:"success",explanation:"The outside bend is where centrifugal force deposited water during flow \u2014 the water table is shallowest there. This is the correct technique. Strain and purify before drinking. Even desert sub-surface water can carry coliform bacteria from animal use upstream."},dig_center:{id:"dig_center",outcome:"poor",explanation:"The center of a wash has the hardest-packed substrate and is often underlain by caliche \u2014 a dense calcified layer that blocks water. Always dig at the outer bend of a curve. You wasted your best energy window of the day after 45 minutes of digging with no result."},veg_choice:{id:"veg_choice",scenario:"You reach the vegetation \u2014 sparse desert willow and some barrel cactus. The green is from shrubs adapted to rocky soil, not necessarily from groundwater. Do you:",options:[{text:"Dig at the base of the largest plant where roots concentrate",next:"dig_roots"},{text:"Cut open a barrel cactus and drink the juice",next:"cactus_juice"}]},dig_roots:{id:"dig_roots",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Desert riparian vegetation doesn't always indicate a water table \u2014 many desert shrubs use capillary moisture from clay or deep taproots that go 30+ feet. You find dry clay at 2 feet. The arroyo was your better bet. Look for cottonwoods or seep willow \u2014 those typically do indicate permanent water."},cactus_juice:{id:"cactus_juice",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Barrel cactus liquid is NOT drinkable. It is high in oxalic acid and magnesium sulfate \u2014 it causes nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea, worsening dehydration faster than not drinking at all. This is one of the most dangerous survival myths. Saguaro and prickly pear fruit pulp (not juice) can be eaten in small quantities, but neither provides enough liquid to matter. The arroyo was the correct primary target."}},relatedGuide:"water-002",tags:["water","advanced","desert","decision-tree"]},{id:"quiz-water-005",category:"water",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You are in a desert with no water source. You have a clear 6-mil plastic sheet (8x8 feet), a shovel, and a collection container. You construct a standard ground solar still with green vegetation added. What is the realistic daily output in IDEAL conditions?",options:[{id:"a",text:"4-6 liters per day \u2014 enough to replace daily fluid loss"},{id:"b",text:"0.5-1 liter per day \u2014 useful supplement but not a primary water source"},{id:"c",text:"2-3 liters per 12 daylight hours if vegetation is added"},{id:"d",text:"Output varies but always exceeds 1 liter \u2014 solar stills are reliable in full sun"}],correct:"b",explanation:"A well-constructed solar still with abundant green vegetation in high sun produces 0.5-1L per day in IDEAL conditions. Most produce less. This is a critical survival fact \u2014 the solar still is a supplemental technique, NOT a primary water strategy. The energy expended digging and the water lost sweating while constructing often approach the yield. Best use: as a backup while you pursue better water sources (arroyo digging, transpiration bags, dew collection). Transpiration bags on living vegetation typically out-produce solar stills with far less effort.",relatedGuide:"water-002",tags:["water","intermediate","solar-still","desert"]}]},593,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,o,r,n,a){r.exports=[{id:"quiz-fire-001",category:"fire",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You've been attempting to produce a coal with a bow drill for 25 minutes. Both your spindle (willow) and fireboard (willow) are locally sourced but it's been raining for 2 days. You're seeing smoke from the notch but no sustained coal. What is the single most likely cause?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Insufficient downward pressure on the handhold"},{id:"b",text:"Wood moisture content is too high \u2014 both spindle and board are saturated"},{id:"c",text:"The notch angle is incorrect \u2014 it should be 1/8 of the depression"},{id:"d",text:"The bow speed is too slow for the wood species combination"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Surface moisture on bow drill components is the #1 cause of failure in field conditions. Wood above ~15% moisture content will not sustain friction ignition \u2014 the steam produced as moisture evaporates cools the dust pile and prevents it from reaching 800\xb0F+ ignition temperature. Solutions: split the wood to expose dry interior heartwood, keep components inside your clothing/sleeping bag overnight, or use a friction fire starter only after exposure to body heat for several hours. Willow is a good wood pairing \u2014 the issue here is moisture, not species selection. Notch should be 1/8 of the fire circle, and pressure/speed are secondary to dry wood.",relatedGuide:"fire-001",tags:["fire","intermediate","bow-drill"]},{id:"quiz-fire-002",category:"fire",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You've collected dry tinder (cattail fluff), finger-size kindling (dry twigs), and wrist-size fuel wood (dead branches). You've selected a site. Place these steps in correct order for a safe, reliable fire build.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Clear a 3-foot radius of dead leaves, pine needles, and dry debris around the fire site"},{id:"2",text:"Build a tinder bundle and place it at center of cleared area"},{id:"3",text:"Build a small teepee of finger-sized kindling above and around the tinder \u2014 leave a 'door' opening on the windward side"},{id:"4",text:"Add 3-4 pieces of wrist-sized fuel in a loose teepee or log cabin around the kindling structure"},{id:"5",text:"Light the tinder bundle through the windward door opening using a match or spark at the base"}],correct_order:["1","2","3","4","5"],explanation:"Always clear the debris radius FIRST \u2014 most wildfires start from embers landing in surrounding material, not from the fire itself. Build from smallest (tinder) to largest \u2014 adding fuel before kindling catches is the most common beginner failure. The windward opening allows oxygen to feed the flame and gives your ignition source access to the base of the tinder. Light at the BASE \u2014 heat rises. Never light from the top. Once the kindling catches, add fuel gradually. Never leave a fire unattended, even for 30 seconds in dry conditions.",relatedGuide:"fire-001",tags:["fire","beginner","fire-lay"]},{id:"quiz-fire-003",category:"fire",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Wet Conditions Fire Start",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"It's been raining for 3 days. Everything looks wet. You need fire to boil water for your group. You have: 2 matches, a ferrocerium rod, and a fixed-blade knife. No commercial tinder. What's your first action?",options:[{text:"Search for dead standing wood (snags) and split it to expose dry heartwood",next:"dead_standing"},{text:"Look for birch trees or resinous pine \u2014 both have ignition-resistant bark and pitch",next:"resinous_sources"}]},dead_standing:{id:"dead_standing",scenario:"Good. A dead standing snag of hardwood will have dry interior even after days of rain. You find a 4-inch diameter dead oak snag. Do you:",options:[{text:"Baton your knife through the center to expose heartwood, then shave fine feather sticks",next:"feather_sticks_oak"},{text:"Try to break it into pieces and use the interior chunks directly",next:"interior_chunks"}]},feather_sticks_oak:{id:"feather_sticks_oak",outcome:"success",explanation:"Dead standing wood retains dry interior even in multi-day rain. Batoning to expose heartwood is the correct technique. Fine feather sticks from dry heartwood are excellent tinder. The ferro rod produces a hotter spark than matches \u2014 save matches for backup. This is the correct wet-weather sequence: find, split, shave, structure, ignite."},interior_chunks:{id:"interior_chunks",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Tinder must be FINE \u2014 the ignition temperature threshold depends on exposed surface area. A chunk of dry wood, no matter how dry, will not catch from a spark or match. You must shave or create feather sticks to expose fine fibers with high surface area. The interior dry wood was the right material \u2014 the wrong form."},resinous_sources:{id:"resinous_sources",scenario:"You find a standing dead pine. The base where dead branches were is packed with dried pitch (fatwood). Fatwood burns even when wet because the resin repels water and has a high BTU content. Do you:",options:[{text:"Collect the pitch-saturated wood at branch junctions and the base, shave tinder from it",next:"fatwood_tinder"},{text:"Use the birch bark you find on a fallen log nearby as your primary tinder",next:"birch_bark"}]},fatwood_tinder:{id:"fatwood_tinder",outcome:"success",explanation:"Fatwood (resin-saturated pine heartwood) is the best wet-weather natural tinder. It ignites at lower temperatures due to turpentine content and burns at over 1,000\xb0F. Always check pine snags and base junctions for yellow-orange resin-soaked wood. It smells strongly of pine resin. This is a top-tier wet fire starting skill."},birch_bark:{id:"birch_bark",outcome:"success",explanation:"Birch bark contains betulin and other oils that make it highly flammable even when damp. Both birch bark and fatwood are excellent wet-condition tinders. Birch bark ignites even when slightly wet due to oil content. Note: only use fallen/dead birch \u2014 peeling live birch bark kills the tree. The outer papery layers are the tinder; the inner layers are kindling material. Use whatever resinous or oil-containing material you can find in wet conditions."}},relatedGuide:"fire-001",tags:["fire","advanced","wet-conditions","decision-tree"]},{id:"quiz-fire-004",category:"fire",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You're setting up camp in a dry pine forest. Wind is from the northwest at about 10mph. You plan to build a fire. Which action is the HIGHEST PRIORITY safety step before lighting?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Build the fire in a depression at least 6 inches deep to contain embers"},{id:"b",text:"Clear all combustible material (dead leaves, pine needles, dry grass) in a minimum 3-foot radius around the fire site"},{id:"c",text:"Position the fire to the southeast of your shelter so smoke blows away from camp"},{id:"d",text:"Limit fire diameter to 18 inches maximum"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Ember control is the #1 priority. The vast majority of wildfire ignitions from campfires happen when a single ember lands in surrounding dry material. The debris clearance radius is non-negotiable \u2014 3 feet minimum in dry conditions, 5 feet in very dry/windy conditions. Building in a depression helps contain heat but doesn't stop airborne embers. Positioning relative to shelter matters for comfort but is not a safety priority. Limiting size is good practice but secondary to clearing the fuel bed. Scrape down to mineral soil in the fire area when possible.",relatedGuide:"fire-002",tags:["fire","beginner","safety"]}]},594,[]);
__d(function(e,t,o,i,r,a,n){r.exports=[{id:"quiz-shelter-dt-001",category:"shelter",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Night Shelter \u2014 No Gear",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"It's 45\xb0F, light rain, no shelter, no fire-starting gear. You have 90 minutes of daylight. What do you do first?",options:[{text:"Build a debris hut immediately",next:"debris_hut"},{text:"Search for natural shelter (cave, rock overhang)",next:"natural_search"},{text:"Gather dry tinder and look for ways to make fire",next:"fire_first"}]},debris_hut:{id:"debris_hut",scenario:"Good. You start building. You find enough dry leaves and branches. But the ground is wet. Do you:",options:[{text:"Build a raised debris platform to sleep on",next:"good_outcome"},{text:"Sleep directly on the leaf pile",next:"bad_outcome_cold"}]},natural_search:{id:"natural_search",scenario:"You spend 30 minutes searching and find a shallow rock overhang. Not deep enough to fully block wind. Do you:",options:[{text:"Use it as a windbreak and pile debris around yourself",next:"good_outcome"},{text:"Keep searching for something better",next:"bad_outcome_dark"}]},fire_first:{id:"fire_first",scenario:"Without fire-starting gear this is risky. 45 minutes pass with no fire. Daylight is almost gone. You now have no shelter and no fire. This was the wrong priority.",outcome:"poor",explanation:"In wet, cold conditions without fire gear, shelter is always the first priority. Hypothermia kills faster than hunger or thirst. Fire is secondary when you have no reliable way to start one."},good_outcome:{id:"good_outcome",outcome:"success",explanation:"Correct. Ground insulation is critical \u2014 cold ground pulls heat from your body faster than cold air. A raised platform or thick debris layer between you and the ground is essential. You survive the night."},bad_outcome_cold:{id:"bad_outcome_cold",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Ground conduction would pull heat from your body all night. Even with debris above you, sleeping directly on wet ground leads to hypothermia. Always insulate from below first."},bad_outcome_dark:{id:"bad_outcome_dark",outcome:"poor",explanation:"The overhang was adequate. Continuing to search costs time and energy \u2014 you run out of daylight with no shelter at all. The first viable option is almost always the right option."}},relatedGuide:"shelter-001",tags:["shelter","hypothermia","advanced"]},{id:"quiz-shelter-002",category:"shelter",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You're building a debris hut for a 40\xb0F night. Which single layer of your debris hut is most critical for preventing hypothermia?",options:[{id:"a",text:"A thick roof layer to block rain (minimum 2 feet of debris)"},{id:"b",text:"The debris packed on the floor beneath you \u2014 minimum 6 inches of dry material"},{id:"c",text:"A leaf-stuffed door plug to block wind at the entrance"},{id:"d",text:"Leaves piled on the outside walls to a thickness of 18 inches"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Ground conduction is the #1 heat thief in shelter scenarios \u2014 the earth will pull body heat away 25x faster than cold air of the same temperature. Six inches minimum of dry debris BELOW you is non-negotiable. Roof thickness matters for insulation and rain but is secondary to floor insulation. The door plug prevents wind intrusion but convective loss is less severe than conductive. A good rule: build your floor first, thick enough that you cannot feel the ground through it, then build the roof. If you can only do one, do the floor.",relatedGuide:"shelter-001",tags:["shelter","beginner","debris-hut"]},{id:"quiz-shelter-003",category:"shelter",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You need to select a campsite for the night. Rank these site selection criteria from HIGHEST to LOWEST priority.",items:[{id:"1",text:"No widow-makers (dead branches or standing dead trees) overhead within falling range"},{id:"2",text:"A natural windbreak on the prevailing wind side (rock outcrop, dense conifers)"},{id:"3",text:"Flat ground for sleeping \u2014 sloped sites cause you to slide and disrupt sleep"},{id:"4",text:"Water source within 100 meters for morning needs"},{id:"5",text:"Natural concealment from sightlines (depression, dense brush)"}],correct_order:["1","2","3","4","5"],explanation:"A dead branch overhead can kill you in your sleep \u2014 this is always #1. No other criterion matters if a widow-maker falls on you. Windbreak is #2 because convective heat loss during sleep is a serious hypothermia risk, and wind-driven rain can destroy any shelter. Flat ground is a comfort and sleep quality concern \u2014 not immediately life-threatening but severely impacts performance. Water proximity is a morning logistics concern \u2014 you can haul water once. Concealment is tactical and relevant in grid-down scenarios but not a primary survival priority vs physical threats.",relatedGuide:"shelter-001",tags:["shelter","intermediate","site-selection"]},{id:"quiz-shelter-004",category:"shelter",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You've built a quinzhee (mounded snow shelter) in winter emergency conditions and have been inside for 3 hours with 2 other people. What is the single greatest risk that could kill you overnight?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Frostbite from contact with the snow walls as body heat melts the surface"},{id:"b",text:"The roof collapsing from snow weight accumulation above"},{id:"c",text:"Ventilation hole becoming blocked \u2014 CO2 buildup leading to suffocation"},{id:"d",text:"Moisture from breath condensing and re-freezing, dropping interior temperature"}],correct:"c",explanation:"CO2 (not CO \u2014 no combustion source) buildup from breathing is the primary killer in snow shelters. Three people in a sealed quinzhee can reach dangerous CO2 levels (above 5%) in under 2 hours if the vent hole is blocked. The vent hole must be maintained \u2014 poke it clear from inside every time you check it. Mark the vent location outside with a ski pole or stick so rescuers can find it. Frostbite from walls is minor \u2014 the interior surface warms above freezing from body heat. Collapse is rare with a properly hardened quinzhee (let it sinter 90 minutes before hollowing). Moisture is an insulation/comfort issue, not a life threat.",relatedGuide:"shelter-002",tags:["shelter","intermediate","snow-shelter","winter"]},{id:"quiz-shelter-dt-002",category:"shelter",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Urban Winter \u2014 Grid Down Day 3",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"3 days after a full grid-down event. Mid-January, outdoor temps at night: 18\xb0F. You are in a 6-story apartment building. Power, heat, and water are out. You have: 2 sleeping bags (rated to 20\xb0F), a propane camp stove with 1 canister, a hand-crank radio, and food for 5 days. Where do you shelter?",options:[{text:"Stay in your 4th-floor apartment and work to retain heat",next:"stay_4th_floor"},{text:"Move to a ground-floor unit (empty, can break in) for easier exit/entry",next:"go_ground"},{text:"Move to the building's stairwell \u2014 it's interior and protected",next:"stairwell"}]},stay_4th_floor:{id:"stay_4th_floor",scenario:"Smart. Upper floors retain heat longer than ground-floor units due to reduced floor conduction and wind exposure. Which heat retention action do you take first?",options:[{text:"Seal the apartment door and windows with duct tape and plastic sheeting to reduce air infiltration",next:"seal_room"},{text:"Move all sleeping gear into one interior bathroom and create a 'room within a room'",next:"interior_room"}]},seal_room:{id:"seal_room",outcome:"success",explanation:"Sealing reduces infiltration significantly. However, the most effective urban cold-weather technique is the 'room within a room' \u2014 concentrate body heat in the smallest interior space possible. The large exterior window is a major thermal bridge. That night, your 580 sq ft apartment drops to 38\xb0F \u2014 survivable in sleeping bags, but cold. Better execution: move to interior room + use sleeping bags together."},interior_room:{id:"interior_room",outcome:"success",explanation:"Excellent. The 'room within a room' principle is the most effective passive heat retention in grid-down urban scenarios. Interior rooms with no exterior walls (typically bathrooms and closets) lose heat only through interior walls, which are insulated against other units. Body heat in ~40 cubic feet combined with sleeping bags rated to 20\xb0F creates a survivable microclimate even in severe cold. The bathroom stays 20\xb0F warmer than the exterior apartment."},go_ground:{id:"go_ground",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Ground-floor units have floor conduction from the cold earth, greater wind infiltration at door seals, and are the first-floor breach point in insecure conditions. The slab foundation conducts cold directly \u2014 ground temperatures in January may be 32-36\xb0F, turning the floor into a massive heat sink. Upper floors with interior rooms are dramatically warmer. Stay above the second floor whenever possible."},stairwell:{id:"stairwell",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Stairwells are the worst possible shelter in a cold apartment building. The chimney effect \u2014 warm air rising and escaping through roof access, drawing cold air in at the base \u2014 creates a continuous cold draft. Without walls on all sides, no heat can accumulate. The stairwell may be useful for brief movement but never for sleeping in cold conditions. Stay in enclosed units with closable doors."}},relatedGuide:"shelter-003",tags:["shelter","advanced","urban","grid-down","winter"]}]},595,[]);
__d(function(e,t,a,o,i,r,n){i.exports=[{id:"quiz-food-001",category:"food",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You've found a plant you cannot identify but need food. You want to perform the Universal Edibility Test (UET) on the leaves. After separating the plant into parts (roots, stems, leaves, berries) what is the FIRST step you perform on the leaf portion?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Boil a small piece for 15 minutes and taste it \u2014 cooking destroys most toxins"},{id:"b",text:"Crush a piece and hold it against your inner wrist or inner elbow for 15 minutes, watching for reaction"},{id:"c",text:"Eat a thumbnail-sized piece and wait 8 hours before eating more"},{id:"d",text:"Smell the broken stem \u2014 bitter almond smell indicates cyanogenic compounds, stop immediately"}],correct:"b",explanation:"The UET sequence is: (1) Separate plant parts. (2) Check smell of broken part \u2014 bitter almond/peach pits = cyanide compounds, STOP. Rancid/acrid smell = STOP. (3) Skin contact test \u2014 crush and hold on inner wrist/elbow for 15 min, watching for burning/rash/blisters. (4) Lip/mouth test \u2014 touch to lips only for 3 minutes. (5) Tongue test \u2014 hold on tongue for 15 min. (6) Chew small amount without swallowing, wait 15 min. (7) Eat thumbnail amount, wait 8 hours. Each stage is a GO/NO-GO gate. Smelling first eliminates obvious cyanogenic plants before you contact them. Boiling does NOT reliably destroy all plant toxins \u2014 many alkaloids and glycosides are heat-stable.",relatedGuide:"food-001",tags:["food","intermediate","foraging","edibility-test"]},{id:"quiz-food-dt-001",category:"food",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"3 Meters of Cord \u2014 Feed Two",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"Day 4 post-grid-down. You are in a temperate woodland. You and one partner have not eaten in 48 hours. You have 3 meters of 550 paracord, a knife, and knowledge of the area. You've identified active rabbit runs \u2014 fresh tracks and scat at 3 separate game trails. What is your trapping strategy?",options:[{text:"Set multiple small snares on the rabbit runs using the paracord",next:"multiple_snares"},{text:"Construct a deadfall trap (Paiute or figure-4) at the most active trail",next:"single_deadfall"}]},multiple_snares:{id:"multiple_snares",scenario:"Good. You split the paracord into the 7 inner strands of each section to create multiple loops. How do you set them?",options:[{text:"Set 3 snares \u2014 one at each active run \u2014 and return in 4-6 hours",next:"three_snares"},{text:"Set 2 snares and keep 1m of paracord in reserve for other uses",next:"two_snares_reserve"}]},three_snares:{id:"three_snares",outcome:"success",explanation:"The trapping principle: more traps = more opportunities. Small game trappers say 'you need 10 traps to guarantee a meal.' With 3 traps on active runs, your odds are reasonable. Snare placement: the loop should hang 4 fingers above the trail surface, anchored to a stake or bent sapling. Loop diameter: 3-4 inches for rabbit. Paracord inner strands (gutted out) make excellent snare wire \u2014 nearly invisible and has good slip. Check every 4-6 hours \u2014 caught animals attract predators and decompose quickly in warm weather."},two_snares_reserve:{id:"two_snares_reserve",outcome:"success",explanation:"Two snares is suboptimal but workable. You catch nothing the first check. Repositioning on the 2nd check yields one rabbit 24 hours later. Keeping cordage in reserve was reasonable planning but trapping success scales directly with the number of sets. The correct mentality: commit your full cordage to trap sets \u2014 if you need cord later, you can recover it from the traps. Use what you have NOW for food \u2014 caloric deficit compounds quickly on day 4+."},single_deadfall:{id:"single_deadfall",outcome:"poor",explanation:"A deadfall requires precise construction and calibration. Without the right trigger wood, you lose 2+ hours building it. The rabbit avoids the unfamiliar object. No catch in 24 hours. Deadfalls work well for experienced trappers who can source precise trigger materials and set the bait correctly. For most people, snares are dramatically more reliable in real field conditions. With only 3 active runs and 3 meters of cord, multiple snares will almost always outperform a single deadfall. Additionally, rabbits often avoid newly disturbed ground \u2014 snares disturb the trail less than deadfall construction. Match your trap type to your skill level and available resources."}},relatedGuide:"food-002",tags:["food","advanced","trapping","snares"]},{id:"quiz-food-003",category:"food",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You have 4 pounds of raw venison. Power has been out for 5 days and won't return. Outside temperature is 65\xb0F. Which preservation method gives this meat the longest shelf life without refrigeration?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Hang it in a cool, shaded area \u2014 air circulation will slow spoilage"},{id:"b",text:"Salt-cure and dry it (make jerky) \u2014 sliced thin, heavily salted, dried to below 10% moisture"},{id:"c",text:"Smoke it over a hardwood fire for 4-6 hours"},{id:"d",text:"Seal it in airtight jars using the open-kettle canning method"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Proper jerky (salt-cured and dried to below 10% moisture, or water activity below 0.85) has a shelf life of 1-4 months at room temperature. Salt draws moisture out via osmosis, inhibiting microbial growth. The drying process further reduces water activity below the threshold for most pathogens. Smoking alone does not dry sufficiently for long-term preservation \u2014 true smoke-preserved meat still requires a salt cure or must reach internal temps that would reduce shelf life anyway. Hanging meat at 65\xb0F will spoil within 24-48 hours. Open-kettle canning is unsafe for low-acid foods (meat) \u2014 botulism risk is high without a pressure canner reaching 240\xb0F. Slice venison 1/4 inch thick, against the grain, salt heavily (or use a salt/cure brine), and dry at 140-160\xb0F until it snaps, not bends.",relatedGuide:"food-003",tags:["food","beginner","preservation","jerky"]},{id:"quiz-food-004",category:"food",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You're selecting which wild-foraged food sources to prioritize in a long-term survival situation where caloric intake is insufficient. Rank these from HIGHEST to LOWEST caloric density (calories per 100g edible portion).",items:[{id:"1",text:"Pine nuts / tree nuts (various)"},{id:"2",text:"Acorns (processed, tannins leached)"},{id:"3",text:"Cattail pollen (collected in season)"},{id:"4",text:"Dandelion greens (leaves)"},{id:"5",text:"Pine cambium (inner bark, raw)"}],correct_order:["1","2","3","4","5"],explanation:"Pine nuts ~673 cal/100g (67% fat content \u2014 the highest caloric density in wild plant foods). Processed acorns ~387 cal/100g (40% carbohydrate, 24% fat \u2014 must leach tannins in cold running water 2-3 days or boil multiple times). Cattail pollen ~340 cal/100g (high starch, protein \u2014 collect by bending heads into a bag in early summer). Dandelion greens ~45 cal/100g (excellent micronutrients but almost no caloric value \u2014 not a survival food for energy). Pine cambium ~20 cal/100g (mostly water and fiber \u2014 emergency starvation food only). KEY PRINCIPLE: In survival, prioritize FATS first (nuts, fatty animal parts), then STARCHES (roots, grains, acorns), then PROTEIN (lean meat), then greens last. Greens are nutritious but calorically irrelevant in a deficiency situation.",relatedGuide:"food-001",tags:["food","intermediate","foraging","calories","wild-plants"]}]},596,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,a,o,r,s){o.exports=[{id:"quiz-medical-001",category:"medical",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"advanced",scenario:"You have a conscious casualty with a gunshot wound to the upper thigh, heavy bleeding, no incoming fire. Put these actions in the correct order.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Apply tourniquet 2\u20133 inches above the wound"},{id:"2",text:"Establish the casualty's airway"},{id:"3",text:"Note the time of tourniquet application"},{id:"4",text:"Move the casualty to cover"},{id:"5",text:"Pack the wound if tourniquet is ineffective"}],correct_order:["4","1","3","5","2"],explanation:"Under fire: move to cover first. Then hemorrhage control is the priority \u2014 tourniquet high and tight. Always mark the time. Pack if the tourniquet alone doesn't control bleeding. Airway comes after hemorrhage when not in immediate danger.",relatedGuide:"medical-002",tags:["medical","TCCC","tourniquet","advanced"]},{id:"quiz-medical-002",category:"medical",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You have a severe laceration to your right forearm near the elbow with arterial bleeding (spurting). You have a CAT tourniquet. You must apply it one-handed to your own arm. Put these steps in correct order.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Thread the strap through the buckle and pull tight, routing proximal to the wound"},{id:"2",text:"Position the tourniquet 2-3 inches proximal (toward the heart) from the wound"},{id:"3",text:"Twist the windlass rod until bleeding completely stops"},{id:"4",text:"Secure the windlass with the locking clip or hook-and-loop"},{id:"5",text:"Write the time of application on the white TQ label or on your skin with a marker"}],correct_order:["2","1","3","4","5"],explanation:"Position before tightening \u2014 2-3 inches proximal to the wound, never over a joint. Tighten the strap as much as possible before touching the windlass \u2014 the strap does most of the compression work. Twist the windlass until bleeding stops completely \u2014 partial application that slows but doesn't stop bleeding is dangerous (it blocks venous return without stopping arterial flow, accelerating blood loss). Secure the windlass \u2014 an unsecured windlass can unwind, causing rebleed. Always mark the time \u2014 tourniquet time determines the evacuation priority and guides the receiving physician on nerve/vascular damage windows. Never remove the tourniquet in the field once applied.",relatedGuide:"medical-002",tags:["medical","tourniquet","self-aid","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-medical-003",category:"medical",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"advanced",scenario:"Your casualty took blunt trauma to the left chest from a vehicle collision. He is conscious but deteriorating rapidly. He shows: decreased breath sounds on the LEFT, respiratory distress, blood pressure dropping (systolic 80), neck veins visibly distended, and trachea deviated toward the RIGHT. Which action is most appropriate?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Position him in recovery position and monitor \u2014 this is a simple pneumothorax"},{id:"b",text:"Needle decompression: 14-gauge needle at the 2nd intercostal space, midclavicular line on the LEFT side"},{id:"c",text:"Needle decompression on the RIGHT (opposite of injury) \u2014 tracheal deviation indicates the right lung is compressed"},{id:"d",text:"Apply a chest seal to the left chest and reassess"}],correct:"b",explanation:"This is a tension pneumothorax. The diagnostic triad: (1) absent/decreased breath sounds on affected side, (2) tracheal deviation AWAY from the injury (trachea pushes toward right = left tension), (3) hypotension + JVD. The trachea deviates AWAY from the tension \u2014 needle decompression goes to the SAME side as the injury (left). Landmark: 2nd ICS, midclavicular line OR 4th-5th ICS, anterior axillary line (now preferred \u2014 less risk of hitting the heart or vessels). A simple pneumothorax does not cause tracheal deviation or hemodynamic instability. An occlusive chest seal can worsen tension PTX if it seals completely \u2014 use a vented chest seal if one is present.",relatedGuide:"medical-003",tags:["medical","advanced","chest-trauma","pneumothorax"]},{id:"quiz-medical-dt-001",category:"medical",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"4 Casualties \u2014 Limited Supplies",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"You arrive at a vehicle accident. 4 casualties. You have: 2 tourniquets, 4 hemostatic gauze packs, 1 chest seal, limited bandages. Casualty A: not breathing, positioned on their back, mouth visibly clear. Casualty B: breathing 24/min, radial pulse strong, GCS 14, controlled bleeding from arm. Casualty C: breathing 32/min, no radial pulse (only carotid), severe thigh wound actively bleeding. Casualty D: walking, complaining of wrist pain. Who do you address FIRST?",options:[{text:"Reposition Casualty A's airway (head-tilt chin-lift) and check for breathing",next:"reposition_A"},{text:"Go directly to Casualty C \u2014 highest visible threat (uncontrolled hemorrhage)",next:"go_to_C"}]},reposition_A:{id:"reposition_A",scenario:"You tilt A's head. No breathing resumes. In START triage, this means EXPECTANT (black tag). You move on. You now see C actively hemorrhaging. Do you:",options:[{text:"Apply tourniquet to C's thigh immediately",next:"tourniquet_C"},{text:"Check B first since B has a higher GCS",next:"check_B_first"}]},tourniquet_C:{id:"tourniquet_C",outcome:"success",explanation:"START triage sequence: (1) Walking? \u2192 Minor (green), move aside. (2) Breathing after repositioning airway? No \u2192 Expectant (black). Yes (>30/min) \u2192 Immediate. (3) Radial pulse present? No \u2192 Immediate (red). Yes \u2192 check GCS. GCS <14 \u2192 Immediate. GCS 14+ and RR 10-30 \u2192 Delayed (yellow). Casualty A: no breathing after reposition = black. Casualty C: RR 32 + no radial pulse = Immediate (red) \u2014 tourniquet now. Casualty B: RR 24, radial pulse, GCS 14 = Delayed (yellow). Casualty D: walking = Minor (green). You triaged and treated correctly."},check_B_first:{id:"check_B_first",outcome:"poor",explanation:"In START triage, uncontrolled external hemorrhage = Immediate (Red) and takes priority over Delayed (Yellow) casualties. Casualty C's no-radial-pulse + RR 32 confirms Immediate status. GCS score does not override hemorrhage control priority. When a casualty is dying NOW from a treatable cause (tourniquet-able hemorrhage), treat it NOW. B was already assessed as stable by radial pulse and RR \u2014 those findings told you B is Yellow. C lost an additional 300ml while you assessed B."},go_to_C:{id:"go_to_C",outcome:"success",explanation:"Going to C first is defensible in operational triage (visible life-threatening hemorrhage), but the purist START protocol requires you to check airway on non-breathing casualties before classifying Expectant \u2014 the 3-second airway check could convert a 'black' to an 'immediate red.' C was correctly prioritized for hemorrhage control. Ensure Casualty A still receives a brief airway check, even if you expect them to remain Expectant. In mass casualty events, follow the protocol consistently so nothing is missed."}},relatedGuide:"medical-004",tags:["medical","advanced","triage","START","mass-casualty"]},{id:"quiz-medical-005",category:"medical",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"advanced",scenario:"Your casualty has: HR 128, blood pressure 86/60, respiratory rate 28/min, skin pale and clammy, Glasgow Coma Scale 13 (confused). Based on ATLS hemorrhagic shock classification, what class of shock is this, and approximately how much blood has been lost?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Class I \u2014 mild, <750ml blood loss, compensated fully"},{id:"b",text:"Class II \u2014 750-1500ml, compensated, anxiety but oriented"},{id:"c",text:"Class III \u2014 1500-2000ml (~30-40% volume), decompensated \u2014 BP dropping, confusion"},{id:"d",text:"Class IV \u2014 >2000ml (>40% volume), immediately life-threatening"}],correct:"c",explanation:"ATLS Hemorrhagic Shock Classes: Class I (<750ml): HR <100, BP normal, RR normal, normal mentation. Class II (750-1500ml): HR 100-120, BP normal-low, RR 20-30, anxious. Class III (1500-2000ml): HR 120-140, BP drops significantly, RR 30-40, confused. Class IV (>2000ml): HR >140, BP severely depressed, lethargy/unconsciousness. This casualty at HR 128 (borderline III), BP 86/60 (significant drop = decompensated), RR 28, GCS 13 (confusion) = Class III, representing ~1500-2000ml blood loss (30-40% of total ~5L adult volume). Field treatment: control the source (tourniquet, wound packing), position supine or modified Trendelenburg if spine clear, prevent hypothermia, expedite evacuation. Permissive hypotension is preferred over aggressive fluid resuscitation in penetrating trauma.",relatedGuide:"medical-005",tags:["medical","advanced","shock","hemorrhage","ATLS"]},{id:"quiz-medical-dt-002",category:"medical",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"intermediate",title:"Unconscious Patient \u2014 No Equipment",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"You find an unconscious adult male, unknown cause. He was eating 5 minutes ago. He does not respond to your voice or a sternal rub. He is face-up. What is your first airway action?",options:[{text:"Perform head-tilt chin-lift to open the airway, then look-listen-feel for breathing",next:"head_tilt"},{text:"Immediately roll him into recovery position",next:"recovery_position"}]},head_tilt:{id:"head_tilt",scenario:"You perform head-tilt chin-lift. You hear gurgling sounds and see partial movement of the chest. Do you:",options:[{text:"Perform a finger sweep of the mouth for any visible obstruction",next:"finger_sweep"},{text:"Apply jaw thrust instead and call for help",next:"jaw_thrust_only"}]},finger_sweep:{id:"finger_sweep",outcome:"success",explanation:"Head-tilt chin-lift is the primary airway maneuver for an unconscious person with no suspected spinal injury. Gurgling indicates a partial obstruction that a finger sweep can clear. Only perform a finger sweep for VISIBLE or PALPABLE obstructions \u2014 blind finger sweeps can push objects deeper. With breathing restored, the recovery position (lateral, stable, head tilted back) prevents aspiration of vomit, which is the #1 secondary airway threat in unconscious patients."},jaw_thrust_only:{id:"jaw_thrust_only",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Jaw thrust is the preferred maneuver when spinal injury is suspected \u2014 it opens the airway without neck extension. However, it does not clear a physical obstruction. If you hear gurgling after any airway maneuver, you must assess for and clear the obstruction. Look in the mouth, sweep for visible material. The jaw thrust plus airway clearance would have been correct."},recovery_position:{id:"recovery_position",outcome:"poor",explanation:"The correct sequence is: check airway, open airway, look-listen-feel for breathing, address obstruction if present, THEN recovery position. Rolling without first checking the airway skips the most critical step. The gurgling (from the partial food obstruction) would have been detected immediately with a proper airway check \u2014 and cleared with a finger sweep before positioning."}},relatedGuide:"medical-001",tags:["medical","intermediate","airway","unconscious","decision-tree"]},{id:"quiz-medical-007",category:"medical",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"A casualty has a deep stab wound to the lateral hip/groin junction \u2014 not amenable to tourniquet placement. Bright red arterial blood. You have hemostatic gauze (QuikClot or similar) and a pressure bandage. Order these steps correctly.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Expose the wound fully \u2014 cut away clothing for clear access"},{id:"2",text:"Pack hemostatic gauze tightly into the deepest portion of the wound cavity, pressing to the bottom"},{id:"3",text:"Continue packing additional gauze on top, filling the cavity completely"},{id:"4",text:"Apply firm direct pressure with your hand for a minimum of 3 minutes (5 min recommended for hemostatic gauze)"},{id:"5",text:"Apply a pressure bandage over the packed wound to maintain compression"},{id:"6",text:"Mark the casualty card or patient's forehead with time of treatment and hemostatic gauze used"}],correct_order:["1","2","3","4","5","6"],explanation:"Exposure first \u2014 you cannot treat what you cannot see. Clothing conceals wound depth and prevents proper packing. Pack to the BOTTOM of the cavity \u2014 the most common packing error is building up from the surface and leaving a dead space at the base where bleeding continues. Fill the cavity completely \u2014 hemostatic gauze works by concentrating clotting factors and applying mechanical pressure. Three to five minutes of FIRM direct pressure is mandatory \u2014 releasing early is the second most common error. Pressure bandage maintains the pack while you move to other casualties. Mark the patient \u2014 receiving providers need to know hemostatic gauze is inside (removal requires irrigation in a surgical setting).",relatedGuide:"medical-002",tags:["medical","intermediate","wound-packing","hemorrhage","hemostatic"]},{id:"quiz-medical-008",category:"medical",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You have a dehydrated partner who is conscious and can swallow. You have clean (boiled) water, table salt, and sugar. What is the WHO-recommended oral rehydration solution formula?",options:[{id:"a",text:"1 teaspoon salt + 8 teaspoons sugar per 1 liter water"},{id:"b",text:"6 level teaspoons sugar + half a teaspoon salt per 1 liter water"},{id:"c",text:"1 tablespoon salt + 1 tablespoon sugar per 1 liter water"},{id:"d",text:"2 teaspoons baking soda + 4 teaspoons sugar per 1 liter water"}],correct:"b",explanation:"WHO ORS formula: 6 level teaspoons (30ml) glucose/sugar + 0.5 teaspoon (2.5ml) salt in 1 liter clean water. The sugar:salt ratio is critical. Too much salt causes hypernatremia (sodium poisoning) \u2014 1 tablespoon salt is 3x the safe dose and can cause seizures in a dehydrated person. The glucose is not just for calories \u2014 it enables sodium-glucose cotransport (SGLT mechanism) in the intestinal lining, dramatically increasing water absorption. Plain water without glucose/salt does not absorb as efficiently. Give 200-400mL every 30 minutes. If vomiting occurs, give smaller sips (30-50mL) every 5 minutes. Escalate to IV fluids if: unconscious, persistent vomiting, signs of shock.",relatedGuide:"medical-001",tags:["medical","beginner","dehydration","ORS","rehydration"]}]},597,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,o,n,a,r){n.exports=[{id:"quiz-nav-001",category:"navigation",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You're in eastern Montana (magnetic declination approximately 10\xb0 East). Your map shows a true north bearing of 045\xb0 (northeast) to your destination. What compass bearing do you walk?",options:[{id:"a",text:"045\xb0 \u2014 declination doesn't affect bearing when traveling northeast"},{id:"b",text:"055\xb0 \u2014 add easterly declination to true bearing to get magnetic bearing"},{id:"c",text:"035\xb0 \u2014 subtract easterly declination from true bearing to get magnetic bearing"},{id:"d",text:"045\xb0 adjusted by GPS correction only \u2014 compasses don't require declination adjustment"}],correct:"c",explanation:"When converting TRUE bearing (map) to MAGNETIC bearing (compass): East declination \u2192 SUBTRACT. West declination \u2192 ADD. Mnemonic: 'East is least (subtract), West is best (add).' With 10\xb0E declination: Magnetic = True \u2212 Declination = 045\xb0 \u2212 10\xb0 = 035\xb0. Your compass needle points to magnetic north, which is 10\xb0 EAST of true north in eastern Montana \u2014 so to walk true northeast (045\xb0), your compass must show 035\xb0. Failure to adjust declination causes systematic directional error \u2014 at 1 mile, 10\xb0 error = 924 feet off target.",relatedGuide:"navigation-001",tags:["navigation","compass","declination","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-nav-002",category:"navigation",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You must navigate 4 miles through dense woodland to a rally point without GPS, using dead reckoning from your known start position. Place these steps in the correct procedural order.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Convert map bearing to magnetic bearing (adjust for declination)"},{id:"2",text:"Identify your start position on the map and mark it"},{id:"3",text:"Measure the straight-line distance to your destination on the map using the scale"},{id:"4",text:"Calculate your pace count for the terrain (establish paces per 100m on similar terrain)"},{id:"5",text:"Begin walking on the established compass bearing, counting paces to track distance"}],correct_order:["2","3","1","4","5"],explanation:"Dead reckoning requires: WHERE ARE YOU (start point) \u2192 WHERE ARE YOU GOING (measure distance) \u2192 WHAT DIRECTION (convert bearing for declination) \u2192 HOW DO YOU MEASURE DISTANCE (pace count calibration) \u2192 EXECUTE. You must know your start position before anything else \u2014 without it, all subsequent steps are useless. Distance measurement from the map gives you the goal. Declination conversion comes before moving. Pace count calibration should be done on similar terrain before committing \u2014 woodland pace count differs from road pace count by 10-20%. Once moving, update position estimates at terrain features (ridgelines, streams) to check cumulative error.",relatedGuide:"navigation-001",tags:["navigation","dead-reckoning","compass","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-nav-003",category:"navigation",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Disoriented in Dense Woodland",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"You've been hiking 6 hours in dense woodland. Your compass works but your map is unclear \u2014 you're not certain of your current position. Visibility is 30 feet. Last known position was a stream crossing 2 hours ago. What do you do first?",options:[{text:"Stop, sit down, and think before moving further \u2014 STOP protocol",next:"stop_think"},{text:"Walk downhill \u2014 water is downhill, follow water to civilization",next:"downhill_move"}]},stop_think:{id:"stop_think",scenario:"Good. You STOP (Stop, Think, Observe, Plan). You observe: you can hear running water faintly to the west. Your compass shows you've been traveling generally north-northeast. The terrain is sloping upward to your right. Based on your last known position, what do you do?",options:[{text:"Move toward the sound of water \u2014 stream is a linear feature that leads out",next:"toward_water"},{text:"Climb to higher ground for better observation and potential map resection",next:"high_ground"}]},toward_water:{id:"toward_water",outcome:"success",explanation:"Water is the best terrain feature for navigation recovery. Streams are linear features that lead to larger water (rivers) which lead to civilization. Once you reach water, follow it DOWNSTREAM unless your map shows it leads into wilderness. The STOP principle prevents panic-driven movement that compounds disorientation. You correctly oriented before moving and used an audible landmark to reestablish position."},high_ground:{id:"high_ground",outcome:"success",explanation:"High ground for observation is a classic navigation recovery technique. From elevation, you can see drainage patterns, ridge lines, and distinctive terrain features for map resection. Resection: identify 2+ known terrain features, take compass bearings to each, back-plot those bearings on the map \u2014 your position is where they intersect. Both this and the water-following approach are correct \u2014 the key was STOPPING first before either."},downhill_move:{id:"downhill_move",outcome:"poor",explanation:"'Go downhill to find water' is a general principle, not a navigation plan. Moving without first stopping to observe and plan violates the STOP protocol and compounds disorientation. Downhill in complex terrain often leads into drainages where navigation features are obscured and travel is difficult. Always STOP first \u2014 movement without orientation wastes energy and takes you further from where rescue teams will search (your last known position)."}},relatedGuide:"navigation-001",tags:["navigation","lost","STOP-protocol","advanced"]},{id:"quiz-nav-004",category:"navigation",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"No compass, clear night, northern hemisphere. You need to find true north. Which star and method is correct?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Orion's Belt always points true north when it's highest in the sky"},{id:"b",text:"Find Polaris (North Star) by locating the two 'pointer stars' on the outer edge of the Big Dipper's bowl and extending a line 5x the distance between them"},{id:"c",text:"Cassiopeia (the W shape) is always due north and can be used directly"},{id:"d",text:"The brightest star in the sky (Sirius) aligns with magnetic north"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Polaris sits within 1\xb0 of true celestial north and does not appear to move as Earth rotates. Locate it: find the Big Dipper, identify the two outermost stars of the bowl (Dubhe and Merak \u2014 the 'pointer stars'), extend a line through them approximately 5x the distance between them, and that line terminates at Polaris. Polaris is a moderately bright star \u2014 not the brightest in the sky (that's Sirius, in the south). Cassiopeia (W shape) is useful for finding Polaris when the Big Dipper is below the horizon \u2014 it's on the opposite side of Polaris from the Big Dipper. Neither Orion's Belt nor Sirius points north.",relatedGuide:"navigation-001",tags:["navigation","stars","night-navigation","beginner"]}]},598,[]);
__d(function(e,i,t,r,n,a,s){n.exports=[{id:"quiz-comms-001",category:"communications",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You need to signal an aircraft approximately 3 miles away. You have a signal mirror (commercial type with aiming hole). Which technique is correct?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Aim the mirror directly at the sun, then reflect sunlight toward the aircraft"},{id:"b",text:"Hold mirror to your eye, sight the aircraft through the aiming hole, tilt until the bright reflection spot on your face aligns with the hole \u2014 then hold"},{id:"c",text:"Flash SOS pattern (3 short-3 long-3 short) continuously at maximum rate"},{id:"d",text:"Only use signal mirrors at noon when the sun is directly overhead \u2014 other angles are ineffective"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Signal mirror with aiming hole: (1) Hold mirror near your eye. (2) Sight the target through the aiming hole. (3) Tilt the mirror until the bright reflected 'fireball' on your face aligns with the aiming hole. (4) The reflection is now aimed at your target. (5) Sweep slowly \u2014 don't flash rapidly, sweep at 2-3 second intervals so observers can see the reflection. A signal mirror can be visible 10-20 miles in direct sunlight. WITHOUT an aiming hole: hold 2 fingers in a V at arm's length, sight the target between the fingers, tilt mirror until reflection hits your fingers and reflects to the target. Do NOT aim directly at the sun \u2014 you're reflecting FROM the sun, not at it. Signal mirrors work at any sun angle as long as the sun is visible.",relatedGuide:"comms-001",tags:["communications","signaling","survival","beginner"]},{id:"quiz-comms-002",category:"communications",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You need to construct a signal fire for daytime aircraft signaling. You have dry wood, green vegetation (leaves/pine boughs), and a working lighter. Order these steps from first to last.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Build a base fire structure using dry wood for reliable ignition (tinder, kindling, fuel)"},{id:"2",text:"Select a site with maximum air visibility \u2014 open clearing, hilltop, or large flat rock"},{id:"3",text:"Gather a large pile of green vegetation (leaves, grass, pine boughs) to pile on once fire is lit"},{id:"4",text:"Light the base fire and allow it to establish for 3-5 minutes"},{id:"5",text:"Add green vegetation on top of established fire to create dense white-grey smoke visible from aircraft"}],correct_order:["2","1","3","4","5"],explanation:"Site selection first \u2014 a brilliant signal fire in a forest clearing is nearly invisible from the air. Open ground, ridge lines, or prominent terrain features are required. Build the ignition base before gathering green material \u2014 green vegetation is heavy to transport and irrelevant until you have fire. Gather green material in quantity while your base is building (time efficiency). Light the base and let it establish before adding green \u2014 adding green to a new fire smothers it. Dense green material produces white/grey smoke visible against terrain. At night: no smoke needed \u2014 bright flames are visible. Signal 3 fires in a triangle (international distress) if material and time permit.",relatedGuide:"comms-001",tags:["communications","signaling","fire","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-comms-003",category:"communications",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You're stranded on a remote lake. A vessel is passing approximately 400 meters away. You have a whistle. What is the internationally recognized whistle distress signal?",options:[{id:"a",text:"One long blast \u2014 used universally for distress on water"},{id:"b",text:"Three short blasts repeated \u2014 the universal distress signal recognized by maritime, SAR, and wilderness protocols"},{id:"c",text:"Two long blasts alternating with two short blasts \u2014 Morse code for 'SOS'"},{id:"d",text:"Continuous blowing for 30 second intervals \u2014 the duration indicates distress"}],correct:"b",explanation:"The universal distress signal is the Rule of 3: three of anything (3 whistle blasts, 3 gunshots, 3 fires in a triangle, 3 mirror flashes). Three short blasts repeated, with a pause between sets, is internationally recognized by maritime and SAR protocols. SOS in Morse code is 3 short / 3 long / 3 short \u2014 but this is not the standard whistle protocol (most people don't recognize Morse code). One long blast on a vessel horn means you're leaving a dock \u2014 it is NOT a distress signal. In water survival: blow 3 short blasts, pause, repeat. A Fox 40 or ACME Thunderer whistle can be heard 1+ mile in calm conditions and requires no breath pressure, unlike voice.",relatedGuide:"comms-001",tags:["communications","signaling","distress","beginner"]}]},599,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,a,o,n,r){o.exports=[{id:"quiz-security-dt-001",category:"security",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Leave or Stay \u2014 Grid-Down Hour 72",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"It's been 72 hours since a major infrastructure failure (suspected EMP/cyber attack). No power, no communications, no water pressure in your suburban neighborhood. You have: 30 days food, 50 gallons water stored, a vehicle with 3/4 tank of fuel, and a rural property 180 miles away. Neighbors are beginning to behave erratically. A group of 6 unknown individuals has set up at the neighborhood entrance. What do you do?",options:[{text:"Bug out immediately \u2014 load up and drive to the rural property tonight",next:"bug_out_night"},{text:"Shelter in place \u2014 you have 30 days supplies and bugging out before the threat is confirmed is premature",next:"shelter_in_place"}]},bug_out_night:{id:"bug_out_night",scenario:"You load your vehicle in daylight and depart. The road 40 miles out is blocked by stalled vehicles \u2014 the EMP disabled older cars. You have to abandon your vehicle and continue on foot with what you can carry. Do you:",options:[{text:"Cache what you can't carry and proceed on foot to the rural property (still 140 miles)",next:"foot_march"},{text:"Return to your neighborhood \u2014 foot march 140 miles is not survivable with current supplies",next:"return_home"}]},foot_march:{id:"foot_march",outcome:"success",explanation:"You made a defensible decision to leave before the threat escalated, but failed to account for vehicle failure contingency. The rule: if you cannot walk your bug-out route, you don't have a real plan. Before committing to a vehicle-dependent bug-out, consider: How far can you walk? What's your contingency if the road is blocked? Bug-out decisions should also weigh the threat level \u2014 at 72 hours with uncertain intel, staying put with 30 days of supplies may have been defensible."},return_home:{id:"return_home",outcome:"success",explanation:"Tactical flexibility is key. Recognizing that the original plan is compromised and adjusting shows good decision-making. Returning preserves your supply cache. This also highlights the importance of having a vetted bug-out route that accounts for road blockage \u2014 a primary route plus 1-2 alternates including foot routes."},shelter_in_place:{id:"shelter_in_place",scenario:"You remain. Day 4: the group at the entrance has grown to 15 and has begun stopping vehicles. Your neighborhood has formed an informal watch. Day 7: 2 houses on your street are broken into. You are approached by neighbors to join a mutual aid group. Do you:",options:[{text:"Join the mutual aid group \u2014 collective security and shared intelligence is better than solo",next:"mutual_aid"},{text:"Maintain strict operational security \u2014 sharing your supply status invites targeting",next:"opsec_solo"}]},mutual_aid:{id:"mutual_aid",outcome:"success",explanation:"In extended grid-down scenarios, small isolated households are the most vulnerable. Collective security \u2014 distributed watch, mutual defense, shared intelligence about neighborhood threats \u2014 dramatically increases survivability. Joining a group that does NOT know your full supply status initially (contribute proportionally, don't broadcast) is the correct balance. Community formation is consistently the most important survival variable in historical grid-down events."},opsec_solo:{id:"opsec_solo",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Strict solo OPSEC (operational security) is unsustainable in a neighborhood grid-down scenario. You cannot maintain 24/7 watch indefinitely alone. Selective disclosure \u2014 forming mutual aid with vetted neighbors without revealing full inventory \u2014 is the correct balance. Pure isolation in a suburban setting leaves you blind and undefended. Isolation works in truly remote locations; it fails in proximity to population centers."}},relatedGuide:"security-001",tags:["security","bug-out","shelter-in-place","advanced"]},{id:"quiz-security-002",category:"security",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You're at a gas station during a grid-down event. A vehicle pulls up with 4 occupants who make eye contact with you, then with your loaded truck, then whisper to each other. You're 30 feet from your truck. What OODA loop stage are you currently in, and what is your next action?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Observe \u2014 continue watching passively and gather more information before moving"},{id:"b",text:"Orient \u2014 you've observed the potential threat indicators, now you must contextualize: are these behaviors consistent with pre-attack indicators?"},{id:"c",text:"Decide \u2014 you've already identified the threat, immediately retrieve your firearm from the truck"},{id:"d",text:"Act \u2014 move immediately to put your truck between you and the threat as cover"}],correct:"b",explanation:"OODA (Observe-Orient-Decide-Act) is a decision loop, not a single-pass sequence. You've completed Observe (eye contact, glance at truck, whispered conversation). Orient is next \u2014 contextualize what you observed: Are these pre-attack indicators? Baseline behavior for a gas station is people pumping gas, not scanning assets and conferring. Moving to your truck without Orienting may alert them prematurely if they're not actually a threat. Orienting allows you to Decide: is this escalating? Do I pre-empt or maintain observation? Conscious awareness of the OODA loop prevents both under-reaction (ignoring clear indicators) and over-reaction (escalating unnecessarily).",relatedGuide:"security-001",tags:["security","OODA","situational-awareness","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-security-003",category:"security",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You've established a safe house in a rural property. You have 4 adults available and standard hardware/supplies. Rank these perimeter security actions from highest to lowest priority.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Establish overlapping fields of view \u2014 no blind spots at approach routes to the structure"},{id:"2",text:"Clear vegetation and debris within 50 feet of the structure to eliminate concealed approach routes"},{id:"3",text:"Establish a communication method between watch positions (radio, signal, or rope pull)"},{id:"4",text:"Set up noise-making early warning on likely approach paths (cans with rocks, fishing line trip alerts)"},{id:"5",text:"Establish a written watch rotation schedule to prevent fatigue-induced security gaps"}],correct_order:["2","1","4","3","5"],explanation:"Clear the vegetation first \u2014 concealment for an approach is more dangerous than any other gap, and clearing it is a one-time labor investment with permanent payoff. Overlapping fields of view (interlocking sectors) ensures no approach goes unobserved \u2014 if one position goes down, others still have coverage. Early warning devices (noise-makers on trip lines) give sleeping personnel time to respond \u2014 critical when watch staffing is thin. Communication between positions is essential for coordinated response \u2014 watch positions that can't signal each other can't respond to threats cooperatively. Written rotation addresses long-term sustainability \u2014 fatigue is the #1 security failure in extended scenarios.",relatedGuide:"security-001",tags:["security","perimeter","safe-house","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-security-dt-002",category:"security",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Approaching Strangers \u2014 Day 10",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"Day 10 post-grid-down. You are at your rural property. A group of 3 adults (2 men, 1 woman) approaches your driveway on foot. They look exhausted and carry light packs. They stop at your gate. One raises his hand in a non-threatening gesture. You are armed. Your family is inside. What do you do?",options:[{text:"Challenge them from a position of cover \u2014 make verbal contact without exposing yourself or your family",next:"challenge_covered"},{text:"Send your family inside and approach the gate alone to speak with them",next:"approach_gate"}]},challenge_covered:{id:"challenge_covered",scenario:"You call from behind cover at 30 feet. They state they walked from a city 60 miles away and are looking for water and food \u2014 they have a 10-year-old child out of sight on the road. Do you:",options:[{text:"Bring them inside \u2014 a family with a child is almost certainly not a threat, and you can spare basic aid",next:"inside_too_fast"},{text:"Provide water at the gate without inviting them inside \u2014 assess further before granting access",next:"gate_aid"}]},gate_aid:{id:"gate_aid",outcome:"success",explanation:"The gate aid protocol: provide basic humanitarian assistance without granting property access. You remain in a defensible position (covered), gather intelligence (their account of conditions, useful situational awareness), and assess behavioral indicators of deception (evasive answers, interest in your structure, inconsistent story). A consistent, detailed story combined with non-threatening body posture is a positive indicator. You maintained security while acting humanely \u2014 both are achievable simultaneously."},inside_too_fast:{id:"inside_too_fast",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Granting property access to unknown individuals in a grid-down environment is a serious security risk regardless of initial appearance. The gate aid protocol (provide aid at the perimeter) achieves humanitarian goals without compromising your defensive position. Appearance and apparent distress can be staged. This is not cynicism \u2014 it is proportionate caution when the stakes are your family's safety. Never invite strangers inside a safe house during grid-down without an extended vetting process."},approach_gate:{id:"approach_gate",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Never sacrifice your defensive position by approaching unknown contacts. The conversation can happen from cover \u2014 your voice carries 30 feet. By approaching the gate, you: (1) separate from your family, (2) reveal yourself as the armed defender rather than maintaining uncertainty about your security posture, (3) lose the option to retreat to cover. Always challenge from a position of cover and use distance as a buffer until threat level is established."}},relatedGuide:"security-001",tags:["security","strangers","grid-down","advanced"]}]},600,[]);
__d(function(e,t,i,a,o,r,n){o.exports=[{id:"quiz-vehicle-001",category:"vehicle",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"Your vehicle has a flat tire. Your hydraulic jack failed. You have a hi-lift jack, a vehicle owner's manual, and basic tools. No nearby help. Which method is most reliable for changing the tire?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Find a hill, drive onto rocks on the good side to tilt the vehicle and create clearance"},{id:"b",text:"Use the hi-lift jack on the vehicle's frame or bumper receiver point as specified in your owner's manual"},{id:"c",text:"Dig out the dirt under the flat tire until the rim clears the ground"},{id:"d",text:"Remove the spare and place it under the axle, then deflate all remaining tires to lower the vehicle"}],correct:"b",explanation:"A Hi-Lift jack (farm jack) is the correct tool \u2014 it can lift a vehicle from frame points, receiver hitches, or bumper mounting points. Consult your owner's manual for the approved jack points \u2014 using wrong points can deform the body or cause the vehicle to slip. Hi-Lift jacks are NOT stable \u2014 always chock the remaining wheels and never put any body part under the vehicle while supported only by a Hi-Lift. If no Hi-Lift: digging under the flat tire (option c) is the backup method \u2014 dig until the rim clears, then work the tire off the rim manually if necessary. Driving up rocks is difficult to control. Deflating all tires creates an additional problem without solving the original.",relatedGuide:"vehicle-001",tags:["vehicle","tires","field-repair","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-vehicle-002",category:"vehicle",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"Your vehicle battery is dead. A good Samaritan has cables. Place the jumper cable connection steps in the correct order to prevent sparking damage to electronics and risk of battery explosion.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Connect red (positive) clamp to dead battery positive terminal"},{id:"2",text:"Connect red (positive) clamp to good battery positive terminal"},{id:"3",text:"Connect black (negative) clamp to good battery negative terminal"},{id:"4",text:"Connect black (negative) clamp to unpainted metal on the DEAD car's engine block or chassis \u2014 NOT the dead battery negative terminal"},{id:"5",text:"Start the good vehicle, allow 2 minutes, then start the dead vehicle"}],correct_order:["2","1","3","4","5"],explanation:"The correct order prevents sparking near the battery: Red to GOOD positive first (establishes circuit reference), Red to DEAD positive (connection to dead battery), Black to GOOD negative, Black to ENGINE BLOCK on dead car (NOT the dead battery negative). Why engine block? Batteries vent hydrogen gas \u2014 a spark near the vent causes explosion. By grounding to the engine block away from the battery, any connection spark happens away from the gas. Disconnect in REVERSE order: Black from engine block \u2192 Black from good \u2192 Red from dead \u2192 Red from good. Never let the clamps touch each other while connected to a live battery.",relatedGuide:"vehicle-001",tags:["vehicle","battery","jump-start","beginner"]},{id:"quiz-vehicle-dt-001",category:"vehicle",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Temperature Light \u2014 60 Miles Out",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"You're bugging out on a highway, 60 miles from your destination. Temperature gauge spikes to red and the warning light activates. Steam is visible from the hood edges. Traffic is minimal. What is your first action?",options:[{text:"Pull off immediately, turn off the engine, do not open the hood yet",next:"pull_off_correct"},{text:"Turn on the heater to full blast and limp to the next exit 8 miles ahead",next:"limp_ahead"}]},pull_off_correct:{id:"pull_off_correct",scenario:"Correct. Engine off. Wait 15-20 minutes before approaching the hood. When you open the hood, the radiator cap is pressurized and hot. Do you:",options:[{text:"Open the radiator cap slowly using a thick cloth, facing away from it",next:"cap_slow"},{text:"Open the overflow reservoir cap \u2014 check level there rather than the pressurized radiator",next:"overflow_check"}]},overflow_check:{id:"overflow_check",scenario:"Smart and safer. The overflow reservoir (usually translucent plastic) shows coolant level without pressurized burn risk. It's empty. You have 2 gallons of water in the vehicle. What do you add?",options:[{text:"Add water to the overflow reservoir only \u2014 never add cold water to a hot engine",next:"add_overflow"},{text:"Wait until the engine is fully cool (45+ min), then add water to the radiator directly",next:"wait_cool"}]},wait_cool:{id:"wait_cool",outcome:"success",explanation:"Waiting for the engine to fully cool before adding water is the safest method. Adding cold water to a hot engine can crack the engine block from thermal shock. The recurring overheat indicates a coolant leak or thermostat failure \u2014 not just low coolant. You got 20 more miles out of the vehicle. At the next overheat, evaluate whether continuing is worth engine destruction. Carry coolant/water and repeat the coolant-add process, or stop and foot-exfil."},add_overflow:{id:"add_overflow",outcome:"success",explanation:"Adding to the overflow reservoir feeds the radiator as it cools and pressure drops \u2014 it is the safer method. The recurring overheat indicates a leak. You may be able to limp to your destination with repeated coolant-add stops. Key rule: when you see the temp gauge rise, pull over BEFORE it redlines to prevent head gasket damage. A blown head gasket ends your vehicle's utility entirely."},cap_slow:{id:"cap_slow",outcome:"success",explanation:"Opening the radiator cap slowly with a thick cloth while facing away reduces burn risk if residual pressure releases. This method works but carries more risk than checking the overflow reservoir first. Once open, confirm coolant level is low, then add water slowly with the engine cool. Never open a hot radiator cap quickly \u2014 pressurized steam causes severe burns."},limp_ahead:{id:"limp_ahead",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Running the heater IS a legitimate short-term overheating mitigation (it pulls heat from the coolant). However, if the temperature is already at maximum, this is not enough. Driving a severely overheating engine causes head gasket failure and potential engine seizure \u2014 both permanently disable the vehicle. Pull off and stop when the temperature gauge is in the red. The 8-mile limp cost you the vehicle. Your gear is now roadside 60 miles from your destination."}},relatedGuide:"vehicle-001",tags:["vehicle","engine","overheating","advanced"]},{id:"quiz-vehicle-004",category:"vehicle",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You want to store 20 gallons of gasoline for emergency generator use. What is the single most important safety practice?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Store all 20 gallons in a single 20-gallon steel drum in your garage for quick access"},{id:"b",text:"Use approved fuel containers, add fuel stabilizer (e.g., Sta-Bil), store in a detached structure with ventilation away from ignition sources"},{id:"c",text:"Gasoline has a 5-year shelf life \u2014 add date labels and rotate annually"},{id:"d",text:"Store in plastic milk jugs \u2014 they're airtight and safe for short-term storage"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Approved red fuel containers (ANSI/ASTM-approved) have pressure-relief valves and proper sealing. Fuel stabilizer (Sta-Bil, PRI-G) extends gasoline shelf life from 30 days (untreated) to 12-24 months. Store AWAY from living spaces \u2014 gasoline vapors are heavier than air and pool at ground level, traveling to ignition sources (water heater pilot lights, electrical panels). A detached garage or outdoor shed with ventilation is ideal. Untreated gasoline degrades in 30-60 days and will varnish carburetors. Steel drums increase the risk of static discharge fires during transfer. Plastic milk jugs are NOT approved containers \u2014 they are not rated for fuel permeation or pressure.",relatedGuide:"vehicle-001",tags:["vehicle","fuel-storage","generator","beginner"]}]},601,[]);
__d(function(e,t,o,a,r,s,i){r.exports=[{id:"quiz-home-001",category:"homesteading",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You're selecting chickens for a self-sufficient homestead. You need breeds that produce both quality eggs and usable meat when culled. Which breed combination best represents true dual-purpose performance?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Leghorn and Cornish Cross \u2014 highest individual production in each category"},{id:"b",text:"Rhode Island Red and Barred Plymouth Rock \u2014 established dual-purpose breeds with good egg production and acceptable meat yield"},{id:"c",text:"Silkie and Polish \u2014 ornamental breeds valued for their laying consistency under stress"},{id:"d",text:"Jersey Giant and Modern Game \u2014 large frame with high laying rate"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Rhode Island Reds: 250-300 brown eggs/year, excellent foragers, cold-hardy, heavy enough for table meat (5-6 lbs dressed). Barred Plymouth Rock: 200-250 eggs/year, calm temperament (important for homestead management), similar meat yield to RIR. Both breeds have been selected for self-sufficient homestead use for over a century. Leghorns are outstanding layers (300+ eggs/year) but are small-framed (minimal meat), flighty, and poor in cold. Cornish Cross reach butcher weight in 6-8 weeks but have no laying value and significant health issues in free-range settings. Silkies and Polish are ornamental with poor production. Jersey Giants have excellent meat but very slow growth (5-6 months to butcher weight).",relatedGuide:"homesteading-001",tags:["homesteading","livestock","chickens","beginner"]},{id:"quiz-home-002",category:"homesteading",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"You are setting up a long-term food storage system for your homestead. Rank these preservation methods from LONGEST to SHORTEST expected shelf life when properly executed.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Freeze-drying (fruits, vegetables, meats \u2014 commercial or home unit)"},{id:"2",text:"Pressure canning (meats, vegetables \u2014 properly processed in USDA-approved recipes)"},{id:"3",text:"Salt curing and drying (jerky, salt pork \u2014 moisture reduced below 10%)"},{id:"4",text:"Root cellaring (potatoes, carrots, beets \u2014 cool, humid, dark)"},{id:"5",text:"Lacto-fermentation (sauerkraut, kimchi, pickles \u2014 salt brine fermentation)"}],correct_order:["1","2","3","5","4"],explanation:"Freeze-drying removes 98%+ of moisture while preserving nutrients and structure \u2014 shelf life 25-30 years at room temperature in sealed containers. Pressure canning: high-acid vegetables 18 months, low-acid (meats, beans) 2-5 years when properly processed. Salt-cured and dried meats: 1-4 months at room temperature, longer if vacuum-sealed and refrigerated. Lacto-fermented vegetables: 3-12 months in cool storage (the lacto-fermentation process produces lactic acid which inhibits spoilage, but quality degrades over time). Root cellar vegetables: 3-6 months in optimal conditions (32-40\xb0F, 90-95% humidity) \u2014 the shortest shelf life without processing. The key principle: reducing water activity (drying/freeze-drying) provides the longest shelf life; microbial inhibition (acid, salt) is secondary; simple cold storage is shortest.",relatedGuide:"homesteading-001",tags:["homesteading","food-preservation","storage","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-home-dt-001",category:"homesteading",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Garden Wipeout \u2014 August",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"It's mid-August. Your main vegetable garden was destroyed by an unexpected early blight that killed your tomatoes, squash, and beans \u2014 60% of your planned food production for the year. You have 6 weeks until first frost. You have seeds, compost, and irrigation. What is your immediate action?",options:[{text:"Immediately replant fast-maturing crops for a partial fall harvest",next:"replant_fast"},{text:"Focus on protein and preservation \u2014 dedicate energy to hunting, fishing, and preserving what's left",next:"protein_focus"}]},replant_fast:{id:"replant_fast",scenario:"Good instinct. With 6 weeks to first frost, which crops do you prioritize?",options:[{text:"Plant fast-maturing greens and root vegetables: radishes (25 days), lettuce (30-45 days), turnips (45-60 days), and spinach (40-50 days)",next:"correct_replant"},{text:"Replant tomatoes and squash from seed \u2014 they were your main crop and you still have seeds",next:"wrong_replant"}]},correct_replant:{id:"correct_replant",outcome:"success",explanation:"In a crop failure pivot, match seed-to-harvest time to your remaining frost-free days. Rule of thumb: maturity days on the seed packet + 2 weeks buffer for frost. Fast-maturing crops \u2014 radishes (25-30 days), arugula (30 days), spinach (40 days), turnips (45 days), lettuce (30-45 days) \u2014 are the correct pivot crops. Cold frames (simple wood frame + clear plastic) extend the season 4-6 weeks beyond first frost for cold-tolerant crops. Brassicas (kale, broccoli) can also work \u2014 they actually improve in flavor after light frost."},wrong_replant:{id:"wrong_replant",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Tomatoes require 70-90 days from transplant to harvest. You are 6 weeks from frost. Even with transplants (not seeds), you will not harvest before the plants die. You've lost the labor and seed investment. Never replant a long-season crop when you don't have the frost-free days to support it. Know your average first frost date, work backward from it, and only plant crops with sufficient days-to-maturity. A common homestead mistake is emotional attachment to lost crops leading to poor recovery planting decisions."},protein_focus:{id:"protein_focus",outcome:"success",explanation:"A pure protein focus is defensible \u2014 animal protein is calorically dense and preservable. However, abandoning a replant opportunity entirely leaves nutrition gaps (vitamins, carbohydrates) that stored goods may not fill. The best answer combines BOTH: plant fast-maturing crops immediately AND pursue protein \u2014 they are not mutually exclusive. This outcome highlights the importance of diversified food production and not over-relying on a single crop."}},relatedGuide:"homesteading-001",tags:["homesteading","gardening","food-production","advanced"]}]},602,[]);
__d(function(e,t,a,i,o,n,r){o.exports=[{id:"quiz-fm-001",category:"field-manual",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"advanced",scenario:"You are in the field with a topographic map and lensatic compass but do not know your exact location. You can see two identifiable terrain features: a distinctive hill to your northeast and a water tower to your south. Perform a map resection to find your location. Order these steps correctly.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Identify both terrain features on your topographic map"},{id:"2",text:"Take a compass bearing to the first feature (the hill)"},{id:"3",text:"Convert the magnetic bearing to a grid/true bearing using declination"},{id:"4",text:"Draw the back-bearing line from the first feature on the map (add or subtract 180\xb0)"},{id:"5",text:"Repeat steps 2-4 for the second terrain feature \u2014 your location is where the two back-bearing lines intersect"}],correct_order:["1","2","3","4","5"],explanation:"Resection (also called triangulation): Identify features on the map first \u2014 confirm what you're looking at before taking bearings. Take magnetic bearing to feature using lensatic compass (front sight to target). Convert to grid bearing (apply declination). Back-bearing = bearing + 180\xb0 (or \u2212 180\xb0 if >180\xb0) \u2014 this is the line drawn FROM the feature TOWARD you. Plot the back-bearing line from the identified feature on the map. Repeat for second feature. Intersection = your position. For accuracy: use 3 features if possible (3-point resection). Errors in terrain feature identification or bearing accuracy are the primary failure modes \u2014 verify each feature carefully.",relatedGuide:"navigation-001",tags:["navigation","map-reading","resection","advanced"]},{id:"quiz-fm-002",category:"field-manual",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"Your pace count is 62 double-paces per 100 meters on flat ground. You've been counting paces and have reached 496 double-paces on a trail with moderate incline. Approximately how far have you traveled, and what correction should you apply for the terrain?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Exactly 800 meters \u2014 pace count is accurate regardless of terrain"},{id:"b",text:"Approximately 800 meters on flat ground, but actual distance may be 10-20% less due to incline shortening stride length \u2014 apply a reduction factor"},{id:"c",text:"496 meters \u2014 the pace count equals meters by standard military convention"},{id:"d",text:"Over 1,000 meters \u2014 inclined terrain requires MORE paces per 100m due to elevation gain"}],correct:"b",explanation:"496 paces \xf7 62 paces/100m = 800 meters (flat ground calculation). However, inclined terrain shortens stride length \u2014 most practitioners add 10-25% more paces per 100m on significant slopes. If your flat-ground pace count is 62/100m, your inclined pace count may be 68-75/100m. Without terrain-specific calibration, your distance estimate is shorter than actual by 10-20%. The solution: calibrate your pace count on multiple terrain types (flat, uphill, downhill, thick vegetation) and record each. Keep a pace count bead counter on your person. At night or in vegetation, your pace count will also increase. 496 meters would only be true if your pace count were 1 pace per 1 meter \u2014 not standard.",relatedGuide:"navigation-001",tags:["navigation","pace-count","dead-reckoning","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-fm-dt-001",category:"field-manual",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"6 Hours to Evacuation \u2014 Casualty Management",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"You have a gunshot casualty, conscious and alert, tourniquet applied to the right thigh 45 minutes ago, bleeding controlled. Evacuation is 6+ hours away. No IV access equipment. Temperature is dropping (55\xb0F, light rain). The casualty is beginning to shiver. What is your primary concern for the next hour?",options:[{text:"Hypothermia prevention \u2014 the Lethal Triad (hypothermia, acidosis, coagulopathy) is now your primary threat",next:"hypothermia_focus"},{text:"Tourniquet conversion \u2014 45 minutes is approaching the window where you should consider loosening the TQ to assess wound",next:"tq_conversion"}]},hypothermia_focus:{id:"hypothermia_focus",scenario:"Correct priority. You cover the casualty with a space blanket or any insulating material. What do you do about the injured limb?",options:[{text:"Leave the tourniquet and monitor \u2014 do not touch it until reaching surgical care unless bleeding restarts",next:"leave_tq"},{text:"Elevate the extremity above heart level to reduce swelling and pain",next:"elevate_limb"}]},leave_tq:{id:"leave_tq",outcome:"success",explanation:"The Lethal Triad of trauma: Hypothermia + Acidosis + Coagulopathy. Each worsens the others \u2014 hypothermia impairs clotting, acidosis worsens hypothermia, coagulopathy causes bleeding which causes acidosis. With hemorrhage controlled (TQ working), the next threat is hypothermia. Cover casualty from the ground up (ground insulation first). Keep the TQ in place \u2014 do not loosen or convert in the field without surgical capability or clear clinical indication. Monitor for: rebleeding (blood soaking through), tourniquet migration, and skin changes distal to TQ."},elevate_limb:{id:"elevate_limb",outcome:"success",explanation:"Limb elevation with a tourniquet in place is not harmful, but it's not the priority. The hypothermia focus was correct \u2014 addressing the Lethal Triad first. Elevation can be maintained while also managing hypothermia. The key teaching point: in extended care scenarios, prioritize hypothermia prevention, pain management (if available), hydration (if no contraindication), and monitoring over interventions that provide marginal benefit."},tq_conversion:{id:"tq_conversion",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Tourniquet conversion is a surgical decision, not a field decision. The 2-hour guideline is about evacuation priority (within 2 hours reduces risk of permanent nerve/vascular damage), NOT a field removal window. In extended care (6+ hours to evac), you MAINTAIN the tourniquet. The risk of uncontrolled rebleeding without surgical backup far outweighs the risk of maintained tourniquet ischemia over 6 hours. Mark the time on the TQ, document it on the casualty card, and expedite evacuation."}},relatedGuide:"field-manual-001",tags:["field-manual","trauma","TCCC","advanced"]},{id:"quiz-fm-004",category:"field-manual",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You're establishing a 5-person patrol base for 3+ days. You need to site a field latrine (straddle trench). Which placement rule is most important?",options:[{id:"a",text:"At least 300 feet (100 meters) downhill and downwind from your water source and sleeping area"},{id:"b",text:"As close to the sleeping area as possible \u2014 distance creates security exposure at night"},{id:"c",text:"Uphill from your water source \u2014 gravity will drain waste away from the water"},{id:"d",text:"In the densest vegetation available \u2014 natural decomposition is faster in shade"}],correct:"a",explanation:"The 300-foot / 100-meter rule from any water source is the foundational field sanitation standard (U.S. Army FM 4-25.12, FM 21-10). Pathogens from fecal contamination travel through soil and reach water sources \u2014 300 feet provides adequate filtration distance for most bacterial pathogens through normal soil. Placement is DOWNHILL from water (never uphill \u2014 contamination flows downhill) and DOWNWIND from sleeping areas (odor and fly vectors). At night, security concerns must be balanced with sanitation \u2014 a well-secured route to the latrine site is preferable to compromising health for convenience. Straddle trench depth: 1-2 feet minimum. When leaving the site, fill and cover with 6+ inches of soil.",relatedGuide:"field-manual-001",tags:["field-manual","sanitation","patrol-base","beginner"]}]},603,[]);
__d(function(e,t,a,o,i,r,n){i.exports=[{id:"quiz-disaster-dt-001",category:"disaster",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"EMP Event \u2014 Hour 1 Decisions",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"Your car stopped in traffic simultaneously with all other vehicles. Traffic lights are off. Your cell phone is completely dead. Store alarms are going off citywide. Based on these indicators, you suspect an EMP event. You are 12 miles from home with your everyday carry bag. What is your first action?",options:[{text:"Begin the 12-mile walk home immediately \u2014 retrieve your family and supplies",next:"walk_home"},{text:"Stop, observe the situation for 10-15 minutes, gather information from people around you before committing to an action",next:"observe_first"}]},observe_first:{id:"observe_first",scenario:"After 15 minutes you confirm: no vehicles work, no cell phones work, no radio from anyone nearby. A police officer on foot approaches saying he received no communications before his radio died. This confirms a broad EM event. Do you:",options:[{text:"Begin walking home \u2014 12 miles is a 4-hour walk, daylight is available",next:"walk_home"},{text:"Look for a pre-1985 diesel vehicle that may have survived \u2014 older vehicles have no solid-state electronics",next:"find_old_vehicle"}]},walk_home:{id:"walk_home",outcome:"success",explanation:"Walking home is correct when the distance is manageable and daylight is available. 12 miles = approximately 4 hours at a comfortable pace. Key walking-home principles: stay off main roads where possible (less exposure to panicking crowds), carry water and a snack, navigate by landmark/sun/compass rather than GPS. At home: implement 72-hour plan immediately \u2014 fill bathtubs, take cash, implement comms plan with out-of-area contact, move critical supplies to a secure location. The first 72 hours are about information gathering and security, not long-term logistics."},find_old_vehicle:{id:"find_old_vehicle",outcome:"success",explanation:"Old diesel vehicles are a legitimate EMP contingency. The challenge: you must find one, the owner must be willing to help you, and fuel availability is uncertain (though mechanical diesel pumps at some stations may still work). This is a viable secondary approach but takes time \u2014 weigh the time cost of searching versus the certainty of walking. If you find a working vehicle in 30 minutes, it's worth it. If it takes 2+ hours, you've lost your daylight walking window."}},relatedGuide:"disaster-001",tags:["disaster","EMP","grid-down","advanced"]},{id:"quiz-disaster-002",category:"disaster",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"advanced",scenario:"You hear a nuclear detonation occurred 15 miles from your location. You are indoors in a concrete building. The wind is blowing TOWARD you from the direction of the detonation. FEMA guidance says: what is the correct action?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Evacuate immediately \u2014 15 miles is within the severe fallout zone and you must leave now"},{id:"b",text:"Shelter-in-place immediately \u2014 go to the center of a middle floor, seal windows/doors, turn off HVAC, and monitor for official guidance within 24 hours"},{id:"c",text:"Evacuate perpendicular to the wind \u2014 drive crosswind to avoid the fallout plume"},{id:"d",text:"Go to the basement for 3-7 days \u2014 underground provides the most shielding"}],correct:"b",explanation:"The FEMA/DHS 'Get Inside, Stay Inside, Stay Tuned' guidance: at 15 miles and winds toward you, fallout arrives in approximately 15-30 minutes. You do NOT have time to safely evacuate \u2014 you will be caught in the open during peak fallout. Shelter-in-place in a substantial building (concrete, brick) dramatically reduces radiation exposure. Fallout intensity decreases by the Rule of 7: for every 7x increase in time after detonation, radiation reduces by a factor of 10 (7 hours = 90% reduction, 49 hours = 99% reduction). The center of a middle floor is optimal (most mass between you and the exterior). Basement is better than nothing but may not be available. Stay sealed for minimum 24 hours, preferably 48-72, or until official guidance. Do NOT open the building during peak fallout.",relatedGuide:"disaster-001",tags:["disaster","nuclear","shelter-in-place","advanced"]},{id:"quiz-disaster-003",category:"disaster",type:"priority_order",difficulty:"beginner",scenario:"You are indoors in a multi-story building when a major earthquake begins. Place these actions in the correct order.",items:[{id:"1",text:"Drop to hands and knees immediately \u2014 prevents being knocked down"},{id:"2",text:"Cover your head and neck with your arms or under a sturdy desk/table"},{id:"3",text:"Hold on until shaking stops \u2014 do not move to exit while the building is moving"},{id:"4",text:"After shaking stops, check yourself and others for injuries before moving"},{id:"5",text:"Evacuate the building using stairs (never elevator) and move to open space away from buildings"}],correct_order:["1","2","3","4","5"],explanation:"DROP-COVER-HOLD ON is the FEMA-recommended earthquake protocol based on injury data analysis. DROP immediately \u2014 being on hands and knees prevents falls and allows movement. COVER \u2014 most earthquake injuries are from falling objects, not building collapse (in modern structures). Get under a desk or cover head/neck if no desk available. HOLD ON \u2014 shaking typically lasts 10-30 seconds. Most injuries happen from people trying to move or exit during shaking. After shaking: assess before moving (shock can mask injuries). Exit via stairs \u2014 elevators may be compromised. Move to open space away from building facades, power lines, and glass. Do NOT run into doorways \u2014 the 'doorframe' myth has been disproven. Interior rooms under structural beams are preferred cover.",relatedGuide:"disaster-001",tags:["disaster","earthquake","drop-cover-hold","beginner"]},{id:"quiz-disaster-004",category:"disaster",type:"multiple_choice",difficulty:"intermediate",scenario:"Floodwaters from a river have receded from your neighborhood. Standing water remains in your yard. Your water well was submerged. When is it safe to use water from the flooded well?",options:[{id:"a",text:"Once the water level returns to normal \u2014 the flood removed contaminants as it receded"},{id:"b",text:"After the well is professionally disinfected with chlorine bleach shock treatment AND tested for bacterial contamination"},{id:"c",text:"After running the pump for 30 minutes to flush flood water out"},{id:"d",text:"Floodwater contaminates wells permanently \u2014 a new well must be drilled"}],correct:"b",explanation:"Flooded wells are contaminated with sewage, agricultural runoff, fuel, chemicals, and biological pathogens. The correct process per CDC/EPA: (1) Wait until floodwaters fully recede. (2) Pump out all standing water from the well. (3) Shock disinfect with regular household bleach (unscented, 8.25% sodium hypochlorite): use CDC formula for your well depth (typically 1-2 cups per 100 gallons of water in the well). (4) Let sit 12-24 hours. (5) Pump until bleach odor is gone. (6) Test with a certified lab for coliform bacteria, E. coli, and nitrates. Do NOT use until test results confirm safety. Running the pump alone does not reach contamination in the well casing and gravel pack. Wells can be remediated \u2014 permanent abandonment is rarely necessary.",relatedGuide:"disaster-001",tags:["disaster","flood","water-safety","intermediate"]},{id:"quiz-disaster-dt-002",category:"disaster",type:"decision_tree",difficulty:"advanced",title:"Category 3 \u2014 36 Hours Out",nodes:{start:{id:"start",scenario:"A Category 3 hurricane (sustained winds 111-129 mph) is forecast to make landfall 36 hours from now, with your location in the forecast cone. Your home is a 1970s wood-frame house in a zone B evacuation area (storm surge 4-6 feet possible). Mandatory evacuation has not been ordered. Do you evacuate or stay?",options:[{text:"Evacuate now \u2014 36 hours gives you time to beat the evacuation traffic",next:"evacuate_now"},{text:"Wait for mandatory evacuation order \u2014 leaving prematurely wastes resources and the storm may turn",next:"wait_mandatory"}]},evacuate_now:{id:"evacuate_now",outcome:"success",explanation:"Zone B (4-6 foot surge) in a wood-frame home from the 1970s is a high-risk combination. Wood-frame homes from the pre-2000 era have inadequate hurricane strapping and can fail in sustained Cat 3 winds. A 4-6 foot storm surge will destroy most ground-floor contents and is life-threatening. Evacuating 36 hours out beats traffic congestion that typically begins at the 18-24 hour mark. Rule: if you have the time, use it. The cost of an unnecessary evacuation is inconvenience. The cost of a failed shelter-in-place is potentially your life."},wait_mandatory:{id:"wait_mandatory",outcome:"poor",explanation:"Wood-frame pre-code construction + Zone B surge + Cat 3 = very high risk for shelter-in-place. The mandatory evacuation order often comes too late for those with limited resources, pets, elderly family, or who are far from highways. The decision to evacuate should be personal \u2014 made at the 36-72 hour mark, not at the 20-hour mark when traffic is gridlocked. In Zone B: if you cannot reach a hardened shelter (Category 5 rated) within your zone, evacuate for anything Cat 2 or higher. The rule of thumb: if you are in a surge zone in any structure built before 2000, evacuate for anything Cat 2 or higher."}},relatedGuide:"disaster-001",tags:["disaster","hurricane","evacuation","advanced"]}]},604,[]);
